{Hello and welcome to this Lifetime Repertoire about the Flank Openings for Black!  I have published two Chessable courses for Black against d4 over the last few years. The first one, The Magnus Queen's Gambit, is based on the moves d4 d5 c4 e6 followed by 3... a6 against both Nf3 and Nc3 . The second course is Lifetime Repertoires: Classical Slav, based on d4 d5 c4 c6 . With this new course, I have aimed to complement both courses with a reply to Nf3 , c4 and all minor first moves, so that you will have a full repertoire against everything except e4 . This was the original intention, but when creating the course I also realized that many of you that follow other courses than my own against d4 might want a complete repertoire against the Flank Openings as well. Therefore, I made sure that this course will fit everybody who plays d4 d5 followed by either 2... e6 or 2... c6 as Black. This also means that the course is twofold – against most of White's setups, I am recommending one system based on ... c6 , and one system based on ... e6 . Another thing that I have put a lot of emphasis on is the explanation of the various move orders, both ups and downs for both sides. As an experienced grandmaster having played endless open tournaments, I know that one of the easiest and most reliable ways to get an opening advantage as White against a weaker player is to alter the move order early on, tricking my opponents into something they did not originally intend to enter. In recent years, this has even become a trend at the top level. This course is aiming to eliminate this problem for you entirely! My main goal is for you never having to worry or feel insecure about the various move orders from White. No matter if White plays c4 , Nf3 or d4 or all 3 in different order, you will be ready after having studied this course.  There are a couple of different approaches to this problem. It's tempting to recommend immediately settling for a specific structure, for instance meeting c4 with e5 , thereby eliminating all move order issues. However, that is a sort of shortcut approach that I don't like too much. I believe, especially at club level, that we should try to get into structures that are familiar to us as much as possible. Therefore, I am consistently aiming for pawn structures that we are well familiar with already from our repertoires against 1. d4 . This means that we need to put a little more effort on the first few moves, in order not to get tricked by a sudden d2 - d4 from White, but we do get a lot in return. Instead of having to learn entirely new structures, with new plans and setups for both sides which we anyway will get to face rarely in practice, we are able to keep within our already familiar structures, and many if not most of the plans, ideas, maneuvers, tricks etc. are already within our toolbox. I am quite happy with how it worked out, and feel confident you will share my positivity.  As usual, when I create a course, it's very, very important for me to not only teach you about the opening moves specifically. In addition to knowing a lot about new openings, you will also learn a lot more about chess in general. I do not believe that the opening is an independent part of the game, but rather just one part of the whole game. Therefore, you will find a lot of discussions about typical middlegame plans and ideas, as well as some typical developments well into the endgame.} 1. Z0 *

