[Black "A Toolbox Approach"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "1"]

{Preparing against c4 and Nf3 is usually a lot trickier than against more straightforward openings such as d4 or e4 . Especially at the amateur level, the goal of most players who play flank openings as White is to get us into structures that, while objectively sound, are not of the type we usually play. This course gives you the flexibility to mix and match your existing repertoire with complementary choices.  I have divided the material into three main parts: one more aimed at Slav players, one more aimed at Queen's Gambit players, and a third part that is good for both. The chapters are like a set of tools accompanied by a detailed instruction manual. The goal is to illustrate the aspect of complementary repertoire choices and to provide you with an understanding of how to choose the right tool each time.  � chapters that pair best with Slav-based repertoires have been marked with a wrench;  � chapters that pair best with QGD-based repertoires have been marked with a hammer;  �️ chapters that can pair well with either and where the choice is mostly about your preference have been marked with both.  It's important to emphasize that the choice is yours. For instance, I am recommending Nf3 d5 g3 Nd7 for Slav players, but if you as a Queen's Gambit player take a look at the chapter and think it looks like something you want to try as Black, then you should definitely go ahead and do so! In this sense, this course is a bit different from most other Lifetime Repertoires.   You could still use it in the “normal” way, just blindly following my propositions, but the course will also work very well for you to make your own picks.   The only thing you need to remember is to always ask “What happens if White plays d2 - d4 here?” in order not to get tricked. But as long as that question has a satisfactory answer, feel free to experiment with picking out just those chapters that tempt you the most!  As for the actual lines I am recommending, I have tried to keep true to my usual style. That means a few things. First and foremost, everything must be objectively sound and healthy – I would never dream of recommending anything I wouldn't want to play myself.   Secondly, I believe chess is a fantastically interesting game, and that we should strive to enjoy it as much as possible. That means that I am trying to recommend lines that give as much and as interesting play as possible – for both sides! If you are looking for the most clinically equalizing lines in the driest and most boring way possible, then I'm afraid my courses are not for you.  The third important factor when I am choosing lines is that of popularity. When choosing between two similar options, I am generally going for the lesser known and popular one, for two reasons. Your opponents will be less familiar with it, and the amount of existing theory is less, meaning your workload becomes less. I don't believe there is any point in remembering more than we have to.   With this approach in mind, there will be many, many examples in the lines where we are leaving more or less all established theory well before move 10!} 1. Z0 *

