1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 {My recommendation. White can, and should, now transpose to the Accelerated Meran with 5. d4 . That line differs from the line that I am recommending in the Classical Slav,, but many of the ideas are still the same, and compared to the a6 -Slav White has fewer options by having committed to e3 , Nf3 and Nc3 .} ({•} 4... e6 {The most popular move in practice. It could still be a viable option in order to meet 5. d4 with 5... a6 , transposing to our Accelerated Meran, but there are two reasons I chose not to recommend it: one is that it's much more popular than 4... a6 , meaning White will likely be more ready for it.} 5. b3 {This is the other reason. When we play 4... a6 we can now develop the c8 -bishop outside the pawn chain. This is still by no means bad for Black, but I feel it's the sort of play that White is looking for.}) ({•} 4... Bf5 {The move we would like to play, however it works out rather badly.} 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Qb3 $1 {Compared to the Slav, we can't play ... Qc7 as the d5 -pawn is hanging.}) 5. d4 {Without any doubt, the critical move. Now we have transposed to the so called Chebanenko variation of the Slav, which is something I don't recommend in my Lifetime Repertoire: Classical Slav . But don't worry, we are not tricked. The big point compared to the normal Chebanenko Slav is that White has already committed their pawn to e3 , which greatly decreases the number of lines possible.} ({Against the normal Chebanenko,} 5. d4 {d5} dxc4 {c6 Nf3 Nf6 Nc3 a6 , I consider the move c5 to be the strongest. Probably} 6. a4 {is the second strongest, and only on 3rd place we find moves like g3 or e3 . So White is in fact the one having been 'tricked' into a suboptimal line!}) 5... e6 {Changing opening once again! With 5... e6 , we are entering the so called Accelerated Meran (or a6 -Meran, as it is also often called). The idea of ... e6 is to strengthen the center, particularly being able to recapture on d5 with the e-pawn instead of the c-pawn.   The deeper point behind our play is to prepare ... dxc4 , followed by ... b5 and ... c5 .} 6. Qc2 ({Another of the moves Gelfand tried in his World Championship match against Anand. White is making a non-committal developing move, not weakening the a5 - e1 diagonal (} 6. b3 {) or losing a tempo with the light squared bishop ( Bd3 )}) 6... c5 {Another move that might look odd at first sight. Aren't we just losing another tempo? The point is that in the open center that will arise after ... c5 , the queen would often be better on d1 than on c2 . It no longer controls the d4 -square, and can get under attack on c2 .} 7. cxd5 {The critical move.} (7. a3 {Such moves are popular in practice, but do not really require a lot of theoretical knowledge to meet.} dxc4 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Bxc4 Nbd7 {Followed by ... O-O and ... b5 ... Bb7 is harmonious for Black.}) 7... exd5 8. dxc5 {This is a solid move. White is trying to prove a small edge due to the isolated pawn, but as so often in the Accelerated Meran we have plenty of counterplay to compensate for that.} Bxc5 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O Be6 ({This is a nice detail. Most often, people play the immediate} 10... Nc6 {, but then} 11. a3 $5 {might be a bit annoying. Starting with ... Be6 is a bit more flexible, as we keep the option of going both to c6 and d7 with the knight.}) 11. Rd1 Qe7 {The same idea as on the previous move - we keep waiting for White to play either a3 or b3 .} 12. b3 Nc6 {Now this makes perfect sense, as White would lose time if they push a3 , b4 .} 13. Bb2 Rfd8 14. Rac1 Ba7 {Such positions are likely to arise. We have nice development and potential for a kingside initiative. If we want to be solid, then pushing ... d4 sometime over the next few moves will likely result in more trades.} *


