1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 {My recommendation. White can, and should, now transpose to the Accelerated Meran with 5. d4 . That line differs from the line that I am recommending in the Classical Slav,, but many of the ideas are still the same, and compared to the a6 -Slav White has fewer options by having committed to e3 , Nf3 and Nc3 .} ({•} 4... e6 {The most popular move in practice. It could still be a viable option in order to meet 5. d4 with 5... a6 , transposing to our Accelerated Meran, but there are two reasons I chose not to recommend it: one is that it's much more popular than 4... a6 , meaning White will likely be more ready for it.} 5. b3 {This is the other reason. When we play 4... a6 we can now develop the c8 -bishop outside the pawn chain. This is still by no means bad for Black, but I feel it's the sort of play that White is looking for.}) ({•} 4... Bf5 {The move we would like to play, however it works out rather badly.} 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Qb3 $1 {Compared to the Slav, we can't play ... Qc7 as the d5 -pawn is hanging.}) 5. d4 {Without any doubt, the critical move. Now we have transposed to the so called Chebanenko variation of the Slav, which is something I don't recommend in my Lifetime Repertoire: Classical Slav . But don't worry, we are not tricked. The big point compared to the normal Chebanenko Slav is that White has already committed their pawn to e3 , which greatly decreases the number of lines possible.} ({Against the normal Chebanenko,} 5. d4 {d5} dxc4 {c6 Nf3 Nf6 Nc3 a6 , I consider the move c5 to be the strongest. Probably} 6. a4 {is the second strongest, and only on 3rd place we find moves like g3 or e3 . So White is in fact the one having been 'tricked' into a suboptimal line!}) 5... e6 {Changing opening once again! With 5... e6 , we are entering the so called Accelerated Meran (or a6 -Meran, as it is also often called). The idea of ... e6 is to strengthen the center, particularly being able to recapture on d5 with the e-pawn instead of the c-pawn.   The deeper point behind our play is to prepare ... dxc4 , followed by ... b5 and ... c5 .} 6. c5 {A strategic move. Normally, releasing the tension is not to be recommended, but here White is arguing that having played ... a6 as Black makes it a lot less attractive to break the pawn chain with ... b6 later on.} Nbd7 7. Qc2 {This is a high class move. By not developing the bishop to d3 , White is making ... e5 a lot less attractive for Black.} b6 {The solid way of playing. We force White to give up on the space advantage. In return, we get a slight weakness on c6 , but that is very hard for White to make any use of.} 8. cxb6 Qxb6 {The first time I saw this position I thought White should have some edge due to the backward c-pawn, but the more I looked, the more I like it for Black. It's actually very hard for White to find a good plan. Attacking the c-pawn will never really lead to anything as it's too easy to defend, but White is also lacking in good pawn breaks. Pushing e4 will generally only make it easier for Black.} 9. Bd2 {Has been the most common move in practical play, but basically we play the same against all White's moves.} Bd6 10. Rc1 Bb7 {Just remember to play ... Bb7 after Rc1 , in order to keep the c-pawn defended. The bishop will still get traded on a6 later on, but we first need to castle and bring our f-rook to c8 .} 11. Bd3 O-O 12. Na4 Qc7 (12... Qa7 {here is not so good because of} 13. Ba5) 13. O-O a5 {We have all the time in the world, as White isn't really threatening anything. After having traded the bishops, we want to play ... Nb6 and try to trade off our weak a-pawn. Under the right circumstances, we could also consider to push ... c5 , especially if we have evacuated our queen from the c-file.} *


