1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 {My recommendation. White can, and should, now transpose to the Accelerated Meran with 5. d4 . That line differs from the line that I am recommending in the Classical Slav,, but many of the ideas are still the same, and compared to the a6 -Slav White has fewer options by having committed to e3 , Nf3 and Nc3 .} ({•} 4... e6 {The most popular move in practice. It could still be a viable option in order to meet 5. d4 with 5... a6 , transposing to our Accelerated Meran, but there are two reasons I chose not to recommend it: one is that it's much more popular than 4... a6 , meaning White will likely be more ready for it.} 5. b3 {This is the other reason. When we play 4... a6 we can now develop the c8 -bishop outside the pawn chain. This is still by no means bad for Black, but I feel it's the sort of play that White is looking for.}) ({•} 4... Bf5 {The move we would like to play, however it works out rather badly.} 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Qb3 $1 {Compared to the Slav, we can't play ... Qc7 as the d5 -pawn is hanging.}) 5. d4 {Without any doubt, the critical move. Now we have transposed to the so called Chebanenko variation of the Slav, which is something I don't recommend in my Lifetime Repertoire: Classical Slav . But don't worry, we are not tricked. The big point compared to the normal Chebanenko Slav is that White has already committed their pawn to e3 , which greatly decreases the number of lines possible.} ({Against the normal Chebanenko,} 5. d4 {d5} dxc4 {c6 Nf3 Nf6 Nc3 a6 , I consider the move c5 to be the strongest. Probably} 6. a4 {is the second strongest, and only on 3rd place we find moves like g3 or e3 . So White is in fact the one having been 'tricked' into a suboptimal line!}) 5... e6 {Changing opening once again! With 5... e6 , we are entering the so called Accelerated Meran (or a6 -Meran, as it is also often called). The idea of ... e6 is to strengthen the center, particularly being able to recapture on d5 with the e-pawn instead of the c-pawn.   The deeper point behind our play is to prepare ... dxc4 , followed by ... b5 and ... c5 .} 6. Bd3 {This is the main move in the normal Meran, but in the Accelerated Meran it's actually a fair bit less popular.} dxc4 7. Bxc4 b5 {This is resembling a normal Meran a lot, but it's specifically this position that gives the name 'Accelerated' its meaning. It is accelerated for Black in the sense that by playing ... a6 instead of ... Nbd7 , we are actually able to push ... c5 one move earlier, as the b5 -pawn is already protected.} 8. Bb3 {Recommended by Sielecki+Hansen in their LTR on 1. Nf3 /1. c4 . It does require a little bit of care.} c5 9. O-O (9. e4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Nbd7 $1 {Preventing e5 .} 11. O-O Bb7 {Transposes to the line we're currently studying.}) 9... Bb7 10. e4 {The only critical move. This is actually a slightly topical line, so we should treat it carefully. The main thing is to not allow White any nasty tactics in the center.} cxd4 11. Nxd4 Nbd7 {Preventing e5 . If given time, we want to develop the f8 -bishop and get castled, after which we would simply be better. If White can’t make any tactical tricks on d5 / e6 work, then the bishop will be misplaced on b3 , and both our bishops better than White’s counterparts.} 12. Re1 {The most interesting move, trying to prepare some tactics along the e-file.} Ne5 {Physically blocking the e-file. It is always a bit risky to move the same piece twice before finish development, so we should make sure we know what we are doing.} 13. Bf4 Bd6 {I like this a lot! Of course the move in itself is nothing special, but it invites a nice pawn sacrifice.} 14. Nf5 {Again, if we were just allowed to castle in peace we would have a very pleasant position.} exf5 15. exf5 O-O {This is the point. We simply give back the piece, and then claim we have full compensation with our strong bishop on b7 .} 16. Bxe5 Bxe5 17. Rxe5 Qc7 18. Re3 Rad8 {We have full compensation in numerous ways. One idea is ... Qf4 , to pick up the f5 -pawn, but moves like ... b4 !? pushing the c3 -knight to a bad square also makes sense. Additionally, the move ... Qc6 !? can put annoying pressure towards g2 .} *


