1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 (2. Nc3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 {This does not really have any independent value, as White should play Nf3 or d4 anyway here.}) 2... d5 3. e3 Nf6 {It's understandable from White's perspective that they don't want to transpose to a 1. d4 -opening, but what I really like about our repertoire is how simple it is to handle everything except the d4 -transpositions.} 4. Qc2 {This is an interesting move, which I even employed myself recently. The idea is simple: White prevents ... Bf5 .} Bg4 {Logical. The f5 -square is not available, so we develop to g4 instead. This theme is also commonly seen in the normal Slav.} 5. Ne5 {The critical move. When playing ... Bg4 in the Slav both with and without d4 , this is the first move one needs to consider as a reply.} (5. Be2 {This fails to put any pressure on Black, and we can continue to develop unhindered.} e6 {Next up, we play our usual Slav style setup with ... Nbd7 , ... Bd6 and O-O . The move 4. Qc2 was primarily aimed at making it harder for us to develop our light squared bishop, so now it’s just a tempo wasted.}) 5... Bh5 6. cxd5 {Again, the natural follow-up. White is trying to argue that the bishop on h5 is far away from the defense of the queenside, and that is true.} Nxd5 {Absolutely obligatory. Normally we don't want to give up on the central control like this, but here we have a fair amount of development as compensation. Still, we should be treating this as a serious attempt by White.} (6... cxd5 7. Bb5+ Nbd7 8. Nxd7 Nxd7 9. Qf5 $1 {Loses a pawn. This goes to show the dangers with developing the c8 -bishop early on.}) 7. d4 {Another logical move.} f6 {The most direct move.} 8. Nd3 e5 {Interesting, but also very logical. Long-term White has the center, and therefore the advantage, which means that we should look for short-term ways to compensate for that. Opening up the center and going for quick counterplay is precisely what we need.} 9. dxe5 fxe5 (9... Na6 {is another way to go for quick development.}) 10. e4 {White's best bet, at least initiating some trades.} Nb4 11. Nxb4 Bxb4+ 12. Nc3 Bf7 {Not necessary, but a nice move. After White has played e4 , we no longer play for a direct attack. Instead, we are switching to positional play, particularly making use of the d4 -square. Our pawn on e5 is isolated, but close to impossible for White to attack. It seems fairly balanced, but we definitely have easy play.} *


