1. c4 c6 2. e4 {The Panov. This one is slightly annoying. Not because it is in any way challenging theoretically, but because it leads to a bit more theory than I usually prefer.} d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. cxd5 {This is an independent line. Actually, when reaching this position from 1. c4 rather than 1. e4 , I believe this is much more likely. This might sound odd, but the reason is that there is a lot less theory here than in the traditional Panov lines. As White played 1. c4 , they are likely not 1. e4 -players, therefore not too interested in learning too much theory that they are anyway not going to reach very often, therefore it's tempting with a smaller sideline.} Nf6 5. Bb5+ {A funky check, typical from many similar openings. The idea is to make it harder for us to regain the d5 -pawn} Nbd7 {Important. We need to be able to play ... Nb6 later on, else we might struggle to regain the d5 -pawn.} 6. Nc3 a6 {We kick the bishop immediately, unpinning the d7 -knight to easier regain the d5 -pawn.} 7. Qa4 {The most testing move, trying to make it harder for us to regain the d5 -pawn.} g6 {Probably the simplest. We are still a pawn down, but the d5 -pawn is such a long term weakness that we should never really worry about getting it back. Our idea is to simply play ... Bg7 and O-O , after which the d7 -knight is finally free to move.} 8. Nf3 Bg7 9. O-O O-O {Now we are threatening ... Nb6 .} 10. Bxd7 {This is the idea of White. If we were to win back the d5 -pawn for nothing, we would simply be better, but White tries to keep it for as long as possible.} Nxd7 {I like this recapture! It looks strange considering the fact that our primary target is the d5 -pawn, but we want to play ... b5 , ... Nb6 and ... Bb7 , after which we will finally win it back. For that reason, the bishop would also be misplaced on d7 .} 11. d4 {The most natural move. White can't really do anything to prevent our plan.} b5 12. Qb3 Nb6 {White is unable to keep the d5 -pawn for long.} *

