1. c4 c6 2. e4 {The Panov. This one is slightly annoying. Not because it is in any way challenging theoretically, but because it leads to a bit more theory than I usually prefer.} d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. d4 {This is now a real Panov.} Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Nf3 {The main move. Now I'd like to suggest an old favorite of mine, that I popularized on higher levels in my game against Mamedyarov in Wijk Aan Zee 2022.} a6 {Slightly provocative but highly interesting! I really enjoy this idea. Normally Panov players are expecting something very solid and well-trodden, but by ... a6 we immediately forces White to play chess! The chess-technical point of the move is simply to prevent Bb5 , while making a useful waiting move. We still have hopes of developing our light squared bishop outside the pawn chain.} 7. c5 {From a theoretical point of view, I believe this is the most challenging. I also played it with White in a classical game against Jorden Van Foreest. After playing that game, though, I realized that the positions are rather more difficult for White to play over the board, and I don't think I would have chosen it again.} Bg4 {This is important. Our main strategic aim is to put pressure on the d4 -pawn.} 8. Be2 g6 {Just like on the previous move, the idea is to put pressure on d4 .} 9. Be3 (9. O-O Bg7 10. Be3 e6 {transposes to the line we're analyzing.}) 9... Bg7 10. O-O e6 {This is an important move order, but one that wasn't played by Van Foreest against me. It sounds strange, but we want to keep the g8 -square for our knight!} 11. h3 {This is very natural, and the move I played after 10... O-O , but here it's kind of a mistake!} Bxf3 12. Bxf3 Ng8 {This is an amazing concept, and something I like a lot. We simply do everything we can to put as much pressure as possible on the d4 -pawn.} 13. Qd2 Nge7 14. Na4 {Defending passively Ne2 doesn't really make sense. We would simply have a nice initiative for free.} Nf5 15. Nb6 {This is the idea. It's not so easy to save the rook.} Ncxd4 {But we sacrifice it! This is the reason I am showing this line. It goes to show just how important the d4 -pawn is. We are happily giving up an exchange for the pawn.} 16. Bd1 O-O {Saving the rook is still not great, as it still didn't have any good squares.} 17. Nxa8 Qxa8 {Objectively it's still close to equal, but in practical play I believe we have a nice edge. The central pawns are very strong, and White has absolutely no counterplay whatsoever. This is kind of the dream scenario after 7. c5 .} *


