1. c4 e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 {This move is, just like against 2... c6 instead of 2... e6 , a fairly critical way for White to play. It is very popular at the higher levels because it tends to lead to less forcing play compared to mainlines with 1. d4 . This should suit us well too - after all, we are not trying to force a draw, but rather looking for a fully fledged fight!} Nf6 4. b3 b6 ({This is our setup. We want to play the position as we do in the lines after} 4... d4 {d5 c4 e6 Nf3 a6 e3 . There are two main ways of facing the system with early e3 by White: one is to go for a quick ... c5 , initiating forcing play and trying to equalize by force. This is very solid, and a well-prepared player has good chances of liquidating most of the pieces.  But it's also boring, and not at all in the spirit of this repertoire or how I like to play chess in general. The other way to play is to just develop the pieces to sensible squares and get an incredibly rich middlegame with all pieces on the board. Needless to say, that fits perfectly with our general approach!}) 5. Bb2 Bb7 6. cxd5 {This is by far the most common and natural move. It's a good rule of thumb for White to always consider cxd5 as soon as Black has played ... b6 . The reason is that after the most natural recapture exd5 , Black no longer has the possibility of putting up the 'Carlsbad' pawn chain with d5 - c6 - b7 .} exd5 {This might seem automatic, but it's worth mentioning that in these lines we should always give some thought on how to recapture on d5 . By the pawn is certainly the move in most cases, but there are some exceptions which will be shown later on.} 7. g3 {This might look odd at first sight, but is in fact a high class move. Didn't White play 3. e3 in order to develop the bishop along the f1 - a6 diagonal? Well, yes, but since then things have changed quite a lot. The most important change is that we have committed to ... b6 . This means that we are well-placed for White pushing d4 due to our control over the e4 -square. Bd3 makes no sense with the pawn on d2 , and Be2 looks a bit passive. So fianchettoing the bishop is simply what remains. Additionally, the move e3 can often become useful in the future.} Bd6 {Just as with White's pawn already on d4 , this is always our setup. In general, we start with ... Bd6 and ... O-O and keep the knight flexible on b8 , as it sometimes wants to go to c6 instead.} 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O Re8 {It doesn't make any real difference here, but just out of principle I prefer to keep delaying ... Nbd7 for a little while.} 10. Nc3 {Again clearly the most natural move. The knight could also be developed to d2 , but c3 is simply a better square. Not only is it putting some pressure on d5 , it also has the possibility of jumping to e2 - f4 later on.} a6 {As a rule of thumb, we always meet Nc3 with ... a6 , just not to think about Nb5 -jumps.} 11. Rc1 {The last of the 'automatic' moves for White. Just as our rook belongs on the semi-open e-file, White's rook belongs on the c-file} Nbd7 {The last of our own obligatory moves. Now is a good time to talk about the middlegame in general. First of all, all pieces are still on the board and the central pawn structure still flexible, which means that a lot of things can happen. White is trying to play a slow maneuvering game, mainly reaction to all our actions. The biggest question is about White playing d4 and us playing ... c5 . In general, we welcome White playing d4 before we have committed our c-pawn. That gives us the possibility of ... Ne4 , but also closes the b2 -bishop and prevents the plan of d3 followed by e4 . If our pawn is already on c5 , then d4 makes a lot more sense for White, as they can still open up the position with dxc5 later on. ... c5 is still one of our main plans, but this means that it should be prepared very carefully before committing to it. Other plans for us includes grabbing more queenside space with ... b5 , but that also creates some targets for White to attack. So all in all, we need to arm ourselves with patience and a flexible mind.} 12. d4 {This makes things easier for us.} Ne4 {The most common reaction. The knight simply stands well here, and if White captures we can extend our bishop's diagonal with dxe4 .} 13. Ne2 a5 {This shows a good reason why White usually waits with d4 before we have committed our a8 -rook. Now we can get quick counterplay with ... a5 - a4 .} *

