1. b3 d5 2. Bb2 Nf6 {Following the Slav vs 1. b3 Chapter and playing 2... Bg4 also makes sense for Queen's Gambit players, because it is immediately a comfortable equality and all lines are independent of a real Slav. Indeed, it is what I always did myself, even before adding the Slav to my repertoire. At the same time it's also reasonable to want to keep also 1. b3 into more 'real' QGD-territories which is also the philosophy of this LTR.} 3. Nf3 e6 ({So we decide to not develop our bishop here either. Most likely, this will now transpose to the c4} 3... e6 {Nf3 d5} 4. e3 {, starting here , but there are a couple of independent lines. The most important thing to note is that White haven't yet committed to playing e2 - e3 . That always means we have to take g3 into account, and be prepared for that.}) 4. c4 {The best move. White keeps flexible between e3 and g3 .} (4. e3 {Another transpositional move order.} b6 {A good rule of thumb us that after e3 , we can always play ... b6 . Generally, g3 -setups are the most critical against ... b6 . Here, White can still do it, but then the move e3 will be a waste.}) 4... Bd6 {White did not yet commit to playing e3 , which means that it's not as good for us to play ... b6 . As usual, we could have played 4... c5 and enter some more theoretical and concrete lines, but I prefer to keep the game independent. We place the bishop on d6 , as it is part of our ... b6 -setup anyway, so we are still ready for White going both e3 and g3 .} (4... b6 {Not the most accurate move, but if you are looking for simplicity then always going for this setup is possible. It's very likely to transpose to Nf3 d5 g3 b6 Bg2 Bb7 O-O e6 b3 Nf6 Bb2 Bd6 . White is a little bit better, but it's definitely playable. You can see the line here .} 5. g3 {The critical move against b6-setups. Other moves would also transpose.} Bb7 6. Bg2 Bd6 7. O-O O-O {transposes to Nf3} 8. cxd5 {g3 b6 Bg2 Bb7 O-O e6 b3 Nf6 Bb2 Bd6 c4 O-O , here .}) 5. e3 {This is not a direct transposition yet, as we have placed our bishop on d6 a bit earlier than usual.} O-O (5... b6 {This does not exactly transpose, unfortunately.} 6. Nc3 {Now White is 'threatening' cxd5 followed by Nb5 , which we usually don't allow.} a6 {The most logical choice.} 7. g3 {White changes track. It's no disaster, but when allowing this in the other situations, the pawn was always still back on a7 .} ({In those lines, for instance c4 e6 Nf3} 7. cxd5 {e3 Nf6 b3 b6 Bb2} Bb7 8. g3 {Bd6 we later played ... a7 - a5 in one move. So most likely we will be one or at minimum half a tempo down to that. Still, it's not a huge deal, but it's enough for me not being able to recommend it with a clear conscience.}) (7. g4 $5 {This is another option where I don't fell entirely confident, having played such slow moves as ... a6 and ... b6 .})) 6. Nc3 a6 {Our usual choice against Nc3 , especially if White hasn't wasted time with g3 yet. Now White has a few different interesting option to avoid transposition.} 7. d4 b6 {This is very likely to transpose to The Magnus Queen's Gambit , chapter 11, starting from here .} 8. g3 {The only independent option. Now we have to be careful. If we just develop lazily, White will get their dream version. The way we avoid it is to go for a quick ... dxc4 followed by ... c5 , immediately attacking White's center. That would not have been possible had White still had their pawn back on d2 .} (8. Bd3 Bb7 9. O-O Nbd7 {Transposes to d4} 10. cxd5 {c4 e6 Nf3 a6 e3 Nf6 Nc3 Nbd7 b3 b6 Bd3 Bb7 O-O Bd6 Bb2 O-O , analyzed in detail in The Magnus Queen's Gambit , chapter 11, 3. Nf3 4th Move Sidelines, starting here .}) 8... Bb7 {Move orders don't matter too much as long as we play ... dxc4 over the next few moves.} 9. Bg2 {If White ever takes on d5 , we transpose back to the 1. c4  e6 2. Nf3  d5 3. e3 chapter.} Nbd7 10. O-O (10. cxd5 exd5 {will eventually transpose to the c4 e6 Nf3 d5 e3 chapter .}) 10... dxc4 {This is the moment. Again, slower moves like ... Re8 or ... Rc8 would let White develop exactly how they want, with some hopes for a small edge.} 11. bxc4 c5 {The idea is to put pressure on the d4 - and c4 -pawns.} 12. d5 {Definitely the critical move, and always the first one should look out for when giving up the center with ... dxc4 .} exd5 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. cxd5 b5 {Gaining queenside space. A very interesting and sharp middlegame position has arisen. If White is able to push e4 - e5 they would be doing very well, but we won't allow that. In the meantime we want to push ... c4 , and then try to prepare ... c3 which, if allowed, would cut out the bishop on b2 entirely.} 15. e4 {The most natural.} Re8 16. Re1 {It looks like White is threatening e5 , but we are just in time.} c4 17. e5 Bb4 {An excellent square. Now we can follow up with ... c3 if we want, but also ... Nc5 - d3 is still relevant. For the purpose of the Quckstarter Guide, the line ends with this move. More detailed analysis can be found here .} *


