1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 {This together with 3. g3 are White's main setups.} Nf6 4. Nc3 {This is frankly a bit of an annoying option.} a6 {My recommendation. White can, and should, now transpose to the Accelerated Meran with 5. d4 . That line differs from the line that I am recommending in the Classical Slav,, but many of the ideas are still the same, and compared to the a6 -Slav White has fewer options by having committed to e3 , Nf3 and Nc3 .} ({•} 4... e6 {The most popular move in practice. It could still be a viable option in order to meet 5. d4 with 5... a6 , transposing to our Accelerated Meran, but there are two reasons I chose not to recommend it: one is that it's much more popular than 4... a6 , meaning White will likely be more ready for it.} 5. b3 {This is the other reason. When we play 4... a6 we can now develop the c8 -bishop outside the pawn chain. This is still by no means bad for Black, but I feel it's the sort of play that White is looking for.}) ({•} 4... Bf5 {The move we would like to play, however it works out rather badly.} 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Qb3 $1 {Compared to the Slav, we can't play ... Qc7 as the d5 -pawn is hanging.}) 5. d4 {Without any doubt, the critical move. Now we have transposed to the so called Chebanenko variation of the Slav, which is something I don't recommend in my Lifetime Repertoire: Classical Slav . But don't worry, we are not tricked. The big point compared to the normal Chebanenko Slav is that White has already committed their pawn to e3 , which greatly decreases the number of lines possible.} ({Against the normal Chebanenko,} 5. d4 {d5} dxc4 {c6 Nf3 Nf6 Nc3 a6 , I consider the move c5 to be the strongest. Probably} 6. a4 {is the second strongest, and only on 3rd place we find moves like g3 or e3 . So White is in fact the one having been 'tricked' into a suboptimal line!}) 5... e6 (5... Bf5 {In some sense this is more similar to the Classical Slav, but again there are two reasons I don't recommend it. Firstly, I think 5... e6 is objectively a slightly better move. Secondly, while 5... Bf5 can lead to similar play as the Classical Slav course after moves like 5. Bd3 , there are also many independent lines that leads to different structure, most notably} 6. Ne5 {and . As we would anyway have to learn new things, we might as well play the strongest option.}) 6. b3 Bb4 {This is the idea of our setup - we need to provoke Bd2 so that the bishop won't get to b2 .} 7. Bd2 (7. Bb2 $2 Ne4 $1 8. Rc1 Qa5 9. Qc2 Qxa2 $1 {This is the tactical justification of 6... Bb4 . White simply loses a pawn.}) 7... Nbd7 8. Bd3 {Here I am recommending two different options. In this chapter, we are going to analyze the solid 8... O-O .} O-O 9. O-O Bd6 ({I'm recommending this instead of} 9... Qe7 {. This was a line Anand played when he defended his World Champion title against Boris Gelfand in 2012. We intend to push ... e5 , after which we will most likely get an isolated d5 -pawn, for which our piece play provides good counterplay. Practice has shown that this is an incredibly solid way to play, and I believe Black equalizes without any real issues. Stylistically, it's slightly towards the dryer side, so it should be considered a sort of opposite of the highly imbalanced 8... dxc4 , which we will study in the next chapter .}) (9... Qe7 {This is another move that is also reliable. I've used it myself to equalize comfortably. Stylistically, it leads to slightly sharper play than Bd6 .}) *


