[ECO "D45"]
[PlyCount "18"]

1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 {My recommendation. White can, and should, now transpose to the Accelerated Meran with 5. d4 . That line differs from the line that I am recommending in the Classical Slav,, but many of the ideas are still the same, and compared to the a6 -Slav White has fewer options by having committed to e3 , Nf3 and Nc3 .} ({•} 4... e6 {The most popular move in practice. It could still be a viable option in order to meet 5. d4 with 5... a6 , transposing to our Accelerated Meran, but there are two reasons I chose not to recommend it: one is that it's much more popular than 4... a6 , meaning White will likely be more ready for it.} 5. b3 {This is the other reason. When we play 4... a6 we can now develop the c8 -bishop outside the pawn chain. This is still by no means bad for Black, but I feel it's the sort of play that White is looking for.}) ({•} 4... Bf5 {The move we would like to play, however it works out rather badly.} 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Qb3 $1 {Compared to the Slav, we can't play ... Qc7 as the d5 -pawn is hanging.}) 5. d4 {Without any doubt, the critical move. Now we have transposed to the so called Chebanenko variation of the Slav, which is something I don't recommend in my Lifetime Repertoire: Classical Slav . But don't worry, we are not tricked. The big point compared to the normal Chebanenko Slav is that White has already committed their pawn to e3 , which greatly decreases the number of lines possible.} ({Against the normal Chebanenko,} 5. d4 {d5} dxc4 {c6 Nf3 Nf6 Nc3 a6 , I consider the move c5 to be the strongest. Probably} 6. a4 {is the second strongest, and only on 3rd place we find moves like g3 or e3 . So White is in fact the one having been 'tricked' into a suboptimal line!}) 5... e6 {Changing opening once again! With 5... e6 , we are entering the so called Accelerated Meran (or a6 -Meran, as it is also often called). The idea of ... e6 is to strengthen the center, particularly being able to recapture on d5 with the e-pawn instead of the c-pawn. The deeper point behind our play is to prepare ... dxc4 , followed by ... b5 and ... c5 .} 6. b3 {This is the best move for White. They anticipate our idea of capturing on c4 , which is now less tempting as it would let White recapture towards the center.} Bb4 {Another surprising shot! The bishop very rarely goes to b4 in the pawn structure with e6 , d5 , c6 but here there is a concrete reason for doing so.} 7. Bb2 {Looks much more natural, but is in fact a huge mistake already!} Qa5 {Suddenly White struggles to keep c3 defended.} 8. Qc2 Ne4 {Increasing the pressure.} 9. Rc1 {The only move to defend c3 .} Qxa2 {Utilizing the pin. We have simply picked up a pawn. White is having some lead in development but that doesn't matter much as we are trading everything on c3 on the next move.} *

