1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 {My recommendation. White can, and should, now transpose to the Accelerated Meran with 5. d4 . That line differs from the line that I am recommending in the Classical Slav,, but many of the ideas are still the same, and compared to the a6 -Slav White has fewer options by having committed to e3 , Nf3 and Nc3 .} ({•} 4... e6 {The most popular move in practice. It could still be a viable option in order to meet 5. d4 with 5... a6 , transposing to our Accelerated Meran, but there are two reasons I chose not to recommend it: one is that it's much more popular than 4... a6 , meaning White will likely be more ready for it.} 5. b3 {This is the other reason. When we play 4... a6 we can now develop the c8 -bishop outside the pawn chain. This is still by no means bad for Black, but I feel it's the sort of play that White is looking for.}) ({•} 4... Bf5 {The move we would like to play, however it works out rather badly.} 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Qb3 $1 {Compared to the Slav, we can't play ... Qc7 as the d5 -pawn is hanging.}) 5. d4 {Without any doubt, the critical move. Now we have transposed to the so called Chebanenko variation of the Slav, which is something I don't recommend in my Lifetime Repertoire: Classical Slav . But don't worry, we are not tricked. The big point compared to the normal Chebanenko Slav is that White has already committed their pawn to e3 , which greatly decreases the number of lines possible.} ({Against the normal Chebanenko,} 5. d4 {d5} dxc4 {c6 Nf3 Nf6 Nc3 a6 , I consider the move c5 to be the strongest. Probably} 6. a4 {is the second strongest, and only on 3rd place we find moves like g3 or e3 . So White is in fact the one having been 'tricked' into a suboptimal line!}) 5... e6 {Changing opening once again! With 5... e6 , we are entering the so called Accelerated Meran (or a6 -Meran, as it is also often called). The idea of ... e6 is to strengthen the center, particularly being able to recapture on d5 with the e-pawn instead of the c-pawn. The deeper point behind our play is to prepare ... dxc4 , followed by ... b5 and ... c5 .} 6. b3 {This is the best move for White. They anticipate our idea of capturing on c4 , which is now less tempting as it would let White recapture towards the center.} Bb4 {Another surprising shot! The bishop very rarely goes to b4 in the pawn structure with e6 , d5 , c6 but here there is a concrete reason for doing so.} 7. Bd2 {This looks a bit stupid in combination with the pawn on b3 , but White has no choice.} Nbd7 {Continuing the development. Long-term our idea is to push ... e5 , so there is no doubt that the knight belongs to d7 .} 8. Bd3 ({The most active and best move.} 8. Be2 {The bishop is just less active on e2 than d3 .} O-O 9. O-O Bd6 {We can simply play in the same way as in the mainline, with a better version.}) 8... O-O 9. Qc2 {Beware of this move! White is trying to trick us, if we are not observant.} Qe7 {Definitely the most solid move. We prepare the ... e5 -push, but without allowing an annoying White option.} (9... Bd6 10. c5 $1 Bc7 11. O-O-O $1 {is the point of White's move order. Next they play e4 or even g4 !?, in both cases with a rather dangerous initiative.}) 10. Ne5 {This is often one of the main strategic ideas for White, creating a sort of Pillsbury attack. This specific move order is not the scariest, though.} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Ng4 {An extra option due to White already having played Qc2 .} 12. f4 (12. Bxh7+ Kh8 13. Bd3 (13. f4 {fails because of} Qh4+ {.}) 13... Nxe5 {This is good for Black as the central pawn is more valuable than the one on h7 .}) 12... f5 {An excellent reaction, played by Carlsen against Topalov. After we play ... f5 White will never have any attack against our king.} 13. exf6 (13. g3 {Topalov's move, preparing h3 without the annoying check on h4 .} Rd8 {One of many good moves, but a clean forcing solution.} 14. h3 Nxe3 $1 15. Bxe3 d4 16. Bd2 dxc3 17. Bxc3 Bxc3+ 18. Qxc3 c5 {Black had no problems whatsoever: 0-1 (29) Topalov-Carlsen, Paris 2017.}) 13... Nxf6 {This is an important structure to understand. If we look only at the pawns, one could become a little bit worried for Black with the hole on e5 . What is important to note is that White's pieces, especially the knight on c3 , are very far away from our weak squares. In fact, we are the ones soon able to create play by pushing ... e5 , with or without activating the a8 -rook first.} *

