1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 {My recommendation. White can, and should, now transpose to the Accelerated Meran with 5. d4 . That line differs from the line that I am recommending in the Classical Slav,, but many of the ideas are still the same, and compared to the a6 -Slav White has fewer options by having committed to e3 , Nf3 and Nc3 .} ({•} 4... e6 {The most popular move in practice. It could still be a viable option in order to meet 5. d4 with 5... a6 , transposing to our Accelerated Meran, but there are two reasons I chose not to recommend it: one is that it's much more popular than 4... a6 , meaning White will likely be more ready for it.} 5. b3 {This is the other reason. When we play 4... a6 we can now develop the c8 -bishop outside the pawn chain. This is still by no means bad for Black, but I feel it's the sort of play that White is looking for.}) ({•} 4... Bf5 {The move we would like to play, however it works out rather badly.} 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Qb3 $1 {Compared to the Slav, we can't play ... Qc7 as the d5 -pawn is hanging.}) 5. d4 {Without any doubt, the critical move. Now we have transposed to the so called Chebanenko variation of the Slav, which is something I don't recommend in my Lifetime Repertoire: Classical Slav . But don't worry, we are not tricked. The big point compared to the normal Chebanenko Slav is that White has already committed their pawn to e3 , which greatly decreases the number of lines possible.} ({Against the normal Chebanenko,} 5. d4 {d5} dxc4 {c6 Nf3 Nf6 Nc3 a6 , I consider the move c5 to be the strongest. Probably} 6. a4 {is the second strongest, and only on 3rd place we find moves like g3 or e3 . So White is in fact the one having been 'tricked' into a suboptimal line!}) 5... e6 {Changing opening once again! With 5... e6 , we are entering the so called Accelerated Meran (or a6 -Meran, as it is also often called). The idea of ... e6 is to strengthen the center, particularly being able to recapture on d5 with the e-pawn instead of the c-pawn. The deeper point behind our play is to prepare ... dxc4 , followed by ... b5 and ... c5 .} 6. b3 {This is the best move for White. They anticipate our idea of capturing on c4 , which is now less tempting as it would let White recapture towards the center.} Bb4 {Another surprising shot! The bishop very rarely goes to b4 in the pawn structure with e6 , d5 , c6 but here there is a concrete reason for doing so.} 7. Bd2 {This looks a bit stupid in combination with the pawn on b3 , but White has no choice.} Nbd7 {Continuing the development. Long-term our idea is to push ... e5 , so there is no doubt that the knight belongs to d7 .} 8. Bd3 ({The most active and best move.} 8. Be2 {The bishop is just less active on e2 than d3 .} O-O 9. O-O Bd6 {We can simply play in the same way as in the mainline, with a better version.}) 8... O-O 9. Qc2 {Beware of this move! White is trying to trick us, if we are not observant.} Qe7 {Definitely the most solid move. We prepare the ... e5 -push, but without allowing an annoying White option.} (9... Bd6 10. c5 $1 Bc7 11. O-O-O $1 {is the point of White's move order. Next they play e4 or even g4 !?, in both cases with a rather dangerous initiative.}) 10. O-O ({•} 10. O-O-O $2 {Makes no sense as long as the center is still open.} dxc4 $1 {Opening up further.} 11. bxc4 c5 {We are just much better. Next up we can even play ... b5 , with a dangerous attack against the White king.}) ({•} 10. c5 $2 e5 {Doesn't work at all for White.}) 10... e5 {Our main strategic idea. We want to open up for our light squared bishop, and at the same time get additional control over the center.} 11. Nxe5 (11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Qxe5 {transposes to the line we're actually studying.}) 11... Nxe5 12. dxe5 Qxe5 13. Nxd5 {A funny tactical motif, but it doesn't bring anything for White.} Nxd5 {Very important. We need to keep our bishop on b4 protected.} (13... Bxd2 $2 14. Nxf6+ $1 Qxf6 15. Qxd2 {gives White an extra pawn for free.}) 14. cxd5 Bxd2 {Now we can safely trade.} 15. Qxd2 Qxd5 {This position has actually been played a fair amount, but I believe it to be entirely harmless. I actually tried it myself as Black recently vs Teimour Radjabov, and had no problems whatsoever. We should simply develop our bishop and fight for the d-file.} 16. Qc2 {The most common move.} g6 {An important part of the concept. It looks positionally dubious to place all (!) our pawns on the same colour as ourbishop, but in fact it doesn't matter. Strategically speaking, with 4v3 on the kingside, White's main plan should be to push the e- an f-pawns. For that reason, we place the pawn on g6 , so that White's f-pawn can't be pushed further than to f4 . Next up, we are ready for ... Be6 and ... Rad8 , with plenty of counterplay along the d-file. The position is definitely equal, but the asymmetrical pawn structure still gives both sides something to play for.} *


