tead of the c-pawn. The deeper point behind our play is to prepare ... dxc4 , followed by ... b5 and ... c5 .} 6. b3 {This is the best move for White. They anticipate our idea of capturing on c4 , which is now less tempting as it would let White recapture towards the center.} Bb4 {Another surprising shot! The bishop very rarely goes to b4 in the pawn structure with e6 , d5 , c6 but here there is a concrete reason for doing so.} 7. Bd2 {This looks a bit stupid in combination with the pawn on b3 , but White has no choice.} Nbd7 {Continuing the development. Long-term our idea is to push ... e5 , so there is no doubt that the knight belongs to d7 .} 8. Bd3 ({The most active and best move.} 8. Be2 {The bishop is just less active on e2 than d3 .} O-O 9. O-O Bd6 {We can simply play in the same way as in the mainline, with a better version.}) 8... O-O 9. Qc2 {Beware of this move! White is trying to trick us, if we are not observant.} Qe7 {Definitely the most solid move. We prepare the ... e5 -push, but without allowing an annoying White option.} (9... Bd6 10. c5 $1 Bc7 11. O-O-O $1 {is the point of White's move order. Next they play e4 or even g4 !?, in both cases with a rather dangerous initiative.}) 10. O-O ({•} 10. O-O-O $2 {Makes no sense as long as the center is still open.} dxc4 $1 {Opening up further.} 11. bxc4 c5 {We are just much better. Next up we can even play ... b5 , with a dangerous attack against the White king.}) ({•} 10. c5 $2 e5 {Doesn't work at all for White.}) 10... e5 {Our main strategic idea. We want to open up for our light squared bishop, and at the same time get additional control over the center.} 11. Nxe5 (11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Qxe5 {transposes to the line we're actually studying.}) 11... Nxe5 12. dxe5 Qxe5 13. cxd5 cxd5 {This time we have to take with the pawn, for the same tactical reason as on the previous move.} (13... Nxd5 14. Nxd5 $1 {Now the b4 -bishop is hanging.} Bxd2 15. Nb6 $1 {Wins for White.}) 14. Na4 {This might look more active, but it's a blank shot and now we can fight for the initiative already.} Bxd2 (14... Bd6 {Also a reasonable option where Black is fine, but trading on d2 makes even more sense here, as we are able to provoke major weaknesses in White’s kingside position.}) 15. Qxd2 Ng4 16. g3 {The only good move to cover the mate.} Qf6 {Very precise. Normally we go via h5 , but here it makes sense to keep the b6 -square covered at the same time} 17. f3 {Not strictly necessary, but White is the one trying to equalize no matter what they do.} Ne5 18. Kg2 Bd7 {It's clear that the knight would be much happier on e2 .} *

