1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 {My recommendation. White can, and should, now transpose to the Accelerated Meran with 5. d4 . That line differs from the line that I am recommending in the Classical Slav,, but many of the ideas are still the same, and compared to the a6 -Slav White has fewer options by having committed to e3 , Nf3 and Nc3 .} ({•} 4... e6 {The most popular move in practice. It could still be a viable option in order to meet 5. d4 with 5... a6 , transposing to our Accelerated Meran, but there are two reasons I chose not to recommend it: one is that it's much more popular than 4... a6 , meaning White will likely be more ready for it.} 5. b3 {This is the other reason. When we play 4... a6 we can now develop the c8 -bishop outside the pawn chain. This is still by no means bad for Black, but I feel it's the sort of play that White is looking for.}) ({•} 4... Bf5 {The move we would like to play, however it works out rather badly.} 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Qb3 $1 {Compared to the Slav, we can't play ... Qc7 as the d5 -pawn is hanging.}) 5. d4 {Without any doubt, the critical move. Now we have transposed to the so called Chebanenko variation of the Slav, which is something I don't recommend in my Lifetime Repertoire: Classical Slav . But don't worry, we are not tricked. The big point compared to the normal Chebanenko Slav is that White has already committed their pawn to e3 , which greatly decreases the number of lines possible.} ({Against the normal Chebanenko,} 5. d4 {d5} dxc4 {c6 Nf3 Nf6 Nc3 a6 , I consider the move c5 to be the strongest. Probably} 6. a4 {is the second strongest, and only on 3rd place we find moves like g3 or e3 . So White is in fact the one having been 'tricked' into a suboptimal line!}) 5... e6 {Changing opening once again! With 5... e6 , we are entering the so called Accelerated Meran (or a6 -Meran, as it is also often called). The idea of ... e6 is to strengthen the center, particularly being able to recapture on d5 with the e-pawn instead of the c-pawn. The deeper point behind our play is to prepare ... dxc4 , followed by ... b5 and ... c5 .} 6. b3 {This is the best move for White. They anticipate our idea of capturing on c4 , which is now less tempting as it would let White recapture towards the center.} Bb4 {Another surprising shot! The bishop very rarely goes to b4 in the pawn structure with e6 , d5 , c6 but here there is a concrete reason for doing so.} 7. Bd2 {This looks a bit stupid in combination with the pawn on b3 , but White has no choice.} Nbd7 {Continuing the development. Long-term our idea is to push ... e5 , so there is no doubt that the knight belongs to d7 .} 8. Bd3 ({The most active and best move.} 8. Be2 {The bishop is just less active on e2 than d3 .} O-O 9. O-O Bd6 {We can simply play in the same way as in the mainline, with a better version.}) 8... O-O 9. Qc2 {Beware of this move! White is trying to trick us, if we are not observant.} Qe7 {Definitely the most solid move. We prepare the ... e5 -push, but without allowing an annoying White option.} (9... Bd6 10. c5 $1 Bc7 11. O-O-O $1 {is the point of White's move order. Next they play e4 or even g4 !?, in both cases with a rather dangerous initiative.}) 10. O-O ({•} 10. O-O-O $2 {Makes no sense as long as the center is still open.} dxc4 $1 {Opening up further.} 11. bxc4 c5 {We are just much better. Next up we can even play ... b5 , with a dangerous attack against the White king.}) ({•} 10. c5 $2 e5 {Doesn't work at all for White.}) 10... e5 {Our main strategic idea. We want to open up for our light squared bishop, and at the same time get additional control over the center.} 11. Nxe5 (11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Qxe5 {transposes to the line we're actually studying.}) 11... Nxe5 12. dxe5 Qxe5 13. cxd5 cxd5 {This time we have to take with the pawn, for the same tactical reason as on the previous move.} (13... Nxd5 14. Nxd5 $1 {Now the b4 -bishop is hanging.} Bxd2 15. Nb6 $1 {Wins for White.}) 14. Ne2 {Played by literally everybody. It's simply necessary for White to bring more defenders towards the king.} Bd6 {We keep the bishop as it's a potential attacker. Additionally, from a principled viewpoint the one with the isolated pawn should try to keep pieces on the board, as it increases the dynamic counterchances.} 15. Ng3 (15. g3 {Would weaken the kingside for no obvious reason.} Qh5 $5 {Intending ... Bh3 next. We are enjoying a solid initiative.}) 15... Qg5 {This and the next few moves are important. If we are not careful, we might end up slightly worse due to the weakness of the d5 -pawn. However, with a few good move we drum up the necessary amount of counterplay.} 16. Bc3 {The most solid move, but it also lets us equalize the game easily.} Bxg3 {A surprising capture, but it's explained on the next move.} 17. hxg3 Ng4 {The point! Now White will never be able to drive the knight away with h2 - h3 , and if f3 the pawn on e3 will be hanging.} 18. Be2 {Necessary to prevent the mate.} Qh5 19. Bxg4 Bxg4 20. f3 Be6 {The position is just equal. It is true that White's bishop is better than ours, but the slightly compromised kingside structure compensates for that. By far the most likely scenario now is that everything will be traded along the c-file.} *

