It's simply necessary for White to bring more defenders towards the king.} Bd6 {We keep the bishop as it's a potential attacker. Additionally, from a principled viewpoint the one with the isolated pawn should try to keep pieces on the board, as it increases the dynamic counterchances.} 15. Ng3 (15. g3 {Would weaken the kingside for no obvious reason.} Qh5 $5 {Intending ... Bh3 next. We are enjoying a solid initiative.}) 15... Qg5 {This and the next few moves are important. If we are not careful, we might end up slightly worse due to the weakness of the d5 -pawn. However, with a few good move we drum up the necessary amount of counterplay.} 16. f4 {The most ambitious move. White is trying to claim that our queen is misplaced.} Qh4 17. Rf3 {Overprotecting the knight on g3 , so that ... Ng4 can be met by h3 .} Re8 {We simply improve our position. Re8 in itself is always a good move, but here the e3 -pawn is additionally weak.} 18. Bc3 ({Looks more active but is also less solid. Even though it's much rarer, I believe it's more important than the more common} 18. Be1) 18... Ng4 {We have to act quickly to generate enough counterplay.} 19. Nf1 Bc5 20. Re1 Bd7 {A natural enough developing move, but it is important that what follows works out well for us.} 21. Rh3 Nxe3 {Strictly the only move - everything else would be dead lost for us. Lucky it works out well.} 22. Rhxe3 Rxe3 23. Rxe3 Rc8 {Another smart move, further increasing the pressure. Now White has to play well to keep the balance.} 24. Qd2 Qxf4 {Followed by Bxe3 , restoring material equality.} *

