1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 {My recommendation. White can, and should, now transpose to the Accelerated Meran with 5. d4 . That line differs from the line that I am recommending in the Classical Slav,, but many of the ideas are still the same, and compared to the a6 -Slav White has fewer options by having committed to e3 , Nf3 and Nc3 .} ({•} 4... e6 {The most popular move in practice. It could still be a viable option in order to meet 5. d4 with 5... a6 , transposing to our Accelerated Meran, but there are two reasons I chose not to recommend it: one is that it's much more popular than 4... a6 , meaning White will likely be more ready for it.} 5. b3 {This is the other reason. When we play 4... a6 we can now develop the c8 -bishop outside the pawn chain. This is still by no means bad for Black, but I feel it's the sort of play that White is looking for.}) ({•} 4... Bf5 {The move we would like to play, however it works out rather badly.} 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Qb3 $1 {Compared to the Slav, we can't play ... Qc7 as the d5 -pawn is hanging.}) 5. d4 {Without any doubt, the critical move. Now we have transposed to the so called Chebanenko variation of the Slav, which is something I don't recommend in my Lifetime Repertoire: Classical Slav . But don't worry, we are not tricked. The big point compared to the normal Chebanenko Slav is that White has already committed their pawn to e3 , which greatly decreases the number of lines possible.} ({Against the normal Chebanenko,} 5. d4 {d5} dxc4 {c6 Nf3 Nf6 Nc3 a6 , I consider the move c5 to be the strongest. Probably} 6. a4 {is the second strongest, and only on 3rd place we find moves like g3 or e3 . So White is in fact the one having been 'tricked' into a suboptimal line!}) 5... e6 {Changing opening once again! With 5... e6 , we are entering the so called Accelerated Meran (or a6 -Meran, as it is also often called). The idea of ... e6 is to strengthen the center, particularly being able to recapture on d5 with the e-pawn instead of the c-pawn. The deeper point behind our play is to prepare ... dxc4 , followed by ... b5 and ... c5 .} 6. b3 {This is the best move for White. They anticipate our idea of capturing on c4 , which is now less tempting as it would let White recapture towards the center.} Bb4 {Another surprising shot! The bishop very rarely goes to b4 in the pawn structure with e6 , d5 , c6 but here there is a concrete reason for doing so.} 7. Bd2 {This looks a bit stupid in combination with the pawn on b3 , but White has no choice.} Nbd7 {Continuing the development. Long-term our idea is to push ... e5 , so there is no doubt that the knight belongs to d7 .} 8. Bd3 ({The most active and best move.} 8. Be2 {The bishop is just less active on e2 than d3 .} O-O 9. O-O Bd6 {We can simply play in the same way as in the mainline, with a better version.}) 8... O-O 9. Qc2 {Beware of this move! White is trying to trick us, if we are not observant.} Qe7 {Definitely the most solid move. We prepare the ... e5 -push, but without allowing an annoying White option.} (9... Bd6 10. c5 $1 Bc7 11. O-O-O $1 {is the point of White's move order. Next they play e4 or even g4 !?, in both cases with a rather dangerous initiative.}) 10. O-O ({•} 10. O-O-O $2 {Makes no sense as long as the center is still open.} dxc4 $1 {Opening up further.} 11. bxc4 c5 {We are just much better. Next up we can even play ... b5 , with a dangerous attack against the White king.}) ({•} 10. c5 $2 e5 {Doesn't work at all for White.}) 10... e5 {Our main strategic idea. We want to open up for our light squared bishop, and at the same time get additional control over the center.} 11. Nxe5 (11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Qxe5 {transposes to the line we're actually studying.}) 11... Nxe5 12. dxe5 Qxe5 13. cxd5 cxd5 {This time we have to take with the pawn, for the same tactical reason as on the previous move.} (13... Nxd5 14. Nxd5 $1 {Now the b4 -bishop is hanging.} Bxd2 15. Nb6 $1 {Wins for White.}) 14. Ne2 {Played by literally everybody. It's simply necessary for White to bring more defenders towards the king.} Bd6 {We keep the bishop as it's a potential attacker. Additionally, from a principled viewpoint the one with the isolated pawn should try to keep pieces on the board, as it increases the dynamic counterchances.} 15. Ng3 (15. g3 {Would weaken the kingside for no obvious reason.} Qh5 $5 {Intending ... Bh3 next. We are enjoying a solid initiative.}) 15... Qg5 {This and the next few moves are important. If we are not careful, we might end up slightly worse due to the weakness of the d5 -pawn. However, with a few good move we drum up the necessary amount of counterplay.} 16. f4 {The most ambitious move. White is trying to claim that our queen is misplaced.} Qh4 17. Rf3 {Overprotecting the knight on g3 , so that ... Ng4 can be met by h3 .} Re8 {We simply improve our position. Re8 in itself is always a good move, but here the e3 -pawn is additionally weak.} 18. Bc3 ({Looks more active but is also less solid. Even though it's much rarer, I believe it's more important than the more common} 18. Be1) 18... Ng4 {We have to act quickly to generate enough counterplay.} 19. Nf1 Bc5 20. Re1 Bd7 {A natural enough developing move, but it is important that what follows works out well for us.} 21. Rh3 Nxe3 {Strictly the only move - everything else would be dead lost for us. Lucky it works out well.} 22. Rhxe3 Rxe3 23. Nxe3 Re8 24. Qc1 Qxe1+ {Beautiful! But also important, as otherwise the whole tactical operation would not work for Black.} 25. Qxe1 Rxe3 26. Qf2 Bf5 {The last key move. White can't save both bishops.} 27. Bd2 (27. Bxf5 $4 Rxc3 {wins immediately for Black.}) 27... Re1+ 28. Bxe1 Bxf2+ 29. Kxf2 Bxd3 {We even ended up with an extra pawn, but the position is an easy draw due to the opposite coloured bishops.} *

