tead of the c-pawn. The deeper point behind our play is to prepare ... dxc4 , followed by ... b5 and ... c5 .} 6. b3 {This is the best move for White. They anticipate our idea of capturing on c4 , which is now less tempting as it would let White recapture towards the center.} Bb4 {Another surprising shot! The bishop very rarely goes to b4 in the pawn structure with e6 , d5 , c6 but here there is a concrete reason for doing so.} 7. Bd2 {This looks a bit stupid in combination with the pawn on b3 , but White has no choice.} Nbd7 {Continuing the development. Long-term our idea is to push ... e5 , so there is no doubt that the knight belongs to d7 .} 8. Bd3 ({The most active and best move.} 8. Be2 {The bishop is just less active on e2 than d3 .} O-O 9. O-O Bd6 {We can simply play in the same way as in the mainline, with a better version.}) 8... O-O 9. O-O Bd6 {When you see this for the first time, it might look very odd. Aren't we just losing a tempo with our bishop? Well, the bishop's main goal on b4 was simply to force White's bishop to the inferior square d2 , so that it can't get to the long diagonal anymore. Now we need our bishop on d6 , in order to execute our main strategic goal: to push ... e5 .} 10. e4 {This is the first move we need to take into account. Pushing e4 is White's most obvious idea in the entire Meran and Accelerated Meran.} dxc4 {Very important. We are getting ready to push ... e5 next.} 11. bxc4 {The best move. White is trying to create an impressive center.} e5 12. d5 {Looks natural but would in fact be a strategic error.} Nc5 {This is fantastic for Black with the excellent square on c5 . Next up, we simply develop with ... Bg4 and bring the rooks towards the center.} *

