1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 {My recommendation. White can, and should, now transpose to the Accelerated Meran with 5. d4 . That line differs from the line that I am recommending in the Classical Slav,, but many of the ideas are still the same, and compared to the a6 -Slav White has fewer options by having committed to e3 , Nf3 and Nc3 .} ({•} 4... e6 {The most popular move in practice. It could still be a viable option in order to meet 5. d4 with 5... a6 , transposing to our Accelerated Meran, but there are two reasons I chose not to recommend it: one is that it's much more popular than 4... a6 , meaning White will likely be more ready for it.} 5. b3 {This is the other reason. When we play 4... a6 we can now develop the c8 -bishop outside the pawn chain. This is still by no means bad for Black, but I feel it's the sort of play that White is looking for.}) ({•} 4... Bf5 {The move we would like to play, however it works out rather badly.} 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Qb3 $1 {Compared to the Slav, we can't play ... Qc7 as the d5 -pawn is hanging.}) 5. d4 {Without any doubt, the critical move. Now we have transposed to the so called Chebanenko variation of the Slav, which is something I don't recommend in my Lifetime Repertoire: Classical Slav . But don't worry, we are not tricked. The big point compared to the normal Chebanenko Slav is that White has already committed their pawn to e3 , which greatly decreases the number of lines possible.} ({Against the normal Chebanenko,} 5. d4 {d5} dxc4 {c6 Nf3 Nf6 Nc3 a6 , I consider the move c5 to be the strongest. Probably} 6. a4 {is the second strongest, and only on 3rd place we find moves like g3 or e3 . So White is in fact the one having been 'tricked' into a suboptimal line!}) 5... e6 {Changing opening once again! With 5... e6 , we are entering the so called Accelerated Meran (or a6 -Meran, as it is also often called). The idea of ... e6 is to strengthen the center, particularly being able to recapture on d5 with the e-pawn instead of the c-pawn. The deeper point behind our play is to prepare ... dxc4 , followed by ... b5 and ... c5 .} 6. b3 {This is the best move for White. They anticipate our idea of capturing on c4 , which is now less tempting as it would let White recapture towards the center.} Bb4 {Another surprising shot! The bishop very rarely goes to b4 in the pawn structure with e6 , d5 , c6 but here there is a concrete reason for doing so.} 7. Bd2 {This looks a bit stupid in combination with the pawn on b3 , but White has no choice.} Nbd7 {Continuing the development. Long-term our idea is to push ... e5 , so there is no doubt that the knight belongs to d7 .} 8. Bd3 ({The most active and best move.} 8. Be2 {The bishop is just less active on e2 than d3 .} O-O 9. O-O Bd6 {We can simply play in the same way as in the mainline, with a better version.}) 8... O-O 9. O-O Bd6 {When you see this for the first time, it might look very odd. Aren't we just losing a tempo with our bishop? Well, the bishop's main goal on b4 was simply to force White's bishop to the inferior square d2 , so that it can't get to the long diagonal anymore. Now we need our bishop on d6 , in order to execute our main strategic goal: to push ... e5 .} 10. Rc1 {Another natural developing move. I'm including it mainly for historical reason, as it was played in the World Championship match between Gelfand and Anand in 2012.} e5 {There is no reason to avoid this typical push.} 11. cxd5 cxd5 {By the way, it's important to note the usefulness of the pawn on a6 here. Without it, Nb5 would be highly annoying, but now there is nothing to worry about on the c-file.} 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Bxe5 14. h3 {This is a slightly better version of the isolated pawn positions than 10. Qc2 for White. The queen is not vulnerable on the c-file, and White can therefore easier execute the plan of Ne2 followed by Bc3 .} (14. Ne2 Ne4 {Keeps preventing Bc3 .}) 14... Bb8 {Important! As soon as White plays h3 , we should be on the lookout for this idea. After ... Qd6 next, White is struggling a bit to cover the mate on h2 . This is precisely the idea that gives us enough counterplay to balance the slight weakness of the d5 -pawn.} 15. Ne2 {Bringing another defender over.} Qd6 16. Ng3 (16. f4 {A strategic mistake, as the e3 -pawn and especially the e4 -square gets too weak.} Ba7 {Followed by ... Re8 .}) 16... Ne4 {Just in time to create enough threats.} 17. Bxe4 {The only good move to prevent ... Nxg3 .} dxe4 {The position is equal. Next up we can move the queen in order to take ... Bxg3 , after which any White hope of an advantage is gone.} *


