[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "�1) Accelerated Meran: 6.b"]
[Black "7.Bd2 Nbd7 8.Bd3 with 9.O-O #"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D45"]
[PlyCount "38"]

1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 {My recommendation. White can, and should, now transpose to the Accelerated Meran with 5. d4 . That line differs from the line that I am recommending in the Classical Slav,, but many of the ideas are still the same, and compared to the a6 -Slav White has fewer options by having committed to e3 , Nf3 and Nc3 .} ({•} 4... e6 {The most popular move in practice. It could still be a viable option in order to meet 5. d4 with 5... a6 , transposing to our Accelerated Meran, but there are two reasons I chose not to recommend it: one is that it's much more popular than 4... a6 , meaning White will likely be more ready for it.} 5. b3 {This is the other reason. When we play 4... a6 we can now develop the c8 -bishop outside the pawn chain. This is still by no means bad for Black, but I feel it's the sort of play that White is looking for.}) ({•} 4... Bf5 {The move we would like to play, however it works out rather badly.} 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Qb3 $1 {Compared to the Slav, we can't play ... Qc7 as the d5 -pawn is hanging.}) 5. d4 {Without any doubt, the critical move. Now we have transposed to the so called Chebanenko variation of the Slav, which is something I don't recommend in my Lifetime Repertoire: Classical Slav . But don't worry, we are not tricked. The big point compared to the normal Chebanenko Slav is that White has already committed their pawn to e3 , which greatly decreases the number of lines possible.} ({Against the normal Chebanenko,} 5. d4 {d5} dxc4 {c6 Nf3 Nf6 Nc3 a6 , I consider the move c5 to be the strongest. Probably} 6. a4 {is the second strongest, and only on 3rd place we find moves like g3 or e3 . So White is in fact the one having been 'tricked' into a suboptimal line!}) 5... e6 {Changing opening once again! With 5... e6 , we are entering the so called Accelerated Meran (or a6 -Meran, as it is also often called). The idea of ... e6 is to strengthen the center, particularly being able to recapture on d5 with the e-pawn instead of the c-pawn. The deeper point behind our play is to prepare ... dxc4 , followed by ... b5 and ... c5 .} 6. b3 {This is the best move for White. They anticipate our idea of capturing on c4 , which is now less tempting as it would let White recapture towards the center.} Bb4 {Another surprising shot! The bishop very rarely goes to b4 in the pawn structure with e6 , d5 , c6 but here there is a concrete reason for doing so.} 7. Bd2 {This looks a bit stupid in combination with the pawn on b3 , but White has no choice.} Nbd7 {Continuing the development. Long-term our idea is to push ... e5 , so there is no doubt that the knight belongs to d7 .} 8. Bd3 ({The most active and best move.} 8. Be2 {The bishop is just less active on e2 than d3 .} O-O 9. O-O Bd6 {We can simply play in the same way as in the mainline, with a better version.}) 8... O-O 9. O-O Bd6 {When you see this for the first time, it might look very odd. Aren't we just losing a tempo with our bishop? Well, the bishop's main goal on b4 was simply to force White's bishop to the inferior square d2 , so that it can't get to the long diagonal anymore. Now we need our bishop on d6 , in order to execute our main strategic goal: to push ... e5 .} 10. Re1 {Another possibility. White anticipates the opening of the center after which the rook will be well placed on e1 .} h6 {An interesting counter-waiting move!} (10... e5 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. e4 {Does not work as well as before for us.} dxe4 (12... exd4 {This is possible, but it looks to me a little bit trickier than the usual lines.} 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. exd5 {The rooks is clearly useful on e1 .}) 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Rxe4 $1 {White will be able to recapture on d4 with the rook instead of the knight, creating annoying pressure.}) 11. e4 {Is possible and logical, but in fact the inclusion of 10. Re1  h6 does not change much - we can still play in exactly the same manner as against 10. e4} dxc4 12. bxc4 e5 13. c5 {Just like in the 10. e4 line, this is strategically necessary for White.} Bc7 14. Qc2 exd4 15. Ne2 {This is the extra option White gets from this move order, and was tried by the strong polish theoretician Wojtaszek.} Ng4 {A good antidote, immediately aiming to play ... Nde5 .} 16. Nexd4 Nde5 {Now we are creating some serious counterplay.} 17. h3 {The best move, forcing our strong knights back.} Nxd3 18. Qxd3 Ne5 19. Nxe5 Bxe5 {This was actually played in 2011 between Bacrot and Rublevsky. Rublevsky does not play a lot of chess anymore, but he used to be one of the world leading experts on the Accelerated Meran! Next up, we play ... Re8 and then activate our queen, most likely to f6 . We have a slight weakness on b7 , but that is compensated for by the bishop pair.} *


