tead of the c-pawn. The deeper point behind our play is to prepare ... dxc4 , followed by ... b5 and ... c5 .} 6. b3 {This is the best move for White. They anticipate our idea of capturing on c4 , which is now less tempting as it would let White recapture towards the center.} Bb4 {Another surprising shot! The bishop very rarely goes to b4 in the pawn structure with e6 , d5 , c6 but here there is a concrete reason for doing so.} 7. Bd2 {This looks a bit stupid in combination with the pawn on b3 , but White has no choice.} Nbd7 {Continuing the development. Long-term our idea is to push ... e5 , so there is no doubt that the knight belongs to d7 .} 8. Bd3 ({The most active and best move.} 8. Be2 {The bishop is just less active on e2 than d3 .} O-O 9. O-O Bd6 {We can simply play in the same way as in the mainline, with a better version.}) 8... O-O 9. O-O Bd6 {When you see this for the first time, it might look very odd. Aren't we just losing a tempo with our bishop? Well, the bishop's main goal on b4 was simply to force White's bishop to the inferior square d2 , so that it can't get to the long diagonal anymore. Now we need our bishop on d6 , in order to execute our main strategic goal: to push ... e5 .} 10. Re1 {Another possibility. White anticipates the opening of the center after which the rook will be well placed on e1 .} h6 {An interesting counter-waiting move!} (10... e5 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. e4 {Does not work as well as before for us.} dxe4 (12... exd4 {This is possible, but it looks to me a little bit trickier than the usual lines.} 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. exd5 {The rooks is clearly useful on e1 .}) 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Rxe4 $1 {White will be able to recapture on d4 with the rook instead of the knight, creating annoying pressure.}) 11. h3 {White is waiting back, but the inclusion of h3 and h6 is usually in our favour.} e5 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. e4 (13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 {is similar to the 10. Rc1 line and we can play in the same way.}) 13... dxe4 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Rxe4 {This was the big problem without h6  h3 included, but here we have much better version.} f5 16. Bc4+ Kh8 17. Rh4 Be7 {Without h6  h3 included, the rook would now have a safe square on h3 , and the kingside attack would be very strong. Here there is no such square, because the h3 -pawn physically blocks it!} 18. Rh5 Qe8 {Hitting the rook once again.} 19. Nxe5 {The only move to save the rook.} Nxe5 20. dxe5 Qg6 {White is a pawn up, but the rook is hopelessly stuck on h5 . Without more pieces, it's not possible for White to create any real threats. In the meantime, we simply play ... Be6 , ... Rad8 and will almost automatically get a strong initiative at the rest of the board.} *


