[PlyCount "42"]

1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 {My recommendation. White can, and should, now transpose to the Accelerated Meran with 5. d4 . That line differs from the line that I am recommending in the Classical Slav,, but many of the ideas are still the same, and compared to the a6 -Slav White has fewer options by having committed to e3 , Nf3 and Nc3 .} ({•} 4... e6 {The most popular move in practice. It could still be a viable option in order to meet 5. d4 with 5... a6 , transposing to our Accelerated Meran, but there are two reasons I chose not to recommend it: one is that it's much more popular than 4... a6 , meaning White will likely be more ready for it.} 5. b3 {This is the other reason. When we play 4... a6 we can now develop the c8 -bishop outside the pawn chain. This is still by no means bad for Black, but I feel it's the sort of play that White is looking for.}) ({•} 4... Bf5 {The move we would like to play, however it works out rather badly.} 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Qb3 $1 {Compared to the Slav, we can't play ... Qc7 as the d5 -pawn is hanging.}) 5. d4 {Without any doubt, the critical move. Now we have transposed to the so called Chebanenko variation of the Slav, which is something I don't recommend in my Lifetime Repertoire: Classical Slav . But don't worry, we are not tricked. The big point compared to the normal Chebanenko Slav is that White has already committed their pawn to e3 , which greatly decreases the number of lines possible.} ({Against the normal Chebanenko,} 5. d4 {d5} dxc4 {c6 Nf3 Nf6 Nc3 a6 , I consider the move c5 to be the strongest. Probably} 6. a4 {is the second strongest, and only on 3rd place we find moves like g3 or e3 . So White is in fact the one having been 'tricked' into a suboptimal line!}) 5... e6 {Changing opening once again! With 5... e6 , we are entering the so called Accelerated Meran (or a6 -Meran, as it is also often called). The idea of ... e6 is to strengthen the center, particularly being able to recapture on d5 with the e-pawn instead of the c-pawn. The deeper point behind our play is to prepare ... dxc4 , followed by ... b5 and ... c5 .} 6. b3 {This is the best move for White. They anticipate our idea of capturing on c4 , which is now less tempting as it would let White recapture towards the center.} Bb4 {Another surprising shot! The bishop very rarely goes to b4 in the pawn structure with e6 , d5 , c6 but here there is a concrete reason for doing so.} 7. Bd2 {This looks a bit stupid in combination with the pawn on b3 , but White has no choice.} Nbd7 {Continuing the development. Long-term our idea is to push ... e5 , so there is no doubt that the knight belongs to d7 .} 8. Bd3 ({The most active and best move.} 8. Be2 {The bishop is just less active on e2 than d3 .} O-O 9. O-O Bd6 {We can simply play in the same way as in the mainline, with a better version.}) 8... O-O 9. O-O Bd6 {When you see this for the first time, it might look very odd. Aren't we just losing a tempo with our bishop? Well, the bishop's main goal on b4 was simply to force White's bishop to the inferior square d2 , so that it can't get to the long diagonal anymore. Now we need our bishop on d6 , in order to execute our main strategic goal: to push ... e5 .} 10. Qc2 {By far the most common move.} e5 ({The most straightforward, but slower moves like} 10... h6 {in order to push ... e5 later also make sense.}) 11. cxd5 {The typical reaction against ... e5} cxd5 12. e4 {In general when we push ... e5 as Black, this reaction is the most critical one. White is not going for a structural edge, but rather opening up the center to utilize the lead in development.} dxe4 {Usually we don't want to release the tension, but here we need to get our queenside pieces out.} 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Bxe4 h6 {In the Accelerated Meran, this is almost always the correct pawn to push. We prevent for Bg5 and Ng5 , whereas instead ... g6 would create too many holes.} 15. dxe5 {The most common move. White is trying to put concrete pressure.} Nxe5 16. Nxe5 Bxe5 17. Rad1 {This was played in the recent game Moranda-Gumularz. I'd advise you to always take some extra care in these situations - the open center leads to rather sharp play, with lots of tactical tricks for both sides.} Bg4 {The most precise move. We should not fear any discovered attacks.} 18. Bb4 {Looks fancy, but only leads to trades.} (18. f3 Qb6+ 19. Kh1 Be6 {We have no problems whatsoever.}) 18... Bxd1 19. Rxd1 Qc8 20. Bxf8 Qxc2 21. Bxc2 Kxf8 {The position is equal, and highly drawish.} *

