tead of the c-pawn. The deeper point behind our play is to prepare ... dxc4 , followed by ... b5 and ... c5 .} 6. b3 {This is the best move for White. They anticipate our idea of capturing on c4 , which is now less tempting as it would let White recapture towards the center.} Bb4 {Another surprising shot! The bishop very rarely goes to b4 in the pawn structure with e6 , d5 , c6 but here there is a concrete reason for doing so.} 7. Bd2 {This looks a bit stupid in combination with the pawn on b3 , but White has no choice.} Nbd7 {Continuing the development. Long-term our idea is to push ... e5 , so there is no doubt that the knight belongs to d7 .} 8. Bd3 ({The most active and best move.} 8. Be2 {The bishop is just less active on e2 than d3 .} O-O 9. O-O Bd6 {We can simply play in the same way as in the mainline, with a better version.}) 8... O-O 9. O-O Bd6 {When you see this for the first time, it might look very odd. Aren't we just losing a tempo with our bishop? Well, the bishop's main goal on b4 was simply to force White's bishop to the inferior square d2 , so that it can't get to the long diagonal anymore. Now we need our bishop on d6 , in order to execute our main strategic goal: to push ... e5 .} 10. Qc2 {By far the most common move.} e5 ({The most straightforward, but slower moves like} 10... h6 {in order to push ... e5 later also make sense.}) 11. cxd5 {The typical reaction against ... e5} cxd5 12. e4 {In general when we push ... e5 as Black, this reaction is the most critical one. White is not going for a structural edge, but rather opening up the center to utilize the lead in development.} dxe4 {Usually we don't want to release the tension, but here we need to get our queenside pieces out.} 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Bxe4 h6 {In the Accelerated Meran, this is almost always the correct pawn to push. We prevent for Bg5 and Ng5 , whereas instead ... g6 would create too many holes.} 15. dxe5 {The most common move. White is trying to put concrete pressure.} Nxe5 16. Nxe5 Bxe5 17. Bc3 {The suggestion of Kuljasevic in his course on Modern Chess.} Bxc3 18. Qxc3 Qb6 {Next up, we want to finish our development with ... Be6 and Rad8 . The position is almost symmetrical, but we need to be just a little careful over the next 2–3 moves to equalize completely.} 19. Rfd1 Be6 20. Qd4 {The only move to put any sort of pressure. White’s idea is that the b7 -pawn is weak.} Qxd4 21. Rxd4 Rad8 ({The most active way, and therefore the move I like most!} 21... Rab8 {followed by slowly untangle with ... Rfe8 , Kf8 etc. is also equalizing effortlessly.}) 22. Rxd8 Rxd8 23. Bxb7 a5 {Followed by ... Rd2 next. In order to free their rook on a1 , White will have to give up the extra queenside pawn. This is a typical and very professional way to force a draw, but as mentioned, there are safe alternatives along the way as well.} *

