oves like} 10... h6 {in order to push ... e5 later also make sense.}) 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. e4 {In general when we push ... e5 as Black, this reaction is the most critical one. White is not going for a structural edge, but rather opening up the center to utilize the lead in development.} dxe4 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Bxe4 h6 {Always this pawn instead of ... g6 , which would be a weakness. Next we trade in the center. White has slightly more active pieces, but they will be pushed back bit by bit over the next couple of moves.} *

