1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 {This together with 3. g3 are White's main setups.} Nf6 4. Nc3 {This is frankly a bit of an annoying option.} a6 {My recommendation. White can, and should, now transpose to the Accelerated Meran with 5. d4 . That is a different line than what I am recommending in the Classical Slav, but many of the ideas are still the same, and compared to the a6 -Slav White is restricted for choice by having committed to e3 , Nf3 and Nc3 .} ({•} 4... e6 {The most popular move in practice. It could still be a viable option in order to meet 5. d4 with 5... a6 , transposing to our Accelerated Meran, but there are two reasons I chose not to recommend it: one is that it's much more popular than 4... a6 , meaning White will likely be more ready for it.} 5. b3 {This is the other reason. When we play 4... a6 we can now develop the c8 -bishop outside the pawn chain. This is still by no means bad for Black, but I feel it's the sort of play that White is looking for.}) ({•} 4... Bf5 {The move we would like to play, however it works out rather badly.} 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Qb3 $1 {Compared to the Slav, we can't play ... Qc7 as the d5 -pawn is hanging.}) 5. d4 e6 (5... Bf5 {In some sense this is more similar to the Classical Slav, but again there are two reasons I don't recommend it. Firstly, I think 5... e6 is objectively a slightly better move. Secondly, while 5... Bf5 can lead to similar play as the Classical Slav course after moves like 5. Bd3 , there are also many independent lines that leads to different structure, most notably} 6. Ne5 {and . As we would anyway have to learn new things, we might as well play the strongest option.}) 6. b3 Bb4 {This is the idea of our setup - we need to provoke Bd2 so that the bishop won't get to b2 .} 7. Bd2 (7. Bb2 $2 Ne4 $1 8. Rc1 Qa5 9. Qc2 Qxa2 $1 {This is the tactical justification of 6... Bb4 . White simply loses a pawn.}) 7... Nbd7 8. Bd3 {Here I am recommending two different options, 8... O-O and 8... dxc4 .} dxc4 {An interesting attempt.} 9. bxc4 (9. Bxc4 {In the Accelerated Meran, this is almost always the worst recapture.} O-O 10. O-O {This is likely to transpose to the previous chapter.} b5 11. Be2 Bd6 $5 {Not necessary, but the simplest.} 12. e4 e5 {We have transposed to O-O O-O Bd6 e4 dxc4} 13. Bc4 {e5 , analyzed here .}) 9... e5 {This is the idea. Here White has a variety of tries, most leading to very interesting play for both sides.} *

