1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. d4 e6 6. b3 Bb4 7. Bd2 Nbd7 8. Bd3 dxc4 {An interesting attempt.} 9. bxc4 (9. Bxc4 {In the Accelerated Meran, this is almost always the worst recapture.} O-O 10. O-O {This is likely to transpose to the previous chapter.} b5 11. Be2 Bd6 $5 {Not necessary, but the simplest.} 12. e4 e5 {We have transposed to O-O O-O Bd6 e4 dxc4} 13. Bc4 {e5 , analyzed here .}) 9... e5 {This is the point of Lokander's novelty. By making use of some small tactical ideas, we can execute the ... e5 -break in the fastest way possible!} 10. Ne4 {This was Vallejo's reaction in his game against me. Afterward he told me that he felt scared by my novelty and tried to play in the most solid way possible.} Bxd2+ {Necessary here, but trading a few pieces means that Black will equalize easily.} 11. Nfxd2 O-O 12. O-O exd4 {Not necessary, but during the game I thought this was the simplest way to a comfortable position.} 13. exd4 Nxe4 14. Nxe4 Nf6 {½-½ (30) Vallejo Pons,F (2680)-Grandelius,N (2689) Durres 2023. Having traded some minor pieces, the White hanging center is more of a weakness than a strength. Still, White should still be OK, as it is hard for Black to attack the pawns.} *

