1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. d4 e6 6. b3 Bb4 7. Bd2 Nbd7 8. Bd3 dxc4 {An interesting attempt.} 9. bxc4 (9. Bxc4 {In the Accelerated Meran, this is almost always the worst recapture.} O-O 10. O-O {This is likely to transpose to the previous chapter.} b5 11. Be2 Bd6 $5 {Not necessary, but the simplest.} 12. e4 e5 {We have transposed to O-O O-O Bd6 e4 dxc4} 13. Bc4 {e5 , analyzed here .}) 9... e5 {This is the point of Lokander's novelty. By making use of some small tactical ideas, we can execute the ... e5 -break in the fastest way possible!} 10. dxe5 {The first move we need to consider.} Ng4 {If nothing special happens now, we will have the superior structure after recapturing the e5 -pawn.} 11. e6 {To my human eyes, this looks by far the most natural move for White.} Nc5 {An unpleasant surprise for White! It turns out that our tactical tricks are by no means over...} 12. Bf5 {From an objective point of view, White should settle for something like this.} Bxe6 13. Bxe6 Nxe6 {Is equal. We have a nice square on c5 , but White has the semi-open b-file and no real weaknesses. But it's certainly a double-edged and interesting fighting position.} *

