1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. d4 e6 6. b3 Bb4 7. Bd2 Nbd7 8. Bd3 dxc4 {An interesting attempt.} 9. bxc4 (9. Bxc4 {In the Accelerated Meran, this is almost always the worst recapture.} O-O 10. O-O {This is likely to transpose to the previous chapter.} b5 11. Be2 Bd6 $5 {Not necessary, but the simplest.} 12. e4 e5 {We have transposed to O-O O-O Bd6 e4 dxc4} 13. Bc4 {e5 , analyzed here .}) 9... e5 {This is the point of Lokander's novelty. By making use of some small tactical ideas, we can execute the ... e5 -break in the fastest way possible!} 10. dxe5 {The first move we need to consider.} Ng4 {If nothing special happens now, we will have the superior structure after recapturing the e5 -pawn.} 11. e6 {To my human eyes, this looks by far the most natural move for White.} Nc5 {An unpleasant surprise for White! It turns out that our tactical tricks are by no means over...} 12. exf7+ Kxf7 13. Bc2 ({If White spots our tactical trick against} 13. Be2 {, then this move is likely to happen. But it's out of the frying pan, into the fire!}) 13... Qf6 {Suddenly it turns out that White can't keep the c3 -knight alive!} 14. O-O ({The only move!} 14. Ne2 $4 Bxd2+ {Leaves White with no good way to recapture on d2 . Try for yourselves...}) 14... Bxc3 15. Bxc3 Qxc3 16. Qd6 {It turns out that White does have almost enough compensation for the piece.} Qxc2 17. Ng5+ Ke8 18. Rad1 {The only move. White needs to keep the pressure up.} Bd7 {Simply preventing the mate on d8 .} 19. Qxc5 Qf5 {We return our queen to the defense. We are not getting mated, but we are also not getting castled anytime soon of course, since our king has already moved. Still, an extra piece is an extra piece and there are no direct threats, so we must be at least somewhat better.} *

