1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. d4 e6 6. b3 Bb4 7. Bd2 Nbd7 8. Bd3 dxc4 {An interesting attempt.} 9. bxc4 (9. Bxc4 {In the Accelerated Meran, this is almost always the worst recapture.} O-O 10. O-O {This is likely to transpose to the previous chapter.} b5 11. Be2 Bd6 $5 {Not necessary, but the simplest.} 12. e4 e5 {We have transposed to O-O O-O Bd6 e4 dxc4} 13. Bc4 {e5 , analyzed here .}) 9... e5 {This is the point of Lokander's novelty. By making use of some small tactical ideas, we can execute the ... e5 -break in the fastest way possible!} 10. dxe5 {The first move we need to consider.} Ng4 {If nothing special happens now, we will have the superior structure after recapturing the e5 -pawn.} 11. Ne4 {An engine suggestion.} Ndxe5 {Keeping the pressure up.} 12. Be2 {The most solid move, keeping everything protected.} Bxd2+ {Probably the simplest way. We accept that White found some good moves into safety, and go for an equal ending.} 13. Qxd2 Nxf3+ 14. gxf3 {This is in fact smarter than taking with the bishop. White gets an open g-file for their rooks, and the f-pawn is actually useful on f3 , protecting the knight on e4 (in case we play ... Nf6 ) or able to move forward (in case we play ... Ne5 ).} (14. Bxf3 Qxd2+ 15. Kxd2 Kd8 $5 {Is also equal. The last move might look odd, but the king is well placed on c7 , guarding our only weakness on b7 .}) 14... Qxd2+ 15. Kxd2 Nf6 {We are not afraid of a doubled f-pawn of our own. There is nothing for White to attack along the g-file anymore, and without knights White can't really attack the pawns.} 16. Nxf6+ (16. Kc3 Nxe4+ 17. fxe4 Bd7 18. Rhg1 g6 {Followed by O-O-O also looks fine for Black.}) 16... gxf6 17. a4 a5 {The last important strategic idea to remember. We always meet a4 with ... a5 , so that the a4 -pawn remains a long-term weakness on the same colour as our bishop. Next up, we play ... Be6 and O-O-O , with no problems whatsoever.} *

