1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. d4 e6 6. b3 Bb4 7. Bd2 Nbd7 8. Bd3 dxc4 {An interesting attempt.} 9. bxc4 (9. Bxc4 {In the Accelerated Meran, this is almost always the worst recapture.} O-O 10. O-O {This is likely to transpose to the previous chapter.} b5 11. Be2 Bd6 $5 {Not necessary, but the simplest.} 12. e4 e5 {We have transposed to O-O O-O Bd6 e4 dxc4} 13. Bc4 {e5 , analyzed here .}) 9... e5 {This is the point of Lokander's novelty. By making use of some small tactical ideas, we can execute the ... e5 -break in the fastest way possible!} 10. Qc2 {This is a very natural square for the queen in the Meran. Here there are some differences to 10. Qb1 - the main one being that the bishop on b4 isn't hanging.} Qe7 {This is highly important. Were we to play ... Bd6 immediately, the queen would simply be better on c2 than on d1 . But now we see another difference with the queen moves: the b4 -bishop isn't hanging, meaning we can safely recapture on e5 .} 11. Be2 {Highlighting the downside for White: they have to lose a tempo as we were again threatening ... e4 , winning a piece. That is the reason the engines are much more in favour of Qb1 instead of Qc2 .} O-O 12. O-O Re8 {The most flexible move. We shouldn't rush with ... Bd6 , as we want to keep the option of ... Bxc3 in some moments.} (12... e4 $2 {It's important to understand that this doesn't work.} 13. Nxe4 $1 Nxe4 14. Bxb4 Qxb4 15. Qxe4) 13. h3 {This might look like any random waiting move, but it actually has a specific purpose. White needs a square on h2 for the knight in case we push ... e4 .} Bd6 {Don't push ... e4 prematurely. We want to keep the option of ... exd4 . I don't believe we need to know any more concrete moves. We follow up with ... h6 next. Later on, both ... e4 and ... exd4 can be relevant, but even just waiting makes sense.} ({a4 The engine gives this as the top move. It makes sense to gain some more space on the queenside.} 13... h6 {Far from forced, but the most logical.} 14. Rab1 {One of many, many logical moves. This line is purely to see how the game might develop and both sides have many options on each move. Bc7 This sort of move is typical for these positions. We are still asking White what they are up to by making a 'small' improvement move. The bishop is better on c7 than d6 because after a later ... e4 the reply Nh4 will not threaten Nf5xd6 . Rfd1} e4 {With both ... h6 and ... Bc7 on the board, we are ready for this. It makes additional sense once White has left f1 with the rook, as they can't really open up with f3 any longer.} 15. Nh2 Nf8 {The typical way to continue. Next we play ... Ng6 , perhaps continuing towards h4 . It's a sort of Kings Indian Attack style position where White is playing on the queenside and we are playing on the kingside, but I think our play is more dangerous practically.}) *

