1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. d4 e6 6. b3 Bb4 7. Bd2 Nbd7 8. Bd3 dxc4 {An interesting attempt.} 9. bxc4 (9. Bxc4 {In the Accelerated Meran, this is almost always the worst recapture.} O-O 10. O-O {This is likely to transpose to the previous chapter.} b5 11. Be2 Bd6 $5 {Not necessary, but the simplest.} 12. e4 e5 {We have transposed to O-O O-O Bd6 e4 dxc4} 13. Bc4 {e5 , analyzed here .}) 9... e5 10. Qb1 (10. dxe5 Ng4 11. e6 Nc5 $1 {White's position is a bit shaky, and we have a lot of tactical possibilities, for instance Nxf2 followed by Bxc3 and a Ne4 + fork in the end.}) 10... Bd6 11. O-O O-O 12. Qc2 Re8 {We want to play ... Qe7 to threaten ... e4 . As soon as White plays Nh4 , we play ... Nf8 to keep the f5 -square covered. Generally, including ... h6 makes sense to prevent Ng5 - e4 . It's hard for White to do anything positive in the center. d5 would give up the c5 -square, dxe5 would leave the c4 -pawn isolated and c5 gives us a nice square on d5 .} *

