1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. d4 e6 6. Qc2 ({Another of the moves Gelfand tried in his World Championship match against Anand. White is making a non-committal developing move, not weakening the a5 - e1 diagonal (} 6. b3 {) or losing a tempo with the light squared bishop ( Bd3 )}) 6... c5 {Another move that might look odd at first sight. Aren't we just losing another tempo? The point is that in the open center that will arise after ... c5 , the queen would often be better on d1 than on c2 . It no longer controls the d4 -square, and can get under attack on c2 .} 7. a3 {This move is fairly common with the queen on d1 instead of c2 , but in both positions it's fairly innocent. I'm adding it here because I actually tried it myself back in 2010!} dxc4 8. Bxc4 {The other option. Now the play resembles some strange Queen's Gambit Accepted, but a good version for us.} b5 9. Ba2 Nbd7 {A healthy developing move, overprotecting c5 so that we don't run into any tricks like dxc5 followed by Nxb5 .} 10. O-O Bb7 11. Rd1 Qc7 {One of many good moves, but it makes sense to step out of the d-file. Next up, we can simply finish our development with ... Be7 and ... O-O , with or without bringing a rook to d8 . These kinds of positions are actually very comfortable for Black to play, and I would imagine most grandmasters picking Black here, if given a choice.} *

