1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. d4 e6 6. Qc2 ({Another of the moves Gelfand tried in his World Championship match against Anand. White is making a non-committal developing move, not weakening the a5 - e1 diagonal (} 6. b3 {) or losing a tempo with the light squared bishop ( Bd3 )}) 6... c5 {Another move that might look odd at first sight. Aren't we just losing another tempo? The point is that in the open center that will arise after ... c5 , the queen would often be better on d1 than on c2 . It no longer controls the d4 -square, and can get under attack on c2 .} 7. a3 {This move is fairly common with the queen on d1 instead of c2 , but in both positions it's fairly innocent. I'm adding it here because I actually tried it myself back in 2010!} dxc4 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Bxc4 Nbd7 10. Bd3 O-O 11. O-O b5 {This was my game against Tiger Hillarp Persson in 2010. With ... Bb7 followed by ... Rc8 coming next, Black is doing well.} 12. Ne4 {This was my attempt at creating something quick, but it was met by a simple and strong response.} Bb7 {Utilizing the hanging bishop on d3 .} 13. Nxf6+ (13. Nxc5 Nxc5 14. Bxh7+ $2 Nxh7 15. Qxc5 Bxf3 16. gxf3 Ng5 $1 {Suddenly gives Black a winning attack!}) 13... Nxf6 14. e4 Rc8 15. Qe2 h6 {We have no problems whatsoever. My game with Tiger was eventually drawn, but Black was definitely the one who put pressure throughout. ½-½ (44) Grandelius,N (2476)-Hillarp Persson,T (2542) Malmo 2010.} *

