1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. d4 e6 6. Qc2 ({Another of the moves Gelfand tried in his World Championship match against Anand. White is making a non-committal developing move, not weakening the a5 - e1 diagonal (} 6. b3 {) or losing a tempo with the light squared bishop ( Bd3 )}) 6... c5 {Another move that might look odd at first sight. Aren't we just losing another tempo? The point is that in the open center that will arise after ... c5 , the queen would often be better on d1 than on c2 . It no longer controls the d4 -square, and can get under attack on c2 .} 7. cxd5 {The critical move.} (7. a3 {Such moves are popular in practice, but do not really require a lot of theoretical knowledge to meet.} dxc4 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Bxc4 Nbd7 {Followed by ... O-O and ... b5 ... Bb7 is harmonious for Black.}) 7... exd5 8. Be2 {The main move. White keeps the central tension.} cxd4 {Usually I don't advocate releasing the tension in the center, but here we want to see how White is recapturing, so that we can develop accordingly.} 9. exd4 {This is the more solid choice, but not enough to put us under pressure.} Nc6 10. O-O Be6 {We simply develop with ... Be7 and O-O . Again, the extra move Qc2 doesn't do anything at all for White, as the queen would be equally good on d1 .} 11. Bg5 {Tried once by the strong Russian Matlakov, but it's entirely innocent.} Be7 12. Rad1 O-O 13. Ne5 Rc8 {Just remember to meet Ne5 with ... Rc8 , so that we keep our solid structure. Now there is nothing to worry about.} *

