1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. d4 e6 6. Qc2 ({Another of the moves Gelfand tried in his World Championship match against Anand. White is making a non-committal developing move, not weakening the a5 - e1 diagonal (} 6. b3 {) or losing a tempo with the light squared bishop ( Bd3 )}) 6... c5 {Another move that might look odd at first sight. Aren't we just losing another tempo? The point is that in the open center that will arise after ... c5 , the queen would often be better on d1 than on c2 . It no longer controls the d4 -square, and can get under attack on c2 .} 7. cxd5 {The critical move.} (7. a3 {Such moves are popular in practice, but do not really require a lot of theoretical knowledge to meet.} dxc4 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Bxc4 Nbd7 {Followed by ... O-O and ... b5 ... Bb7 is harmonious for Black.}) 7... exd5 8. Be2 {The main move. White keeps the central tension.} cxd4 {Usually I don't advocate releasing the tension in the center, but here we want to see how White is recapturing, so that we can develop accordingly.} 9. Nxd4 Bd6 {This is one of the reasons we take on d4 so early - now the bishop can immediately establish itself on the most active diagonal. Our long-term plan is a kingside attack, so the bishop should definitely be here.} 10. e4 {Only played a handful of times, but I think it's an interesting attempt.} dxe4 11. Bg5 O-O 12. O-O-O {This was played in a recent correspondence game. White is trying to hard to utilize the lead in development, but castling long in such an open position is always double-edged.} Be5 {This looks risky, but in fact works out well.} 13. Ne6 {The only critical move.} Bxe6 {The point. We give up our queen, but the resulting position is much more dangerous for White than for Black.} 14. Rxd8 Rxd8 {If we get one more move, our attack would already be close to crushing.} 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Qxe4 Nd7 {Finishing development. White has a slight lead in development, but our bishops are incredibly strong and the White king will soon be under heavy fire. The engines are giving equality, but in a practical game I think it's much easier to be Black.} *

