1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. d4 e6 6. Qc2 ({Another of the moves Gelfand tried in his World Championship match against Anand. White is making a non-committal developing move, not weakening the a5 - e1 diagonal (} 6. b3 {) or losing a tempo with the light squared bishop ( Bd3 )}) 6... c5 {Another move that might look odd at first sight. Aren't we just losing another tempo? The point is that in the open center that will arise after ... c5 , the queen would often be better on d1 than on c2 . It no longer controls the d4 -square, and can get under attack on c2 .} 7. cxd5 {The critical move.} (7. a3 {Such moves are popular in practice, but do not really require a lot of theoretical knowledge to meet.} dxc4 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Bxc4 Nbd7 {Followed by ... O-O and ... b5 ... Bb7 is harmonious for Black.}) 7... exd5 8. Be2 {The main move. White keeps the central tension.} cxd4 {Usually I don't advocate releasing the tension in the center, but here we want to see how White is recapturing, so that we can develop accordingly.} 9. Nxd4 Bd6 {This is one of the reasons we take on d4 so early - now the bishop can immediately establish itself on the most active diagonal. Our long-term plan is a kingside attack, so the bishop should definitely be here.} 10. O-O O-O 11. b3 Nc6 12. Nxc6 {Again, other moves gives us a good version of 8. dxc5} bxc6 {The so-called hanging pawn structure is always double-edged. If we don't get enough activity the pawns might end up weak, but in this specific situation our chances of creating enough kingside counterplay are pretty good, as White's pieces are somewhat stuck on the queenside.} 13. Bb2 Re8 ({A move based on a tactical finesse.} 13... Bd7 {would be more solid, but also slower in terms of generating counterplay.}) 14. Rac1 Ng4 {Immediately going for the attack} 15. h3 Bh2+ ({An interesting idea.} 15... Qh4 {would also work fine.}) 16. Kh1 Bb8 {The point! We prepare ... Qd6 , with very dangerous threats.} 17. Bxg4 Bxg4 {Our attack is still ongoing, and we have picked up the bishop pair in the meantime. The best White can hope for is probably some sort of perpetual check.} *

