1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. d4 e6 6. Qc2 ({Another of the moves Gelfand tried in his World Championship match against Anand. White is making a non-committal developing move, not weakening the a5 - e1 diagonal (} 6. b3 {) or losing a tempo with the light squared bishop ( Bd3 )}) 6... c5 {Another move that might look odd at first sight. Aren't we just losing another tempo? The point is that in the open center that will arise after ... c5 , the queen would often be better on d1 than on c2 . It no longer controls the d4 -square, and can get under attack on c2 .} 7. cxd5 {The critical move.} (7. a3 {Such moves are popular in practice, but do not really require a lot of theoretical knowledge to meet.} dxc4 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Bxc4 Nbd7 {Followed by ... O-O and ... b5 ... Bb7 is harmonious for Black.}) 7... exd5 8. Be2 {The main move. White keeps the central tension.} cxd4 {Usually I don't advocate releasing the tension in the center, but here we want to see how White is recapturing, so that we can develop accordingly.} 9. Nxd4 Bd6 {This is one of the reasons we take on d4 so early - now the bishop can immediately establish itself on the most active diagonal. Our long-term plan is a kingside attack, so the bishop should definitely be here.} 10. O-O O-O 11. b3 Nc6 12. Nxc6 {Again, other moves gives us a good version of 8. dxc5} bxc6 {The so-called hanging pawn structure is always double-edged. If we don't get enough activity the pawns might end up weak, but in this specific situation our chances of creating enough kingside counterplay are pretty good, as White's pieces are somewhat stuck on the queenside.} 13. Bb2 Re8 ({A move based on a tactical finesse.} 13... Bd7 {would be more solid, but also slower in terms of generating counterplay.}) 14. Na4 Ne4 {We don't want to spend time protecting our pawns if we don't have to. And here it turns out that we don't!} 15. Qxc6 {The only critical move. On everything else, our attack would develop organically.} Rb8 {This now quite reminds me of the chapter on the Meran attempt. We have invested a pawn, but all our pieces are active and White is a bit low on defenders on the kingside.} 16. Rad1 ({The most natural move, making Qxd5 a threat on the next move.} 16. Qc2 Bf5 17. Qd1 Re6 {With excellent kingside prospects.}) 16... Bb7 17. Qc2 Rc8 18. Qd3 (18. Qb1 $2 {would simply leave the queen too far from the kingside.} Bxh2+ $1 19. Kxh2 Qh4+ 20. Kg1 Rc6 $1 {There is no good way to defend against Rh6 / Rg6 .}) 18... Bxh2+ {Continuing the attack with normal moves would also make sense, but this forces a pretty draw.} 19. Kxh2 Qh4+ 20. Kg1 Rc6 21. Qd4 {The only move to prevent ... Rh6 .} Rg6 22. Bf3 Ng5 {This beautiful tactic is the point of Black's play} 23. Qxh4 Nxf3+ 24. Kh1 Nxh4 {Winning back the queen while keeping the pressure on in the ending.} *

