1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. d4 e6 6. Qc2 c5 7. cxd5 {The critical move.} (7. a3 {Such moves are popular in practice, but do not really require a lot of theoretical knowledge to meet.} dxc4 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Bxc4 Nbd7 {Followed by ... O-O and ... b5 ... Bb7 is harmonious for Black.}) 7... exd5 8. Be2 (8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O Be6 {Very important! if a3 followed by b4 , we want to play Nbd7 to keep the c-file open, and reroute the knight towards c4 . But if White plays b3 , we want to play Nc6 , as it's the more active square.} 11. b3 Nc6 $1 ({a3} 11... Nbd7 $1)) 8... cxd4 {Important! We want to lure White's knight away from the defense of the kingside.} 9. Nxd4 Bd6 10. O-O O-O 11. b3 Nc6 12. Nxc6 bxc6 {The hanging pawns generally provides good counterplay. White lacks enough defenders on the kingside, and straightforward attacking moves like ... Ng4 will give a lot of counterplay. If White tries to play h3 , controlling g4 , the plan of Bc7 , Qd6 becomes really strong.} *

