1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. d4 e6 6. Bd3 {Frankly, this is a bit annoying. White is deliberately going for a worse version of the Queen's Gambit Accepted, but that is not our main opening! Still, there aren't that many lines to know and having the knight on c3 really, really limits White.} (6. c5 {A strategic move aimed at gaining queenside space. It used to be one of the most challenging lines, but has now gone out of fashion. The main question for Black is whether to go for the ... e5 - or the ... b6 -break. I've chosen to recommend going for ... b6 . The reason is that it's a bit simpler and more straightforward to play and understand. We simply want to undermine the White queenside to remove the space advantage.} Nbd7 (6... b6 {This is possible immediately as well, and is certainly solid, but delaying it one move keeps White guessing our intentions a little bit.}) 7. b4 {Most natural and common.} ({•} 7. Qc2 {A high-level move, but in my view not that difficult to handle.} b6 8. cxb6 Qxb6 {This looks a bit shaky at first, but it's actually rather simple to play. Again, an important factor is that the c1 -bishop is passive.} 9. Bd2 Bd6 {Sample line to show how to develop the pieces:} 10. Rc1 Bb7 11. Bd3 O-O 12. O-O a5 $1 {Intending Rfc8 followed by ... Ba6 , trading the bishops. In the long run White will not be able to prevent us from playing ... c5 .}) ({•} 7. Bd3 $6 {Visually natural but inaccurate.} e5 $1 {Works well now as the d3 -bishop will be hanging once we recapture the e5 -pawn.}) 7... b6 8. Bb2 a5 9. a3 {A sequence often seen in the Queen's Gambit Accepted. This is a better version for us though, as the White bishop would be much better outside the pawn chain on f4 , rather than being passive on b2 .} Be7 {It's not really a theoretical position where we need to know anything else. Our plan is to prepare ... Ba6 but we wait for White to first move their f1 -bishop.}) 6... dxc4 {This is the whole point of 5... a6 , so other moves doesn't really make sense.} 7. Bxc4 b5 8. Bb3 {Recommended by Sielecki+Hansen in their LTR on 1. Nf3 /1. c4 . It does require a little bit of care.} ({•} 8. Bd3 Bb7 {Followed by ... c5 is rather pleasant for us. Actually, it we can often take over the initiative in the middlegame.} 9. O-O c5 10. Qe2 Nbd7 11. Rd1 Qb8 $5 {The main idea to remember in these structures. The queen is well-placed on b8 . It steps out of the d-file, but also controls the key e5 -square and even puts pressure towards h2 .}) ({•} 8. Be2 Nbd7 9. O-O c5 {The typical way to get counterplay.} 10. d5 {The only move to know.} exd5 11. Nxd5 Bb7 12. Nxf6+ Qxf6 {This position is almost fantastic for Black.} 13. a4 {Without this move, we would most likely already be better.} b4 {Looks ugly, but our pieces are very active.} 14. e4 h6 $1 {Preventing the highly annoying Bg5 . Now the c1 -bishop is actually not doing too much. The first time you see it it might feel a bit shaky for Black by giving up the c4 -square and then having to waste a move on ... h6 , but our active pieces compensates for that. ... Bd6 , O-O and bringing the rooks to the center will provide excellent counterplay.}) ({•} 8. Be2 c5 9. O-O Bb7 {This is the other main option for Black. It's also very solid, and more popular, but I feel the play here is much more similar to the real Queen's Gambit Accepted, and therefore doesn't go too well with our repertoire.} 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. Qxd8+ Kxd8 12. Nd2 {Is the mainline. Black is certainly solid, but it's not the sort of position we are aiming for.}) 8... c5 9. O-O Bb7 {Compared to 8. Be2 , we are not afraid of dxc5 , as then the bishop would be misplaced on b3 .} 10. e4 cxd4 11. Nxd4 Nbd7 {Preventing e5 . If given time, we want to develop the f8 -bishop and get castled, after which we would simply be better. If White can’t make any tactical tricks on d5 / e6 work, then the bishop will be misplaced on b3 , and both our bishops better than White’s counterparts.} 12. Re1 Ne5 {Important, as White was threatening e5 . If we get to finish development now, we would be doing nicely, so White has to try something concrete. I'd recommend you to study the main chapter on this rather carefully.} 13. Bd5 {Sielecki+Hansen's attempt.} exd5 {It's not necessary to take the bishop, but when I checked the various options I concluded that this is in fact rather promising for Black. But again, it's important to know what you are doing here.} 14. exd5 Bd6 {We are not intending to keep the piece, but give it back in a good way.} 15. f4 Nxd5 16. fxe5 Bb4 {Our great asset is the unopposed b7 -bishop.} 17. Qg4 Ne7 {The last key move to remember. White can't capture on g7 , so we are able to safely castle on the next move.} *

