1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. d4 e6 6. c5 {A strategic move. Normally, releasing the tension is not to be recommended, but here White is arguing that having played ... a6 as Black makes it a lot less attractive to break the pawn chain with ... b6 later on.} Nbd7 7. Bd3 {This looks like a natural developing move, but I actually consider it a bit inaccurate.} e5 {Positionally this is always our desired break once White has played c5 , but it's only against 7. Bd3 it works well.} 8. Nxe5 Nxe5 9. dxe5 Ng4 10. f4 {This is a more ambitious way for White, but it also comes with high risk.} Bxc5 11. Qf3 Qb6 12. Na4 Qb4+ 13. Nc3 d4 (13... Qb6 {Of course repeating is also possible.}) 14. a3 Qa5 15. exd4 Bxd4 {With excellent counterplay. With our strong bishop on d4 , White is struggling to get castled.} *

