1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. d4 e6 6. c5 {A strategic move. Normally, releasing the tension is not to be recommended, but here White is arguing that having played ... a6 as Black makes it a lot less attractive to break the pawn chain with ... b6 later on.} Nbd7 7. Bd3 {This looks like a natural developing move, but I actually consider it a bit inaccurate.} e5 {Positionally this is always our desired break once White has played c5 , but it's only against 7. Bd3 it works well.} 8. dxe5 Ng4 9. Na4 {Defending the c5 -pawn, which is the more valuable one.} Ndxe5 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 {This is the problem with playing Bd3 as White - the bishop is now hanging on d3 .} 11. O-O Be7 12. Be2 O-O {We have nothing to complain about. Next up, we can simply develop with ... Re8 and even ... Bf5 . Worst case, the knight can be rerouted via d7 - f6 .} *

