1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. d4 e6 6. c5 {A strategic move. Normally, releasing the tension is not to be recommended, but here White is arguing that having played ... a6 as Black makes it a lot less attractive to break the pawn chain with ... b6 later on.} Nbd7 7. Qc2 {This is a high class move. By not developing the bishop to d3 , White is making ... e5 a lot less attractive for Black.} b6 {The solid way of playing. We force White to give up on the space advantage. In return, we get a slight weakness on c6 , but that is very hard for White to make any use of.} 8. cxb6 Qxb6 {The first time I saw this position I thought White should have some edge due to the backward c-pawn, but the more I looked, the more I like it for Black. It's actually very hard for White to find a good plan. Attacking the c-pawn will never really lead to anything as it's too easy to defend, but White is also lacking in good pawn breaks. Pushing e4 will generally only make it easier for Black.} 9. Bd2 {Has been the most common move in practical play, but basically we play the same against all White's moves.} Bd6 10. Rc1 Bb7 {Just remember to play ... Bb7 after Rc1 , in order to keep the c-pawn defended. The bishop will still get traded on a6 later on, but we first need to castle and bring our f-rook to c8 .} 11. Bd3 O-O 12. O-O a5 {A key part of the concept. We slowly get ready to trade the bishops on a6 .} 13. Na4 Qa7 {This is an additional resource in case White delays Na4 .} *

