1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. d4 e6 6. c5 {A strategic move. Normally, releasing the tension is not to be recommended, but here White is arguing that having played ... a6 as Black makes it a lot less attractive to break the pawn chain with ... b6 later on.} Nbd7 7. b4 {The main move by far.} b6 {Just like against 7. Qc2 this is necessary, as we need to fight against White's space advantage.} 8. Bb2 a5 9. a3 Be7 {This is a sort of position most often seen in the Queen's Gambit Declined, but the big difference is that there the bishop is on f4 rather than b2 . On b2 it's considerably more passive, which means that we have a good version. The main idea is to trade the light squared bishops and then start fighting for the a-file. Don't release the tension by taking on b4 or c5 unless there is a specific reason for doing so!} 10. Bd3 Qc7 {A small move order finesse. We are going for bishop trade before castling.} (10... O-O 11. O-O Ba6 (11... Qc7 12. Qe2 $1 {prevents} Ba6) 12. Bxa6 Rxa6 13. b5 $5 cxb5 14. c6 Nb8 15. Ne5 b4 {Leads to a messy situation. Black is OK, but I find it a bit unnecessary to allow it.}) 11. Qe2 axb4 12. axb4 Rxa1+ {This is the point of delaying castling - White can't recapture with the rook.} 13. Bxa1 bxc5 14. bxc5 e5 {With excellent counterplay.} *

