1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. d4 e6 6. Bd3 {This is the main move in the normal Meran, but in the Accelerated Meran it's actually a fair bit less popular.} dxc4 7. Bxc4 b5 {This is resembling a normal Meran a lot, but it's specifically this position that gives the name 'Accelerated' its meaning. It is accelerated for Black in the sense that by playing ... a6 instead of ... Nbd7 , we are actually able to push ... c5 one move earlier, as the b5 -pawn is already protected.} 8. Bd3 Bb7 ({A small move order subtlety.} 8... c5 9. a4 b4 10. Ne4 {is slightly annoying.}) 9. O-O (9. e4 c5 {Gives excellent counterplay. Again, it's an advantage not having had to play ... Nbd7 yet.}) 9... c5 {Gives good play against the center. It's important that we managed to play it before White got e4 in.} 10. dxc5 {Very timid. Optimally, White would only want to play this after we have already moved our f8 -bishop.} Bxc5 11. Qe2 {The most common move. White is trying to push e4 .} Nbd7 {A nice move order subtlety. Delaying ... O-O gives us an extra tempo in the fight for the center.} 12. e4 Bd6 {This is the difference. We manage to prevent White from playing e5 , after which the White position doesn't really make much sense.} 13. Rd1 Qb8 {A typical move for these positions. With e5 firmly under control, we have absolutely nothing to worry about. Next up we have time to castle after which we are ready to fight for the initiative, for example by ... Ne5 .} *

