1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. d4 e6 6. Bd3 {This is the main move in the normal Meran, but in the Accelerated Meran it's actually a fair bit less popular.} dxc4 7. Bxc4 b5 {This is resembling a normal Meran a lot, but it's specifically this position that gives the name 'Accelerated' its meaning. It is accelerated for Black in the sense that by playing ... a6 instead of ... Nbd7 , we are actually able to push ... c5 one move earlier, as the b5 -pawn is already protected.} 8. Bd3 Bb7 ({A small move order subtlety.} 8... c5 9. a4 b4 10. Ne4 {is slightly annoying.}) 9. O-O (9. e4 c5 {Gives excellent counterplay. Again, it's an advantage not having had to play ... Nbd7 yet.}) 9... c5 {Gives good play against the center. It's important that we managed to play it before White got e4 in.} 10. Qe2 {A logical move. White wants to bring a rook to the d-file, but also gets ready to take on c5 and push e4 - e5 .} Nbd7 {Other moves also equalizes easily, but generally I really like the knight on d7 in these positions. It fights for the key e5 -square, but also keeps the diagonal open for the b7 -bishop.} 11. Rd1 Qb8 {Stepping out of the d-file. It's a bit more common to place the queen on c7 , but then White plays Bd2 and Rc1 , after which our queen would have to move again. Instead, let's go immediately to b8 . Now we are ready to develop our f8 -bishop.} 12. e4 {By far the most common move, but this is precisely what we want to see.} cxd4 13. Nxd4 Bd6 {Securing control over the key e5 -square, while gaining a tempo in the process. White has no real plan, so actually Black is just better.} *

