1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. d4 e6 6. Bd3 {This is the main move in the normal Meran, but in the Accelerated Meran it's actually a fair bit less popular.} dxc4 7. Bxc4 b5 {This is resembling a normal Meran a lot, but it's specifically this position that gives the name 'Accelerated' its meaning. It is accelerated for Black in the sense that by playing ... a6 instead of ... Nbd7 , we are actually able to push ... c5 one move earlier, as the b5 -pawn is already protected.} 8. Bb3 {Recommended by Sielecki+Hansen in their LTR on 1. Nf3 /1. c4 . It does require a little bit of care.} c5 9. O-O (9. e4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Nbd7 $1 {Preventing e5 .} 11. O-O Bb7 {Transposes to the line we're currently studying.}) 9... Bb7 10. e4 {The only critical move. This is actually a slightly topical line, so we should treat it carefully. The main thing is to not allow White any nasty tactics in the center.} cxd4 11. Nxd4 Nbd7 {Preventing e5 . If given time, we want to develop the f8 -bishop and get castled, after which we would simply be better. If White can’t make any tactical tricks on d5 / e6 work, then the bishop will be misplaced on b3 , and both our bishops better than White’s counterparts.} 12. Re1 {The most interesting move, trying to prepare some tactics along the e-file.} Ne5 {Physically blocking the e-file. It is always a bit risky to move the same piece twice before finish development, so we should make sure we know what we are doing.} 13. Nd5 {A funny idea, but it is not as scary as it looks.} Nfd7 (13... exd5 $2 14. exd5 Bd6 15. f4 $1 {This works much worse here than against 13. Bd5 . The bishop on b3 is simply a much better piece than the knight on c3 once the position opens up. In the 13. Bd5 -line, one of our main strategic ideas is to get an unopposed light squared bishop on b7 , which is not happening now. Additionally, the bishop on d5 created a lot of threats, whereas we are able to play around the knight on d5 .}) 14. Nf4 {This was tried by the current European Champion, Sarana, but it was not classical chess and very likely not a prepared idea, as it doesn't really work.} Nc5 {Overprotecting the e6 -pawn. Now White has no good way to follow up, so we are easily getting castled.} 15. Bc2 Rc8 {White does not have enough firepower available.} *

