1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. d4 e6 6. Bd3 {This is the main move in the normal Meran, but in the Accelerated Meran it's actually a fair bit less popular.} dxc4 7. Bxc4 b5 {This is resembling a normal Meran a lot, but it's specifically this position that gives the name 'Accelerated' its meaning. It is accelerated for Black in the sense that by playing ... a6 instead of ... Nbd7 , we are actually able to push ... c5 one move earlier, as the b5 -pawn is already protected.} 8. Bb3 {Recommended by Sielecki+Hansen in their LTR on 1. Nf3 /1. c4 . It does require a little bit of care.} c5 9. O-O (9. e4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Nbd7 $1 {Preventing e5 .} 11. O-O Bb7 {Transposes to the line we're currently studying.}) 9... Bb7 10. e4 {The only critical move. This is actually a slightly topical line, so we should treat it carefully. The main thing is to not allow White any nasty tactics in the center.} cxd4 11. Nxd4 Nbd7 {Preventing e5 . If given time, we want to develop the f8 -bishop and get castled, after which we would simply be better. If White can’t make any tactical tricks on d5 / e6 work, then the bishop will be misplaced on b3 , and both our bishops better than White’s counterparts.} 12. Re1 {The most interesting move, trying to prepare some tactics along the e-file.} Ne5 {Physically blocking the e-file. It is always a bit risky to move the same piece twice before finish development, so we should make sure we know what we are doing.} 13. Bd5 {This is the recommendation by Sielecki and Hansen in their Lifetime Repertoire on 1. c4 and 1. Nf3 . If it comes as a surprise, it's easy to panic as Black, but once we calm ourselves down and begin to look at the options, we realize that there are numerous decent ways.} exd5 ({Not an obvious choice. Keeping the tension with} 13... Qd7 $5 {also makes a lot of sense and is a sensible practical choice, but I do like the positions arising after the more principled capture.}) 14. exd5 Bd6 15. f4 {The only interesting move. Now we need to be careful and know one key move.} Nxd5 16. fxe5 Bb4 {If we would get one more move, we would be doing fantastically with the bishop pair, but White can put some immediate pressure.} 17. Qg4 Ne7 {This is they key move we need to know. It prevents Qxg7 due to ... Rg8 (remember our key bishop on b7 !) but it also stops Nf5 , which is the main attacking idea for White. Furthermore, it lets us castle, as Bh6 can now be met by ... Ng6 .} 18. Be3 O-O 19. Rad1 Qc8 {Sielecki and Hansen end here saying that Black is fine, and I do agree. I'd even go a little further and say that our position is slightly more pleasant. This is perhaps due to my optimistic nature, but I do love the look of the b7 -bishop towards White's king.} ({e6 the engine's proposal to keep the game equal.} 19... f5 $5 {One of many good moves.} 20. Nxf5 {This is White's idea. The b4 -bishop is hanging.} Nxf5 21. Qxb4 {Qxe6 This is the position I wanted to mention. Objectively it's for sure equal, but the bishop on b7 towards the weak g2 -point makes me feel optimistic as Black.}) *

