1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. d4 e6 6. Bd3 {This is the main move in the normal Meran, but in the Accelerated Meran it's actually a fair bit less popular.} dxc4 7. Bxc4 b5 {This is resembling a normal Meran a lot, but it's specifically this position that gives the name 'Accelerated' its meaning. It is accelerated for Black in the sense that by playing ... a6 instead of ... Nbd7 , we are actually able to push ... c5 one move earlier, as the b5 -pawn is already protected.} 8. Bb3 {Recommended by Sielecki+Hansen in their LTR on 1. Nf3 /1. c4 . It does require a little bit of care.} c5 9. O-O (9. e4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Nbd7 $1 {Preventing e5 .} 11. O-O Bb7 {Transposes to the line we're currently studying.}) 9... Bb7 10. e4 {The only critical move. This is actually a slightly topical line, so we should treat it carefully. The main thing is to not allow White any nasty tactics in the center.} cxd4 11. Nxd4 Nbd7 {Preventing e5 . If given time, we want to develop the f8 -bishop and get castled, after which we would simply be better. If White can’t make any tactical tricks on d5 / e6 work, then the bishop will be misplaced on b3 , and both our bishops better than White’s counterparts.} 12. Re1 {The most interesting move, trying to prepare some tactics along the e-file.} Ne5 {Physically blocking the e-file. It is always a bit risky to move the same piece twice before finish development, so we should make sure we know what we are doing.} 13. Bf4 Bd6 {I like this a lot! Of course the move in itself is nothing special, but it invites a nice pawn sacrifice.} 14. Nf5 {Again, if we were just allowed to castle in peace we would have a very pleasant position.} exf5 15. exf5 O-O {This is the point. We simply give back the piece, and then claim we have full compensation with our strong bishop on b7 .} 16. Bxe5 Bxe5 17. Rxe5 Qc7 18. Re3 {The only good square! White needs to be able to hide their queen behind the rook.} (18. Re1 $2 Rad8 19. Qc1 Ng4 {would already be a winning attack!}) 18... Rad8 {We have full compensation in numerous ways. One idea is ... Qf4 , to pick up the f5 -pawn, but moves like ... b4 !? pushing the c3 -knight to a bad square also makes sense. Additionally, the move ... Qc6 !? can put annoying pressure towards g2 .} *

