1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. d4 e6 6. Bd3 {This is the main move in the normal Meran, but in the Accelerated Meran it's actually a fair bit less popular.} dxc4 7. Bxc4 b5 {This is resembling a normal Meran a lot, but it's specifically this position that gives the name 'Accelerated' its meaning. It is accelerated for Black in the sense that by playing ... a6 instead of ... Nbd7 , we are actually able to push ... c5 one move earlier, as the b5 -pawn is already protected.} 8. Be2 {This modest looking move is actually the most dangerous one for Black. As we are going to play ... c5 anyway, the bishop is vulnerable on both d3 and b3 , therefore White tries to tuck it safely away on e2 .} c5 9. O-O {Overwhelmingly the main move.} Nbd7 {An important move order. We want to dissuade White from capturing on c5 .} 10. d5 {By far the most critical.} exd5 11. Nxd5 Bb7 12. Nxf6+ {Nothing else makes sense.} Qxf6 {This is important. Now we don't want to trade queens. Instead, we want to utilize our strong b7 -bishop, by playing ... Bd6 and ... Ne5 to create some tension on the kingside.} 13. a4 {A good inclusion for White, as our light squares (especially c4 ) becomes weak. Still, our active pieces definitely compensates for that.} b4 14. Ra2 {A funny looking move recently tried by Carlsen, but objectively it's a bit too much.} Rd8 {Was a bit more precise than what Aronian did.} 15. b3 Ne5 16. Rd2 {I presume this was Carlsen's idea, but it doesn't work out too well.} Nxf3+ 17. Bxf3 Rxd2 18. Bxd2 Bxf3 19. Qxf3 Qxf3 20. gxf3 Kd7 {Bringing the king to c6 . Afterwards we develop the bishop and rook. Our 3-2 on the queenside seems much more dangerous than White's majority on the kingside, so White is definitely the one having to be more careful.} *

