1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. d4 e6 6. Bd3 {This is the main move in the normal Meran, but in the Accelerated Meran it's actually a fair bit less popular.} dxc4 7. Bxc4 b5 {This is resembling a normal Meran a lot, but it's specifically this position that gives the name 'Accelerated' its meaning. It is accelerated for Black in the sense that by playing ... a6 instead of ... Nbd7 , we are actually able to push ... c5 one move earlier, as the b5 -pawn is already protected.} 8. Be2 {This modest looking move is actually the most dangerous one for Black. As we are going to play ... c5 anyway, the bishop is vulnerable on both d3 and b3 , therefore White tries to tuck it safely away on e2 .} c5 9. O-O {Overwhelmingly the main move.} Nbd7 {An important move order. We want to dissuade White from capturing on c5 .} 10. d5 {By far the most critical.} exd5 11. Nxd5 Bb7 12. Nxf6+ {Nothing else makes sense.} Qxf6 {This is important. Now we don't want to trade queens. Instead, we want to utilize our strong b7 -bishop, by playing ... Bd6 and ... Ne5 to create some tension on the kingside.} 13. a4 {A good inclusion for White, as our light squares (especially c4 ) becomes weak. Still, our active pieces definitely compensates for that.} b4 14. e4 {The best move. The pawn can't really be taken.} h6 {This is a high class move. White really wanted to develop with Bg5 , so we simply prevent it. Next up, we will still have time for our own idea of ... Bd6 and ... Ne5 .} 15. Qc2 (15. Bc4 Bd6 16. Bd5 {This idea looked natural to me the first time I saw the position, but it's too slow.} Bxd5 17. Qxd5 O-O 18. Rd1 {It looks like we have problems on the d-file, but in fact White is the one!} Rfd8 19. Qxd6 Ne5 {Winning.}) 15... Bd6 16. Rd1 Rd8 {Keeps everything defended on the d-file.} 17. Be3 O-O 18. Nd2 Rfe8 {Looks very harmonious for Black.} 19. f3 Nf8 {Preparing ... Ne6 - d4 / f4 .} 20. Nc4 Bc7 {With excellent counterplay. We are happily giving up the c5 -pawn if we can establish a knight on d4 .} *

