1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. d4 e6 6. Bd3 {This is the main move in the normal Meran, but in the Accelerated Meran it's actually a fair bit less popular.} dxc4 7. Bxc4 b5 {This is resembling a normal Meran a lot, but it's specifically this position that gives the name 'Accelerated' its meaning. It is accelerated for Black in the sense that by playing ... a6 instead of ... Nbd7 , we are actually able to push ... c5 one move earlier, as the b5 -pawn is already protected.} 8. Be2 {This modest looking move is actually the most dangerous one for Black. As we are going to play ... c5 anyway, the bishop is vulnerable on both d3 and b3 , therefore White tries to tuck it safely away on e2 .} c5 9. O-O {Overwhelmingly the main move.} Nbd7 {An important move order. We want to dissuade White from capturing on c5 .} 10. d5 {By far the most critical.} exd5 11. Nxd5 Bb7 12. Nxf6+ {Nothing else makes sense.} Qxf6 {This is important. Now we don't want to trade queens. Instead, we want to utilize our strong b7 -bishop, by playing ... Bd6 and ... Ne5 to create some tension on the kingside.} 13. a4 {A good inclusion for White, as our light squares (especially c4 ) becomes weak. Still, our active pieces definitely compensates for that.} b4 14. e4 {The best move. The pawn can't really be taken.} h6 {This is a high class move. White really wanted to develop with Bg5 , so we simply prevent it. Next up, we will still have time for our own idea of ... Bd6 and ... Ne5 .} 15. Qc2 (15. Bc4 Bd6 16. Bd5 {This idea looked natural to me the first time I saw the position, but it's too slow.} Bxd5 17. Qxd5 O-O 18. Rd1 {It looks like we have problems on the d-file, but in fact White is the one!} Rfd8 19. Qxd6 Ne5 {Winning.}) 15... Bd6 16. Be3 O-O 17. Nd2 {This is how Radjabov played against Ding in the World Cup 2019, but he got nowhere at all.} Bf4 {17... Rfe8 !? Would also make sense, just keeping the tension a bit longer.} 18. Bxf4 Qxf4 19. f3 Rfd8 20. Nc4 Ne5 {The key idea. Without knights, White can't really create anything at all.} 21. Nxe5 {Otherwise, we would jump ... Nc6 - d4} Qxe5 22. Rac1 Rac8 {Black is fine. Next up, establishing the rook on d4 makes sense. Flicking in ... a5 is also useful so that the pawn never hangs. Most likely some rooks will get traded along the d-file, but for every trade, our queenside majority gets more potent.} *

