1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. d4 e6 6. Bd3 (6. c5 Nbd7 7. b4 (7. Qc2 b6 8. cxb6 Qxb6 {It's important that this structure is innocent. The c6 -pawn can't ever really be attacked.} 9. Bd2 Bd6 10. Rc1 Bb7 11. Bd3 O-O 12. Na4 Qc7 13. O-O a5 $1 {Again, a key idea is to trade off the light squared bishops. We won't get to play ... c5 anytime soon, but White is also lacking a clear plan.}) 7... b6 8. Bb2 a5 9. a3 Be7 10. Bd3 Qc7 11. O-O Ba6 {An important trade strategically. After the trade a good plan is to double the rooks on the a-file, as it is bounds to get open later on.}) 6... dxc4 7. Bxc4 b5 8. Be2 (8. Bb3 c5 {The 'acceleration' that gives the Accelerated Meran it's name. The move 5... a6 already protected the b5 -pawn, meaning we can push ... c5 faster than usual.} 9. O-O Bb7 10. e4 {Never take this pawn, it always gives too much initiative.} cxd4 11. Nxd4 Nbd7 {Long-term our position is great, so we should only look out for quick tactical ideas.} 12. Re1 Ne5 13. Bd5 exd5 $1 {Generally White gets the piece back but not more than that.} 14. exd5 Bd6) 8... c5 9. O-O Nbd7 10. d5 exd5 11. Nxd5 Bb7 12. Nxf6+ Qxf6 13. a4 b4 {It's important that while structurally this looks dubious for Black, it works well due to the very active piece play we get.} *

