1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 {It's understandable from White's perspective that they don't want to transpose to a 1. d4 -opening, but what I really like about our repertoire is how simple it is to handle everything except the d4 -transpositions.} 4. Nc3 (4. Qc2 Bg4 {Whenever possible we prefer to develop the bishop outside the pawn chain.} 5. Ne5 Bh5 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. Nc3 (7. d4 f6 $5 8. Nd3 e5 $1 {We should act quickly to utilize our lead in development.}) 7... Nxc3 8. bxc3 Nd7 9. Nxd7 Qxd7 10. f4 e6 11. d4 Be7 12. Bd3 f5 {White has the center, but importantly it doesn't really matter, as it can't move anywhere. We will eventually get to play ... c5 and put pressure along the c-file. The hole on e5 doesn't matter, as there are no knights on the board.}) 4... a6 5. Qc2 (5. b3 Bf5 {Still very solid for us. Losing a tempo with ... a6 is not a big deal, as the position is not of a sharp nature.} 6. Nh4 Bg6 7. Nxg6 hxg6 {A position reminiscent of the Slow Slav, but White's move b3 doesn't really belong there. Now, we can even go for a quick ... e5 -push.}) 5... e6 {We are trying to transpose to the Accelerated Meran after 6. d4} 6. b3 c5 {An important concept! We want to push ... d4 next.} 7. cxd5 exd5 {Now ... d4 is less good for us as it would make the pawn isolated.} 8. Bb2 Nc6 9. Rc1 {Simon William's recommendation.} b5 {Our antidote. It's strategically very sharp, but I believe in our chances.} *

