[PlyCount "12"]

1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 (2. Nc3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 {This does not really have any independent value, as White should play Nf3 or d4 anyway here.}) 2... d5 3. e3 Nf6 {It's understandable from White's perspective that they don't want to transpose to a 1. d4 -opening, but what I really like about our repertoire is how simple it is to handle everything except the d4 -transpositions.} 4. Qc2 {This is an interesting move, which I even employed myself recently. The idea is simple: White prevents ... Bf5 .} Bg4 {Logical. The f5 -square is not available, so we develop to g4 instead. This theme is also commonly seen in the normal Slav.} 5. d4 {Is possible, but does not prevent us from developing normally. As usual in these Slav positions, if we are able to develop the bishop outside the pawn chain and then develop normally, we have no problems whatsoever.} e6 6. Nbd2 Nbd7 {I don't really believe we need to know any more concrete theory.} *

