White's best bet, at least initiating some trades.} Nb4 11. Nxb4 Bxb4+ 12. Nd2 Nd7 ({•} 12... O-O $4 13. Qb3+ {Drops a piece!}) ({•} 12... Bf7 13. Bc4 $1 {It is not what we want - the trade of bishops is in White's favour, and the knight is much better on d2 than c3 .}) 13. Bc4 Rf8 {It looks strange to play ... Rf8 instead of trying to castle, but it turns out that White also has some hidden issues in their position.} 14. O-O b5 {Important! We need to keep the pressure up. Now the bishop on c4 is removed from the c4 - e2 diagonal, giving us access to the e2 -square.} 15. Bb3 Qf6 {This is the point. We are now threatening ... Be2 . Additionally, the knight on d2 has no good squares available anymore.} 16. f3 {At least preventing ... Be2 .} Rd8 {Preparing ... Nc5 - d3 . Another way to fight for the initiative is to push ... g5 - g4 . It's a very strange position, where in some sense both sides stand badly. Long term, it looks a bit loose for us with some weaknesses here and there, but on the other hand White's pieces are all strangely placed and we have a decent lead in development.} *

