1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 (2. Nc3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 {This does not really have any independent value, as White should play Nf3 or d4 anyway here.}) 2... d5 3. e3 Nf6 {It's understandable from White's perspective that they don't want to transpose to a 1. d4 -opening, but what I really like about our repertoire is how simple it is to handle everything except the d4 -transpositions.} 4. Nc3 (4. Qc2 Bg4 {Whenever possible we prefer to develop the bishop outside the pawn chain.} 5. Ne5 Bh5 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. Nc3 (7. d4 f6 $5 8. Nd3 e5 $1 {We should act quickly to utilize our lead in development.}) 7... Nxc3 8. bxc3 Nd7 9. Nxd7 Qxd7 10. f4 e6 11. d4 Be7 12. Bd3 f5 {White has the center, but importantly it doesn't really matter, as it can't move anywhere. We will eventually get to play ... c5 and put pressure along the c-file. The hole on e5 doesn't matter, as there are no knights on the board.}) 4... a6 {This move requires some explanation. Normally we don't play ... a6 in the Slav, but here we do it as a sort of waiting move. The issue is that we can't quite develop our c8 -bishop yet, as it would run into the typical issue of Qb3 , with strong pressure on b7 . Therefore, we make a sort of waiting move, keeping the option of developing the bishop on the next move. The downside is of course that White can still play d4 , and transpose to a version of the Slav which is outside the scope of the Classical Slav. We are happy with entering the Accelerated Meran though, and that actually makes the move 4... a6 really convenient. Basically, the only critical way at all for White is to play d4 over the next moves, but presumably White started with 1. c4 or 1. Nf3 precisely in order to avoid that!} 5. Qc2 e6 ({Important! Against h3 we play} 5... Nbd7 {in order to force d4 , but here Nbd7} 6. d4 {would lead to a version of the Accelerated Meran where we played Nbd7 too early.}) 6. b3 (6. d4 c5 {Transposes to the Accelerated Meran, 6. Qc2  chapter .}) 6... c5 {As usual in the Slav, when White develops the queen to c2 early on, we should always consider the tempo losing ... c6 - c5 . The reason is that White has lost control over the d4 -square, but also that once our knight gets to c6 , it can already threaten to jump to b4 .} 7. cxd5 {The most common move. Otherwise, we would even push ... d4 ourselves.} (7. Bb2 {This is the move order of Simon Williams in his LTR on the Modern Reti. It gives us an extra possibility of} d4 {, but for simplicity we can also just transpose. Nc6 cxd5 exd5 Transposes to the next line in this chapter.}) 7... exd5 8. d4 {Another way to play, but we are not afraid of the isolated d-pawn.} Nc6 {As White has not yet committed the f1 -bishop, we don't take on d4 . If we take too early, White will find it easier to play either g3 , or put the bishop on d3 .} 9. dxc5 {Strategically necessary, else White's play makes no sense.} Bxc5 10. Bb2 O-O 11. Be2 Be6 {Natural development. Next up, we want to play ... Qe7 and bring the rooks to the d- and c-files. Most likely, we will play ... d4 later on and rid ourselves of the weakness.} *

