s the queen to c2 early on, we should always consider the tempo losing ... c6 - c5 . The reason is that White has lost control over the d4 -square, but also that once our knight gets to c6 , it can already threaten to jump to b4 .} 7. cxd5 {The most common move. Otherwise, we would even push ... d4 ourselves.} (7. Bb2 {This is the move order of Simon Williams in his LTR on the Modern Reti. It gives us an extra possibility of} d4 {, but for simplicity we can also just transpose. Nc6 cxd5 exd5 Transposes to the next line in this chapter.}) 7... exd5 8. Bb2 Nc6 {We have easy development and a healthy position. If we are allowed to develop peacefully, we would even be a bit better with our nice central control.} 9. Na4 {Trying to attack our only weakness, the c5 -pawn.} Nb4 10. Qb1 {The only square, otherwise ... Bf5 would come with great effect.} Be6 {Possible now that c5 is no longer hanging. Everything is well defended, and we have nothing to complain about. If we feel ambitious, we could even play ... b5 !? next, gaining further space.} *

