1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 (2. Nc3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 {This does not really have any independent value, as White should play Nf3 or d4 anyway here.}) 2... d5 3. e3 Nf6 {It's understandable from White's perspective that they don't want to transpose to a 1. d4 -opening, but what I really like about our repertoire is how simple it is to handle everything except the d4 -transpositions.} 4. Nc3 (4. Qc2 Bg4 {Whenever possible we prefer to develop the bishop outside the pawn chain.} 5. Ne5 Bh5 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. Nc3 (7. d4 f6 $5 8. Nd3 e5 $1 {We should act quickly to utilize our lead in development.}) 7... Nxc3 8. bxc3 Nd7 9. Nxd7 Qxd7 10. f4 e6 11. d4 Be7 12. Bd3 f5 {White has the center, but importantly it doesn't really matter, as it can't move anywhere. We will eventually get to play ... c5 and put pressure along the c-file. The hole on e5 doesn't matter, as there are no knights on the board.}) 4... a6 {This move requires some explanation. Normally we don't play ... a6 in the Slav, but here we do it as a sort of waiting move. The issue is that we can't quite develop our c8 -bishop yet, as it would run into the typical issue of Qb3 , with strong pressure on b7 . Therefore, we make a sort of waiting move, keeping the option of developing the bishop on the next move. The downside is of course that White can still play d4 , and transpose to a version of the Slav which is outside the scope of the Classical Slav. We are happy with entering the Accelerated Meran though, and that actually makes the move 4... a6 really convenient. Basically, the only critical way at all for White is to play d4 over the next moves, but presumably White started with 1. c4 or 1. Nf3 precisely in order to avoid that!} 5. Qc2 e6 ({Important! Against h3 we play} 5... Nbd7 {in order to force d4 , but here Nbd7} 6. d4 {would lead to a version of the Accelerated Meran where we played Nbd7 too early.}) 6. b3 (6. d4 c5 {Transposes to the Accelerated Meran, 6. Qc2  chapter .}) 6... c5 {As usual in the Slav, when White develops the queen to c2 early on, we should always consider the tempo losing ... c6 - c5 . The reason is that White has lost control over the d4 -square, but also that once our knight gets to c6 , it can already threaten to jump to b4 .} 7. cxd5 {The most common move. Otherwise, we would even push ... d4 ourselves.} (7. Bb2 {This is the move order of Simon Williams in his LTR on the Modern Reti. It gives us an extra possibility of} d4 {, but for simplicity we can also just transpose. Nc6 cxd5 exd5 Transposes to the next line in this chapter.}) 7... exd5 8. Bb2 Nc6 {We have easy development and a healthy position. If we are allowed to develop peacefully, we would even be a bit better with our nice central control.} 9. Rc1 {This is Simon's recommendation. The idea is to play Na4 next and always be able to meet ... Nb4 with Qb1 .} b5 {In my view the most principled, but also the nicest solution. We simply prevent Na4 . The extra space is also nice to have, as now d4 can always be met by ... c4 .} 10. a4 {This is the only argument against ... b5 . White is putting immediate pressure against our pawns.} b4 {The only move. Generally we should be hesitant about giving up the light squares like this, but here it works well.} 11. Ne2 Na5 {This is the key reason why we don't mind pushing ... b4 . a5 is an amazing square for the knight, attacking the b3 -pawn but also controlling c4 .} 12. Ng3 Bb7 {The last important move. We need to be able to get a rook to c8 as quickly as possible.} 13. d4 (13. Be2 {Too modest.} Rc8 14. O-O Bd6 15. Nf5 O-O {Normally we would really not want to give White the bishop pair, but here the b3 -pawn is so weak and all our pieces so nice that we happily oblige.} 16. Nxd6 Qxd6 {We can even consider pushing ... d4 soon, opening up for the b7 -bishop.}) 13... c4 {The idea of the previous move. It comes down to a pawn sacrifice, but our compensation is fantastic.} 14. bxc4 {White has to take, otherwise ... c3 is just strategically winning.} dxc4 15. Bxc4 Nxc4 16. Qxc4 Rc8 {We are a pawn down, but the b7 -bishop is a monster. Additionally, the White pieces are actually not doing that much.} 17. Qe2 h5 {Very strong. In order to get any activity at all, White really needs to push e4 . Our move ... h5 is an active move, but it can also be called prophylaxis against e4 by White. By hitting the g3 -knight we make it impossible for White to get e4 in.} 18. h4 Bd6 {Now the g3 -knight is hanging for real. Again, the b7 -bishop, but also the generally more active pieces, provides enough compensation. As both e4 and d5 are impossible to achieve, the b2 -bishop will also remain bad for a long while. We should also not remember that b4 is a protected passed pawn!} *

