1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 (2. Nc3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 {This does not really have any independent value, as White should play Nf3 or d4 anyway here.}) 2... d5 3. e3 Nf6 {It's understandable from White's perspective that they don't want to transpose to a 1. d4 -opening, but what I really like about our repertoire is how simple it is to handle everything except the d4 -transpositions.} 4. Nc3 (4. Qc2 Bg4 {Whenever possible we prefer to develop the bishop outside the pawn chain.} 5. Ne5 Bh5 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. Nc3 (7. d4 f6 $5 8. Nd3 e5 $1 {We should act quickly to utilize our lead in development.}) 7... Nxc3 8. bxc3 Nd7 9. Nxd7 Qxd7 10. f4 e6 11. d4 Be7 12. Bd3 f5 {White has the center, but importantly it doesn't really matter, as it can't move anywhere. We will eventually get to play ... c5 and put pressure along the c-file. The hole on e5 doesn't matter, as there are no knights on the board.}) 4... a6 {This move requires some explanation. Normally we don't play ... a6 in the Slav, but here we do it as a sort of waiting move. The issue is that we can't quite develop our c8 -bishop yet, as it would run into the typical issue of Qb3 , with strong pressure on b7 . Therefore, we make a sort of waiting move, keeping the option of developing the bishop on the next move. The downside is of course that White can still play d4 , and transpose to a version of the Slav which is outside the scope of the Classical Slav. We are happy with entering the Accelerated Meran though, and that actually makes the move 4... a6 really convenient. Basically, the only critical way at all for White is to play d4 over the next moves, but presumably White started with 1. c4 or 1. Nf3 precisely in order to avoid that!} 5. h3 {This is one of those moves that can be bothersome for Black if they don't have the Accelerated Meran in their repertoire. But we do, which gives us an easy fix.} Nbd7 {The exclamation is deserved for the understanding of move orders this move shows!} 6. cxd5 {The only independent move. We were threatening ... e5} (6. d4 {This is by far the most common and best move for White, but now it's a direct transposition.} e6 {transposes to d4 e6 h3 Nbd7 , analyzed in Accelerated Meran, Various 6th Moves starting from here .}) 6... cxd5 7. d4 {Again necessary, to prevent ... e5 .} e6 {This is now some sort of Exchange Slav. In these positions one should always be a bit careful about having the knight on d7 rather than the better c6 -square, but the big takeaway here is that White has already committed to e3 , making the c1 -bishop much worse. Generally, the Exchange Slav is entirely innocent when the c1 -bishop is stuck within the pawn chain, and this is no exception.} 8. Bd3 Bd6 {Developing with ... b6 or ... b5 also makes sense, but this looks simplest.} 9. O-O O-O {There is nothing really to know. On the next move we could push ... e5 if we want to reach positions very similar to the Accelerated Meran with 6. b3 , but we could also play more modestly with ... b6 , ... Bb7 . In both cases, we have nothing to complain about.} *

