fore, we have to do something else. Luckily, there is a good solution available.}) 5... dxc4 {This might look strange compared to our repertoire, but in fact we are very likely to transpose to the a6 -Meran with 6. Bd3 .} 6. Bxc4 b5 {No matter where White goes with the bishop, they will likely follow up with d4 and transpose to the a6 -Meran.} 7. Be2 (7. Bb3 c5 8. O-O (8. d4 e6 {Transposes to Accelerated Meran, Various 6th Moves, starting here .}) 8... e6 9. d4 {White has nothing better than this.} Bb7 {, transposing to d4 e6 Bd3 dxc4} 10. Bc4 {b5 Bb3 c5 O-O Bb7 , once again analyzed in the Accelerated Meran, Various 6th Moves chapter, starting from here .}) 7... c5 {Again White can't really do without d4 , transposing.} 8. O-O e6 9. d4 Nbd7 {Transposes to the Accelerated Meran, Various 6th Moves chapter, starting from here .} *

