1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 (2. Nc3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 {This does not really have any independent value, as White should play Nf3 or d4 anyway here.}) 2... d5 3. e3 Nf6 {It's understandable from White's perspective that they don't want to transpose to a 1. d4 -opening, but what I really like about our repertoire is how simple it is to handle everything except the d4 -transpositions.} 4. Nc3 (4. Qc2 Bg4 {Whenever possible we prefer to develop the bishop outside the pawn chain.} 5. Ne5 Bh5 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. Nc3 (7. d4 f6 $5 8. Nd3 e5 $1 {We should act quickly to utilize our lead in development.}) 7... Nxc3 8. bxc3 Nd7 9. Nxd7 Qxd7 10. f4 e6 11. d4 Be7 12. Bd3 f5 {White has the center, but importantly it doesn't really matter, as it can't move anywhere. We will eventually get to play ... c5 and put pressure along the c-file. The hole on e5 doesn't matter, as there are no knights on the board.}) 4... a6 {This move requires some explanation. Normally we don't play ... a6 in the Slav, but here we do it as a sort of waiting move. The issue is that we can't quite develop our c8 -bishop yet, as it would run into the typical issue of Qb3 , with strong pressure on b7 . Therefore, we make a sort of waiting move, keeping the option of developing the bishop on the next move. The downside is of course that White can still play d4 , and transpose to a version of the Slav which is outside the scope of the Classical Slav. We are happy with entering the Accelerated Meran though, and that actually makes the move 4... a6 really convenient. Basically, the only critical way at all for White is to play d4 over the next moves, but presumably White started with 1. c4 or 1. Nf3 precisely in order to avoid that!} 5. b3 {This is the most popular move against 4... e6 , but here it is less interesting for White.} Bf5 {Of course! As soon as White plays b3 , we no longer have to worry about Qb3 , so it's safe to develop the bishop. The only downside is that White can hunt the bishop down, but we are used to this from the Classical Slav, and know that we usually get good compensation for the bishop pair.} 6. Nh4 {This is the only ambitious move for White, going for the bishop pair.} Bg6 {There are options, but I don't mind trading the bishop. It seems to me we have a good version of the Slow Slav type of positions, as b3 , Bb2 does not really belong in these structures.} 7. Nxg6 hxg6 8. g3 (8. Bb2 e5 {Gives us a strong center.}) 8... d4 {Fighting hard for the dark squares.} 9. exd4 Qxd4 10. Bb2 Nbd7 {If we could keep the blockade on d4 forever, we would be doing very well, but the queen is not the best blockading piece.} 11. Qe2 (11. Bg2 $2 Ne5 {Would give us a monster knight on d3 on the next move!}) 11... O-O-O {Our king is completely safe on the queenside here. It's more important to develop quickly and getting a rook to the semi-open file. Evacuating the king from the center also lets us play ... e5 without worrying about the center opening.} 12. Na4 {Probably White's safest bet, not letting us play ... e5 and affirm our control over the key d4 -square.} Qg4 {Trading queens. The ending is fine for us. We will still follow up with ... e5 , and as usual the dark squares and easy development compensated for the two bishops.} *

