the Classical Slav, and know that we usually get good compensation for the bishop pair.} 6. Nh4 {This is the only ambitious move for White, going for the bishop pair.} Bg6 {There are options, but I don't mind trading the bishop. It seems to me we have a good version of the Slow Slav type of positions, as b3 , Bb2 does not really belong in these structures.} 7. Nxg6 hxg6 8. d4 {After this, the play really resembles a Slow Slav. There, the move ... a6 is not the most useful, but White would also never play b3 , Bb2 instead of developing the kingside.} Nbd7 9. Bb2 e5 {Not at all necessary, but I usually like to put as much pressure on our opponents as possible.} (9... e6 {Gives a typical Slow Slav position, full of life and interesting for both sides.}) 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. dxe5 Nxe5 {We have an isolated pawn, but White should be really careful as we have a lot of potential counterplay.} 12. g3 Ne4 {Immediately going for it!} 13. Bg2 Bb4 14. Rc1 Qf6 {Every move increases the pressure. Things look dire for White, but they can survive by sacrificing some material.} 15. O-O {Strictly the only move.} Bxc3 16. Bxc3 Nxc3 17. Rxc3 Nf3+ {Winning the exchange.} 18. Qxf3 Qxc3 19. Qxd5 O-O {White will get two pawns, but in the open position the rooks are strong. Probably fairly balanced, but I think it's a bit easier to play with the rooks.} *

