1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 {It's understandable from White's perspective that they don't want to transpose to a 1. d4 -opening, but what I really like about our repertoire is how simple it is to handle everything except the d4 -transpositions.} 4. Nc3 (4. Qc2 Bg4 {Whenever possible we prefer to develop the bishop outside the pawn chain.} 5. Ne5 Bh5 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. Nc3 (7. d4 f6 $5 8. Nd3 e5 $1 {We should act quickly to utilize our lead in development.}) 7... Nxc3 8. bxc3 Nd7 9. Nxd7 Qxd7 10. f4 e6 11. d4 Be7 12. Bd3 f5 {White has the center, but importantly it doesn't really matter, as it can't move anywhere. We will eventually get to play ... c5 and put pressure along the c-file. The hole on e5 doesn't matter, as there are no knights on the board.}) 4... a6 5. b3 Bf5 6. Nh4 Bg6 7. Nxg6 hxg6 {Good version of these positions. We are even able to quickly push ... e5 .} 8. d4 Nbd7 9. Bb2 e5 {Excellent counterplay. Usually in the Slav we are not able to push ... e5 in one move. The open h-file also gives potential for counterplay, so do not rush to castle!} *

