1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3 {The Reti. When I started to play chess, this was considered something to play when one wanted to avoid all theory. Needless to say, 15 years later, things are very different. Now it's just a mainline, and White is certainly intending to add theoretical pressure.} dxc4 {From the White side this was always what bothered me the most, and it goes well together with the rest of our repertoire.} ({•} 3... Bg4 {This, together with it's sibling 3... Bf5 , is perhaps the 'purest' Slav move, but I have played and analyzed this a lot from the White side for many years already, and my conclusion is that it's very pleasant for White. Perhaps it's not an objective advantage per se, but the amount of details Black need to be familiar with to equalize is simply too many. Even more important though is that if both White and Black play 'by hand' I believe White's position is much easier to play!}) ({•} 3... g6 {Very solid, and if you have the Gruenfeld in your repertoire it makes a lot of sense. For our repertoire though it leads to rather different structures, and insofar as possible I prefer to avoid fianchettoing our dark squared bishop.}) 4. Bg2 e6 {This one is highly controversial though! Basically we have only one idea: as soon as the knight appears on a3 , we want to take it!} (4... Nd7 5. O-O Ngf6 6. Qc2 Nb6 7. Na3 Be6 {In a correspondence game, this would probably be my choice. It's also what Shankland recommends in his LTR. The reason I am against it is again connected to the practical side. As White, I have won a few games straight out of the opening here, even in classical chess against grandmasters, and therefore I know how tricky it is for Black. In general, I am against lines where one small misstep leads to disaster, and I feel this is one such line.}) 5. O-O (5. a4 {Another possible move order for White that is very likely to transpose later on.} Nf6 6. Na3 (6. O-O Nbd7 {transposes to the current line.}) 6... Bxa3 {We always take this knight once it appears on a3 .} 7. Rxa3 O-O 8. O-O Nbd7 {again transposes to the line we are studying.}) 5... Nf6 {Apart from the fact that we basically can't be move order tricked, the other big advantage with this setup is that it's still relatively rare, meaning your opponents likely won't be familiar with it at all.} 6. a4 {The main move, and Shankland's recommendation in his LTR on the Reti. Most sources I found actually stops here and says that White has a pleasant position, and I recognize this is what you can expect from a well-prepared player. Needless to say, having your opponents out of book by move 6 should be considered an achievement!} (6. Na3 Bxa3 7. bxa3 O-O {The doubled a-pawns is actually not a big concern for White here, as they provide open files and diagonals. The problem for White is rather that we will keep our pawn with ... b5 next, and then have easy development with ... Bb7 and ... Nbd7 .}) 6... Nbd7 {Flexibility is important here. We don't decide yet if we want to play ... b6 or not.} 7. Na3 (7. Qc2 b6 {... b5 is too dangerous. Now we calmly develop with ... Bb7 , eventually followed by ... c5 to oppose on the long diagonal.}) 7... Bxa3 {Always take!} 8. Rxa3 O-O {This is an interesting strategical position. With the pawn already on a4 we will not be able to keep our c4 -pawn. The first time I saw the position, I thought White would have an edge with the bishop pair, but that's not really true. We will place our pawns on a5 and c5 , and likely also e5 eventually. This gives us good central control and control over the dark squares.   The bishop goes to the long diagonal, intending a trade if allowed. If White's a-pawn was back on a2 , they could try to open up with a3 , b4 in the long run, but as it stands now White will struggle to open up the game anywhere, meaning they struggle to come up with a good plan.} *

