1. c4 c6 2. g3 d5 3. Bg2 {This move order is sometimes tried, but I don't really get it. It just gives Black extra options.} e5 {I like this. Why not just grab the center?} ({•} 3... Nf6 4. Nf3 dxc4 {Is a good option, very likely to transpose to the rest of the chapter. However, there is the extra option} 5. Qc2 $5 {Qc2} b5 6. a4 Bb7 7. b3 {This should be OK for Black, but it doesn't quite transpose to our repertoire.}) ({•} 3... dxc4 {This is in fact not to be recommended.} 4. Na3 $1 {We can't take the knight as we didn't have time to play ... e6 yet.}) 4. cxd5 cxd5 5. d4 {This is how White plays. Against more modest moves, we would simply have the center for free.} e4 6. Nc3 Bb4 {A good strategic move. White is going to attack our center with f3 , so we are getting ready to swap off the c3 -knight if the central pressure gets too strong.} 7. f3 {White is trying to put quick pressure against our center. Generally, we never want to take on f3 , but instead play to keep e4 alive.} Nf6 8. Bg5 {Putting pressure on the knight on f6 , but we have a simple reply.} Nbd7 9. Bxf6 Bxc3+ {Just remember to take here first before recapturing, otherwise the bishop is lost!} 10. bxc3 Nxf6 {White can't put enough pressure on e4 , so we are simply better.} *

