1. c4 c6 2. g3 d5 3. Bg2 {This move order is sometimes tried, but I don't really get it. It just gives Black extra options.} e5 {I like this. Why not just grab the center?} ({•} 3... Nf6 4. Nf3 dxc4 {Is a good option, very likely to transpose to the rest of the chapter. However, there is the extra option} 5. Qc2 $5 {Qc2} b5 6. a4 Bb7 7. b3 {This should be OK for Black, but it doesn't quite transpose to our repertoire.}) ({•} 3... dxc4 {This is in fact not to be recommended.} 4. Na3 $1 {We can't take the knight as we didn't have time to play ... e6 yet.}) 4. cxd5 cxd5 5. d4 {This is how White plays. Against more modest moves, we would simply have the center for free.} e4 6. Nc3 Bb4 {A good strategic move. White is going to attack our center with f3 , so we are getting ready to swap off the c3 -knight if the central pressure gets too strong.} 7. Nh3 h6 {An important move to remember! We want to play ... Nf6 without allowing Bg5 . Again, it's all about the fight for the e4 -square.} 8. O-O Nf6 9. f3 {Strategically, the only way that makes sense for White. If we are allowed to finish development calmly, we would simply be much better.} O-O {The simplest solution.} 10. fxe4 Bxc3 {There are more ambitious ways to play, but this looks like comfortable equality immediately.} 11. bxc3 Bxh3 12. Bxh3 Nxe4 {The knight is an excellent blockading piece on e4 .} 13. Qd3 Nd7 14. c4 {Strategically, the only move. If we got one more move for ... Rc8 , the c3 -pawn would be forever weak.} Ndf6 15. cxd5 Re8 {A small detail. The immediate ... Qxd5 would maybe have been met by Rf5 - e5 , but now there is no way for White to stop it on the next move. We are overprotecting our key knight on e4 , and as long as it is there it's hard for White to do anything at all.} *

