1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3 {The Reti. When I started to play chess, this was considered something to play when one wanted to avoid all theory. Needless to say, 15 years later, things are very different. Now it's just a mainline, and White is certainly intending to add theoretical pressure.} dxc4 {From the White side this was always what bothered me the most, and it goes well together with the rest of our repertoire.} ({•} 3... Bg4 {This, together with it's sibling 3... Bf5 , is perhaps the 'purest' Slav move, but I have played and analyzed this a lot from the White side for many years already, and my conclusion is that it's very pleasant for White. Perhaps it's not an objective advantage per se, but the amount of details Black need to be familiar with to equalize is simply too many. Even more important though is that if both White and Black play 'by hand' I believe White's position is much easier to play!}) ({•} 3... g6 {Very solid, and if you have the Gruenfeld in your repertoire it makes a lot of sense. For our repertoire though it leads to rather different structures, and insofar as possible I prefer to avoid fianchettoing our dark squared bishop.}) 4. Bg2 e6 {Another controversial decision! This is not the cleanest way to kill the game, but it is an easy and underestimated line that equalizes with much less effort. We accept that the bishop will have to be developed via b7 or a6 instead. By playing ... e6 we prepare to capture a knight appearing on a3 , and for the rest we are just going to develop normally.} ({•} 4... Nf6 5. O-O e6 {This move order also works well.}) ({•} 4... Nd7 {Over the last years the lines with ... Nd7 - b6 have been the most topical, with the current mainline being} 5. O-O Ngf6 6. Qc2 Nb6 7. Na3 Be6 8. Ne5 h5 $1 {This seems to be holding up well theoretically, and Shankland indeed recommends it in his LTR. My own opinion is that the entire complex with Nd7 - b6 is rather impractical for Black, though. White has an incredible number of interesting ways to play that are not giving an advantage, but forces Black to show precision and knowledge. Instead, I want to play in a much less forcing manner, getting a normal game instead of a memory test.}) 5. Na3 Bxa3 {This is something we should get used to. We are giving up the bishop pair, but gaining some time for development.} 6. bxa3 {When seeing it for the first time, such a doubled pawn looks very odd, but it's in fact a rather normal idea for White in the Reti. As compensation White has an open b-file, and the pawns might even turn out useful, for example if we play ... b5 White can attack our pawn chain with a4 .} Nf6 7. O-O O-O 8. Qc2 b6 {This is a common idea in these positions. We are happy to give back the pawn in order to get free development. The pawn is useful on b6 as we want to play ... c5 , ... Nc6 if possible.} 9. Ne5 (9. Qxc4 $2 Ba6 {wins the e2 -pawn!}) 9... Nd5 {Clogging up the long diagonal so that we can play ... c5 . next.} 10. Nxc4 c5 {This is our typical scenario. The pawns are equal, but our pieces will soon all be on good squares, and we have no weaknesses.} *

