1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3 {The Reti. When I started to play chess, this was considered something to play when one wanted to avoid all theory. Needless to say, 15 years later, things are very different. Now it's just a mainline, and White is certainly intending to add theoretical pressure.} dxc4 {From the White side this was always what bothered me the most, and it goes well together with the rest of our repertoire.} ({•} 3... Bg4 {This, together with it's sibling 3... Bf5 , is perhaps the 'purest' Slav move, but I have played and analyzed this a lot from the White side for many years already, and my conclusion is that it's very pleasant for White. Perhaps it's not an objective advantage per se, but the amount of details Black need to be familiar with to equalize is simply too many. Even more important though is that if both White and Black play 'by hand' I believe White's position is much easier to play!}) ({•} 3... g6 {Very solid, and if you have the Gruenfeld in your repertoire it makes a lot of sense. For our repertoire though it leads to rather different structures, and insofar as possible I prefer to avoid fianchettoing our dark squared bishop.}) 4. Bg2 e6 {Another controversial decision! This is not the cleanest way to kill the game, but it is an easy and underestimated line that equalizes with much less effort. We accept that the bishop will have to be developed via b7 or a6 instead. By playing ... e6 we prepare to capture a knight appearing on a3 , and for the rest we are just going to develop normally.} ({•} 4... Nf6 5. O-O e6 {This move order also works well.}) ({•} 4... Nd7 {Over the last years the lines with ... Nd7 - b6 have been the most topical, with the current mainline being} 5. O-O Ngf6 6. Qc2 Nb6 7. Na3 Be6 8. Ne5 h5 $1 {This seems to be holding up well theoretically, and Shankland indeed recommends it in his LTR. My own opinion is that the entire complex with Nd7 - b6 is rather impractical for Black, though. White has an incredible number of interesting ways to play that are not giving an advantage, but forces Black to show precision and knowledge. Instead, I want to play in a much less forcing manner, getting a normal game instead of a memory test.}) 5. Na3 Bxa3 {This is something we should get used to. We are giving up the bishop pair, but gaining some time for development.} 6. bxa3 {When seeing it for the first time, such a doubled pawn looks very odd, but it's in fact a rather normal idea for White in the Reti. As compensation White has an open b-file, and the pawns might even turn out useful, for example if we play ... b5 White can attack our pawn chain with a4 .} Nf6 7. O-O O-O 8. Bb2 {White is playing for quick development instead of regaining the pawn immediately.} b5 {With Qc2 instead of Bb2 I was a bit hesitant about this due to White opening up the position quickly with Rd1 and d3 , but now we gain an important tempo as White still needs to spend a move on Qc2 .} 9. Qc2 Bb7 {The bishop belongs on the long diagonal, as we long term want to oppose the g2 -bishop and if possible trade it.} 10. Rad1 Nbd7 11. d3 {The logical way for White.} c5 {I think this is really instructive. We should not hang on to the extra pawn forever, but rather give it back to fight for the initiative.} 12. dxc4 Be4 {Good to flick in, as otherwise Ng5 could be on the agenda for White.} 13. Qc1 Qb6 {Pawns are equal, but we have finished development and have freed our position. As soon as the f3 -knight moves, we get the desirable trade of bishops. If White never moves the f3 -knight, we bring the rooks into the game.} *

