1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3 {The Reti. When I started to play chess, this was considered something to play when one wanted to avoid all theory. Needless to say, 15 years later, things are very different. Now it's just a mainline, and White is certainly intending to add theoretical pressure.} dxc4 {From the White side this was always what bothered me the most, and it goes well together with the rest of our repertoire.} ({•} 3... Bg4 {This, together with it's sibling 3... Bf5 , is perhaps the 'purest' Slav move, but I have played and analyzed this a lot from the White side for many years already, and my conclusion is that it's very pleasant for White. Perhaps it's not an objective advantage per se, but the amount of details Black need to be familiar with to equalize is simply too many. Even more important though is that if both White and Black play 'by hand' I believe White's position is much easier to play!}) ({•} 3... g6 {Very solid, and if you have the Gruenfeld in your repertoire it makes a lot of sense. For our repertoire though it leads to rather different structures, and insofar as possible I prefer to avoid fianchettoing our dark squared bishop.}) 4. Bg2 e6 {Another controversial decision! This is not the cleanest way to kill the game, but it is an easy and underestimated line that equalizes with much less effort. We accept that the bishop will have to be developed via b7 or a6 instead. By playing ... e6 we prepare to capture a knight appearing on a3 , and for the rest we are just going to develop normally.} ({•} 4... Nf6 5. O-O e6 {This move order also works well.}) ({•} 4... Nd7 {Over the last years the lines with ... Nd7 - b6 have been the most topical, with the current mainline being} 5. O-O Ngf6 6. Qc2 Nb6 7. Na3 Be6 8. Ne5 h5 $1 {This seems to be holding up well theoretically, and Shankland indeed recommends it in his LTR. My own opinion is that the entire complex with Nd7 - b6 is rather impractical for Black, though. White has an incredible number of interesting ways to play that are not giving an advantage, but forces Black to show precision and knowledge. Instead, I want to play in a much less forcing manner, getting a normal game instead of a memory test.}) 5. Qc2 b5 6. a4 Bb7 {Generally speaking, in these lines it's often smart to delay ... Nf6 for a while, as the tempo can be put to better use elsewhere} 7. b3 (7. O-O Nf6 {Transposes to Qc2} 8. axb5 {a4 Bb7 , here .}) 7... cxb3 8. Qxb3 b4 {This is a huge difference. With ... Nf6 instead of ... e6 , the pawn would simply be hanging. But now it is defended, and White does not have enough play for the pawn.} *

