1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3 {The Reti. When I started to play chess, this was considered something to play when one wanted to avoid all theory. Needless to say, 15 years later, things are very different. Now it's just a mainline, and White is certainly intending to add theoretical pressure.} dxc4 {From the White side this was always what bothered me the most, and it goes well together with the rest of our repertoire.} ({•} 3... Bg4 {This, together with it's sibling 3... Bf5 , is perhaps the 'purest' Slav move, but I have played and analyzed this a lot from the White side for many years already, and my conclusion is that it's very pleasant for White. Perhaps it's not an objective advantage per se, but the amount of details Black need to be familiar with to equalize is simply too many. Even more important though is that if both White and Black play 'by hand' I believe White's position is much easier to play!}) ({•} 3... g6 {Very solid, and if you have the Gruenfeld in your repertoire it makes a lot of sense. For our repertoire though it leads to rather different structures, and insofar as possible I prefer to avoid fianchettoing our dark squared bishop.}) 4. Bg2 e6 {Another controversial decision! This is not the cleanest way to kill the game, but it is an easy and underestimated line that equalizes with much less effort. We accept that the bishop will have to be developed via b7 or a6 instead. By playing ... e6 we prepare to capture a knight appearing on a3 , and for the rest we are just going to develop normally.} ({•} 4... Nf6 5. O-O e6 {This move order also works well.}) ({•} 4... Nd7 {Over the last years the lines with ... Nd7 - b6 have been the most topical, with the current mainline being} 5. O-O Ngf6 6. Qc2 Nb6 7. Na3 Be6 8. Ne5 h5 $1 {This seems to be holding up well theoretically, and Shankland indeed recommends it in his LTR. My own opinion is that the entire complex with Nd7 - b6 is rather impractical for Black, though. White has an incredible number of interesting ways to play that are not giving an advantage, but forces Black to show precision and knowledge. Instead, I want to play in a much less forcing manner, getting a normal game instead of a memory test.}) 5. O-O (5. a4 {Another possible move order for White that is very likely to transpose later on.} Nf6 6. Na3 (6. O-O Nbd7 {transposes to the current line.}) 6... Bxa3 {We always take this knight once it appears on a3 .} 7. Rxa3 O-O 8. O-O Nbd7 {again transposes to the line we are studying.}) 5... Nf6 {Continuing development. We don't want to move the f8 -bishop as we want to capture on a3 in one move, but we also don't want to move the b-pawn, as it is not yet clear if we want ... b6 or ... b5 .} ({By the way, this position is also commonly reached from a Queen's Gambit move order, i.e. c4 e6 Nf3 d5 g3 dxc4 Bg2} 5... Nf6 {O-O c6 , so Queen's Gambit players can easily pick it up as well. Stylistically, it's not very clearly aimed at neither Slav nor QGD, but should go well with both.}) 6. a4 {The main move, and Shankland's recommendation in his LTR on the Reti. Most sources I found actually stops here and says that White has a pleasant position, and I recognize this is what you can expect from a well-prepared player. Needless to say, having your opponents out of book by move 6 should be considered an achievement!} (6. Na3 Bxa3 7. bxa3 O-O {The doubled a-pawns is actually not a big concern for White here, as they provide open files and diagonals. The problem for White is rather that we will keep our pawn with ... b5 next, and then have easy development with ... Bb7 and ... Nbd7 .}) 6... Nbd7 {We don't want to move our f8 -bishop as we want to capture a knight on a3 in one move. We also don't want to move the b-pawn, as it is not yet clear where it is going. So only the b8 -knight remains.} 7. Na3 Bxa3 {We always take this knight!} 8. Rxa3 O-O {An interesting position. We should never try to keep the c4 -pawn alive. Instead, we should play for the squares on the queenside. The main idea is to play ... a5 to get access to the b4 -square. The other thing we want is to place our central pawns on dark squares, i.e. to push ... e5 and ... c5 . As we have given up the dark squared bishop, we should make sure not to lose control over the dark squares entirely.} 9. b3 cxb3 10. a5 {This is an interesting suggestion from the engine. It looks a bit odd, but the b2 -pawn was the least important pawn for White, and exchanging it for a few tempi often makes sense in these Reti positions.} e5 11. Qxb3 {Now White is intending d4 next, so we don't really have time to play the slow ... h6 as in the previous line.} e4 12. Ng5 h6 {The cleanest solution. We give back the pawn, but in return get enough time for developing.} 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Bxe4 Nc5 {The point. We win back the bishop pair.} 15. Bh7+ {A small trick to gain a tempo.} Kxh7 16. Qc2+ Kg8 17. Qxc5 Re8 {Sometimes we should be a bit careful when the opponents have two extra central pawns like here. In this specific situation this is compensated for by the slightly weakened light squares around White's king, as well as the fact that we traded a couple of minor pieces, which makes the effect of the center much less.} *

