eenside. The main idea is to play ... a5 to get access to the b4 -square. The other thing we want is to place our central pawns on dark squares, i.e. to push ... e5 and ... c5 . As we have given up the dark squared bishop, we should make sure not to lose control over the dark squares entirely.} 9. a5 {This is an important move. When White plays a5 , our main strategic idea of playing ... a5 and sitting on the queenside squares disappear, which means that we lost some of our long term compensation for the bishop pair. This in turn means that we need to act more quickly.} e5 {Creating counterplay in the center while White picks up the c4 -pawn.} 10. Qc2 h6 {An important move. We want to play ... e4 , but currently it can be strongly met by Ng5 .} 11. e4 {The safest for White, not allowing us to play e4 .} Ne8 {A beautiful idea! The knight is heading towards d4 via d6 - b5 !} 12. Qxc4 Nd6 13. Qc2 Nb5 14. Ra4 c5 {Cementing our control over the d4 -square. This square in itself is enough compensation for the bishop pair, and apart from that White's pieces are also somewhat stupidly placed. For instance, the bishop on g2 is not doing much with the pawn on e4 blocking it. Next we can build slowly, but also jump ... Nd4 whenever we feel like it.} *

