esting ways to play that are not giving an advantage, but forces Black to show precision and knowledge. Instead, I want to play in a much less forcing manner, getting a normal game instead of a memory test.}) 5. O-O (5. a4 {Another possible move order for White that is very likely to transpose later on.} Nf6 6. Na3 (6. O-O Nbd7 {transposes to the current line.}) 6... Bxa3 {We always take this knight once it appears on a3 .} 7. Rxa3 O-O 8. O-O Nbd7 {again transposes to the line we are studying.}) 5... Nf6 {Continuing development. We don't want to move the f8 -bishop as we want to capture on a3 in one move, but we also don't want to move the b-pawn, as it is not yet clear if we want ... b6 or ... b5 .} ({By the way, this position is also commonly reached from a Queen's Gambit move order, i.e. c4 e6 Nf3 d5 g3 dxc4 Bg2} 5... Nf6 {O-O c6 , so Queen's Gambit players can easily pick it up as well. Stylistically, it's not very clearly aimed at neither Slav nor QGD, but should go well with both.}) 6. a4 {The main move, and Shankland's recommendation in his LTR on the Reti. Most sources I found actually stops here and says that White has a pleasant position, and I recognize this is what you can expect from a well-prepared player. Needless to say, having your opponents out of book by move 6 should be considered an achievement!} (6. Na3 Bxa3 7. bxa3 O-O {The doubled a-pawns is actually not a big concern for White here, as they provide open files and diagonals. The problem for White is rather that we will keep our pawn with ... b5 next, and then have easy development with ... Bb7 and ... Nbd7 .}) 6... Nbd7 {We don't want to move our f8 -bishop as we want to capture a knight on a3 in one move. We also don't want to move the b-pawn, as it is not yet clear where it is going. So only the b8 -knight remains.} 7. Qc2 {The main move. White is simply trying to win the pawn back.} b6 {We still don't want to move the f8 -bishop. Playing ... b5 is too risky with White's pawn already on a4 , so we settle for the more modest ... b6 .} 8. Na3 {This looks like the critical move. White is aiming to win the bishop pair.} Bxa3 9. Rxa3 Bb7 {Important. We have to be ready to oppose on the long diagonal.} 10. Qxc4 O-O {A very interesting position. White has the two bishops and no real weaknesses, but all our pieces are well-placed, and we have many simple moves to improve our position. The main issue for White is that it's very hard to come up with a plan. There are no good pawn breaks, and as soon as the f3 -knight moves we are able to trade off the bishop pair. Meanwhile, we first play ... c5 , but then just keep improving with small moves like ... Re8 , ... Qe7 , ... Rad8 etc. Flicking in ... a5 to strengthen our grip on the queenside squares also makes sense.} 11. d4 c5 12. dxc5 Bd5 {A typical intermediate move, forcing the queen to choose a side.} 13. Qh4 (13. Qc2 Nxc5 {We have no problems whatsoever with our beautifully active pieces.}) 13... bxc5 {With the queen far away from the queenside, it makes sense to put some pressure along the b-file. White is very far away from being able to put pressure on the isolated c-pawn.} *

