, so we settle for the more modest ... b6 .} 8. Na3 {This looks like the critical move. White is aiming to win the bishop pair.} Bxa3 9. Rxa3 Bb7 {Important. We have to be ready to oppose on the long diagonal.} 10. Qxc4 O-O {A very interesting position. White has the two bishops and no real weaknesses, but all our pieces are well-placed, and we have many simple moves to improve our position. The main issue for White is that it's very hard to come up with a plan. There are no good pawn breaks, and as soon as the f3 -knight moves we are able to trade off the bishop pair. Meanwhile, we first play ... c5 , but then just keep improving with small moves like ... Re8 , ... Qe7 , ... Rad8 etc. Flicking in ... a5 to strengthen our grip on the queenside squares also makes sense.} 11. b4 {The only forcing move. We should not let White grab additional space undisturbed.} a5 12. bxa5 (12. b5 cxb5 {Utilizing the fact that the positionally desirable Qxb5 is not possible due to ... Ba6 , winning the e2 -pawn.}) 12... Rxa5 {We get good counterplay against the a-pawn.} *

