1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3 {The Reti. When I started to play chess, this was considered something to play when one wanted to avoid all theory. Needless to say, 15 years later, things are very different. Now it's just a mainline, and White is certainly intending to add theoretical pressure.} dxc4 {From the White side this was always what bothered me the most, and it goes well together with the rest of our repertoire.} ({•} 3... Bg4 {This, together with it's sibling 3... Bf5 , is perhaps the 'purest' Slav move, but I have played and analyzed this a lot from the White side for many years already, and my conclusion is that it's very pleasant for White. Perhaps it's not an objective advantage per se, but the amount of details Black need to be familiar with to equalize is simply too many. Even more important though is that if both White and Black play 'by hand' I believe White's position is much easier to play!}) ({•} 3... g6 {Very solid, and if you have the Gruenfeld in your repertoire it makes a lot of sense. For our repertoire though it leads to rather different structures, and insofar as possible I prefer to avoid fianchettoing our dark squared bishop.}) 4. Bg2 e6 5. O-O (5. a4 {Another possible move order for White that is very likely to transpose later on.} Nf6 6. Na3 (6. O-O Nbd7 {transposes to the current line.}) 6... Bxa3 {We always take this knight once it appears on a3 .} 7. Rxa3 O-O 8. O-O Nbd7 {again transposes to the line we are studying.}) 5... Nf6 6. a4 {The main move, and Shankland's recommendation in his LTR on the Reti. Most sources I found actually stops here and says that White has a pleasant position, and I recognize this is what you can expect from a well-prepared player. Needless to say, having your opponents out of book by move 6 should be considered an achievement!} (6. Na3 Bxa3 7. bxa3 O-O {The doubled a-pawns is actually not a big concern for White here, as they provide open files and diagonals. The problem for White is rather that we will keep our pawn with ... b5 next, and then have easy development with ... Bb7 and ... Nbd7 .}) 6... Nbd7 7. Qc2 (7. Na3 Bxa3 {We always take this knight.} 8. Rxa3 O-O 9. Qc2 a5 $1 {We fix our pawns on dark squares, to fight against White's dark squared bishop.}) 7... b6 8. Na3 (8. Qxc4 Bb7 {Entirely innocent as we easily get to play ... c5 and oppose on the long diagonal.}) 8... Bxa3 9. Rxa3 Bb7 10. Qxc4 O-O 11. b3 c5 12. Bb2 a5 {Our dark squared control gives us enough stability to compensate the bishop pair. There is no rush, so just activate our pieces bit by bit.} *

