1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 ({Basically we have the same choices as after} 2. c4 c6 {Nf3} 3. cxd5 {g3 , and they all have the same downsides.}) (2. b3 Nf6 3. Bb2 e6 {transposes to chapter 16 . This is the move order chosen by FM Dalton Perrine and GM Yaroslav Zherebukh in their The Reti: Nimzo-Larsen Attack .}) 2... Nd7 {Trying to provoke d4 , which often takes Reti players out of their comfort zone. By the way, even if you are a Queen's Gambit player, it can be worth considering adding the 2... Nd7 line to your repertoire. It's true that it's stylistically slightly more similar to the Slav than the QGD, but all the lines are independent and fresh, so you won't ever have to worry about transpositions.} (2... Nc6 {Another funky line that has gotten some popularity recently. It's fairly fresh and although not the most solid still a viable alternative. Stylistically, I prefer 2... Nd7 as it reminds a bit more about the Slav.}) 3. d4 (3. Bg2 {Plichta's recommendation in his Reti course.} e5 4. O-O Ngf6 5. d3 {The pure King's Indian Attack.} (5. d4 {This is his idea.} e4 6. Ne5 Bd6 7. Nxd7 Bxd7 8. c4 h6 $1 {An important move to remember. We need to prevent Bg5 .} 9. cxd5 O-O {We have sacrificed a pawn, but our e4 -pawn is a great asset and all our pieces have natural squares.}) 5... Be7 6. Nbd2 O-O 7. e4 {Never try to keep the center with ... c6 once White attacks it like this. We shouldn't forget that we are playing Black, after all.} dxe4 8. dxe4 c6 {This is our setup. Now there are various ways to develop our pieces, but in my view the most harmonious is ... Qc7 , ... Re8 and then push the a-pawn.}) 3... Nb6 {Basically, the whole idea is that we can safely develop our bishop outside the pawn chain, and the loss of time doesn't matter much as White struggles to open up the center quickly.} (3... b5 {As a less mature chess player, I jabbed a bit with this sideline. At first, it looks provocative and interesting, but nowadays, I think it's a bit too much.}) 4. Nc3 {Actually the main move. White has a concrete idea in mind.} ({•} 4. Nbd2 Bf5 5. Nh4 {This is the only other thing to keep in mind. It's a little less common than 4. Nc3 , but as 5... Bg4 is starting to gain in popularity, I predict more people might switch to 4. Nbd2 .} e6 (5... Bg4 $6 {Unfortunately, this works less well here, which is the reason for 4. Nbd2 .} 6. h3 Bh5 7. Ng2 $1 {If we continue along similar paths as against 4. Nc3 , the knight will simply be much better on d2 .}) 6. Nxf5 exf5 {This is now a better version than against 4. Nc3 . There are two reasons: White does not have the tempo-gaining move Qd3 available, and the other and more important that the knight is blocking White from playing Bg5 , meaning we get to keep our knight.}) ({•} 4. Bg2 Bf5 5. O-O e6 {If White plays slowly we have nothing to worry about. Just develop with ... Ngf6 , ... Be7 and ... c6 .}) 4... Bf5 5. Nh4 Bg4 {This is the move that resparked my interesting in the 2... Nd7 -line. We save the bishop, or at least invite White to make some serious concessions to trap it. It's the perfect balance between provocative and healthy. It's still fairly rare, and I believe your opponents will most likely be taken off-guard by it.} (5... e6 {This is what White is hoping for} 6. Nxf5 exf5 {A quick sample line to show why White is better:} 7. Qd3 g6 8. Bg2 {White is waiting for ... Nf6 . We can delay it for a while, but eventually it has to be played.} Bg7 9. O-O Nf6 10. Bg5 $1 {This is the issue. White simply wants to trade on f6 , remove the c3 -knight and slowly push c4 . In the meantime, there is very little Black can do to get counterplay.}) 6. h3 (6. Qd3 Nf6 7. Bg2 e6 8. e4 {The only thing to remember is to not trade on e4} Be7 {With a perfectly healthy position. If White pushes e5 we get an excellent version of the French or the Caro-Kann.}) 6... Bh5 7. Ng2 {The critical attempt. It was played against be my the strong GM Theodorou, but I find it rather unlikely to be played on lower levels.} e6 {An important move order subtletly. We delay ... Nf6 for a little while.} 8. Nf4 Bg6 9. Nxg6 {Not the only move, but the most logical one.} hxg6 10. Bg2 f5 {This is why we delayed ... Nf6 ! Now we get an excellent grip on the e4 -square and can develop peacefully. The knight on c3 is also looking a bit strange. If you face a well-prepared player, I believe this position is rather likely to arise.} *

