1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 ({Basically we have the same choices as after} 2. c4 c6 {Nf3} 3. cxd5 {g3 , and they all have the same downsides.}) (2. b3 Nf6 3. Bb2 e6 {transposes to chapter 16 . This is the move order chosen by FM Dalton Perrine and GM Yaroslav Zherebukh in their The Reti: Nimzo-Larsen Attack .}) 2... Nd7 ({A controversial choice! Recently, both} 2... Nc6 {and Nd7 has gotten some popularity. I prefer putting the knight on d7 , as many of the resulting lines are similar to what we get in the Slav repertoire. Another thing I really like with Nd7 is that we are the ones choosing the direction of the game. White is more or less obliged to play into positions that we are more familiar with, whereas if we would play a system based on for example Bg4 (which many Slav players do) it is primarily White who can choose the central structure.}) 3. Bg2 {The automatic response, but it does allow us to execute our idea.} e5 4. O-O Ngf6 {A healthy developing move. 4... e4 would be overextending a bit, as we are not ready to support such a big center.} 5. d4 {This is recommended by Plichta in his LTR: King's Indian Attack.} e4 {The most ambitious move, intending to keep the center alive. We should be careful when playing such ambitious moves in the opening, especially with the black pieces, but here it seems to work out well.} 6. Ne5 Bd6 7. Nxd7 ({The only good move.} 7. Bf4 Qe7 {Would force the exchange anyway, while winning quite some time for Black.}) 7... Bxd7 8. Bg5 {Seeing our next move, it's a logical question to ask why not this first.} h6 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 10. c4 h5 {This is the answer to the question on move 8. It turns out that we very quickly are drumming up a strong attack!} 11. Nc3 h4 12. c5 {Already the only move not to be significantly worse.} hxg3 13. fxg3 Qh6 14. cxd6 Qxh2+ 15. Kf2 {Amazingly, we are not yet winning here.} Bh3 16. Rg1 e3+ {This is the best I was able to find. We win back the piece with an ongoing attack, but there is no direct breakthrough.} 17. Kxe3 Bxg2 18. dxc7 O-O {The White king is still vulnerable, and the material is equal, but with correct play White is still defending. Still not a bad outcome of the opening, though!} *

