1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 ({Basically we have the same choices as after} 2. c4 c6 {Nf3} 3. cxd5 {g3 , and they all have the same downsides.}) (2. b3 Nf6 3. Bb2 e6 {transposes to chapter 16 . This is the move order chosen by FM Dalton Perrine and GM Yaroslav Zherebukh in their The Reti: Nimzo-Larsen Attack .}) 2... Nd7 ({A controversial choice! Recently, both} 2... Nc6 {and Nd7 has gotten some popularity. I prefer putting the knight on d7 , as many of the resulting lines are similar to what we get in the Slav repertoire. Another thing I really like with Nd7 is that we are the ones choosing the direction of the game. White is more or less obliged to play into positions that we are more familiar with, whereas if we would play a system based on for example Bg4 (which many Slav players do) it is primarily White who can choose the central structure.}) 3. Bg2 {The automatic response, but it does allow us to execute our idea.} e5 4. O-O Ngf6 {A healthy developing move. 4... e4 would be overextending a bit, as we are not ready to support such a big center.} 5. d4 {This is recommended by Plichta in his LTR: King's Indian Attack.} e4 {The most ambitious move, intending to keep the center alive. We should be careful when playing such ambitious moves in the opening, especially with the black pieces, but here it seems to work out well.} 6. Ne5 Bd6 7. Nxd7 ({The only good move.} 7. Bf4 Qe7 {Would force the exchange anyway, while winning quite some time for Black.}) 7... Bxd7 8. c4 {Strategically, the only move that makes sense, as White needs to fight against the center.} h6 {This is highly important! White was intending to play Bg5 , putting pressure on our center.} 9. cxd5 O-O {We are a pawn down for the time being, but it's a doubled pawn and our pieces are moving harmoniously.} 10. Nc3 Re8 11. Qc2 {The most logical move, and the recommendation in Plichta's course.} Qe7 12. f3 {The most logical move. f3 is really the main idea for White strategically, and delaying it will not really improve matters.} exf3 (12... e3 $5 {is even sharper and can definitely be investigated as well.}) 13. Bxf3 c5 {Remember this idea! We are OK with exchanging off the doubled pawns in order to open up the position and fight for the initiative.} 14. dxc6 Bxc6 {The main source of compensation is connected to the squares in the center. White will never really be able to push e4 , which means that we can plant a knight there later on. Additionally, the White king is a bit soft and all our pieces are incredibly active.} 15. Qf5 {Plichta's recommendation. The threat is Bxc6 followed by Bxh6 , and the f6 -knight is hanging.} (15. Bd2 Bb4 $5 {would further increase our control over the key e4 -square.}) 15... Bd7 16. Qd3 Bh3 {If we do not want to repeat moves, then this is the best option.} 17. Rf2 Qe6 {Preventing Nd5 . Next up, we bring our rook to d8 . Later, the main idea of counterplay is connected to ... Ng4 , which would force White to give up their best bishop.} 18. e4 Rad8 {The White center looks strong, but is in fact very loose.} *

