[ECO "A54"]
[PlyCount "28"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 ({Basically we have the same choices as after} 2. c4 c6 {Nf3} 3. cxd5 {g3 , and they all have the same downsides.}) (2. b3 Nf6 3. Bb2 e6 {transposes to chapter 16 . This is the move order chosen by FM Dalton Perrine and GM Yaroslav Zherebukh in their The Reti: Nimzo-Larsen Attack .}) 2... Nd7 ({A controversial choice! Recently, both} 2... Nc6 {and Nd7 has gotten some popularity. I prefer putting the knight on d7 , as many of the resulting lines are similar to what we get in the Slav repertoire. Another thing I really like with Nd7 is that we are the ones choosing the direction of the game. White is more or less obliged to play into positions that we are more familiar with, whereas if we would play a system based on for example Bg4 (which many Slav players do) it is primarily White who can choose the central structure.}) 3. Bg2 {The automatic response, but it does allow us to execute our idea.} e5 4. O-O Ngf6 {A healthy developing move. 4... e4 would be overextending a bit, as we are not ready to support such a big center.} 5. d3 {Overwhelmingly most common in practical play, but rather innocent from an objective viewpoint. The King's Indian Attack has gotten some new popularity over the last few years, and is now considered a relatively serious attempt at an advantage for White. Therefore, it's important to understand why this is not a normal King's Indian Attack. The big reason why we have a better version as Black is the fact that we have managed to push ... e5 in one move, without stopping by on e6 first. This basically gives us an extra tempo over many of the traditional King's Indian Attack lines. Still, despite our center looking pretty, we should not get too ambitious. We are comfortably equal, but definitely not better. This also means that when White pushes e4 or c4 , we generally just swap pawns and go for equality rather than trying to keep both pawns on d5 and e5 .} Be7 {The most flexible move. Putting the bishop on c5 looks more active, but I like to keep that square for the knight later on.} 6. c4 {Reti players are likely to play this instead. White is trying to make the g2 -bishop as strong as possible.} dxc4 {Again, don't try to keep the e5 , d5 center alive. It would become more of a weakness than a strength.} 7. dxc4 O-O 8. Nc3 c6 {This move is always a part of our setup. We blunt the g2 -bishop and prepare a nice square on c7 for our queen.} 9. Qc2 Qc7 {This line is not at all forced, and there are many possible move orders. We can basically play our setup with ... Qc7 , ... Re8 and ... h6 against everything.} 10. b3 {The most popular and logical move. The bishop is simply best placed on b2 .} Re8 11. Bb2 h6 {A useful move. One day we might want to push ... e4 (for example, if the knight moves from c3 ) and then Ng5 is no longer possible as a reply. It's also a bit of a waiting move.} 12. Rfd1 {Again, White could play many different moves and move orders here, but it's an entirely unforcing position, so all we need are a couple of ideas of how to play the middlegame.} Bf8 {Always useful. We overprotect e5 (in case we want to move our d7 -knight, which we most likely want next) and open up for a later ... e4 -push.} 13. a3 a5 {This is always our reaction to a3 . We don't want White to gain more space with b4 .} 14. Nd2 Nc5 {Without any pressure on the e5 -pawn, this makes a lot of sense. We have an active and perfectly healthy position.} *

