1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 ({Basically we have the same choices as after} 2. c4 c6 {Nf3} 3. cxd5 {g3 , and they all have the same downsides.}) (2. b3 Nf6 3. Bb2 e6 {transposes to chapter 16 . This is the move order chosen by FM Dalton Perrine and GM Yaroslav Zherebukh in their The Reti: Nimzo-Larsen Attack .}) 2... Nd7 ({A controversial choice! Recently, both} 2... Nc6 {and Nd7 has gotten some popularity. I prefer putting the knight on d7 , as many of the resulting lines are similar to what we get in the Slav repertoire. Another thing I really like with Nd7 is that we are the ones choosing the direction of the game. White is more or less obliged to play into positions that we are more familiar with, whereas if we would play a system based on for example Bg4 (which many Slav players do) it is primarily White who can choose the central structure.}) 3. Bg2 {The automatic response, but it does allow us to execute our idea.} e5 4. O-O Ngf6 {A healthy developing move. 4... e4 would be overextending a bit, as we are not ready to support such a big center.} 5. d3 {Overwhelmingly most common in practical play, but rather innocent from an objective viewpoint. The King's Indian Attack has gotten some new popularity over the last few years, and is now considered a relatively serious attempt at an advantage for White. Therefore, it's important to understand why this is not a normal King's Indian Attack. The big reason why we have a better version as Black is the fact that we have managed to push ... e5 in one move, without stopping by on e6 first. This basically gives us an extra tempo over many of the traditional King's Indian Attack lines. Still, despite our center looking pretty, we should not get too ambitious. We are comfortably equal, but definitely not better. This also means that when White pushes e4 or c4 , we generally just swap pawns and go for equality rather than trying to keep both pawns on d5 and e5 .} Be7 {The most flexible move. Putting the bishop on c5 looks more active, but I like to keep that square for the knight later on.} 6. Nbd2 {The traditional King's Indian Attack move.} O-O 7. e4 dxe4 {As previously mentioned, we always trade as soon as a pawn shows up on e4 or c4 . It's especially tempting to trade after e4 , as we now make the g2 -bishop worse.} 8. dxe4 c6 {This is our setup. The queen is excellently placed on c7 , the rook goes to e8 to support our e5 -pawn, and long term we are going to grab space on the queenside with ... a5 , ... b5 etc. Meanwhile, it's hard for White to create anything, as our position is so solid.} 9. b3 {The most common move in practice. The bishop belong to b2 .} Qc7 {Starting with ... Re8 is also fine and most likely leads to the same thing.} 10. Bb2 Re8 {Overdefending the e5 -pawn. If White attacks it again with Nc4 we can safely defend by ... Bf8 , and apart from that White doesn't really have many active possibilities. We are ready to push ... a5 - a4 next. Don't worry about the c8 -bishop. It will get out eventually, most likely via b7 / a6 after pushing the b-pawn, but there is also no rush to develop it immediately as we have many other useful ideas and plans anyway.} *

