1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 ({Basically we have the same choices as after} 2. c4 c6 {Nf3} 3. cxd5 {g3 , and they all have the same downsides.}) (2. b3 Nf6 3. Bb2 e6 {transposes to chapter 16 . This is the move order chosen by FM Dalton Perrine and GM Yaroslav Zherebukh in their The Reti: Nimzo-Larsen Attack .}) 2... Nd7 ({A controversial choice! Recently, both} 2... Nc6 {and Nd7 has gotten some popularity. I prefer putting the knight on d7 , as many of the resulting lines are similar to what we get in the Slav repertoire. Another thing I really like with Nd7 is that we are the ones choosing the direction of the game. White is more or less obliged to play into positions that we are more familiar with, whereas if we would play a system based on for example Bg4 (which many Slav players do) it is primarily White who can choose the central structure.}) 3. c4 {A rare move, as it does nothing to stop us from playing ... e5 in one move.} dxc4 4. Bg2 (4. Qc2 {Does not really have an independent value.} e5 5. Qxc4 Bd6 {White should play Bg2 soon, transposing to the mainline.} 6. Bg2 Nb6 7. Qc2 Nf6 {transposing.}) 4... e5 {This is one of the main points of 2... Nd7 - we are able to push ... e5 in one go.} 5. Qc2 {Preventing ... e4 and preparing to win back the pawn on c4 .} Bd6 {It's possible to develop our pieces in many different ways, but I quite like the setup with the bishop on d6 and knight on f6 , as it feels the most Slav-esque.} 6. Qxc4 {With the pawn defended on e5 we were threatening to protect our c4 -pawn with ... Nb6 .} Nb6 7. Qc2 Nf6 (7... Ne7 {is another good move, but generally speaking the knight belongs on f6 , of course. This is an entirely untested position with loads of possible moves for both sides, so it's very hard to predict how the game will develop from here on.}) 8. O-O O-O 9. Nc3 h6 {Interesting. ... h6 is always a useful move in these positions, preventing a later Bg5 and especially Ng5 (for example, if we get to play ... e4 later).} 10. d4 {This looks like the critical move, breaking in the center.} ({•} 10. d3 Re8 {Looks very harmonious for us.}) ({•} 10. Rd1 c5 {Simply preventing d4 .}) 10... exd4 11. Nxd4 Bxg3 {Picking up the gauntlet. Without this option, White would enjoy some strategic edge, due to having more central pawns.} 12. hxg3 Qxd4 13. Nb5 {The critical move, winning back the sacrificed pawn.} Qe5 14. Nxc7 Bf5 {Importantly, White does not have enough time to consolidate here.} 15. Qc3 (15. e4 Bxe4 16. Bxe4 Rac8 $1 {Is a nice point. We win back the piece and keep the extra pawn.}) 15... Qxc3 16. bxc3 Rac8 {The small structural deficit compensates for the bishop pair, so the ending is balanced.} *

