1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 ({Basically we have the same choices as after} 2. c4 c6 {Nf3} 3. cxd5 {g3 , and they all have the same downsides.}) (2. b3 Nf6 3. Bb2 e6 {transposes to chapter 16 . This is the move order chosen by FM Dalton Perrine and GM Yaroslav Zherebukh in their The Reti: Nimzo-Larsen Attack .}) 2... Nd7 ({A controversial choice! Recently, both} 2... Nc6 {and Nd7 has gotten some popularity. I prefer putting the knight on d7 , as many of the resulting lines are similar to what we get in the Slav repertoire. Another thing I really like with Nd7 is that we are the ones choosing the direction of the game. White is more or less obliged to play into positions that we are more familiar with, whereas if we would play a system based on for example Bg4 (which many Slav players do) it is primarily White who can choose the central structure.}) 3. d4 (3. Bg2 {Plichta's recommendation in his Reti course.} e5 4. O-O Ngf6 5. d3 {The pure King's Indian Attack.} (5. d4 {This is his idea.} e4 6. Ne5 Bd6 7. Nxd7 Bxd7 8. c4 h6 $1 {An important move to remember. We need to prevent Bg5 .} 9. cxd5 O-O {We have sacrificed a pawn, but our e4 -pawn is a great asset and all our pieces have natural squares.}) 5... Be7 6. Nbd2 O-O 7. e4 {Never try to keep the center with ... c6 once White attacks it like this. We shouldn't forget that we are playing Black, after all.} dxe4 8. dxe4 c6 {This is our setup. Now there are various ways to develop our pieces, but in my view the most harmonious is ... Qc7 , ... Re8 and then push the a-pawn.}) 3... Nb6 {This is the move that brought 2... Nd7 into fashion again, when Alekseenko used it to beat Karjakin in the Grand Swiss 2019, and qualified for the Candidates. It looks a bit clumsy to put the knight on b6 , and indeed it is, but the main thing is that we have provoked d4 . In almost all Reti systems, White is trying to make the g2 -bishop strong, but here that is almost impossible. We will develop our bishop to f5 , then support the center with both ... e6 and ... c6 . This means that the g2 -bishop will be blunted basically forever. The downside for us is that it does take some time, and the knight is in itself not that great on b6 .} 4. Nbd2 {This is an interesting line, especially if we are aware of the lines after 4. Nc3 . White is basically trying to do the same thing, but the knight on d2 instead of c3 makes quite a difference.} Bf5 5. Nh4 e6 {An exception to the rule of always playing ... Bg4 after Nh4 . Luckily for us, in the positions after exf5 , the knight is quite badly placed on d2 , as it blocks the bishop on c1 .} (5... Bg4 {This was tried by David Anton Guijarro, but it works less well than against 4. Nc3 .} 6. h3 Bh5 7. Ng2 e6 8. Nf4 Bg6 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. e4 {This is the problem. With the knight on c3 we would now make the pin ... Bb4 , and White's center would be vulnerable. Here that does not exist, so White will simply end up with the center and the bishop pair.}) 6. Nxf5 exf5 7. Bg2 c6 {A good cementing move, making sure we can safely meet c4 with dxc4 .} 8. O-O Nf6 {Here White would really like to play Bg5 , as we will see in the line after 4. Nc3 .} 9. Nb3 {This is the critical move. White insists on getting Bg5 to work.} Bd6 10. Qd3 {The best move. White is trying to attack us concretely before we have time to castle.} Qc8 {Stepping out of the g5 - d8 pin. Now Bg5 can always be met by ... Ne4 .} 11. Bh3 {This is the point of White.} g6 12. Bh6 {Just in time before we can castle. This line eventually works out great for Black, but it's important to know it.} Bf8 {We need to be able to castle.} 13. Qe3+ {The point! Trading dark squared bishops is good for us, and if the bishop had retreated, we would play ... Bg7 and get castled.} Qe6 14. Qxe6+ fxe6 15. Bxf8 {It looks like White is just trading off their good pieces for our more passive ones, but there is a concrete idea in the end.} Rxf8 16. Nc5 {This is the whole point of the line starting with 10.Qd3! Had we gotten one more move the ending would simply be better for us, but now White wins a pawn.} Ke7 17. Nxb7 Rfc8 {Luckily for us, even a pawn down, we have a great position. The reason is that all our pieces are very active (or soon to be active) whereas the White bishop is completely out of play on h3 . Moreover, our king is much closer to the action, which is always a good thing in the ending. What we need to do now is to get rid of the annoying White knight, preferably trade it for one of our own, then push ... c5 and combine pressure on the b- and c-files. I've played around a fair bit with this position, and it seems to me that by natural moves from both sides, White is the one more likely ending up in trouble!} *

