1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 ({Basically we have the same choices as after} 2. c4 c6 {Nf3} 3. cxd5 {g3 , and they all have the same downsides.}) (2. b3 Nf6 3. Bb2 e6 {transposes to chapter 16 . This is the move order chosen by FM Dalton Perrine and GM Yaroslav Zherebukh in their The Reti: Nimzo-Larsen Attack .}) 2... Nd7 ({A controversial choice! Recently, both} 2... Nc6 {and Nd7 has gotten some popularity. I prefer putting the knight on d7 , as many of the resulting lines are similar to what we get in the Slav repertoire. Another thing I really like with Nd7 is that we are the ones choosing the direction of the game. White is more or less obliged to play into positions that we are more familiar with, whereas if we would play a system based on for example Bg4 (which many Slav players do) it is primarily White who can choose the central structure.}) 3. d4 (3. Bg2 {Plichta's recommendation in his Reti course.} e5 4. O-O Ngf6 5. d3 {The pure King's Indian Attack.} (5. d4 {This is his idea.} e4 6. Ne5 Bd6 7. Nxd7 Bxd7 8. c4 h6 $1 {An important move to remember. We need to prevent Bg5 .} 9. cxd5 O-O {We have sacrificed a pawn, but our e4 -pawn is a great asset and all our pieces have natural squares.}) 5... Be7 6. Nbd2 O-O 7. e4 {Never try to keep the center with ... c6 once White attacks it like this. We shouldn't forget that we are playing Black, after all.} dxe4 8. dxe4 c6 {This is our setup. Now there are various ways to develop our pieces, but in my view the most harmonious is ... Qc7 , ... Re8 and then push the a-pawn.}) 3... Nb6 {This is the move that brought 2... Nd7 into fashion again, when Alekseenko used it to beat Karjakin in the Grand Swiss 2019, and qualified for the Candidates. It looks a bit clumsy to put the knight on b6 , and indeed it is, but the main thing is that we have provoked d4 . In almost all Reti systems, White is trying to make the g2 -bishop strong, but here that is almost impossible. We will develop our bishop to f5 , then support the center with both ... e6 and ... c6 . This means that the g2 -bishop will be blunted basically forever. The downside for us is that it does take some time, and the knight is in itself not that great on b6 .} 4. Bg2 {Overwhelmingly most popular, but in my view actually a bit sloppy! Basically, if we manage to get our setup, we will be completely fine, so White should try to hit us with something concrete quickly. And for this purpose, Bg2 is not the most direct move.} Bf5 {We always develop the bishop outside the pawn chain. This is one of the big points of our system.} 5. O-O e6 {We should think about the move orders. Usually, delaying ... Nf6 is a good idea. One reason is that ... Nf6 allows the Bg5 -pin, and another that we no longer can play ... f6 if White plays Ne5 . The pawn should always go to e6 , so it makes the most sense to start with it.} 6. Ne5 {This was Karjakin's attempt in the famous game with Alekseenko, but it hasn't really caught on since then.} c6 {Starting with 6... Nf6 also makes sense, especially if you want to avoid the complications in our mainline.} 7. f3 {This has been tried a couple of times, and also makes sense. White is intending to push e4 .} h5 {A slightly provocative but very interesting novelty. f3 has weakened White's kingside, so we immediately play to attack it!} 8. e4 Bh7 {Don't worry too much about White getting the center with e4 . There is no obvious way to utilize it, and meanwhile we can continue with our own play.} 9. Be3 h4 {We are of course not attacking with a lot of pieces, but the h-file will be open and the g3 -pawn a bit soft.} 10. g4 {Trying to keep the kingside blocked, but it looks ugly!} h3 11. Bh1 f6 12. Nd3 e5 {Highlighting the vulnerability of White's kingside.} 13. dxe5 Nc4 14. Bf2 dxe4 15. fxe4 Nxe5 {Winning back the pawn and keeping some initiative. The white kingside looks rather vulnerable.} *

