.. e6 and ... c6 . This means that the g2 -bishop will be blunted basically forever. The downside for us is that it does take some time, and the knight is in itself not that great on b6 .} 4. Bg2 {Overwhelmingly most popular, but in my view actually a bit sloppy! Basically, if we manage to get our setup, we will be completely fine, so White should try to hit us with something concrete quickly. And for this purpose, Bg2 is not the most direct move.} Bf5 {We always develop the bishop outside the pawn chain. This is one of the big points of our system.} 5. O-O e6 {We should think about the move orders. Usually, delaying ... Nf6 is a good idea. One reason is that ... Nf6 allows the Bg5 -pin, and another that we no longer can play ... f6 if White plays Ne5 . The pawn should always go to e6 , so it makes the most sense to start with it.} 6. Ne5 {This was Karjakin's attempt in the famous game with Alekseenko, but it hasn't really caught on since then.} c6 {Starting with 6... Nf6 also makes sense, especially if you want to avoid the complications in our mainline.} 7. f3 {This has been tried a couple of times, and also makes sense. White is intending to push e4 .} h5 {A slightly provocative but very interesting novelty. f3 has weakened White's kingside, so we immediately play to attack it!} 8. e4 Bh7 {Don't worry too much about White getting the center with e4 . There is no obvious way to utilize it, and meanwhile we can continue with our own play.} 9. Be3 h4 {We are of course not attacking with a lot of pieces, but the h-file will be open and the g3 -pawn a bit soft.} 10. Nd2 hxg3 11. hxg3 Qc7 12. Bf2 Bd6 {We have good counterplay. ... f6 is on the agenda, but even just developing with ... Nf6 makes sense. The White center looks rather vulnerable, and our king will probably be safe on the queenside after castling long. It's a highly imbalanced and double-edged position to play, so should be fun!} *

