1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 ({Basically we have the same choices as after} 2. c4 c6 {Nf3} 3. cxd5 {g3 , and they all have the same downsides.}) (2. b3 Nf6 3. Bb2 e6 {transposes to chapter 16 . This is the move order chosen by FM Dalton Perrine and GM Yaroslav Zherebukh in their The Reti: Nimzo-Larsen Attack .}) 2... Nd7 ({A controversial choice! Recently, both} 2... Nc6 {and Nd7 has gotten some popularity. I prefer putting the knight on d7 , as many of the resulting lines are similar to what we get in the Slav repertoire. Another thing I really like with Nd7 is that we are the ones choosing the direction of the game. White is more or less obliged to play into positions that we are more familiar with, whereas if we would play a system based on for example Bg4 (which many Slav players do) it is primarily White who can choose the central structure.}) 3. d4 (3. Bg2 {Plichta's recommendation in his Reti course.} e5 4. O-O Ngf6 5. d3 {The pure King's Indian Attack.} (5. d4 {This is his idea.} e4 6. Ne5 Bd6 7. Nxd7 Bxd7 8. c4 h6 $1 {An important move to remember. We need to prevent Bg5 .} 9. cxd5 O-O {We have sacrificed a pawn, but our e4 -pawn is a great asset and all our pieces have natural squares.}) 5... Be7 6. Nbd2 O-O 7. e4 {Never try to keep the center with ... c6 once White attacks it like this. We shouldn't forget that we are playing Black, after all.} dxe4 8. dxe4 c6 {This is our setup. Now there are various ways to develop our pieces, but in my view the most harmonious is ... Qc7 , ... Re8 and then push the a-pawn.}) 3... Nb6 {This is the move that brought 2... Nd7 into fashion again, when Alekseenko used it to beat Karjakin in the Grand Swiss 2019, and qualified for the Candidates. It looks a bit clumsy to put the knight on b6 , and indeed it is, but the main thing is that we have provoked d4 . In almost all Reti systems, White is trying to make the g2 -bishop strong, but here that is almost impossible. We will develop our bishop to f5 , then support the center with both ... e6 and ... c6 . This means that the g2 -bishop will be blunted basically forever. The downside for us is that it does take some time, and the knight is in itself not that great on b6 .} 4. Bg2 {Overwhelmingly most popular, but in my view actually a bit sloppy! Basically, if we manage to get our setup, we will be completely fine, so White should try to hit us with something concrete quickly. And for this purpose, Bg2 is not the most direct move.} Bf5 {We always develop the bishop outside the pawn chain. This is one of the big points of our system.} 5. O-O e6 {We should think about the move orders. Usually, delaying ... Nf6 is a good idea. One reason is that ... Nf6 allows the Bg5 -pin, and another that we no longer can play ... f6 if White plays Ne5 . The pawn should always go to e6 , so it makes the most sense to start with it.} 6. Nbd2 {A logical developing move, but not enough to put us under pressure.} Nf6 7. b3 {This looks natural and the first time I saw the line I thought something like this makes the most sense for White. But it's not so simple, as b3 is also costing White a tempo, and a bishop on b2 is not doing that much.} h6 {Not necessary at all, but when White gives us so much time we might as well save the bishop.} 8. c4 c6 {We should never take on c4 if White can recapture with a pawn. Now White can gain further space with c5 , but as we know from for instance the Fianchetto Slav, this will give us good counterplay based on a later ... e5 -break.} 9. Bb2 Be7 {We are fine, and I don't see any reason for knowing more concrete moves. Next we castle, and for further plans pushing ... a5 - a4 is always a good idea. Jumping ... Ne4 could also make sense, but there is no rush. White can't really push e4 in a good way, and apart from that there really aren't that many plans available.} *

