[Black "3.d4 Nb6 4.a4 #1"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D02"]
[PlyCount "18"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 ({Basically we have the same choices as after} 2. c4 c6 {Nf3} 3. cxd5 {g3 , and they all have the same downsides.}) (2. b3 Nf6 3. Bb2 e6 {transposes to chapter 16 . This is the move order chosen by FM Dalton Perrine and GM Yaroslav Zherebukh in their The Reti: Nimzo-Larsen Attack .}) 2... Nd7 ({A controversial choice! Recently, both} 2... Nc6 {and Nd7 has gotten some popularity. I prefer putting the knight on d7 , as many of the resulting lines are similar to what we get in the Slav repertoire. Another thing I really like with Nd7 is that we are the ones choosing the direction of the game. White is more or less obliged to play into positions that we are more familiar with, whereas if we would play a system based on for example Bg4 (which many Slav players do) it is primarily White who can choose the central structure.}) 3. d4 (3. Bg2 {Plichta's recommendation in his Reti course.} e5 4. O-O Ngf6 5. d3 {The pure King's Indian Attack.} (5. d4 {This is his idea.} e4 6. Ne5 Bd6 7. Nxd7 Bxd7 8. c4 h6 $1 {An important move to remember. We need to prevent Bg5 .} 9. cxd5 O-O {We have sacrificed a pawn, but our e4 -pawn is a great asset and all our pieces have natural squares.}) 5... Be7 6. Nbd2 O-O 7. e4 {Never try to keep the center with ... c6 once White attacks it like this. We shouldn't forget that we are playing Black, after all.} dxe4 8. dxe4 c6 {This is our setup. Now there are various ways to develop our pieces, but in my view the most harmonious is ... Qc7 , ... Re8 and then push the a-pawn.}) 3... Nb6 {This is the move that brought 2... Nd7 into fashion again, when Alekseenko used it to beat Karjakin in the Grand Swiss 2019, and qualified for the Candidates. It looks a bit clumsy to put the knight on b6 , and indeed it is, but the main thing is that we have provoked d4 . In almost all Reti systems, White is trying to make the g2 -bishop strong, but here that is almost impossible. We will develop our bishop to f5 , then support the center with both ... e6 and ... c6 . This means that the g2 -bishop will be blunted basically forever. The downside for us is that it does take some time, and the knight is in itself not that great on b6 .} 4. a4 a5 {This is almost universally the reaction. Otherwise the knight ends up on a stupid square.} 5. b3 Bf5 6. Ba3 c6 {In general against Ba3 I like this reaction. Playing ... e6 immediately and recapturing with the king is also OK, but I quite like to be able to castle later. And after White has played b3 , the knight is anyway not doing a lot on b6 .} 7. Bg2 Nd7 8. O-O e6 9. Bxf8 Nxf8 {We will be able to develop peacefully and the loss of time is not that relevant, as White is unable to open up the position quickly.} *

