.. e6 and ... c6 . This means that the g2 -bishop will be blunted basically forever. The downside for us is that it does take some time, and the knight is in itself not that great on b6 .} 4. Nc3 {This is the most critical move for White, although in practice it hasn't yet taken over. When I faced this line myself as White, I choose 4. Nc3 , and when I prepared to play it with Black, it was 4. Nc3 that was my main focus of attention. Indeed, the one classical game I tried the Nd7 - b6 line my opponent played 4. Nc3 . The point for White is rather specific - they anticipate us playing ... Bf5 next, and want to meet it with Nh4 . Surprisingly, the g2 -square is going to be needed for the knight rather than the bishop! Sounds strange, but it will all become clear once we look at the concrete lines.} Bf5 5. Nh4 {The most direct move, and the point of 4. Nc3 .} Bg4 {This is our concept. We don't want to allow White to take on f5 . It is my understanding that the idea of ... Bg4 is still an underestimated one. For instance, when I got to play it myself recently against the very strong GM Theodorou he was completely unaware what to do against it, and I myself when playing this line with White hadn't really taken ... Bg4 seriously, instead expecting to get the very pleasant positions after Nxf5 next. Generally, ... Bg4 to my taste is the perfect balance between being somewhat provocative while still sound.} 6. Qd3 {This is one of the important options. Without our bishop on f4 , White is able to push e4 .} Nf6 7. Bg2 e6 8. e4 Be7 {This is our normal reaction. We are not afraid of White pushing e5 , as the resulting French/Caro-Kann style position is in our favour with the bishop outside the pawn chain and possibilities to immediately attack the center with ... c5 .} 9. O-O (9. h3 Bh5 10. g4 {Is similar to the position with both sides having castled.} Nxe4 11. Nxe4 Bxh4 $1 ({Just avoid the trick} 11... dxe4 $2 12. Qb5+ $1) 12. gxh5 dxe4 13. Qxe4 c6 {Black is very solid.}) 9... O-O 10. exd5 (10. e5 {This is strategically dubious.} Nfd7 11. Nf3 c5 $1 {The white center is just collapsing.}) 10... exd5 {These Exchange French style positions are very healthy for us, as we have no weaknesses and no bad pieces.} 11. Nf5 Bb4 {Saving the bishop. The knight on f5 is pretty, but that's really the only thing going for White.} *

