1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 ({Basically we have the same choices as after} 2. c4 c6 {Nf3} 3. cxd5 {g3 , and they all have the same downsides.}) (2. b3 Nf6 3. Bb2 e6 {transposes to chapter 16 . This is the move order chosen by FM Dalton Perrine and GM Yaroslav Zherebukh in their The Reti: Nimzo-Larsen Attack .}) 2... Nd7 ({A controversial choice! Recently, both} 2... Nc6 {and Nd7 has gotten some popularity. I prefer putting the knight on d7 , as many of the resulting lines are similar to what we get in the Slav repertoire. Another thing I really like with Nd7 is that we are the ones choosing the direction of the game. White is more or less obliged to play into positions that we are more familiar with, whereas if we would play a system based on for example Bg4 (which many Slav players do) it is primarily White who can choose the central structure.}) 3. d4 (3. Bg2 {Plichta's recommendation in his Reti course.} e5 4. O-O Ngf6 5. d3 {The pure King's Indian Attack.} (5. d4 {This is his idea.} e4 6. Ne5 Bd6 7. Nxd7 Bxd7 8. c4 h6 $1 {An important move to remember. We need to prevent Bg5 .} 9. cxd5 O-O {We have sacrificed a pawn, but our e4 -pawn is a great asset and all our pieces have natural squares.}) 5... Be7 6. Nbd2 O-O 7. e4 {Never try to keep the center with ... c6 once White attacks it like this. We shouldn't forget that we are playing Black, after all.} dxe4 8. dxe4 c6 {This is our setup. Now there are various ways to develop our pieces, but in my view the most harmonious is ... Qc7 , ... Re8 and then push the a-pawn.}) 3... Nb6 {This is the move that brought 2... Nd7 into fashion again, when Alekseenko used it to beat Karjakin in the Grand Swiss 2019, and qualified for the Candidates. It looks a bit clumsy to put the knight on b6 , and indeed it is, but the main thing is that we have provoked d4 . In almost all Reti systems, White is trying to make the g2 -bishop strong, but here that is almost impossible. We will develop our bishop to f5 , then support the center with both ... e6 and ... c6 . This means that the g2 -bishop will be blunted basically forever. The downside for us is that it does take some time, and the knight is in itself not that great on b6 .} 4. Nc3 {This is the most critical move for White, although in practice it hasn't yet taken over. When I faced this line myself as White, I choose 4. Nc3 , and when I prepared to play it with Black, it was 4. Nc3 that was my main focus of attention. Indeed, the one classical game I tried the Nd7 - b6 line my opponent played 4. Nc3 . The point for White is rather specific - they anticipate us playing ... Bf5 next, and want to meet it with Nh4 . Surprisingly, the g2 -square is going to be needed for the knight rather than the bishop! Sounds strange, but it will all become clear once we look at the concrete lines.} Bf5 5. Nh4 {The most direct move, and the point of 4. Nc3 .} Bg4 {This is our concept. We don't want to allow White to take on f5 . It is my understanding that the idea of ... Bg4 is still an underestimated one. For instance, when I got to play it myself recently against the very strong GM Theodorou he was completely unaware what to do against it, and I myself when playing this line with White hadn't really taken ... Bg4 seriously, instead expecting to get the very pleasant positions after Nxf5 next. Generally, ... Bg4 to my taste is the perfect balance between being somewhat provocative while still sound.} 6. Qd3 {This is one of the important options. Without our bishop on f4 , White is able to push e4 .} Nf6 7. Bg2 e6 8. O-O {This cunning move order was recommended by Roiz in his Modern Chess repertoire on the Reti.} Be7 9. h3 {Roiz's idea, snatching the bishop pair.} Bh5 10. g4 Bg6 11. Nxg6 hxg6 {A typical scenario for this line. Normally, we are a bit hesitant giving up the bishop pair voluntarily, but here White has weakened their kingside position with g4 , which is especially important as White has already committed to O-O . This combined with the potential dark squares (especially f4 ) gives us plenty of compensation for the bishop pair} 12. e4 {The most logical choice.} dxe4 {We shouldn’t allow e4 - e5 .} 13. Nxe4 c6 {A good solidifying move. Next up, we play …Qc7, already hinting at Nxg4 -tricks, as well as …Nd5 to take control over the f4 -square. Considering White’s kingside weaknesses, even castling long can be an interesting option in the future.} *

