1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 ({Basically we have the same choices as after} 2. c4 c6 {Nf3} 3. cxd5 {g3 , and they all have the same downsides.}) (2. b3 Nf6 3. Bb2 e6 {transposes to chapter 16 . This is the move order chosen by FM Dalton Perrine and GM Yaroslav Zherebukh in their The Reti: Nimzo-Larsen Attack .}) 2... Nd7 ({A controversial choice! Recently, both} 2... Nc6 {and Nd7 has gotten some popularity. I prefer putting the knight on d7 , as many of the resulting lines are similar to what we get in the Slav repertoire. Another thing I really like with Nd7 is that we are the ones choosing the direction of the game. White is more or less obliged to play into positions that we are more familiar with, whereas if we would play a system based on for example Bg4 (which many Slav players do) it is primarily White who can choose the central structure.}) 3. d4 (3. Bg2 {Plichta's recommendation in his Reti course.} e5 4. O-O Ngf6 5. d3 {The pure King's Indian Attack.} (5. d4 {This is his idea.} e4 6. Ne5 Bd6 7. Nxd7 Bxd7 8. c4 h6 $1 {An important move to remember. We need to prevent Bg5 .} 9. cxd5 O-O {We have sacrificed a pawn, but our e4 -pawn is a great asset and all our pieces have natural squares.}) 5... Be7 6. Nbd2 O-O 7. e4 {Never try to keep the center with ... c6 once White attacks it like this. We shouldn't forget that we are playing Black, after all.} dxe4 8. dxe4 c6 {This is our setup. Now there are various ways to develop our pieces, but in my view the most harmonious is ... Qc7 , ... Re8 and then push the a-pawn.}) 3... Nb6 {This is the move that brought 2... Nd7 into fashion again, when Alekseenko used it to beat Karjakin in the Grand Swiss 2019, and qualified for the Candidates. It looks a bit clumsy to put the knight on b6 , and indeed it is, but the main thing is that we have provoked d4 . In almost all Reti systems, White is trying to make the g2 -bishop strong, but here that is almost impossible. We will develop our bishop to f5 , then support the center with both ... e6 and ... c6 . This means that the g2 -bishop will be blunted basically forever. The downside for us is that it does take some time, and the knight is in itself not that great on b6 .} 4. Nc3 {This is the most critical move for White, although in practice it hasn't yet taken over. When I faced this line myself as White, I choose 4. Nc3 , and when I prepared to play it with Black, it was 4. Nc3 that was my main focus of attention. Indeed, the one classical game I tried the Nd7 - b6 line my opponent played 4. Nc3 . The point for White is rather specific - they anticipate us playing ... Bf5 next, and want to meet it with Nh4 . Surprisingly, the g2 -square is going to be needed for the knight rather than the bishop! Sounds strange, but it will all become clear once we look at the concrete lines.} Bf5 5. a4 a5 {Necessary, as we never want to allow a5 . This is a double-edged inclusion, but all in all I would say beneficial for White. Having the pawn on a5 makes it slightly more difficult for us to castle long, but there is also a concrete reason where the b6 -knight is hanging later on.} 6. Nh4 {Just like without a4  a5 included, this is the only point of White's play.} Bg4 7. h3 (7. f3 Bd7 {This is a worse version for White, as the a4 -pawn will be hanging and our bishop safer on b4 .}) 7... Bh5 8. Qd3 {Pushing for e4 is also possible, just like without a4  a5 included.} Nf6 9. e4 {Possible, but apart from our usual reaction with ... e6 this specific move order gives us an additional possibility.} dxe4 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Qxe4 Qd5 {After the trade of queens White's space advantage means even less, so we are comfortably equal here.} *

