1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 ({Basically we have the same choices as after} 2. c4 c6 {Nf3} 3. cxd5 {g3 , and they all have the same downsides.}) (2. b3 Nf6 3. Bb2 e6 {transposes to chapter 16 . This is the move order chosen by FM Dalton Perrine and GM Yaroslav Zherebukh in their The Reti: Nimzo-Larsen Attack .}) 2... Nd7 ({A controversial choice! Recently, both} 2... Nc6 {and Nd7 has gotten some popularity. I prefer putting the knight on d7 , as many of the resulting lines are similar to what we get in the Slav repertoire. Another thing I really like with Nd7 is that we are the ones choosing the direction of the game. White is more or less obliged to play into positions that we are more familiar with, whereas if we would play a system based on for example Bg4 (which many Slav players do) it is primarily White who can choose the central structure.}) 3. d4 (3. Bg2 {Plichta's recommendation in his Reti course.} e5 4. O-O Ngf6 5. d3 {The pure King's Indian Attack.} (5. d4 {This is his idea.} e4 6. Ne5 Bd6 7. Nxd7 Bxd7 8. c4 h6 $1 {An important move to remember. We need to prevent Bg5 .} 9. cxd5 O-O {We have sacrificed a pawn, but our e4 -pawn is a great asset and all our pieces have natural squares.}) 5... Be7 6. Nbd2 O-O 7. e4 {Never try to keep the center with ... c6 once White attacks it like this. We shouldn't forget that we are playing Black, after all.} dxe4 8. dxe4 c6 {This is our setup. Now there are various ways to develop our pieces, but in my view the most harmonious is ... Qc7 , ... Re8 and then push the a-pawn.}) 3... Nb6 {This is the move that brought 2... Nd7 into fashion again, when Alekseenko used it to beat Karjakin in the Grand Swiss 2019, and qualified for the Candidates. It looks a bit clumsy to put the knight on b6 , and indeed it is, but the main thing is that we have provoked d4 . In almost all Reti systems, White is trying to make the g2 -bishop strong, but here that is almost impossible. We will develop our bishop to f5 , then support the center with both ... e6 and ... c6 . This means that the g2 -bishop will be blunted basically forever. The downside for us is that it does take some time, and the knight is in itself not that great on b6 .} 4. Nc3 {This is the most critical move for White, although in practice it hasn't yet taken over. When I faced this line myself as White, I choose 4. Nc3 , and when I prepared to play it with Black, it was 4. Nc3 that was my main focus of attention. Indeed, the one classical game I tried the Nd7 - b6 line my opponent played 4. Nc3 . The point for White is rather specific - they anticipate us playing ... Bf5 next, and want to meet it with Nh4 . Surprisingly, the g2 -square is going to be needed for the knight rather than the bishop! Sounds strange, but it will all become clear once we look at the concrete lines.} Bf5 5. a4 a5 {Necessary, as we never want to allow a5 . This is a double-edged inclusion, but all in all I would say beneficial for White. Having the pawn on a5 makes it slightly more difficult for us to castle long, but there is also a concrete reason where the b6 -knight is hanging later on.} 6. Nh4 {Just like without a4  a5 included, this is the only point of White's play.} Bg4 7. h3 (7. f3 Bd7 {This is a worse version for White, as the a4 -pawn will be hanging and our bishop safer on b4 .}) 7... Bh5 8. Ng2 {Still the most critical move.} e6 {Just like without a4  a5 included, this is our reaction. We delay ... Nf6 to keep the possibility of pushing ... f5 .} 9. Nf4 Bg6 10. h4 {The only critical move. Now our bishop is in a fair amount of danger on g6 , so we need to be precise.} (10. Nxg6 hxg6 {This is even more pleasant than before for Black. We still push ... f5 before ... Nf6 , and long/term the plan of attacking the center with ... c5 is very much relevant.}) 10... Nf6 11. f3 {White is insisting on trying to trap our bishop.} (11. h5 {This is a mistake, as we are now in time to save our bishop.} Bf5 12. f3 h6 $1 {Simply giving the bishop a square on h7 . White's strategy has simply failed.}) 11... Be7 {Very important! This might look like a random developing move, but we are anticipating White's idea and prepare a strong antidote.} (11... Bd6 {This does not work with the inclusion of a4 / a5 .} 12. Nb5 $1 Bxf4 13. Bxf4 {We have to spend a move defending c7 , but that's a very important tempo to lose.} Rc8 14. g4 $1 {Just in time to prevent ... Nh5 . White is significantly better.}) 12. h5 Bf5 13. e4 {The only move. We were again threatening to save our bishop with ... h6 .} (13. g4 $2 {This does not work for White, and that's the point of 11... Be7 .} Nxg4 $1 14. fxg4 Bh4+ {The point!} 15. Kd2 Nc4#) 13... dxe4 14. g4 {White is burning all bridges, but by this point it's too late to go back. This is an important line to know, as it is easy to end up in trouble with incorrect play.} g5 {The only move. Now the tactics work out in our favour.} 15. gxf5 {The other option, also leading to a chaotic position.} gxf4 16. fxe4 exf5 17. Bxf4 ({The only good move.} 17. exf5 $2 Qd6 {Let us keep the f4 -pawn. After a later ... Nbd5 White is in deep trouble.}) 17... Bb4 {There are many tempting options, but I like this non-materialistic approach.} 18. exf5 Nbd5 19. Bd2 Bxc3 {Giving up the bishop, but now our knight on d5 is strong and White's king feeling very vulnerable.} 20. bxc3 Qd6 {Next we intend to castle long, after which we have a strong attack. White will try to hide their king on d1 , but with a rook coming to e8 we will threaten ... Ne4 with all sorts of threats.} *

