ategy has simply failed.}) 11... Be7 {Very important! This might look like a random developing move, but we are anticipating White's idea and prepare a strong antidote.} (11... Bd6 {This does not work with the inclusion of a4 / a5 .} 12. Nb5 $1 Bxf4 13. Bxf4 {We have to spend a move defending c7 , but that's a very important tempo to lose.} Rc8 14. g4 $1 {Just in time to prevent ... Nh5 . White is significantly better.}) 12. h5 Bf5 13. e4 {The only move. We were again threatening to save our bishop with ... h6 .} (13. g4 $2 {This does not work for White, and that's the point of 11... Be7 .} Nxg4 $1 14. fxg4 Bh4+ {The point!} 15. Kd2 Nc4#) 13... dxe4 14. g4 {White is burning all bridges, but by this point it's too late to go back. This is an important line to know, as it is easy to end up in trouble with incorrect play.} g5 {The only move. Now the tactics work out in our favour.} 15. hxg6 Bxg6 ({Now our bishop is saved! The position is still very messy, but we have an extra pawn and a lead in development, so we really shouldn't complain. g5 This is the best move for White, but I imagine it would be very easy to go completely wrong as White here in a practical game. Nxg6 fxg6 fxe4 e5! Gives nice counterplay on the dark squares.} 15... Nfd5 {Nxg6 Nxc3! Otherwise, White could take Nxe4 next. bxc3 fxg6} 16. fxe4 Bg5 {Qg4 The only move. White prevents ... Bh4 + and attacks e6 . Now follows a forced line. Bxc1 Qxe6+ Qe7 Qxe7+ Kxe7 Rxc1 Nxa4 We are still a pawn up. White has an impressive looking center, but with so many pieces traded it's less of a factor. Complicated and double-edged, just how we like it!}) *

