1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 ({Basically we have the same choices as after} 2. c4 c6 {Nf3} 3. cxd5 {g3 , and they all have the same downsides.}) (2. b3 Nf6 3. Bb2 e6 {transposes to chapter 16 . This is the move order chosen by FM Dalton Perrine and GM Yaroslav Zherebukh in their The Reti: Nimzo-Larsen Attack .}) 2... Nd7 3. d4 (3. Bg2 {Plichta's recommendation in his Reti course.} e5 4. O-O Ngf6 5. d3 {The pure King's Indian Attack.} (5. d4 {This is his idea.} e4 6. Ne5 Bd6 7. Nxd7 Bxd7 8. c4 h6 $1 {An important move to remember. We need to prevent Bg5 .} 9. cxd5 O-O {We have sacrificed a pawn, but our e4 -pawn is a great asset and all our pieces have natural squares.}) 5... Be7 6. Nbd2 O-O 7. e4 {Never try to keep the center with ... c6 once White attacks it like this. We shouldn't forget that we are playing Black, after all.} dxe4 8. dxe4 c6 {This is our setup. Now there are various ways to develop our pieces, but in my view the most harmonious is ... Qc7 , ... Re8 and then push the a-pawn.}) 3... Nb6 4. Nc3 Bf5 5. a4 (5. Nh4 Bg4 6. h3 (6. Qd3 Nf6 7. Bg2 e6 8. e4 Be7 $1 {Don't trade on e4 . If White pushes e5 , we get an excellent French/Caro type position.}) 6... Bh5 7. Ng2 e6 8. Nf4 Bg6 9. Nxg6 hxg6 {Important that we have not played ... Nf6 yet, so that ... f5 is possible to gain more control over the center.}) 5... a5 6. Nh4 Bg4 7. h3 Bh5 8. Ng2 e6 9. Nf4 Bg6 10. h4 Nf6 11. f3 Be7 {White is often able to trap our bishop, but in doing so they neglect development which gives us tactical counterplay.} 12. h5 Bf5 13. g4 Nxg4 14. fxg4 Bh4+ 15. Kd2 Nc4# {Typical line showing that White forgot about development.} *

