[White "�️ 8) Nimzo-Larsen: 1.b3"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "A01"]
[PlyCount "16"]

1. b3 d5 2. Bb2 Bg4 {Obviously as Slav players, we should feel happy to develop the bishop before playing ... e6 . But choosing between f5 and g4 is a trickier thing! They are fairly similar and both in very good theoretical health. Finally, I chose g4 because of my usual reasons. It's slightly less known, there is slightly less material published about it, and last but not least it's slightly more provocative!} ({Just as with Nf3 d5 g3} 2... Nd7 {, this line can perfectly well be played also by Queen's Gambit players, as the lines are independent of any 1. d4 -transpositions.}) 3. f3 {This is the Cowboy move!} (3. Nf3 Nf6 {In my own games I have often captures on f3 , but nowadays, I consider it a bit simpler just to keep developing.} 4. e3 (4. g3 e6 {We play our usual Slav setup. As White is not putting any sort of immediate pressure, there is no need to know any more concrete knowledge.}) 4... e6 5. h3 Bh5 6. g4 {It's good to be familiar with this, just so that you won't get shocked during your games.} Bg6 7. Ne5 Nbd7 8. Nxg6 hxg6 {This structures we happily allow. Compared to the Slow Slav White has unnecessarily weakened themselves with h3 , g4 and the bishop is not too great on b2 .}) 3... Bd7 {Slightly odd, but the f3 -pawn is really ugly for White.} (3... Bf5 {More natural, but gets too chaotic for my taste.} 4. e4 $5 dxe4 5. Nc3 {This is the sort of shenanigans I prefer to avoid if there is a good alternative. If I could prove a clear edge for Black I would still be tempted to go for it, but surprisingly it seems that White is somewhat OK even objectively.}) 4. e4 Nf6 {In my view a beautiful move! We lose even further time, but for every pawn move White is ruining their position further.} 5. e5 Ng8 6. c4 {The only move to keep the balance. White needs counterplay to compensate for the structural deficits.} (6. d4 c5 {Immediately attack the center. The bishop is badly placed on b2 and having the pawn on f3 is a disaster.}) 6... Bf5 {Losing even more time, but the bishop belongs outside the pawn chain!} 7. d4 e6 8. Nc3 Ne7 {White has no good way to open the position and we will simply develop while putting pressure on the center. Most likely, our king will castle long.} *

