[Result "*"]
[ECO "A12"]
[PlyCount "18"]

1. b3 d5 {There are other good moves against 1. b3 of course, but insofar as possible I like to keep the structures within Slav territory.} 2. Bb2 Bg4 ({A move I've dabbed with a fair amount myself throughout the years. It's slightly less solid than} 2... Bf5 {, but it's provocative in a nice way. We invite White to attack our bishop, but in doing so they would weaken their position. And should White choose to leave the bishop be on g4 , then it's simply well-placed there.}) 3. Nf3 {This is the lazy approach for White. They simply develop without bothering to look too carefully at what we are doing.} Nf6 {In my own practice I've often taken on f3 here, but nowadays, I think it's a bit simpler to simply keep developing.} 4. g3 {This is the other typical setup for White.} e6 5. Bg2 Bd6 {It's a difficult question where to place this bishop. Putting it on e7 also makes sense, but I quite like to have it on d6 in order to push ... e5 later on. In general, this is not at all a theoretical position, and general guidelines should be enough. Our setup is O-O , c6 , Nbd7 , h6 and then go for the ... e5 -push if possible.} 6. O-O O-O 7. c4 (7. d3 {If White plays even more modestly like this, we can allow ourselves a little more ambition.} c5 $5 {Intending ... Nc6 and eventually ... e5 .} 8. c4 Nc6) 7... c6 {This position is more common with the bishop on f5 instead of g4 , but the bishop on g4 also makes a lot of sense. It will not come under attack as easily, for instance by Nd4 , and we never have to worry about the e4 -push. But overarching, the positions are both quite similar.} 8. d3 {There are many ways to play for both sides, but this makes sense.} Nbd7 9. cxd5 {If White takes on d5 , then generally both pawn recaptures are fine, depending on your mood.} cxd5 {The simplest. Here Nd4 - b5 would be a thing if we had our bishop on f5 , but now White is not in time. I'd say Black is ever so slightly more comfortable, and our moves are easy. ... a6 , ... Qe7 and rooks to the c-file.} *

