1. b3 d5 {There are other good moves against 1. b3 of course, but insofar as possible I like to keep the structures within Slav territory.} 2. Bb2 Bg4 ({A move I've dabbed with a fair amount myself throughout the years. It's slightly less solid than} 2... Bf5 {, but it's provocative in a nice way. We invite White to attack our bishop, but in doing so they would weaken their position. And should White choose to leave the bishop be on g4 , then it's simply well-placed there.}) 3. Nf3 {This is the lazy approach for White. They simply develop without bothering to look too carefully at what we are doing.} Nf6 {In my own practice I've often taken on f3 here, but nowadays, I think it's a bit simpler to simply keep developing.} 4. e3 {Another way to play. Against the ... Bf5 -setups this is even more innocent than g3 , but against ... Bg4 I would actually say e3 is the more ambitious setup. The reason is that White has an additional plan of hunting down our g4 -bishop here.} e6 5. h3 Bh5 {Actually, trading on f3 is always possible as well, and leads to positions similar to many from the Classical Slav. Still, it seems to me a bit more ambitious to try to keep the bishop.} 6. g4 {This can also be done immediately, but it's a less flexible version for White.} Bg6 7. Ne5 Nbd7 8. Nxg6 hxg6 {We have seen many, many examples of giving up the light squared bishop in the Slav. This version is even a bit better than usual, as the pawns on h3 / g4 creates some weaknesses. We want to play ... g5 to increase our control over the dark squares, and then develop with ... Bd6 and ... c6 if needed. Long-term, we might even consider maneuvering the d7 -knight to g6 , strengthening our grip on the weak squares around White's kingside.} *

