1. b3 d5 {There are other good moves against 1. b3 of course, but insofar as possible I like to keep the structures within Slav territory.} 2. Bb2 Bg4 ({A move I've dabbed with a fair amount myself throughout the years. It's slightly less solid than} 2... Bf5 {, but it's provocative in a nice way. We invite White to attack our bishop, but in doing so they would weaken their position. And should White choose to leave the bishop be on g4 , then it's simply well-placed there.}) 3. Nf3 {This is the lazy approach for White. They simply develop without bothering to look too carefully at what we are doing.} Nf6 {In my own practice I've often taken on f3 here, but nowadays, I think it's a bit simpler to simply keep developing.} 4. e3 {Another way to play. Against the ... Bf5 -setups this is even more innocent than g3 , but against ... Bg4 I would actually say e3 is the more ambitious setup. The reason is that White has an additional plan of hunting down our g4 -bishop here.} e6 5. h3 Bh5 {Actually, trading on f3 is always possible as well, and leads to positions similar to many from the Classical Slav. Still, it seems to me a bit more ambitious to try to keep the bishop.} 6. d3 {This looks like the trickiest move. White wants to play g4 , but it's a bit more flexible to start with d3 .} a5 {A concrete reaction. We immediately ask White some questions. Getting the pawn to a4 is a big nuisance for White.} 7. g4 Bg6 8. Nh4 a4 {Something like this looks nice for us. The main idea is to play ... a3 at an appropriate moment, after which the entire White queenside will feel vulnerable. But we also do not need to rush, as the pawn on a4 is also annoying for White.} *

