1. b3 d5 {There are other good moves against 1. b3 of course, but insofar as possible I like to keep the structures within Slav territory.} 2. Bb2 Bg4 ({A move I've dabbed with a fair amount myself throughout the years. It's slightly less solid than} 2... Bf5 {, but it's provocative in a nice way. We invite White to attack our bishop, but in doing so they would weaken their position. And should White choose to leave the bishop be on g4 , then it's simply well-placed there.}) 3. Nf3 {This is the lazy approach for White. They simply develop without bothering to look too carefully at what we are doing.} Nf6 {In my own practice I've often taken on f3 here, but nowadays, I think it's a bit simpler to simply keep developing.} 4. e3 {Another way to play. Against the ... Bf5 -setups this is even more innocent than g3 , but against ... Bg4 I would actually say e3 is the more ambitious setup. The reason is that White has an additional plan of hunting down our g4 -bishop here.} e6 5. h3 Bh5 {Actually, trading on f3 is always possible as well, and leads to positions similar to many from the Classical Slav. Still, it seems to me a bit more ambitious to try to keep the bishop.} 6. d3 {This looks like the trickiest move. White wants to play g4 , but it's a bit more flexible to start with d3 .} a5 {A concrete reaction. We immediately ask White some questions. Getting the pawn to a4 is a big nuisance for White.} 7. a3 {Far and away the most natural move for White.} a4 {This is our idea. It's not always a good idea, but here it works out well. We are simply fighting for the initiative already!} 8. b4 {The only move that makes strategic sense.} c5 {This is the point of our play. We trade a c-pawn for a b-pawn which is not normally great, but we gain a lot of time in the process. Pushing ... c5 also means that our knight gets a great square on c6 , and long-term we might be able to push ... e5 , gaining even more space.} 9. g4 {This was tried in the only game reaching this position, but there Black was quickly better.} Bg6 10. bxc5 Bxc5 11. g5 Nh5 12. Be2 {This was Heider-Blübaum 2022. It might look like our h5 -knight is in trouble, but in fact it's White who should be careful.} Nc6 {A very logical novelty. We intend to push ... d4 , giving the knight access to the f4 -square.} 13. d4 {The only move. White's only hope is that our knight is out of play.} Bb6 14. Rg1 h6 {The simplest. By opening the h-file we make sure that the knight is never in trouble.} 15. h4 Bf5 {One of many possible moves. We want to play ... g6 , further strengthening the h5 -knight but also giving it a square on g7 , should it be necessary later. Both White and Black are placed a bit strange, but it's just the sort of strategically imbalanced positions that we like! One of the issues for White is that they have nowhere good to place their king, even long-term.} *

