1. b3 d5 {There are other good moves against 1. b3 of course, but insofar as possible I like to keep the structures within Slav territory.} 2. Bb2 Bg4 ({A move I've dabbed with a fair amount myself throughout the years. It's slightly less solid than} 2... Bf5 {, but it's provocative in a nice way. We invite White to attack our bishop, but in doing so they would weaken their position. And should White choose to leave the bishop be on g4 , then it's simply well-placed there.}) 3. g3 {This does not have a lot of independent value, as White is anyway going to play Nf3 sooner or later.} Nf6 4. Bg2 e6 {White doesn't really have anything better than transposing with Nf3 .} 5. d3 (5. Nf3 Bd6 {Transposing to Nf3 Nf6 g3 e6 Bg2 Bd6 , the first line in this chapter.}) 5... Bd6 6. h3 {This is some kind of independent option. White is trying to put their knight on e2 instead of f3 .} Bh5 7. g4 Bg6 8. e3 {Intending Ne2 and keeping the option of putting a pawn on f4 . It can be played, but it's a bit too weird to be really good.} c5 {When White is playing so modestly, we might as well grab the center.} 9. Ne2 Nc6 10. f4 {This is supposedly White's strategic idea.} d4 {A nice opportunity for this. Usually I would be hesitant to allow e4 , but here we have a concrete idea in mind.} 11. e4 Nd7 {This is the point. We play ... f6 next, and then push ... e5 with an excellent grip over the center. Importantly, we haven't yet committed to short castle, meaning we might still consider castling long later on.} *

