1. b3 d5 {There are other good moves against 1. b3 of course, but insofar as possible I like to keep the structures within Slav territory.} 2. Bb2 Bg4 ({A move I've dabbed with a fair amount myself throughout the years. It's slightly less solid than} 2... Bf5 {, but it's provocative in a nice way. We invite White to attack our bishop, but in doing so they would weaken their position. And should White choose to leave the bishop be on g4 , then it's simply well-placed there.}) 3. h3 ({It's also possible to start with this, but play will most likely resemble} 3. Nf3 {.}) 3... Bh5 4. g4 {An independent option. It looks fun to play in this way, but again I believe it's a bit too much to ask for.} Bg6 5. Bg2 Nc6 {I like this very much. The old rule of always meeting a flank attack with play in the center can be applied here with great effect. Normally in the Queen's pawn openings we don't want to put a knight on c6 due to White playing d4 , but here that would close the b2 -bishop and make our own bishop on g6 much stronger. But without d4 it's hard for White to stop us from playing ... e5 .} 6. c4 {Objectively, this is the only move that gets close to keeping the balance.} e6 {Simply defending d5 .} 7. Nf3 {Now at least we can't get ... e5 in a good way.} d4 {It's not necessary to release the tension in the center, but cementing our space advantage makes sense.} 8. O-O Nf6 {Simple development. We don't need to be fancy here, as we are the ones with the long term strategic advantage.} 9. e3 Bc5 {Overprotecting the center. Next we are ready to castle short, with a very healthy position. Even though we have no way to utilize it immediately, White will always struggle with the pawn on g4 in the long run.} *

