1. b3 d5 {There are other good moves against 1. b3 of course, but insofar as possible I like to keep the structures within Slav territory.} 2. Bb2 Bg4 ({A move I've dabbed with a fair amount myself throughout the years. It's slightly less solid than} 2... Bf5 {, but it's provocative in a nice way. We invite White to attack our bishop, but in doing so they would weaken their position. And should White choose to leave the bishop be on g4 , then it's simply well-placed there.}) 3. h3 ({It's also possible to start with this, but play will most likely resemble} 3. Nf3 {.}) 3... Bh5 4. g4 {An independent option. It looks fun to play in this way, but again I believe it's a bit too much to ask for.} Bg6 5. Bg2 Nc6 {I like this very much. The old rule of always meeting a flank attack with play in the center can be applied here with great effect. Normally in the Queen's pawn openings we don't want to put a knight on c6 due to White playing d4 , but here that would close the b2 -bishop and make our own bishop on g6 much stronger. But without d4 it's hard for White to stop us from playing ... e5 .} 6. Nf3 {The most common move in practice.} h5 {Now even stronger than on the last move. If White doesn't react, we trade on g4 and h1 , and then attack the g4 -pawn.} 7. g5 {The only move that's been played, and definitely the most natural one. But it doesn't work...} e5 {The refutation. White can't take twice on e5 as the g5 -pawn is hanging, but White can't take either. So it's just a disaster.} *

