1. b3 d5 {There are other good moves against 1. b3 of course, but insofar as possible I like to keep the structures within Slav territory.} 2. Bb2 Bg4 ({A move I've dabbed with a fair amount myself throughout the years. It's slightly less solid than} 2... Bf5 {, but it's provocative in a nice way. We invite White to attack our bishop, but in doing so they would weaken their position. And should White choose to leave the bishop be on g4 , then it's simply well-placed there.}) 3. f3 {Adhiban's recommendation, and therefore our mainline. To me, f3 looks rather ugly, but these ' b3 -cowboys' don't seem to mind such too much.} Bf5 {This looks like the most critical move, but it's not better for Black and leads to a sort of chaos where I feel it's probably harder to be Black than White. Had it led to a definite advantage for Black, we could consider putting in the effort of studying it despite the complications, but now it's simply not worth it.} 4. e4 {I will just give one of the main lines for you to get an idea of what is going on.} dxe4 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. g4 Bg6 7. Qe2 Nc6 8. O-O-O Nd4 9. Qg2 {As you can see, the play is highly unusual and complicated.} exf3 10. Nxf3 c6 11. h4 h5 12. Ne5 Bxc2 13. Bc4 e6 14. g5 {Complete chaos appears. Fun, yes definitely, but unfortunately more fun for White than Black!} *

