1. b3 d5 {There are other good moves against 1. b3 of course, but insofar as possible I like to keep the structures within Slav territory.} 2. Bb2 Bg4 ({A move I've dabbed with a fair amount myself throughout the years. It's slightly less solid than} 2... Bf5 {, but it's provocative in a nice way. We invite White to attack our bishop, but in doing so they would weaken their position. And should White choose to leave the bishop be on g4 , then it's simply well-placed there.}) 3. f3 {Adhiban's recommendation, and therefore our mainline. To me, f3 looks rather ugly, but these ' b3 -cowboys' don't seem to mind such too much.} Bd7 {This one is a bit controversial. It looks like an odd square, but the point is simply to tuck the bishop away, not giving White further tempi against it. Meanwhile, we are arguing that f3 is quite a big weakness, and prevents White from developing normally.} 4. f4 {This also makes some sense, going for a Bird style position. Here the bishop is not too great on d7 , but the Bird is such an opening that we have a good margin.} c5 {Grabbing more central control makes a lot of sense.} 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. e3 e6 {This is a setup I used to play a lot against the Dutch with colours reversed, and it seems to work fairly well here as well. Our idea is to keep the option of playing ... f6 , in case White tries to establish a knight on e5 .} 7. Bb5 {Had our knight already been on f6 , this would be annoying. But now we have an extra possibility.} f6 {The difference! White's play is revolved around utilizing the e5 -square, but that will never be an issue now.} 8. O-O a6 {Forcing White's hand. Taking on c6 does not make too much sense as we then control both the dark and the light squares. But retreating is losing some time.} 9. Bd3 {Dutch players (and reversely 1. f4 players) usually like funky moves like this.} Qc7 {Important. White had a nice trick prepared against the more natural ... Bd6 .} (9... Bd6 $6 10. Ne5 $1 fxe5 $2 11. Qh5+ {would be crushing.}) 10. c4 d4 {This is a good version for us. The extra tempo a6 is actually really useful, as Na3 - b5 is no longer an option. Therefore, we will easily be able to keep our strong pawn on d4 , which secures us a good position. By the way, it's even possible to castle long soon, should we feel extra ambitious.} *

