1. b3 d5 {There are other good moves against 1. b3 of course, but insofar as possible I like to keep the structures within Slav territory.} 2. Bb2 Bg4 ({A move I've dabbed with a fair amount myself throughout the years. It's slightly less solid than} 2... Bf5 {, but it's provocative in a nice way. We invite White to attack our bishop, but in doing so they would weaken their position. And should White choose to leave the bishop be on g4 , then it's simply well-placed there.}) 3. f3 {Adhiban's recommendation, and therefore our mainline. To me, f3 looks rather ugly, but these ' b3 -cowboys' don't seem to mind such too much.} Bd7 {This one is a bit controversial. It looks like an odd square, but the point is simply to tuck the bishop away, not giving White further tempi against it. Meanwhile, we are arguing that f3 is quite a big weakness, and prevents White from developing normally.} 4. f4 {This also makes some sense, going for a Bird style position. Here the bishop is not too great on d7 , but the Bird is such an opening that we have a good margin.} c5 {Grabbing more central control makes a lot of sense.} 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. e3 e6 {This is a setup I used to play a lot against the Dutch with colours reversed, and it seems to work fairly well here as well. Our idea is to keep the option of playing ... f6 , in case White tries to establish a knight on e5 .} 7. Be2 Nf6 {After some analysis, I've come to the conclusion that this simple developing move actually makes the most sense. Playing with ... f6 instead is still possible, and arguably more ambitious, but compared to the 7. Bb5 lines we lack the extra move ... a6 , and that is rather important. Additionally, ... Nf6 is a better version here, as White can't swap our knight on c6 before jumping Ne5 .} 8. O-O Be7 9. Ne5 (9. d3 d4 $1 {An important idea to keep in mind.} 10. e4 Ng4 {Black is just better.}) 9... O-O {Looks healthy for Black. What I like about this setup is that our move ... Bd7 , which normally looks strange, now makes perfect sense. It protects c6 (we never want doubled c-pawns!) and also prepares ... Rad8 . Once we've gotten ... Qc7 and ... Rad8 in, it's time to look for the ... d4 -push.} *

