1. b3 d5 {There are other good moves against 1. b3 of course, but insofar as possible I like to keep the structures within Slav territory.} 2. Bb2 Bg4 ({A move I've dabbed with a fair amount myself throughout the years. It's slightly less solid than} 2... Bf5 {, but it's provocative in a nice way. We invite White to attack our bishop, but in doing so they would weaken their position. And should White choose to leave the bishop be on g4 , then it's simply well-placed there.}) 3. f3 {Adhiban's recommendation, and therefore our mainline. To me, f3 looks rather ugly, but these ' b3 -cowboys' don't seem to mind such too much.} Bd7 {This one is a bit controversial. It looks like an odd square, but the point is simply to tuck the bishop away, not giving White further tempi against it. Meanwhile, we are arguing that f3 is quite a big weakness, and prevents White from developing normally.} 4. e4 {Adhiban's move, and clearly the most ambitious.} Nf6 {Another controversial move, but this time I simply really like it!} 5. e5 {Far and away the most logical.} Ng8 {So why did we spend two moves getting White's pawn to e5 ? Well, the pawn is really not great on e5 . It blocks the b2 -bishop, which otherwise is the pride of White's position. Additionally, it allows us to play ... Bf5 before ... e6 . Previously, f5 was a vulnerable square, but now it's simply a great one.} 6. c4 {This shows good understanding by White. Should they continue with normal moves, we would simply be better.} (6. d4 c5 $1 {Immediately attacking the center. This looks like a fantastic Advanced French for Black.}) 6... Bf5 7. d4 e6 {We have gotten some sort of weird Advanced Caro-Kann on the board. Counting only tempi, we are a fair bit behind, but the extra moves that White has gotten are really not great. The bishop doesn't really belong to b2 , and the pawn on f3 is just ugly. Additionally, in the Caro-Kann we wouldn't have access to the c6 -square for the knight.} 8. Nc3 Ne7 {Important, so that we never have to recapture on d5 with the pawn.} 9. Nge2 Nbc6 {Continuing the development. It's actually already pretty hard for White to make sensible moves.} 10. g4 {In for a penny, in for a pound... Basically, White must keep going aggressively, as it's too late to play solid with all those weaknesses.} Bg6 11. h4 h5 {Keeping the bishop alive. The weakness doesn't matter, as we are anyway for sure going to put our king on the queenside.} 12. a3 {Simply necessary, in order to prevent ... Nb4 .} dxc4 {A good moment for this, as White was starting to seriously consider taking twice on d5 (followed by Nf4 ).} 13. bxc4 Qd7 {Simple play. We want to castle long and put pressure on the d4 -pawn.} 14. Qa4 {Already the only move for White. Getting a rook to d1 is imperative to defend d4 .} O-O-O 15. Rd1 Kb8 {A nice prophylactic move, defending a7 so that d5 can be met by ... Nxe5 . Next up, we are ready to either play ... Nc8 - b6 , overprotecting our queenside, or more direct play with ... f6 , hitting White's center.} *

