1. b3 d5 2. Bb2 Bg4 3. f3 {Cowboy move.} (3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. h3 Bh5 6. d3 {White is getting ready to win our bishop with g4 , Nh4 .} a5 $1 {Getting counterplay on the dark squares like this is a key idea when giving up the light squared bishop.} 7. a3 a4 $1 8. b4 c5 9. bxc5 Bxc5 {We have plenty of counterplay. If White insists on g4 , the king will never be really safe.}) 3... Bd7 {A somewhat strange square, but the bishop simply steps out of danger.} 4. e4 Nf6 5. e5 Ng8 {We lose a lot of time, but White is ruining their position more and more by each move.} 6. c4 Bf5 7. d4 e6 8. Nc3 Ne7 {Don't worry about the lack of space. Our pieces have good squares, and the White d4 -pawn will eventually get weak. Castling long is a useful extra possibility.} *

