1. c4 c6 2. e4 {An annoying move! Not because it in any way theoretically challenging, but because it leads to lines more known after 1. e4 . Of course, if you are a Caro-Kann player, you will already be well familiar with this. For the rest of us, we just have to accept that we need to be familiar also with these lines.} d5 {Nothing else makes sense.} 3. exd5 cxd5 4. d4 {The real Panov.} (4. cxd5 {This is an independent option, and for players starting with 1. c4 probably more tempting than entering the entire Panov complex.} Nf6 5. Nc3 (5. Bb5+ {This check is useful to be familiar with.} Nbd7 {The thing we need to know here is that there is no rush to win back the d5 -pawn. We will finish development with ... g6 , Bg7 , O-O , and only then recapture the pawn.} 6. Nc3 a6) 5... Nxd5 6. Nf3 Nc6 {Basically both sides can play numerous different things at every move here, and it will all be OK.} 7. Bb5 {The most common move.} (7. Bc4 Nb6 8. Bb5 Bg4 {8... g6 is again a decent option, but I like this. Long-term, we have chances against the isolated d-pawn.}) 7... e6 {It's hard to choose here. 7... g6 is another good option, but as usual we stick to not fianchettoing our bishops.} 8. d4 Bd6 {A typical IQP-position. We castle, play h6 and then look to develop the c8 -bishop.}) 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Nf3 (6. Bg5 Be6 $5 {This looks very strange, but White is likely to take on f6 at some point, after which we recapture with the e-pawn, reaching harmony.} (6... dxc4 {The most solid move, but I feel 6... Be6 goes better together with my recommendation in the mainline.} 7. Bxc4 h6 8. Bh4 e6 9. Nf3 {Actually transposes to a line of the Queen's Gambit Declined!}) 7. a3 {The most cunning waiting move.} g6 8. Bxf6 exf6 {It's important to understand that the exf6 -structure is decent for us. It provides us with the safer king, and the bishop pair. White could create a passed d-pawn, but that will be as much a weakness as a strength.}) 6... a6 {My own line, which I will happily recommend. It leads to much more interesting play than the traditional mainlines.} (6... Bg4 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Qb3 Bxf3 9. gxf3 e6 10. Qxb7 {is the old mainline with thousands of games. As far as I know, it's considered to equalize without too many issues, but it's a lot of theory and next to no winning chances for Black. Practically speaking, I consider it entirely unattractive for Black.}) 7. cxd5 {The most popular move.} (7. c5 Bg4 {This is the idea. Intending g6 , Bg7 and pressure against the d4 -pawn.}) 7... Nxd5 8. Bc4 Be6 {This is a funny way to develop, but basically the most likely scenario is that pieces will be traded. And for every trade, the white d-pawn gets weaker.} 9. Bb3 (9. Ng5 {Forcing.} Nxc3 10. Bxe6 Nxd1 11. Bxf7+ Kd7 12. Be6+ Ke8 {Is a draw by repetition.} (12... Kc7 $5 {A risky way to play on. White has full compensation for the queen, but probably not more than that.})) 9... g6 {This is the only controversial decision in the ... a6 -complex.} (9... Na5 {Also possible but in my view much more demanding from Black.}) 10. O-O Bg7 11. Ng5 {Else we are developing indisturbed.} Nxc3 12. bxc3 Bd5 {With a perfectly healthy position.} *

