1. c4 c6 2. e4 {The Panov. This one is slightly annoying. Not because it is in any way challenging theoretically, but because it leads to a bit more theory than I usually prefer.} d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. cxd5 {This is an independent line. Actually, when reaching this position from 1. c4 rather than 1. e4 , I believe this is much more likely. This might sound odd, but the reason is that there is a lot less theory here than in the traditional Panov lines. As White played 1. c4 , they are likely not 1. e4 -players, therefore not too interested in learning too much theory that they are anyway not going to reach very often, therefore it's tempting with a smaller sideline.} Nf6 5. Bb5+ {A funky check, typical from many similar openings. The idea is to make it harder for us to regain the d5 -pawn} Nbd7 {Important. We need to be able to play ... Nb6 later on, else we might struggle to regain the d5 -pawn.} 6. Nc3 a6 {We kick the bishop immediately, unpinning the d7 -knight to easier regain the d5 -pawn.} 7. Be2 {This was played recently by the reigning European champion, Alexey Sarana, but it fails to impress theoretically.} b5 {7... Nb6 with the idea of later fianchettoing the dark squared bishop also makes a lot of sense.} 8. d4 b4 {Simply winning the pawn back.} 9. Na4 Nxd5 10. Bf3 e6 {White has an isolated pawn on d4 , but we have some small weaknesses on the queenside. Therefore, the position is equal, but still full of play for both sides. With the solid blockade on d5 we can never really be worse, though.} *

