1. c4 c6 2. e4 {The Panov. This one is slightly annoying. Not because it is in any way challenging theoretically, but because it leads to a bit more theory than I usually prefer.} d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. cxd5 {This is an independent line. Actually, when reaching this position from 1. c4 rather than 1. e4 , I believe this is much more likely. This might sound odd, but the reason is that there is a lot less theory here than in the traditional Panov lines. As White played 1. c4 , they are likely not 1. e4 -players, therefore not too interested in learning too much theory that they are anyway not going to reach very often, therefore it's tempting with a smaller sideline.} Nf6 5. Bb5+ {A funky check, typical from many similar openings. The idea is to make it harder for us to regain the d5 -pawn} Nbd7 {Important. We need to be able to play ... Nb6 later on, else we might struggle to regain the d5 -pawn.} 6. Nc3 a6 {We kick the bishop immediately, unpinning the d7 -knight to easier regain the d5 -pawn.} 7. Qa4 {The most testing move, trying to make it harder for us to regain the d5 -pawn.} g6 {Probably the simplest. We are still a pawn down, but the d5 -pawn is such a long term weakness that we should never really worry about getting it back. Our idea is to simply play ... Bg7 and O-O , after which the d7 -knight is finally free to move.} 8. Nf3 Bg7 9. O-O O-O {Now we are threatening ... Nb6 .} 10. Bxd7 {This is the idea of White. If we were to win back the d5 -pawn for nothing, we would simply be better, but White tries to keep it for as long as possible.} Nxd7 {I like this recapture! It looks strange considering the fact that our primary target is the d5 -pawn, but we want to play ... b5 , ... Nb6 and ... Bb7 , after which we will finally win it back. For that reason, the bishop would also be misplaced on d7 .} 11. Qh4 {White is trying to get some sort of attack going, but we are solid.} Nf6 {11... b5 is possible as well, but now the d5 -pawn is really hanging.} 12. d4 Nxd5 13. Bh6 Bf6 {A good antidote. Keeping the bishops should be in our favor, as we have the bishop pair, but also to make it harder for White to attack our king.} 14. Qe4 Nxc3 15. bxc3 Re8 {White is simply lacking firepower to drum up any sort of attack. Trading queens would be the dream for us, but also just getting the bishop to d5 is enough for us to be happy.} *

