1. c4 c6 2. e4 {The Panov. This one is slightly annoying. Not because it is in any way challenging theoretically, but because it leads to a bit more theory than I usually prefer.} d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. cxd5 {This is an independent line. Actually, when reaching this position from 1. c4 rather than 1. e4 , I believe this is much more likely. This might sound odd, but the reason is that there is a lot less theory here than in the traditional Panov lines. As White played 1. c4 , they are likely not 1. e4 -players, therefore not too interested in learning too much theory that they are anyway not going to reach very often, therefore it's tempting with a smaller sideline.} Nf6 5. Qa4+ ({This check is very similar to} 5. Bb5+ {. White is trying to make it harder for us to regain the d5 -pawn.}) 5... Nbd7 6. Nc3 g6 {The same reaction as against 5. Bb5 +. We want to get out of the a4 - e8 pin, so that we can play ... Nb6 and pick up the d5 -pawn. If we are able to do that we are likely to be better, as our structure is preferable. Therefore, White has to try to hold on to d5 by all means available.} 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. Bc4 a6 {This is a small move order point. We delay castling in order to quickly push ... b5 .} 9. O-O O-O {Always castle when White castles. Now if White plays d6 we can simply take it, as there are no issues along the e-file once we have already castled.} 10. Qa3 (10. d3 $4 b5 11. Bxb5 Nb6 {is an essential trick we need to be familiar with. This is always possible once we have castled.}) 10... Nb6 11. d3 Nfxd5 {We are simply better, as White has no compensation for their inferior structure.} *

