1. c4 c6 2. e4 {The Panov. This one is slightly annoying. Not because it is in any way challenging theoretically, but because it leads to a bit more theory than I usually prefer.} d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. cxd5 {This is an independent line. Actually, when reaching this position from 1. c4 rather than 1. e4 , I believe this is much more likely. This might sound odd, but the reason is that there is a lot less theory here than in the traditional Panov lines. As White played 1. c4 , they are likely not 1. e4 -players, therefore not too interested in learning too much theory that they are anyway not going to reach very often, therefore it's tempting with a smaller sideline.} Nf6 5. Qa4+ ({This check is very similar to} 5. Bb5+ {. White is trying to make it harder for us to regain the d5 -pawn.}) 5... Nbd7 6. Nc3 g6 {The same reaction as against 5. Bb5 +. We want to get out of the a4 - e8 pin, so that we can play ... Nb6 and pick up the d5 -pawn. If we are able to do that we are likely to be better, as our structure is preferable. Therefore, White has to try to hold on to d5 by all means available.} 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. Bc4 a6 {This is a small move order point. We delay castling in order to quickly push ... b5 .} 9. d3 {This is how White usually reacts to ... a6 . The c4 -bishop is protected, which will be important later on.} Rb8 {Continuing to delay castling. This certainly not necessary, but looks like the most straightforward to me.} 10. Bb3 {Simply saving the bishop} b5 11. Qf4 {Trying to prevent ... Nc5 , but it's too artificial to be good.} Bb7 12. O-O Nc5 {Now that the b8 -rook is no longer hanging.} 13. d6 {This was tried in Bortnyk-Svane. It's one of the typical ideas, but it doesn't work out at all here.} Qxd6 14. Qxd6 exd6 15. Re1+ Kd7 {This would have been much better than the passive ... Kf8 ?! by Svane.} 16. Bxf7 {Presumably the reason Black went with the king to f8 in the game.} Rhf8 17. Bb3 {We have amazing compensation with many moves..} b4 {Kicking the knight away seems like the strongest. Our king is not at all vulnerable on d7 while we have fantastic piece activity. If we want to, we can get the pawn back on d3 next move with a continuous initiative.} *

