1. c4 c6 2. e4 {The Panov. This one is slightly annoying. Not because it is in any way challenging theoretically, but because it leads to a bit more theory than I usually prefer.} d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. cxd5 {This is an independent line. Actually, when reaching this position from 1. c4 rather than 1. e4 , I believe this is much more likely. This might sound odd, but the reason is that there is a lot less theory here than in the traditional Panov lines. As White played 1. c4 , they are likely not 1. e4 -players, therefore not too interested in learning too much theory that they are anyway not going to reach very often, therefore it's tempting with a smaller sideline.} Nf6 5. Qa4+ ({This check is very similar to} 5. Bb5+ {. White is trying to make it harder for us to regain the d5 -pawn.}) 5... Nbd7 6. Nc3 g6 {The same reaction as against 5. Bb5 +. We want to get out of the a4 - e8 pin, so that we can play ... Nb6 and pick up the d5 -pawn. If we are able to do that we are likely to be better, as our structure is preferable. Therefore, White has to try to hold on to d5 by all means available.} 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. Bc4 a6 {This is a small move order point. We delay castling in order to quickly push ... b5 .} 9. d3 {This is how White usually reacts to ... a6 . The c4 -bishop is protected, which will be important later on.} Rb8 {Continuing to delay castling. This certainly not necessary, but looks like the most straightforward to me.} 10. Bb3 {Simply saving the bishop} b5 11. Qh4 {More harmonious, but also lets us do what we want.} Nc5 {Now we are ready to pick up the d5 -pawn.} 12. O-O Nxb3 13. axb3 Nxd5 14. Bh6 {The only move for White. Should we get one more move we would have a significant strategic advantage with the bishop pair and better structure.} O-O {Don't worry about an attack here - we have enough defenders. There is only one line we need to know.} 15. Ng5 ({This is the only scary-looking move.} 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. Nxd5 Qxd5 17. Qxe7 Bb7 {We have massive compensation for the pawn. White should be looking for ways to survive into a drawish ending.}) 15... Nf6 16. Nce4 Nh5 {This is the key move, disconnecting the queen from the bishop. Now, the play gets concrete for a couple of moves.} 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 18. g4 {Again, if we were given just one move, we would consolidate and have a clear strategic edge.} Bxg4 {Not the only way, but the nicest. We will win the piece back next.} 19. Qxg4 h6 {This is the point. If the knight moves, we have ... f5 regaining the piece.} 20. Nxf7 {The only equalizing move.} Rxf7 21. Rxa6 Rb6 {White is technically a pawn up, but this is not felt at all. Our knight will be excellent on f4 , and our king looks safe enough. Most probably the game will peter out to some form of equality, but anything can still happen.} *

