1. c4 c6 2. e4 {The Panov. This one is slightly annoying. Not because it is in any way challenging theoretically, but because it leads to a bit more theory than I usually prefer.} d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. cxd5 {This is an independent line. Actually, when reaching this position from 1. c4 rather than 1. e4 , I believe this is much more likely. This might sound odd, but the reason is that there is a lot less theory here than in the traditional Panov lines. As White played 1. c4 , they are likely not 1. e4 -players, therefore not too interested in learning too much theory that they are anyway not going to reach very often, therefore it's tempting with a smaller sideline.} Nf6 5. Nc3 Nxd5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Bc4 {Another common move. Should we play slowly with ... e6 , the bishop is a bit better on c4 than b5 .} Nb6 8. Bb5 Bg4 {The maximalist approach. We want to bishop outside the pawn chain before playing ... e6 . Another excellent move is 8... g6 .} 9. h3 Bh5 10. g4 {The only critical move. Should we be allowed to develop normally, we would simply be better due to the weak d-pawn.} Bg6 11. Ne5 {Again, White has to act fast.} Rc8 12. Qf3 {It looks like White is getting a strong initiative, but we have a good solution.} e6 {Sacrificing a pawn. It turns out that the White position is rather overextended.} 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Bxc6+ Nd7 {We are a pawn down, and still a few moves from castling, but still we are well. Firstly, White has no good way of preventing ... Bd6 followed by O-O next. After that, even if we don't have anything direct, we still have excellent strategic compensation. Our pawn structure is more compact (the d-pawn for instance is eternally weak), the white kingside is weak, and the queen on f3 combined with the bishop on c6 makes a shaky impression. None of these factors are by themselves enough compensation, but together they add up. I'd definitely pick Black here in a practical game.} *

