1. c4 c6 2. e4 {The Panov. This one is slightly annoying. Not because it is in any way challenging theoretically, but because it leads to a bit more theory than I usually prefer.} d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. cxd5 {This is an independent line. Actually, when reaching this position from 1. c4 rather than 1. e4 , I believe this is much more likely. This might sound odd, but the reason is that there is a lot less theory here than in the traditional Panov lines. As White played 1. c4 , they are likely not 1. e4 -players, therefore not too interested in learning too much theory that they are anyway not going to reach very often, therefore it's tempting with a smaller sideline.} Nf6 5. Nc3 Nxd5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Bb5 ({This is an independent option for White. 7.d4 a6 transposes to} 7. d4 Nf6 {Nc3 Nc6 Nf3 a6 cxd5} 8. Nd5 {, analyzed here .}) 7... e6 (7... g6 {is also a good option.}) 8. d4 (8. O-O Bd6 9. d4 O-O {Transposes the current line.}) 8... Bd6 {I like this square for the bishop. It's a bit more active than e7 , and importantly it also allows for ... Nce7 later. That can be a very useful idea to support both the kingside, but also the key d5 -square.} 9. O-O O-O 10. Bd3 {This probably makes the most sense. It looks like White loses a tempo, but as White never wants to take on c6 , the bishop wasn't really doing anything on b5 anyway. Now we should be a bit careful to not get under attack on the kingside.} h6 {Remember this setup. We prevent Ng5 and Bg5 . Next up, we want to play ... Nf6 to further defend our kingside. Remember, if nothing happens, White will be stuck with the isolated pawn on d4 , giving us a long-term edge.} 11. Re1 Nf6 ({Preparing to play ... b6 .} 11... b6 {This is strategically dubious.} 12. Nxd5 $1 exd5 {This structure is completely equal if our pawn is being back on b7 , but the ... b6 -move actually changes the evaluation quite a bit. The knight on c6 lacks support, and the b6 -square is not available for our queen. It's still not much, but I imagine White is a bit happy here.}) 12. Ne4 Nxe4 13. Bxe4 Bd7 {Also looks completely fine. Every trade is in principle in our favor as White is the one with the isolated pawn.} *

