1. c4 c6 2. e4 {The Panov. This one is slightly annoying. Not because it is in any way challenging theoretically, but because it leads to a bit more theory than I usually prefer.} d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. d4 {This is now a real Panov.} Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5 {This is a sharp sideline. We basically only need to know one line here, but if we don't, then it can be really unpleasant.} Be6 {Looks very odd, but White is almost certainly going to take on f6 , and after we recapture with the e-pawn the bishop on e6 looks normal again.} 7. Nf3 g6 (7... a6 {transposing to Nf3 a6 Bg5 Be6 , the next line in the chapter, is of course also a good option.}) 8. Qb3 {This one is also useful to know. White is trying to hit us before we have developed.} Na5 {This is the typical reaction against Qb3 's in these lines.} 9. Qa3 Bg7 {Don't get greedy and try to win the c-pawn. Development is the most important still.} 10. cxd5 Nxd5 11. Bb5+ Nc6 12. O-O Qd6 {The last move to know. Castling immediately would leave the e7 -pawn hanging in the end, but this easily solves all our problems. No matter how White reacts next, we will be able to castle.} *

