1. c4 c6 2. e4 {The Panov. This one is slightly annoying. Not because it is in any way challenging theoretically, but because it leads to a bit more theory than I usually prefer.} d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. d4 {This is now a real Panov.} Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5 {This is a sharp sideline. We basically only need to know one line here, but if we don't, then it can be really unpleasant.} Be6 {Looks very odd, but White is almost certainly going to take on f6 , and after we recapture with the e-pawn the bishop on e6 looks normal again.} 7. c5 {A logical move in itself after ... Be6 , but it's not that well combined with Bg5 .} Ne4 {An excellent response. If White trades on e4 the d4 -pawn will get very weak.} 8. Be3 ({This is the move White really wants to play, and indeed it's the most popular by far. Unfortunately for White, it doesn't really work.} 8. Bf4 g6 {Followed by ... Bg7 and ... O-O looks like nice counterplay for Black.}) 8... Nxc5 {A small but important tactic.} 9. dxc5 d4 {We win back the piece while keeping the initiative. The f8 -bishop will be developed via g7 .} *

