1. c4 c6 2. e4 {The Panov. This one is slightly annoying. Not because it is in any way challenging theoretically, but because it leads to a bit more theory than I usually prefer.} d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. d4 {This is now a real Panov.} Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Nf3 {The main move. Now I'd like to suggest an old favorite of mine, that I popularized on higher levels in my game against Mamedyarov in Wijk Aan Zee 2022.} a6 {Slightly provocative but highly interesting! I really enjoy this idea. Normally Panov players are expecting something very solid and well-trodden, but by ... a6 we immediately forces White to play chess! The chess-technical point of the move is simply to prevent Bb5 , while making a useful waiting move. We still have hopes of developing our light squared bishop outside the pawn chain.} 7. Bg5 Be6 {This is similar to 6. Bg5 . However, the move ... a6 is perhaps not the most useful here, so White arguably have a slightly better version. This is far from enough to claim an advantage, though.} 8. c5 {The best move. White wants to play Bd3 , but then the pawn on c4 would be hanging for real.} g6 9. Bd3 {If White doesn't place the bishop here, we will be able to play ... Ne4 later on.} Bg7 {Now we are ready for ... Bg4 next.} 10. h3 {Preventing ... Bg4 .} Nd7 {This is smart. We attack the pawn on d4 , but what we really do is prepare to break White's pawn chain.} 11. Bc2 b6 {Now the c5 -pawn is hanging for real.} 12. cxb6 Qxb6 {White has no good way of defending d4 , but can trade it for our d5 -pawn after which the position is likely to be rather equal.} 13. O-O Nxd4 14. Ba4 {The point. White has just enough pressure to keep the balance.} Nxf3+ 15. Qxf3 Qb7 16. Rad1 O-O 17. Bxd7 {Liquidating everything.} Qxd7 18. Nxd5 Bxd5 19. Rxd5 Qb7 {The position is equal. Most likely, the queens will get traded soon. White has a queenside majority, but it's not really moving anywhere.} *

