1. c4 c6 2. e4 {The Panov. This one is slightly annoying. Not because it is in any way challenging theoretically, but because it leads to a bit more theory than I usually prefer.} d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. d4 {This is now a real Panov.} Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Nf3 {The main move. Now I'd like to suggest an old favorite of mine, that I popularized on higher levels in my game against Mamedyarov in Wijk Aan Zee 2022.} a6 {Slightly provocative but highly interesting! I really enjoy this idea. Normally Panov players are expecting something very solid and well-trodden, but by ... a6 we immediately forces White to play chess! The chess-technical point of the move is simply to prevent Bb5 , while making a useful waiting move. We still have hopes of developing our light squared bishop outside the pawn chain.} 7. h3 {A cunning waiting move, which I have employed myself as White.} dxc4 {A concrete reaction. In the isolated queen's pawn positions, the move h3 is a lot less useful than our ... a6 .} (7... g6 {is an interesting option, but now White can play} 8. c5 $5 {without us being able to reply ... Bg4 .}) 8. Bxc4 e6 {We continue with natural development.} 9. O-O Be7 {This time White is a bit faster opening up with d5 , so we should put the bishop on e7 to block the e-file.} 10. a3 {A typical move to give the bishop a nice square on a2 .} O-O {The most likely scenario here is that White pushes d5 and loads of trades will appear.} 11. Re1 {This gives us an extra option.} b5 12. Ba2 b4 {Before White could play d5 . Still equal, but a bit livelier play than the mainline.} *

