1. c4 c6 2. e4 {The Panov. This one is slightly annoying. Not because it is in any way challenging theoretically, but because it leads to a bit more theory than I usually prefer.} d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. d4 {This is now a real Panov.} Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Nf3 {The main move. Now I'd like to suggest an old favorite of mine, that I popularized on higher levels in my game against Mamedyarov in Wijk Aan Zee 2022.} a6 {Slightly provocative but highly interesting! I really enjoy this idea. Normally Panov players are expecting something very solid and well-trodden, but by ... a6 we immediately forces White to play chess! The chess-technical point of the move is simply to prevent Bb5 , while making a useful waiting move. We still have hopes of developing our light squared bishop outside the pawn chain.} 7. c5 {From a theoretical point of view, I believe this is the most challenging. I also played it with White in a classical game against Jorden Van Foreest. After playing that game, though, I realized that the positions are rather more difficult for White to play over the board, and I don't think I would have chosen it again.} Bg4 {This is important. Our main strategic aim is to put pressure on the d4 -pawn.} 8. Be2 g6 {Just like on the previous move, the idea is to put pressure on d4 .} 9. Be3 (9. O-O Bg7 10. Be3 e6 {transposes to the line we're analyzing.}) 9... Bg7 10. O-O e6 {This is an important move order, but one that wasn't played by Van Foreest against me. It sounds strange, but we want to keep the g8 -square for our knight!} 11. b4 {The best move. Now the ideas with ... Ng8 are a bit slow, as White is opening up the queenside.} O-O 12. h3 {Logical now that ... Ng8 no longer exists.} Bxf3 13. Bxf3 h6 {Another excellent move. The idea is not easy to spot at first glance, but if we know the previous line we might figure it out. We want ... Kh7 , followed by Ng8 - e7 again! Amazingly, White seems to have no good way to stop it.} 14. Ne2 {White is anticipating our idea and overprotects d4 .} (14. g3 Kh7 15. Rb1 Ng8 {We will get our usual counterplay.}) 14... e5 {A good moment for this, as the knight on c3 is gone. Here it's also important that we have our pawn on h6 , preventing the annoying Bg5 -pin.} 15. dxe5 Nxe5 {We have excellent pieces. The d5 -pawn is more of a strength than a weakness, and all our pieces are well-placed. White is suffering from having the b- and c-pawns too far advanced.} *

