1. c4 c6 2. e4 {The Panov. This one is slightly annoying. Not because it is in any way challenging theoretically, but because it leads to a bit more theory than I usually prefer.} d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. d4 {This is now a real Panov.} Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Nf3 {The main move. Now I'd like to suggest an old favorite of mine, that I popularized on higher levels in my game against Mamedyarov in Wijk Aan Zee 2022.} a6 {Slightly provocative but highly interesting! I really enjoy this idea. Normally Panov players are expecting something very solid and well-trodden, but by ... a6 we immediately forces White to play chess! The chess-technical point of the move is simply to prevent Bb5 , while making a useful waiting move. We still have hopes of developing our light squared bishop outside the pawn chain.} 7. cxd5 {We should probably regard this as the mainline. It's logical to open the center when we play a slow move like ... a6 .} Nxd5 8. Bd3 g6 {This is very similar 8. Bc4 .} 9. Be4 Be6 {Usually a good square for the bishop in these lines. We don't want to take on c3 too early.} 10. O-O Bg7 11. Ng5 Nxc3 {Once again, a good reaction to Ng5 .} 12. bxc3 Bc4 (12... Bd5 $4 13. Qf3 $1 {This is the only trick we should be mindful of. As we haven't castled, f7 is hanging and we are busted.}) 13. Re1 O-O {Now f7 is defended, and we are ready for ... Bd5 next.} *

