1. c4 c6 2. e4 {The Panov. This one is slightly annoying. Not because it is in any way challenging theoretically, but because it leads to a bit more theory than I usually prefer.} d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. d4 {This is now a real Panov.} Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Nf3 {The main move. Now I'd like to suggest an old favorite of mine, that I popularized on higher levels in my game against Mamedyarov in Wijk Aan Zee 2022.} a6 {Slightly provocative but highly interesting! I really enjoy this idea. Normally Panov players are expecting something very solid and well-trodden, but by ... a6 we immediately forces White to play chess! The chess-technical point of the move is simply to prevent Bb5 , while making a useful waiting move. We still have hopes of developing our light squared bishop outside the pawn chain.} 7. cxd5 {We should probably regard this as the mainline. It's logical to open the center when we play a slow move like ... a6 .} Nxd5 8. Bc4 Be6 {This looks funky, but it works out well here.} 9. Ng5 {This move has been tried a few times. It's an attempt to force a draw.} Nxc3 10. Bxe6 Nxd1 11. Bxf7+ Kd7 12. Be6+ Ke8 13. Bf7+ {White is obliged to force the draw.} Kd7 14. Be6+ Kc7 (14... Ke8 {draws, but if we want chaos, it's possible to play on. Objectively, it is OK, but I have to be honest and say that I would rather play White in the ensuing complications.}) 15. Bf4+ Kb6 16. Rxd1 Ka7 {Tucking the king safely away on a7 . We are not getting mated, but White has good compensation for the queen nevertheless.} 17. d5 Qa5+ 18. Bd2 Nb4 19. O-O {All these moves are forced for both sides. The most likely thing to happen now is that we will give back another piece. We still have a material advantage, and White still has good compensation.} Qb5 20. Be3+ b6 21. Nf7 Rg8 22. Ne5 g6 {It's imperative that we manage to develop our pieces. For this purpose, even giving up the rook on g8 is worth it.} 23. Nc6+ {Very far from the only move, but just an example of how play might develop.} Nxc6 24. dxc6 Qxc6 25. Bxg8 e6 {Material it's getting closer to equality. We have soaked up some of the pressure, but I still believe the position is easier for White to play. Still, it's an incredibly complicated fight and not worse for Black objectively, so if you want to live on the edge, please go ahead!} *

