1. c4 c6 2. e4 {The Panov. This one is slightly annoying. Not because it is in any way challenging theoretically, but because it leads to a bit more theory than I usually prefer.} d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. d4 {This is now a real Panov.} Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Nf3 {The main move. Now I'd like to suggest an old favorite of mine, that I popularized on higher levels in my game against Mamedyarov in Wijk Aan Zee 2022.} a6 {Slightly provocative but highly interesting! I really enjoy this idea. Normally Panov players are expecting something very solid and well-trodden, but by ... a6 we immediately forces White to play chess! The chess-technical point of the move is simply to prevent Bb5 , while making a useful waiting move. We still have hopes of developing our light squared bishop outside the pawn chain.} 7. cxd5 {We should probably regard this as the mainline. It's logical to open the center when we play a slow move like ... a6 .} Nxd5 8. Bc4 Be6 {This looks funky, but it works out well here.} 9. Bb3 ({The most natural move, and overwhelmingly most popular.} 9. Qb3 Na5 {already wins a piece! This shows another advantage of ... a6 .}) 9... g6 ({This looks like the simplest solution to me.} 9... Na5 {is also possible, and very complicated, but developing naturally and getting the king to safety is very tempting.}) 10. Ng5 {A direct attempt, but we have enough resources.} Nxc3 {This is almost always the reaction against Ng5 .} 11. bxc3 Bd5 12. c4 {The idea. Suddenly, our bishop is in trouble.} Bxg2 13. Rg1 h6 {It's very important to remember this. Counterattacking is the only way to save our bishop.} 14. Nxf7 Qxd4 {Another key move. Once we know this, we are fine.} 15. Rxg2 Qxa1 16. Nxh8 Qxh8 {We have a pawn up, but in the messy position that emerged it does not matter much. More important is that our king is also safe, and we get counterplay with ... Rd8 on the next move.} *

