1. c4 c6 2. e4 {The Panov. This one is slightly annoying. Not because it is in any way challenging theoretically, but because it leads to a bit more theory than I usually prefer.} d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. d4 {This is now a real Panov.} Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Nf3 {The main move. Now I'd like to suggest an old favorite of mine, that I popularized on higher levels in my game against Mamedyarov in Wijk Aan Zee 2022.} a6 {Slightly provocative but highly interesting! I really enjoy this idea. Normally Panov players are expecting something very solid and well-trodden, but by ... a6 we immediately forces White to play chess! The chess-technical point of the move is simply to prevent Bb5 , while making a useful waiting move. We still have hopes of developing our light squared bishop outside the pawn chain.} 7. cxd5 {We should probably regard this as the mainline. It's logical to open the center when we play a slow move like ... a6 .} Nxd5 8. Bc4 Be6 {This looks funky, but it works out well here.} 9. Bb3 ({The most natural move, and overwhelmingly most popular.} 9. Qb3 Na5 {already wins a piece! This shows another advantage of ... a6 .}) 9... g6 ({This looks like the simplest solution to me.} 9... Na5 {is also possible, and very complicated, but developing naturally and getting the king to safety is very tempting.}) 10. O-O Bg7 11. Ng5 {The only move that has been tried in practice.} Nxc3 {Always our reaction.} 12. bxc3 Bd5 {Next we castle, with an entirely healthy position. Long-term, we want to trade as many pieces as possible and attack the c- and d-pawns.} *

