1. c4 c6 2. e4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. d4 (4. cxd5 Nf6 5. Qa4+ Nbd7 6. Nc3 g6 {Don't worry about not winning back the d5 -pawn immediately. We will play ... Bg7 , O-O and eventually the d5 -pawn will drop off anyway.}) 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Nf3 a6 7. c5 ({•} 7. Bg5 Be6 8. a3 g6 9. Bxf6 exf6 {Important that the doubled f-pawns isn't a concern. If White trades on d5 , the remaining passed d-pawn will be more weak than strong. Additionally, our dark squared bishop is generally stronger than any White minor piece.}) ({•} 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Bc4 Be6 {Looks clumsy, but actually by playing ... g6 next we get harmonious development.}) 7... Bg4 8. Be3 g6 {We always develop the bishop to g7 , as our main target is the d4 -pawn.} *

