1. f4 {The Bird's Opening. There are different approaches to meet all of these sidelines, but my recommendation is always to go for healthy setups rather than trying to punish it too hard. The most likely thing that will happen is that we will get improved versions of more known lines.} (1. g3 d5 2. Bg2 e5 3. d3 Nf6 4. Nf3 {White has nothing better than this.} Nbd7 {Transposing to Nf3 d5 g3 Nd7 Bg2 e5 d3 Ngf6 . Don't worry about that chapter being primarily aimed at Slav players - firstly the entire 2... Nd7 chapter is well suited for both QGD and Slav, but more importantly having gotten to play both ... d5 and ... e5 the structure is more of a universal one.}) 1... d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. g3 (3. e3 e6 4. b3 Be7 5. Bb2 O-O 6. Be2 b6 {We will put our bishop on b7 and push ... c5 . Once the knight gets to e5 , we challenge it by ... Nc6 .}) 3... e6 {A solid, simple and universal system. I believe this fits well for both Queen's Gambit and Slav players.} (3... Bf5 $5 {Such moves are also clearly viable. The only reason 1. f4 can be tricky to meet is because there are too many tempting replies!}) 4. Bg2 b5 {My recommendation. We grab space on the queenside while preparing ... Bb7 to fight for the long diagonal. To me, it just looks like a very nice position, and White will get no real benefit from having the pawn on f4 .} *

