1. Nc3 (1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 Nf6 {This has no real independent value, as White needs to transpose to another part of the repertoire.} 3. b3 (3. c4 c6 {Transposes to c4 c6 Nf3} 4. cxd5 {e3 Nf6 , analyzed starting here .}) 3... Bg4 4. Bb2 e6 {transposes to b3 d5 Bb2 Bg4 Nf3 Nf6 e3 e6 , analyzed starting here .}) 1... d5 {White really should play d4 , transposing to the Classical Slav LTR.} 2. e4 {This is surprisingly common but in my view simply a bad move. White loses too much time.} d4 3. Nce2 (3. Nd5 e5 {Threatening ... c6 . This is entirely hopeless for White.}) 3... e5 4. Ng3 Be6 {This is a key move to remember. Our setup is ... Be6 and ... f6 . This is very good because it fights against both White's knights on g3 and f3 . Later on, we can either play ... c5 to support the center, or even the immediate ... Nc6 , potentially followed by ... Qd7 and ... O-O-O} 5. c3 {The recommendation of Lawrence Trent in his 1. Nc3 course.} Nc6 6. Bb5 Nge7 {We should never allow the doubled c-pawns, as they are entirely inflexible.} 7. d3 Qd6 {An interesting setup. We are one day intending ... O-O-O .} 8. Nf3 f6 ({The immediate} 8... Qc5 {is also possible, but a bit too messy for my taste.}) 9. O-O a6 {Simple chess. Our center is very solid, so we are starting to kick White back.} 10. Ba4 ({Probably} 10. Bxc6+ {is objectively sounder, but that would leave us with a very comfortable position without effort.}) 10... dxc3 11. bxc3 O-O-O {The point of our play. Now White struggles to defend the d3 -pawn.} 12. Bc2 {Perhaps giving up the pawn is practically stronger, but there is far from enough compensation.} h5 {The last key move of our idea. We are getting ready to kick back the knights with …h4 and …g5- g4 next, after which the initiative is entirely in our hands.} *

