1. Nc3 (1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 Nf6 {This has no real independent value, as White needs to transpose to another part of the repertoire.} 3. b3 (3. c4 c6 {Transposes to c4 c6 Nf3} 4. cxd5 {e3 Nf6 , analyzed starting here .}) 3... Bg4 4. Bb2 e6 {transposes to b3 d5 Bb2 Bg4 Nf3 Nf6 e3 e6 , analyzed starting here .}) 1... d5 {White really should play d4 , transposing to the Classical Slav LTR.} 2. e4 {This is surprisingly common but in my view simply a bad move. White loses too much time.} d4 3. Nce2 (3. Nd5 e5 {Threatening ... c6 . This is entirely hopeless for White.}) 3... e5 4. d3 c5 {This leads to some sort of King’s Indian with reversed colors, but an entirely unattractive version for White. The only thing we need to remember is to trade on f4 if White plays it, so that we get the e5 -square for a piece.} 5. f4 Nc6 {Trading immediately is also OK, but we might as well start with this.} 6. Nf3 exf4 7. Bxf4 Nge7 {Followed by ... Ng6 and ... Bd6 , with nice control over the e5 -square.} *

