1. g3 {It's rare to start with this move order, but it doesn't have too much independent value.} d5 2. Bg2 {This is actually slightly tricky. We can't play like we usually do against 1. Nf3 /2. g3 . On the other hand, there is a big downside with White's move order.} e5 {When given the chance to grab such a big center, I believe we should take it.} 3. Nf3 {This is some sort of reversed Alekhine, but g3 / Bg2 does not fit into the Alekhine at all.} ({•} 3. c4 c6 {transposes to c4 c6 g3} 4. cxd5 {Bg2 e5 , analyzed here .}) ({•} 3. d3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Nbd7 {Not necessary, but the simplest solution. We are now transposing to Nf3 d5 g3 Nd7 Bg2 e5 with 5. d3 , here .}) 3... e4 4. Nd4 c5 5. Nb3 c4 {The hunting variation is not so great for White in the normal Alekhine, but here White has wasted two moves on g3 , Bg2 which makes it work well.} 6. Nd4 Bc5 7. c3 (7. e3 {This is worse than c3 for White, as the c1 -bishop is blocked in and the light squares are weakened.} Nf6 8. d3 cxd3 {The simplest. We keep our strong e4 -pawn.} 9. cxd3 O-O {We are simply better. The e4 -pawn is strong, and we can build up an initiative on the kingside with moves like ... Qe7 and ... Bg4 . Eventually, even pushing ... h5 - h4 will make sense.}) 7... Nf6 8. d3 {White has to break in the center sooner or later.} cxd3 9. exd3 O-O 10. dxe4 dxe4 {We are simply better. The e4 -pawn is a strength more than a weakness, and White has wasted too much time with their knight.} *

