1. b4 {The Orangutan! Basically this is similar to 1. b3 , but the pawn on b4 means that White is likely having to spend another tempo defending it with a3 later on. It is true that White also gains some space, but I don't think that is a relevant factor at all.} d5 2. Bb2 Bg4 {I quite like the idea of playing the same as against 1. b3 Again, what will most probably happen is that we get a slightly improved version of those lines.} 3. c4 {This is an independent option. With the pawn on b4 White has access to the b3 -square for their queen.} ({•} 3. Nf3 Nf6 {This will be similar to b3 d5 Bb2 Bg4 Nf3 Nf6 . We don’t really need to know anything more. Sooner or later White will lose some time protecting the b4 -pawn, and the extra queenside space isn’t really relevant, as all our pieces have comfortable developing squares either way.}) ({•} 3. h3 Bh5 {Again similar to the 1. b3 -lines, without White getting any real benefit from having the pawn on b4 . Indeed, it will most likely prove to be a target rather than a strength.}) 3... c6 {A small move order point. We want to be able to recapture on d5 with the c-pawn, after which the pawn on b4 makes even less sense.} 4. Qb3 e6 5. e3 Nf6 {With the usual kind of play. We can still go for ... Nbd7 , ... Bd6 and O-O . Always recapture on d5 with the c-pawn. There isn't really much else to know.} *

