1. b4 {The Orangutan. Obviously we can do basically whatever we want, but there is nothing wrong with our favorite setup.} d5 2. Bb2 Nf6 3. Nf3 e6 {Obviously far from the only move, but it makes sense to just stick to our setup.} 4. b5 Bd6 5. e3 O-O {The only difference is that we should not really play ... b6 here, as then the pawn on b5 would suddenly make a lot of sense. Instead, we try to prepare ... e5 .} 6. a4 (6. c4 c6 {Intending to take on b5 , if allowed.} 7. a4 Nbd7 {transposes.}) 6... Nbd7 7. c4 c6 {This looks more like a Slav or Semislav move, but the position is of course independent as White has spent so many tempi moving queenside pawns. As usual, I enjoy meeting flank play with a central strategy, and here it certainly works well.} *

