1. f4 {This is not a good move. As the legendary Swedish grandmaster Ulf Andersson explained to me as a kid: 1. f4 weakens not only the diagonal a7 - g1 , but also the second rank.} (1. e3 {This is highly likely to transpose elsewhere.} d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nf3 (4. d4 {transposes to the Classical Slav .}) 4... a6 {transposes to c4 c6 Nf3} 5. cxd5 {e3 Nf6 Nc3 a6 , i.e. the starting position for chapters 1-4 and part of chapter 5.}) 1... d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 ({The same setup is also possible against 3. b3 . This will be a bit similar to b3 d5 Bb2} 3... Bg4 {f3 Bd7 f4 , but our bishop will be more harmoniously placed on b7 than d7 , so we should have an even easier time here.}) 4. Be2 Be7 5. O-O O-O {It's a nice touch to castle before playing ... c5 , so that Bb5 + is never any concern. It wouldn't have been anyway, but still no reason to allow it.} 6. b3 {This is how White usually develops in this line.} b6 7. Bb2 Bb7 8. Ne5 c5 {It's very similar to the 1. b3 line. We should slowly begin to challenge the e5 -knight. Once we get a rook to d8 , pushing ... d4 will always be something to keep in mind.} *

