1. f4 {This is not a good move. As the legendary Swedish grandmaster Ulf Andersson explained to me as a kid: 1. f4 weakens not only the diagonal a7 - g1 , but also the second rank.} (1. e3 {This is highly likely to transpose elsewhere.} d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nf3 (4. d4 {transposes to the Classical Slav .}) 4... a6 {transposes to c4 c6 Nf3} 5. cxd5 {e3 Nf6 Nc3 a6 , the Accelerated Meran, Qc2 chapter .}) 1... d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. g3 {This is definitely the most interesting move. White is going for the Reversed Leningrad Dutch.} e6 {I like this setup. It is also how Kramnik achieved an excellent position against Carlsen.} 4. Bg2 b5 {This is our idea! Long term, in the Leningrad Dutch White is trying to push e4 , therefore we really want our bishop on b7 to prevent that. We play ... b5 rather than ... b6 because our own long-term plan is to grab as much space as possible on the queenside.} 5. O-O Bb7 {The moves can be played in different move orders around here, but it will usually come down to the same thing.} 6. d3 Be7 7. a4 b4 {This is always our reaction to a4 . The inclusion of the two moves does not alter the position much.} *

