1. c4 e6 {For a Queen's Gambit Declined player, this is by far the most logical reaction to 1. c4 .} 2. Nf3 ({•} 2. d4 d5 {Transposes to d4} 3. cxd5 {c4 e6 .}) ({•} 2. Nc3 d5 3. d4 {Transposes to d4 d5} dxc4 {e6 Nc3 . My own Magnus Queen's Gambit recommends 3... a6 here, but if you have any other 3rd move in your repertoire you can obviously play it as well. That is one of the perks of this LTR - it can be combined not just with my own previous courses, but any course on the Slav or the Queen's Gambit Declined.}) 2... d5 3. e3 {The main question for White is always wether to fianchetto the light squared bishop or not. In this chapter we focus on White not fianchettoing it.} Nf6 4. b3 (4. Nc3 b6 {transposes here .}) 4... b6 {This is my universal solution to all the e3 -setups. Stylistically, it leads to a rich game where often all pieces remain on the board. It is NOT an attempt to clinically forcing equality move-by-move, but rather a way to get playable fighting positions full of life. One of the main advantages of playing the b6 -setup is that it can be played against almost any move orders, making it much easier for us to remember.} (4... c5 {This would be my choice if trying to force a draw.} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bb2 Nc6 7. Bb5 Bd6 8. O-O O-O 9. d4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Bc7 $1 {Is the modern mainline, where Black is equalizing without too many issues.}) 5. Bb2 (5. d4 {It's not unreasonable for White to play this, now that we have committed to ... b6 .} Bd6 {It's the same setup even with the pawn on d4 . If you want to, you could also transpose to the Magnus Queen's Gambit by playing 5... a6 , but there is no great need to give a tempo away.}) 5... Bb7 6. cxd5 {Generally speaking, this is White's main idea against our b6 -setup.} ({•} 6. g3 {Beware of this! Fianchettoing the bishop is always the most ambitious option for White. The move e2 - e3 doesn't really belong, though, which means this is a better version for Black. Still, we should always take care after g3 .} c5 {Changing setup - that's how important the choice of fianchettoing the f1 -bishop is!} (6... Bd6 {If you are feeling lazy, then this is the approach. Not having played cxd5 is slightly beneficial for White, but it's not the end of the world, and I believe Black's position is fully playable. Still, White might keep the tiniest of edges and therefore I don't feel comfortable recommending it as my main choice.} 7. Bg2 O-O 8. O-O {White is delaying cxd5 in order to keep maximum flexibility.} Re8 9. Nc3 Nbd7 10. Qe2 {Here it's harder for Black to make a good move, as White did not yet trade on d5 .} Ne4 $5 {My proposed solution, initiating some trades. Again, White might have the tiniest of advantages, but Black is solid.}) 7. Bg2 Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. Nc3 Qc8 $5 {This funny-looking move is an old favorite of mine, and my recommendation. The basic idea is to always be able to recapture on d5 with a piece rather than a pawn. And if White does nothing, we play ... Rd4 followed by ... d4 , grabbing the initiative.}) ({•} 6. Nc3 {One of the slightly more annoying lines.} Nbd7 7. Rc1 a6 {Necessary, to prepare ... Bd6 without Nb5 .} 8. cxd5 exd5 {On any normal move, we simply play our usual setup.} 9. Ne2 $5 {The recommendation of Sielecki and Hansen.} c5 $5 {As we anyway have to play ... g6 next move, we might as well fianchetto the bishop.} 10. Ng3 g6 {Necessary, as bishop moves are met by Nf5 . It's slightly annoying having to play ... g6 , but we fianchetto the bishop, finish development and have nice counterplay in the center.}) 6... exd5 7. g3 {Actually the main move! The simple truth is that the bishop is simply much better on g2 than on e2 / d3 .} Bd6 {Now all our next moves are the typical setup, which we are very, very likely to reach after 3. e3 .} 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O Re8 10. Nc3 a6 {Always necessary after Nc3 , as Nb5 is an annoying idea otherwise.} 11. Rc1 Nbd7 {An interesting position full of life. Both sides have a lot of plans available and the middlegame is very rich.} *

