1. c4 e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 {This move is, just like against 2... c6 instead of 2... e6 , a fairly critical way for White to play. It is very popular at the higher levels because it tends to lead to less forcing play compared to mainlines with 1. d4 . This should suit us well too - after all, we are not trying to force a draw, but rather looking for a fully fledged fight!} Nf6 4. Nc3 {If we choose another setup against 4. b3 , then this move is very important and leads to quite different kind of play. However, when we play with ... b6 it doesn't really matter, as the logical play will transpose to b3 -setups later on.} b6 5. cxd5 (5. b3 {Sielecki and Hansen's move order in their LTR on 1. c4 / 1. Nf3 , but it's quickly going to transpose.} Bb7 6. Bb2 Nbd7 {transposes to b3 b6 Bb2 Bb7 Nc3 Nbd7 , starting here .}) 5... exd5 6. b4 {This is a funny extra option, recommended by the engine and tried by a couple of strong grandmasters.} Bd6 7. Qb3 c6 {This is an exception to our rule of always playing ... Bb7 . The point is that against the queen on b3 we want to be able to play ... Be6 , but perhaps also later to utilize the 'hook' on b4 by playing ... a5 .} 8. Bb2 O-O 9. b5 {The most logical move, trying to hit our pawn chain.} Be6 10. Qc2 c5 11. Ng5 {The only challenging move, else we would have time to develop and simply enjoy our central space advantage.} Nbd7 {White can snatch the bishop pair, but that would leave their king light on defenders.} 12. Bd3 h6 13. Nxe6 fxe6 {White has the bishop pair, but that is compensated for by our space advantage and active pieces.} 14. O-O Bxh2+ 15. Kxh2 Ng4+ {gives us a winning attack.} 16. Kg3 Nxf2 {Highlighting the lack of defenders. White is getting mated shortly.} *

