1. c4 e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 {This move is, just like against 2... c6 instead of 2... e6 , a fairly critical way for White to play. It is very popular at the higher levels because it tends to lead to less forcing play compared to mainlines with 1. d4 . This should suit us well too - after all, we are not trying to force a draw, but rather looking for a fully fledged fight!} Nf6 4. Nc3 {If we choose another setup against 4. b3 , then this move is very important and leads to quite different kind of play. However, when we play with ... b6 it doesn't really matter, as the logical play will transpose to b3 -setups later on.} b6 5. cxd5 (5. b3 {Sielecki and Hansen's move order in their LTR on 1. c4 / 1. Nf3 , but it's quickly going to transpose.} Bb7 6. Bb2 Nbd7 {transposes to b3 b6 Bb2 Bb7 Nc3 Nbd7 , starting here .}) 5... exd5 6. g3 {This was tried by the German prodigy Vincent Keymer. Of course, b3 at any point would transpose to 4. b3 , but Keymer tried to play entirely without b3 .} Bd6 {One of the great things with our system is that we can play the same moves against almost everything.} 7. Bg2 O-O 8. O-O Re8 {Usually the most flexible move.} 9. Re1 {Keymer's move.} Nbd7 {Without a rook on its way to c1 we don't really have to worry about Nb5 , which in turn means we can save on ... a6 .} 10. d3 {This is how Keymer played, intending a quick e4 .} Bb7 {For some reason, Ding didn't play this simple move. Now e4 is prevented and most probably White would have to play b3 anyway, leading to the sort of play we are well familiar with.} *

