1. c4 e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 {This move is, just like against 2... c6 instead of 2... e6 , a fairly critical way for White to play. It is very popular at the higher levels because it tends to lead to less forcing play compared to mainlines with 1. d4 . This should suit us well too - after all, we are not trying to force a draw, but rather looking for a fully fledged fight!} Nf6 4. b3 b6 ({This is our setup. We want to play the position as we do in the lines after} 4... d4 {d5 c4 e6 Nf3 a6 e3 . There are two main ways of facing the system with early e3 by White: one is to go for a quick ... c5 , initiating forcing play and trying to equalize by force. This is very solid, and a well-prepared player has good chances of liquidating most of the pieces.  But it's also boring, and not at all in the spirit of this repertoire or how I like to play chess in general. The other way to play is to just develop the pieces to sensible squares and get an incredibly rich middlegame with all pieces on the board. Needless to say, that fits perfectly with our general approach!}) 5. d4 {In general, White usually refrains from playing this too early. For us, it's no issue, as we can at the bare minimum immediately transpose to the Magnus Queen's Gambit repertoire with 5... a6 , or just play in the same way but saving on the a6 -move.} Bd6 {Makes a lot of sense, basically giving an improved version for Black, as ... a6 is not the most useful move here.} (5... a6 {is a direct transposition to the Magnus Queen's Gambit.}) *

