1. c4 e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 {This move is, just like against 2... c6 instead of 2... e6 , a fairly critical way for White to play. It is very popular at the higher levels because it tends to lead to less forcing play compared to mainlines with 1. d4 . This should suit us well too - after all, we are not trying to force a draw, but rather looking for a fully fledged fight!} Nf6 4. b3 b6 ({This is our setup. We want to play the position as we do in the lines after} 4... d4 {d5 c4 e6 Nf3 a6 e3 . There are two main ways of facing the system with early e3 by White: one is to go for a quick ... c5 , initiating forcing play and trying to equalize by force. This is very solid, and a well-prepared player has good chances of liquidating most of the pieces.  But it's also boring, and not at all in the spirit of this repertoire or how I like to play chess in general. The other way to play is to just develop the pieces to sensible squares and get an incredibly rich middlegame with all pieces on the board. Needless to say, that fits perfectly with our general approach!}) 5. Bb2 Bb7 6. g3 {This requires careful consideration! Flexibility is the name of the game in this line, and here White is being flexible with trading on d5 .} c5 {A bit controversial, but I think this is the best objectively. The logic behind it is that once White has committed to g3 , we can always recapture on d5 with a piece.} 7. cxd5 Qxd5 {This is the rarest of the recaptures, but here it makes sense. The queen will retreat to d7 later on, which is a very decent square.} 8. Bg2 Nc6 {Important. We don't normally put our knight on c6 , but here it creates a harmonious position.} 9. Nc3 Qd7 10. O-O Be7 {This is completely safe for us. We will have similar positions in the 3. g3 lines, but here due to the somewhat meaningless e3 -move, we simply have a better version.} *

