1. c4 e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 {This move is, just like against 2... c6 instead of 2... e6 , a fairly critical way for White to play. It is very popular at the higher levels because it tends to lead to less forcing play compared to mainlines with 1. d4 . This should suit us well too - after all, we are not trying to force a draw, but rather looking for a fully fledged fight!} Nf6 4. b3 b6 ({This is our setup. We want to play the position as we do in the lines after} 4... d4 {d5 c4 e6 Nf3 a6 e3 . There are two main ways of facing the system with early e3 by White: one is to go for a quick ... c5 , initiating forcing play and trying to equalize by force. This is very solid, and a well-prepared player has good chances of liquidating most of the pieces.  But it's also boring, and not at all in the spirit of this repertoire or how I like to play chess in general. The other way to play is to just develop the pieces to sensible squares and get an incredibly rich middlegame with all pieces on the board. Needless to say, that fits perfectly with our general approach!}) 5. Bb2 Bb7 6. g3 {This requires careful consideration! Flexibility is the name of the game in this line, and here White is being flexible with trading on d5 .} c5 {A bit controversial, but I think this is the best objectively. The logic behind it is that once White has committed to g3 , we can always recapture on d5 with a piece.} 7. Bg2 Be7 {Keeping the option of recapturing on d5 with the queen.} 8. O-O O-O 9. Nc3 {Now we have transposed to a very, very popular position that I have played with both colours. Normally I don't like entering big theoretical lines from other openings, but in this case I think it's fine to make an exception. Although there are many games, the amount of theory one needs to know is very limited as the position is not forcing in nature.} Qc8 {I have liked this move for many years already. It looks odd, but the idea is actually very simple. We always want to be able to recapture on d5 with a piece, and for that reason we don't want to play ... Nc6 . But by playing ... Qc8 , we get ready to overprotect d5 with ... Rd8 , after which we are finally ready to play ... Nc6 . Meanwhile, it's not easy for White to do anything about it.} 10. cxd5 Nxd5 11. Nxd5 Bxd5 {Such continuations are always very solid for Black. We keep the long diagonal open, so that we always can trade bishops as soon as the f3 -knight moves.} 12. d4 Nd7 {To recapture on c5 with the knight. Next we play ... Qb7 and bring a rook to the d-file. It's very comfortable equality.} *

