a piece, and for that reason we don't want to play ... Nc6 . But by playing ... Qc8 , we get ready to overprotect d5 with ... Rd8 , after which we are finally ready to play ... Nc6 . Meanwhile, it's not easy for White to do anything about it.} 10. Qe2 {The most common move. This is simply how White puts their pieces in this line.} Rd8 {Even creating a small threat of ... d4 - d3} 11. Rfc1 {This is an interesting attempt by White. The rook creates an unpleasant x-ray against our queen.} dxc4 {Changing plan. Opening the d-file makes sense after Rfc1 , as the rook now clearly belongs on d1 instead.} ({•} 11... Nc6 {Would be the other natural move, but also works less well with a rook on c1 .} 12. cxd5 Nxd5 13. Nxd5 {Objectively, taking with the e-pawn on d5 is better and fully playable, but it wasn't our idea. Nxd5 d4 Again a little unpleasant due to the pressure on the c-file.}) ({•} 11... d4 $2 12. exd4 cxd4 13. Nd5 $1 {This is White's tactical point. Due to the discovered attack on the c-file White is massively better.}) 12. bxc4 Ne4 {Very solid. We will play ... Nd7 and then most likely trade more pieces with ... Bf6 later on.} *

