a piece, and for that reason we don't want to play ... Nc6 . But by playing ... Qc8 , we get ready to overprotect d5 with ... Rd8 , after which we are finally ready to play ... Nc6 . Meanwhile, it's not easy for White to do anything about it.} 10. Qe2 {The most common move. This is simply how White puts their pieces in this line.} Rd8 {Even creating a small threat of ... d4 - d3} 11. d3 Nc6 {Now we are ready for this.} 12. Rfd1 (12. cxd5 Nxd5 13. Nxd5 Rxd5 {White will most probably have to play d4 and initiate trades, but that means we are completely fine.}) 12... d4 {Not necessary, but good.} 13. exd4 cxd4 {These Benoni type positions are usually something I try to avoid in this course, but here we have an excellent version, as neither the bishop on b2 nor the rook on d1 really makes any sense.} 14. Nb5 Bc5 15. b4 {Strategically necessary. If the b5 -knight were to retreat we would simply prepare ... e5 with complete control over the center.} Bxb4 16. Nbxd4 Nxd4 17. Nxd4 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 Qd7 {The position has calmed down. We have slightly the better structure, but White's b2 -bishop is a bit more active than ours. I believe it's slightly easier to play Black, but in fact it's probably just equal.} *

