1. c4 e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 {This move is, just like against 2... c6 instead of 2... e6 , a fairly critical way for White to play. It is very popular at the higher levels because it tends to lead to less forcing play compared to mainlines with 1. d4 . This should suit us well too - after all, we are not trying to force a draw, but rather looking for a fully fledged fight!} Nf6 4. b3 b6 ({This is our setup. We want to play the position as we do in the lines after} 4... d4 {d5 c4 e6 Nf3 a6 e3 . There are two main ways of facing the system with early e3 by White: one is to go for a quick ... c5 , initiating forcing play and trying to equalize by force. This is very solid, and a well-prepared player has good chances of liquidating most of the pieces.  But it's also boring, and not at all in the spirit of this repertoire or how I like to play chess in general. The other way to play is to just develop the pieces to sensible squares and get an incredibly rich middlegame with all pieces on the board. Needless to say, that fits perfectly with our general approach!}) 5. Bb2 Bb7 6. g3 {This requires careful consideration! Flexibility is the name of the game in this line, and here White is being flexible with trading on d5 .} Bd6 {It's possible to play in our usual fashion as well, but White might end up a little bit more pleasant.} 7. Bg2 O-O 8. O-O Re8 {We are of course inviting White to capture on d5 at any moment, as it would transpose to 6. cxd5} 9. Nc3 Nbd7 {In general, White is a bit more flexible here and has some extra options. It's not at all bad for Black, but not as straightforward as the mainline.} 10. Qc2 {This is another way for White to make use of not having traded on d5 .} c5 {This is an idea to keep in mind after Qc2 . Once the c-file is opened, the queen will feel a bit uneasy on c2 .} 11. cxd5 {The usual reaction for White.} Nxd5 {Taking with the pawn would let White get their dream position with d4 , and pressure against our center. But here taking with the knight works well, as the queen is not great on c2 .} 12. Nxd5 Bxd5 13. d4 {This is the usual reaction for White. After the center is opened, the b2 -bishop will be strong.} Rc8 {Our idea. Now White loses a tempo on the queen. One tempo might not sound like much, but it's enough for us to solidify our position.} 14. Qe2 Qc7 {We are just in time to get developed. It's important to remove the queen from the d-file as White will soon put a rook there.} 15. e4 Bb7 {Visually White looks a little more active, but as we have no weaknesses we will easily equalize within the next couple of moves.} *

