1. c4 e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 {This move is, just like against 2... c6 instead of 2... e6 , a fairly critical way for White to play. It is very popular at the higher levels because it tends to lead to less forcing play compared to mainlines with 1. d4 . This should suit us well too - after all, we are not trying to force a draw, but rather looking for a fully fledged fight!} Nf6 4. b3 b6 ({This is our setup. We want to play the position as we do in the lines after} 4... d4 {d5 c4 e6 Nf3 a6 e3 . There are two main ways of facing the system with early e3 by White: one is to go for a quick ... c5 , initiating forcing play and trying to equalize by force. This is very solid, and a well-prepared player has good chances of liquidating most of the pieces.  But it's also boring, and not at all in the spirit of this repertoire or how I like to play chess in general. The other way to play is to just develop the pieces to sensible squares and get an incredibly rich middlegame with all pieces on the board. Needless to say, that fits perfectly with our general approach!}) 5. Bb2 Bb7 6. g3 {This requires careful consideration! Flexibility is the name of the game in this line, and here White is being flexible with trading on d5 .} Bd6 {It's possible to play in our usual fashion as well, but White might end up a little bit more pleasant.} 7. Bg2 O-O 8. O-O Re8 {We are of course inviting White to capture on d5 at any moment, as it would transpose to 6. cxd5} 9. Nc3 Nbd7 {In general, White is a bit more flexible here and has some extra options. It's not at all bad for Black, but not as straightforward as the mainline.} 10. Qe2 {This is one of the extra options. The queen would make no sense here if the trade on d5 was included, but now the setup with Qe2 , Rfd1 makes sense.} Ne4 {The logical behind this move is that Ne2 is no longer available as a reply. As the c3 -knight has no other good squares available, we basically force the trade of knights, after which we are ready for ... a5 - a4 . This might be a sound way to play, and in case you for some reason wish to avoid studying 6... c5 it is acceptable.} (10... a6 11. Rfd1 {White can play both d3 and} d4 {next, in both cases with an improved version. Flexibility matters in chess!}) 11. Rfd1 {White as usual has many options.} Nxc3 {Our idea. We've seen this trade before as well. White's c3 -knight is simply a bit better than ours, and it makes our a-pawn push stronger.} 12. Bxc3 a5 {Again, we are not going to rush with ... a4 , but it's always in the air.} 13. Rac1 dxc4 {Not necessary, but an interesting extra option after the trade of knights.} 14. bxc4 e5 {The idea. With the queen on e2 , White can't play d4 and take back with the e-pawn, so now we get counterplay in the center. It's an unusual and complicated structure, but not bad at all for Black.} *

