1. c4 e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 {This move is, just like against 2... c6 instead of 2... e6 , a fairly critical way for White to play. It is very popular at the higher levels because it tends to lead to less forcing play compared to mainlines with 1. d4 . This should suit us well too - after all, we are not trying to force a draw, but rather looking for a fully fledged fight!} Nf6 4. b3 b6 ({This is our setup. We want to play the position as we do in the lines after} 4... d4 {d5 c4 e6 Nf3 a6 e3 . There are two main ways of facing the system with early e3 by White: one is to go for a quick ... c5 , initiating forcing play and trying to equalize by force. This is very solid, and a well-prepared player has good chances of liquidating most of the pieces.  But it's also boring, and not at all in the spirit of this repertoire or how I like to play chess in general. The other way to play is to just develop the pieces to sensible squares and get an incredibly rich middlegame with all pieces on the board. Needless to say, that fits perfectly with our general approach!}) 5. Bb2 Bb7 6. Nc3 {This is a little bit tricky. Normally we automatically play ... a6 once Nc3 comes, but here White still has the option of playing g3 without trading on d5 first, which we should not allow.} Nbd7 7. g3 {Doesn't work that well here.} dxc4 {One of a few different ways to create quick counterplay.} 8. bxc4 e5 {The point.} 9. Bg2 e4 10. Nd4 Ne5 11. O-O Qd7 {Our pawn on e4 and knight on e5 is a real nuisance for White. Next up, we can even allow ourselves to castle long.} *

