1. c4 e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 {This move is, just like against 2... c6 instead of 2... e6 , a fairly critical way for White to play. It is very popular at the higher levels because it tends to lead to less forcing play compared to mainlines with 1. d4 . This should suit us well too - after all, we are not trying to force a draw, but rather looking for a fully fledged fight!} Nf6 4. b3 b6 ({This is our setup. We want to play the position as we do in the lines after} 4... d4 {d5 c4 e6 Nf3 a6 e3 . There are two main ways of facing the system with early e3 by White: one is to go for a quick ... c5 , initiating forcing play and trying to equalize by force. This is very solid, and a well-prepared player has good chances of liquidating most of the pieces.  But it's also boring, and not at all in the spirit of this repertoire or how I like to play chess in general. The other way to play is to just develop the pieces to sensible squares and get an incredibly rich middlegame with all pieces on the board. Needless to say, that fits perfectly with our general approach!}) 5. Bb2 Bb7 6. Nc3 {This is a little bit tricky. Normally we automatically play ... a6 once Nc3 comes, but here White still has the option of playing g3 without trading on d5 first, which we should not allow.} Nbd7 7. Qc2 {This is the recommendation by the GingerGM in his LTR Modern Reti. By playing Qc2 instead of Rc1 White keeps the option of O-O-O} a6 {Our usual reply. We want to play ... Bd6 .} 8. Be2 Bd6 9. Rg1 ({White can of course castle short, leading to a slower game similar to what we have seen many, many times before.} 9. Rg1 {is much more interesting and sharp, though.}) 9... c5 ({Whenever possible, I always like to meet a flank attack with play in the center. Here it leads to highly complicated play, but I feel the position is much more dangerous for White than Black. That being said, it also makes sense to simply prevent White's play by playing} 9... h5 $5 {.}) 10. g4 {Clearly the idea.} d4 {Initiating forcing play. We need to play this before White has time for g5 , which would kick our knight away.} 11. exd4 cxd4 12. Nxd4 Bxh2 {We have traded a flank pawn for a central one. Not normally a good idea, but here we have concrete ideas to justify it.} 13. Rf1 Nc5 14. Nf3 {The only move.} Bxf3 (14... Nd3+ {would lead to a rather equal ending, but the text move is much more interesting.}) 15. Bxf3 Nd3+ {The point. White won't castle in this game!} 16. Ke2 Nxb2 {Now it would be fantastic for us if White recaptured on b2 , but unfortunately our rook is hanging. It turns out though that we get excellent compensation for the rook. As usual, it mainly comes down to king's safety. The White king will be forever vulnerable on e2 , as there is no time to run it towards the queenside for safety.} 17. Bc6+ {A smart intermediate move, forcing our king to move.} Ke7 18. Bxa8 Qxa8 19. Qxb2 Rd8 {Materially speaking we are a full exchange down, but our compensation is plentiful. The king on e2 is the main issue, but also the pawn on g4 is too far forward. Next up, ... Qg2 is a nice idea to put pressure, and ... Be5 another good move to create threats. The engines are just about managing to hold on to a draw for White, but practically it's a nightmare.} *

