1. c4 e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 {This move is, just like against 2... c6 instead of 2... e6 , a fairly critical way for White to play. It is very popular at the higher levels because it tends to lead to less forcing play compared to mainlines with 1. d4 . This should suit us well too - after all, we are not trying to force a draw, but rather looking for a fully fledged fight!} Nf6 4. b3 b6 ({This is our setup. We want to play the position as we do in the lines after} 4... d4 {d5 c4 e6 Nf3 a6 e3 . There are two main ways of facing the system with early e3 by White: one is to go for a quick ... c5 , initiating forcing play and trying to equalize by force. This is very solid, and a well-prepared player has good chances of liquidating most of the pieces.  But it's also boring, and not at all in the spirit of this repertoire or how I like to play chess in general. The other way to play is to just develop the pieces to sensible squares and get an incredibly rich middlegame with all pieces on the board. Needless to say, that fits perfectly with our general approach!}) 5. Bb2 Bb7 6. Nc3 {This is a little bit tricky. Normally we automatically play ... a6 once Nc3 comes, but here White still has the option of playing g3 without trading on d5 first, which we should not allow.} Nbd7 7. Rc1 a6 {We really need this before playing ... Bd6 .} 8. cxd5 {White takes now, with a specific idea in mind.} (8. g3 {Still doesn't really work.} dxc4 9. bxc4 Be7 10. Bg2 Ne5 $1 {With the rook on c1 , ... Nd3 comes with greater force.}) 8... exd5 9. Ne2 {This is the idea. It looks provocative, but actually it makes sense. The point is that the knight will go to g3 , almost forcing us to play ... g6 .} c5 {As White is playing slowly, we try to quickly grab more space.} 10. Ng3 {The point. We can't really develop our f8 -bishop now.} g6 {To be honest, it's slightly annoying having to play ... g6 here. On the other hand, now the knight is not doing much on g3 , and it did take quite some time to get it there.} 11. d4 {This was played once in Malakhov-Anand, 2021. It's logical, but White should finish development first.} h5 12. Bd3 {This was the game, but now our play comes very fast.} h4 13. Ne2 h3 14. g3 c4 {Here this would have been a very strong improvement. White can't take twice due to f3 hanging, but then we get a massive space advantage on both sides of the board.} *

