1. c4 e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 {This move is, just like against 2... c6 instead of 2... e6 , a fairly critical way for White to play. It is very popular at the higher levels because it tends to lead to less forcing play compared to mainlines with 1. d4 . This should suit us well too - after all, we are not trying to force a draw, but rather looking for a fully fledged fight!} Nf6 4. b3 b6 ({This is our setup. We want to play the position as we do in the lines after} 4... d4 {d5 c4 e6 Nf3 a6 e3 . There are two main ways of facing the system with early e3 by White: one is to go for a quick ... c5 , initiating forcing play and trying to equalize by force. This is very solid, and a well-prepared player has good chances of liquidating most of the pieces.  But it's also boring, and not at all in the spirit of this repertoire or how I like to play chess in general. The other way to play is to just develop the pieces to sensible squares and get an incredibly rich middlegame with all pieces on the board. Needless to say, that fits perfectly with our general approach!}) 5. Bb2 Bb7 6. cxd5 {This is by far the most common and natural move. It's a good rule of thumb for White to always consider cxd5 as soon as Black has played ... b6 . The reason is that after the most natural recapture exd5 , Black no longer has the possibility of putting up the 'Carlsbad' pawn chain with d5 - c6 - b7 .} exd5 {This might seem automatic, but it's worth mentioning that in these lines we should always give some thought on how to recapture on d5 . By the pawn is certainly the move in most cases, but there are some exceptions which will be shown later on.} 7. Bb5+ {This was played against me once by Swedish GM Slavko Cicak. White is provoking a small weakness.} c6 8. Be2 {We would slightly prefer to have our pawn on c7 instead of c6 here, but the more important factor is that the bishop is simply worse on e2 than g2 .} Bd6 9. O-O O-O 10. d4 {Always possible, but also always pleasant for us.} Qe7 ({It is also possible to start with} 10... Nbd7 {.}) 11. Nc3 Nbd7 {We are doing well with our usual plans. Centralize the rooks and jump ... Ne4 are the main ideas. It's true that the pawn looks a little ugly on c6 , but on the other hand it also prevents Nb5 , so we can save a move on not having to play ... a6 . White's bishop is also worse on e2 than d3 . All in all, it's a good version of something that is already pleasant to play.} *

