1. c4 e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 {This move is, just like against 2... c6 instead of 2... e6 , a fairly critical way for White to play. It is very popular at the higher levels because it tends to lead to less forcing play compared to mainlines with 1. d4 . This should suit us well too - after all, we are not trying to force a draw, but rather looking for a fully fledged fight!} Nf6 4. b3 b6 ({This is our setup. We want to play the position as we do in the lines after} 4... d4 {d5 c4 e6 Nf3 a6 e3 . There are two main ways of facing the system with early e3 by White: one is to go for a quick ... c5 , initiating forcing play and trying to equalize by force. This is very solid, and a well-prepared player has good chances of liquidating most of the pieces.  But it's also boring, and not at all in the spirit of this repertoire or how I like to play chess in general. The other way to play is to just develop the pieces to sensible squares and get an incredibly rich middlegame with all pieces on the board. Needless to say, that fits perfectly with our general approach!}) 5. Bb2 Bb7 6. cxd5 {This is by far the most common and natural move. It's a good rule of thumb for White to always consider cxd5 as soon as Black has played ... b6 . The reason is that after the most natural recapture exd5 , Black no longer has the possibility of putting up the 'Carlsbad' pawn chain with d5 - c6 - b7 .} exd5 {This might seem automatic, but it's worth mentioning that in these lines we should always give some thought on how to recapture on d5 . By the pawn is certainly the move in most cases, but there are some exceptions which will be shown later on.} 7. Bb5+ {This was played against me once by Swedish GM Slavko Cicak. White is provoking a small weakness.} c6 8. Be2 {We would slightly prefer to have our pawn on c7 instead of c6 here, but the more important factor is that the bishop is simply worse on e2 than g2 .} Bd6 9. O-O O-O 10. d3 {This is how Cicak played against me.} Re8 {Always useful, but also a very deliberate waiting move.} 11. Nbd2 (11. Nc3 {This would be much better in case we play ... c5 , but we don't have to!} Nbd7 {Now we play without ... c5 . Again, we can treat it as an improved version of 7. g3 .}) 11... c5 {This is still not at all necessary, but it makes a lot of sense once White has played Nbd2 , and what I did in my game with Cicak.} 12. d4 {This is almost universally the reaction to ... c5 by Black in these structures. But now the knight would be much more active on c3 than d2 .} Nc6 {We are doing well. If White at any points takes on c5 , we recapture with the pawn and the 'hanging pawns' in the center provides us with a lot of dynamic counterplay. If White doesn't take, it's hard to come up with another plan.} *

