ol over the e4 -square. Bd3 makes no sense with the pawn on d2 , and Be2 looks a bit passive. So fianchettoing the bishop is simply what remains. Additionally, the move e3 can often become useful in the future.} Bd6 {Just as with White's pawn already on d4 , this is always our setup. In general, we start with ... Bd6 and ... O-O and keep the knight flexible on b8 , as it sometimes wants to go to c6 instead.} 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O Re8 {It doesn't make any real difference here, but just out of principle I prefer to keep delaying ... Nbd7 for a little while.} 10. Nc3 {Again clearly the most natural move. The knight could also be developed to d2 , but c3 is simply a better square. Not only is it putting some pressure on d5 , it also has the possibility of jumping to e2 - f4 later on.} a6 {As a rule of thumb, we always meet Nc3 with ... a6 , just not to think about Nb5 -jumps.} 11. Rc1 {The last of the 'automatic' moves for White. Just as our rook belongs on the semi-open e-file, White's rook belongs on the c-file} Nbd7 {The last of our own obligatory moves. Now is a good time to talk about the middlegame in general. First of all, all pieces are still on the board and the central pawn structure still flexible, which means that a lot of things can happen. White is trying to play a slow maneuvering game, mainly reaction to all our actions. The biggest question is about White playing d4 and us playing ... c5 . In general, we welcome White playing d4 before we have committed our c-pawn. That gives us the possibility of ... Ne4 , but also closes the b2 -bishop and prevents the plan of d3 followed by e4 . If our pawn is already on c5 , then d4 makes a lot more sense for White, as they can still open up the position with dxc5 later on. ... c5 is still one of our main plans, but this means that it should be prepared very carefully before committing to it. Other plans for us includes grabbing more queenside space with ... b5 , but that also creates some targets for White to attack. S