1. c4 e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. b3 b6 5. Bb2 Bb7 6. cxd5 (6. g3 {If White plays g3 without trading on d5 , we have to be a bit more careful.} c5 $1 {After White has played g3 , we always recapture with a piece on d5 .} 7. Bg2 Be7 8. cxd5 Qxd5 $1 {A healthy structure for us. White would really want the e-pawn back on e2 .}) 6... exd5 7. g3 Bd6 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O Re8 10. Nc3 a6 11. Rc1 Nbd7 {Our basic setup, which we are highly likely to reach.} 12. Re1 (12. d4 {This always makes it easier for us.} Ne4 13. Ne2 a5 $1 {An important way to gain counterplay.}) 12... h6 {There is no rush in this structure. We are waiting for White to play d4 , in order to get ... Ne4 in with counterplay.} 13. d3 Rc8 {Long-term we want to push ... c5 and ... b5 . It's important to never allow the hanging pawn structure, as White is perfectly placed to combat that. Therefore if we play ... c5 , we always have to be ready to meet d4 with ... c4 , gaining further queenside space.} *

