1. c4 e6 2. g3 {Fianchettoing the bishop is the other main option for White.} d5 3. Bg2 {On higher levels it's considered a little more accurate to start with Bg2 instead of Nf3 as it keeps the long diagonal open a while longer, making it harder for us to develop the c8 -bishop.} dxc4 {I have chosen to always recommend capturing on c4 . One of the biggest advantages of that is that it goes well with all different Queen's Gambit versions. Don't worry that you might end up in a real Catalan - you won't! It will always be independent lines, where we have independent solutions.} ({•} 3... Nf6 {This is of course a perfectly reasonable move, but one big downside is that we have to keep being ready for d2 - d4 from White.} 4. d4 {While most setups against the Catalan still works, we for instance no longer have the possibility to follow the Magnus Queen's Gambit anymore, as we have Nf6 instead of a6 .} (4. Nf3 $5 {Also ask some questions, as White can still play d2 - d4 on the next move.})) ({•} 3... d4 {This is the other independent line. Theoretically it makes a lot of sense as it's equalizing while keeping the game independent. I just don't feel confident recommending it, as the arising Reversed Benoni structures are highly demanding from Black in a practical game.}) 4. Qa4+ {The main move in this move order.} (4. Nf3 {Transposes to c4 e6 g3 d5 Nf3 dxc4 Bg2 , this line .}) 4... Qd7 {A move exactly in my spirit. Highly unusual, rather provocative, but still logical and healthy!} (4... c6 5. Qxc4 c5 {Is my alternative suggestion. Play is very similar to the mainline, but there are a few minor differences.} 6. d3 Nf6 7. Qb5+ $5 {A check that 95% of your opponents won't even consider. The point is that we really want our knight on c6 , so White tries to force Nbd7 .} Nc6 {But we can play it anyway!} 8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. Qxc6+ Bd7 10. Qa6 Rb8 {With decent compensation for the pawn. Yes, White has a healthy structure and we won't win the pawn back, but on the other hand we have a potentially very strong bishop pair, a lead in development and an open b-file. I believe it's full compensation and wouldn't mind playing Black, but I can understand if it's not to everybody's taste.}) 5. Qxc4 c5 {The idea of ... Qd7 is that our knight gets a good square on c6 . Usually developing the c8 -bishop is the main issue for Black in the Reti (and indeed in the entire Catalan and Neo-Catalan) but here after ... Nc6 we will happily develop with ... b6 , ... Bb7 . By the way, this position has only been reached in less than 10 classical games, meaning it's a completely fresh area.} 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O Nf6 8. Nc3 Be7 9. Rd1 {These are some normal developing moves, although White can choose from many different setups. The important thing to keep in mind is to never allow d4 in a good way.} e5 {Preventing d4 . It's an ambitious way to play, but it looks highly interesting!} *

