1. c4 e6 2. g3 {Fianchettoing the bishop is arguably White's most critical way of playing. Very often, the game now transposes to a normal Catalan. Of course, that's outside the scope of our repertoire, but we never have to allow a real transposition.} d5 3. Bg2 dxc4 {I have chosen to always recommend the capture on c4 . This eliminates the risk of a real Catalan transposition, which is a big upside. The other way to avoid that is to play 3... d4 , but I feel that those positions are much trickier to handle for Black, and also leads to structures that we are a lot less familiar with.} 4. Na3 ({Another possibility for White. It's a lot less popular, mainly because it leads to much riskier positions for White than} 4. Qa4+ {.}) 4... Bxa3 {Whenever we have the possibility to capture the knight on a3 , we do it.} 5. bxa3 Nc6 {This is a nice extra option, and one of the reasons White usually plays 4. Qa4 + than 4. Na3 . The knight is well-placed on c6 as it lets us play ... e5 as quickly as possible.} 6. Bb2 e5 7. Qa4 {The best move. Now we have to choose which pawn to give up.} (7. Nf3 f6 {This is entirely bad for White. We play ... Be6 next and keep our extra pawn.}) 7... Nge7 {I like this, as it gives us the fastest development.} 8. Bxe5 O-O {Winning yet another tempo.} 9. Bc3 Be6 {Defending c4 . The material is equal, but the strategic features very different. White has more central pawns and the bishop pair, but we are ahead in development and will soon get very annoying knights on d5 and d4 . I think White has to be very careful to maintain the balance here.} *

