1. c4 e6 2. g3 {Fianchettoing the bishop is arguably White's most critical way of playing. Very often, the game now transposes to a normal Catalan. Of course, that's outside the scope of our repertoire, but we never have to allow a real transposition.} d5 3. Bg2 dxc4 {I have chosen to always recommend the capture on c4 . This eliminates the risk of a real Catalan transposition, which is a big upside. The other way to avoid that is to play 3... d4 , but I feel that those positions are much trickier to handle for Black, and also leads to structures that we are a lot less familiar with.} 4. Qa4+ Qd7 {Very controversial! From thousands of games, this has only been played in a handful. I was unaware of the move until my good friend and teammate, the highly creative GM Mateusz Bartel, played it in an important game in the European Club Cup, winning in excellent style.} 5. Qxc4 c5 {This is the idea. The queen looks strange on d7 , but it gives us the possibility of playing ... Nc6 without every worrying about White capturing the c6 -knight. Now we want to play ... Nc6 , ... Nf6 , ... Be7 and ... O-O , but after that we have two ways of developing, depending on what White does: either ... b6  Bb7 , or, in case White tries to push d4 , to play ... e5 ourselves, preventing that.} 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O Nf6 8. b3 {Such moves are always possible, but they rarely prove challenging.} b6 {Generally when White is not going for a quick d4 -break, we want to develop with ... b6 ... Bb7 instead. Additionally, White was perhaps intending Ba3 to put pressure on our c5 -pawn, so we are prophylactically defending it.} 9. Bb2 Bb7 10. d4 {A logical move. Else we would just finish development peacefully.} cxd4 11. Nxd4 Nxd4 12. Qxd4 Qxd4 13. Bxd4 Bxg2 14. Kxg2 O-O-O {A small touch to spice things up a bit. It's still rather equal, but with the kings on opposite sides we are creating a little bit of an imbalance. If we feel ambitious, a plan of ... Nd5 intending to push ... f6 , e5 makes sense. There is certainly still a lot of play left in the position.} *

