1. c4 e6 2. g3 {Fianchettoing the bishop is arguably White's most critical way of playing. Very often, the game now transposes to a normal Catalan. Of course, that's outside the scope of our repertoire, but we never have to allow a real transposition.} d5 3. Bg2 dxc4 {I have chosen to always recommend the capture on c4 . This eliminates the risk of a real Catalan transposition, which is a big upside. The other way to avoid that is to play 3... d4 , but I feel that those positions are much trickier to handle for Black, and also leads to structures that we are a lot less familiar with.} 4. Qa4+ Qd7 {Very controversial! From thousands of games, this has only been played in a handful. I was unaware of the move until my good friend and teammate, the highly creative GM Mateusz Bartel, played it in an important game in the European Club Cup, winning in excellent style.} 5. Qxc4 c5 {This is the idea. The queen looks strange on d7 , but it gives us the possibility of playing ... Nc6 without every worrying about White capturing the c6 -knight. Now we want to play ... Nc6 , ... Nf6 , ... Be7 and ... O-O , but after that we have two ways of developing, depending on what White does: either ... b6  Bb7 , or, in case White tries to push d4 , to play ... e5 ourselves, preventing that.} 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O Nf6 8. d4 {This is the most direct move. White will win the pawn back.} cxd4 9. Rd1 e5 {We never want to allow White Nxd4 calmly, as it would lead to a dream Catalan position. Therefore, we almost always plays ... e5 whenever White starts action in the center.} 10. e3 Qg4 {This is another highly interesting point of ... Qd7 . I haven't really seen this idea in other lines, but the queen is pretty strong on g4 / h5 .} 11. exd4 Nxd4 12. Qd3 Bc5 {While White wins back the e5 -pawn, we are getting castled and the game looks balanced.} *

