1. c4 e6 2. g3 {Fianchettoing the bishop is arguably White's most critical way of playing. Very often, the game now transposes to a normal Catalan. Of course, that's outside the scope of our repertoire, but we never have to allow a real transposition.} d5 3. Bg2 dxc4 {I have chosen to always recommend the capture on c4 . This eliminates the risk of a real Catalan transposition, which is a big upside. The other way to avoid that is to play 3... d4 , but I feel that those positions are much trickier to handle for Black, and also leads to structures that we are a lot less familiar with.} 4. Qa4+ Qd7 {Very controversial! From thousands of games, this has only been played in a handful. I was unaware of the move until my good friend and teammate, the highly creative GM Mateusz Bartel, played it in an important game in the European Club Cup, winning in excellent style.} 5. Qxc4 c5 {This is the idea. The queen looks strange on d7 , but it gives us the possibility of playing ... Nc6 without every worrying about White capturing the c6 -knight. Now we want to play ... Nc6 , ... Nf6 , ... Be7 and ... O-O , but after that we have two ways of developing, depending on what White does: either ... b6  Bb7 , or, in case White tries to push d4 , to play ... e5 ourselves, preventing that.} 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O Nf6 8. Nc3 {The most flexible and natural developing move. The knight simply belongs on c3 .} Be7 9. d4 {Once again, this break is one of the most important to keep in mind.} cxd4 10. Rd1 e5 {We always defend the d4 -pawn with ... e5 in these situations. The inclusion of ... e5 and e3 is in our favor, as it opens up the c8 - h3 diagonal and closes down the c1 - h6 one.} 11. e3 d3 {This, combined with the previous move, is one of the key ideas we really need to know. By playing ... d3 we don't let White open up for the g2 -bishop.} 12. Ng5 {This was how Bartel's opponent replied in the key game from the European Club Cup mentioned above.} O-O 13. Rxd3 Qe8 {Bartel's choice. f5 and g4 were both good alternative squares for the queen, but this is the most combative. Next we develop our bishop and it's a fully fledged fight.} *

