1. c4 e6 2. g3 {Fianchettoing the bishop is arguably White's most critical way of playing. Very often, the game now transposes to a normal Catalan. Of course, that's outside the scope of our repertoire, but we never have to allow a real transposition.} d5 3. Bg2 dxc4 {I have chosen to always recommend the capture on c4 . This eliminates the risk of a real Catalan transposition, which is a big upside. The other way to avoid that is to play 3... d4 , but I feel that those positions are much trickier to handle for Black, and also leads to structures that we are a lot less familiar with.} 4. Qa4+ Qd7 {Very controversial! From thousands of games, this has only been played in a handful. I was unaware of the move until my good friend and teammate, the highly creative GM Mateusz Bartel, played it in an important game in the European Club Cup, winning in excellent style.} 5. Qxc4 c5 {This is the idea. The queen looks strange on d7 , but it gives us the possibility of playing ... Nc6 without every worrying about White capturing the c6 -knight. Now we want to play ... Nc6 , ... Nf6 , ... Be7 and ... O-O , but after that we have two ways of developing, depending on what White does: either ... b6  Bb7 , or, in case White tries to push d4 , to play ... e5 ourselves, preventing that.} 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O Nf6 8. Nc3 {The most flexible and natural developing move. The knight simply belongs on c3 .} Be7 9. d4 {Once again, this break is one of the most important to keep in mind.} cxd4 10. Rd1 e5 {We always defend the d4 -pawn with ... e5 in these situations. The inclusion of ... e5 and e3 is in our favor, as it opens up the c8 - h3 diagonal and closes down the c1 - h6 one.} 11. e3 d3 {This, combined with the previous move, is one of the key ideas we really need to know. By playing ... d3 we don't let White open up for the g2 -bishop.} 12. e4 {The most interesting move.} O-O 13. Rxd3 Qe8 {Important! ... Qe6 doesn't work due to Nd5 , and by method of elimination we have to go to e8 . It looks a bit odd, but the important thing is being able to play ... Be6 next.} 14. Nd5 Be6 15. Bg5 {The most logical move, trying to put some pressure.} h6 {I like this slightly provocative move, although ... Rc8 is a good alternative. The differences are subtle and not really relevant, but the important thing to take away is that we are not at all worried about a doubled f-pawn.} 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Nxf6+ {Probably one of the most natural moves, but I will go so far as to call it a small strategic mistake! Other moves would lead to a balanced game.} gxf6 {The point is that the minor pieces are greatly in our favor. The knight is ready to jump to d4 as soon as the f3 -knight leaves, and our bishop on e6 controls the key f5 -square. Meanwhile, the bishop is doing absolutely nothing on g2 .} *

