1. c4 e6 2. g3 {Fianchettoing the bishop is arguably White's most critical way of playing. Very often, the game now transposes to a normal Catalan. Of course, that's outside the scope of our repertoire, but we never have to allow a real transposition.} d5 3. Bg2 dxc4 {I have chosen to always recommend the capture on c4 . This eliminates the risk of a real Catalan transposition, which is a big upside. The other way to avoid that is to play 3... d4 , but I feel that those positions are much trickier to handle for Black, and also leads to structures that we are a lot less familiar with.} 4. Qa4+ Qd7 {Very controversial! From thousands of games, this has only been played in a handful. I was unaware of the move until my good friend and teammate, the highly creative GM Mateusz Bartel, played it in an important game in the European Club Cup, winning in excellent style.} 5. Qxc4 c5 {This is the idea. The queen looks strange on d7 , but it gives us the possibility of playing ... Nc6 without every worrying about White capturing the c6 -knight. Now we want to play ... Nc6 , ... Nf6 , ... Be7 and ... O-O , but after that we have two ways of developing, depending on what White does: either ... b6  Bb7 , or, in case White tries to push d4 , to play ... e5 ourselves, preventing that.} 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O Nf6 8. Nc3 {The most flexible and natural developing move. The knight simply belongs on c3 .} Be7 9. e3 {Another way to prepare d4 .} b6 {There are many ways to play, but this one looks interesting to me. The point will be explained on the next move.} 10. d4 Bb7 {The idea. As usual with the pawn on e3 , we don't really want to take on d4 as it opens up for the c1 -bishop. Therefore, we keep the central tension, and for this reason we need the c5 -pawn protected.} 11. dxc5 bxc5 ({Another interesting point. Usually we refrain from such an isolated pawn, but here our pieces are well-placed for getting counterplay. Moves like ... Nb4 followed by ... Ba6 are in the air. And if Rd1 then} 11... Qc8 {.}) *

