1. c4 e6 2. g3 {Fianchettoing the bishop is arguably White's most critical way of playing. Very often, the game now transposes to a normal Catalan. Of course, that's outside the scope of our repertoire, but we never have to allow a real transposition.} d5 3. Bg2 dxc4 {I have chosen to always recommend the capture on c4 . This eliminates the risk of a real Catalan transposition, which is a big upside. The other way to avoid that is to play 3... d4 , but I feel that those positions are much trickier to handle for Black, and also leads to structures that we are a lot less familiar with.} 4. Qa4+ Qd7 {Very controversial! From thousands of games, this has only been played in a handful. I was unaware of the move until my good friend and teammate, the highly creative GM Mateusz Bartel, played it in an important game in the European Club Cup, winning in excellent style.} 5. Qxc4 c5 {This is the idea. The queen looks strange on d7 , but it gives us the possibility of playing ... Nc6 without every worrying about White capturing the c6 -knight. Now we want to play ... Nc6 , ... Nf6 , ... Be7 and ... O-O , but after that we have two ways of developing, depending on what White does: either ... b6  Bb7 , or, in case White tries to push d4 , to play ... e5 ourselves, preventing that.} 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O Nf6 8. Nc3 {The most flexible and natural developing move. The knight simply belongs on c3 .} Be7 9. Rd1 {In my view the most critical move because it's also the most flexible. White obviously wants to push d4 , but keeps the option of d2 - d3 if circumstances change.} e5 {Absolutely essential! We really can't let White push d4 without first forcing e3 .} 10. d3 {This is an interesting strategical idea. White is arguing that ... e5 has weakened our light squares, and therefore prepares either Bg5xf6 or even Ng5 - e4xf6 , in both cases fighting for control over d5 .} Qc7 {A good move, trying to get ... Be6 as quickly as possible.} 11. Bg5 Be6 {Just in time to control d5 .} 12. Qa4 O-O 13. Rac1 Rac8 {We need to be able to defend the c5 -pawn with ... b6 later on, therefore we overprotect the c6 -knight and step out of the long diagonal.} 14. Bxf6 {The most direct. Else we simply continue to build up.} Bxf6 15. Ne4 b6 {Again we are forced to allow the doubled f-pawns, and again we don't mind!} 16. Nxf6+ gxf6 {This is a better version for White than previously as the pawn is still on e2 so White doesn't struggle with the d4 -square. Even so, we are alright, as there is no real way for White to utilize our kingside weaknesses. White simply lacks enough pieces to provide any kind of pressure.} *

