1. c4 e6 2. g3 {Fianchettoing the bishop is arguably White's most critical way of playing. Very often, the game now transposes to a normal Catalan. Of course, that's outside the scope of our repertoire, but we never have to allow a real transposition.} d5 3. Bg2 dxc4 {I have chosen to always recommend the capture on c4 . This eliminates the risk of a real Catalan transposition, which is a big upside. The other way to avoid that is to play 3... d4 , but I feel that those positions are much trickier to handle for Black, and also leads to structures that we are a lot less familiar with.} 4. Qa4+ Qd7 {Very controversial! From thousands of games, this has only been played in a handful. I was unaware of the move until my good friend and teammate, the highly creative GM Mateusz Bartel, played it in an important game in the European Club Cup, winning in excellent style.} 5. Qxc4 c5 {This is the idea. The queen looks strange on d7 , but it gives us the possibility of playing ... Nc6 without every worrying about White capturing the c6 -knight. Now we want to play ... Nc6 , ... Nf6 , ... Be7 and ... O-O , but after that we have two ways of developing, depending on what White does: either ... b6  Bb7 , or, in case White tries to push d4 , to play ... e5 ourselves, preventing that.} 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O Nf6 8. Nc3 {The most flexible and natural developing move. The knight simply belongs on c3 .} Be7 9. Rd1 {In my view the most critical move because it's also the most flexible. White obviously wants to push d4 , but keeps the option of d2 - d3 if circumstances change.} e5 {Absolutely essential! We really can't let White push d4 without first forcing e3 .} 10. d3 {This is an interesting strategical idea. White is arguing that ... e5 has weakened our light squares, and therefore prepares either Bg5xf6 or even Ng5 - e4xf6 , in both cases fighting for control over d5 .} Qc7 {A good move, trying to get ... Be6 as quickly as possible.} 11. Ng5 {A typical idea for such positions. White is trading off their worse knight and keeps the good one. It's all about the d5 -square!} O-O 12. Nge4 b6 13. Nxf6+ {The most natural, but not subtle enough to create problems.} Bxf6 14. Nd5 Qd8 {It might look strange to retreat here instead of to d6 , but there is a concrete reason.} 15. Nxf6+ Qxf6 {It's important to understand that this is a good scenario for us. White has the bishop pair, but we got rid of our passive bishop. If we manage to trade the light square bishops as well, something that isn't unlikely, we will simply be better due to our space advantage. White has enough resources to keep the balance, but it's the sort of position where Black can quickly take over if White is not careful enough.} *

