1. c4 e6 2. g3 {Fianchettoing the bishop is arguably White's most critical way of playing. Very often, the game now transposes to a normal Catalan. Of course, that's outside the scope of our repertoire, but we never have to allow a real transposition.} d5 3. Bg2 dxc4 {I have chosen to always recommend the capture on c4 . This eliminates the risk of a real Catalan transposition, which is a big upside. The other way to avoid that is to play 3... d4 , but I feel that those positions are much trickier to handle for Black, and also leads to structures that we are a lot less familiar with.} 4. Qa4+ Qd7 {Very controversial! From thousands of games, this has only been played in a handful. I was unaware of the move until my good friend and teammate, the highly creative GM Mateusz Bartel, played it in an important game in the European Club Cup, winning in excellent style.} 5. Qxc4 c5 {This is the idea. The queen looks strange on d7 , but it gives us the possibility of playing ... Nc6 without every worrying about White capturing the c6 -knight. Now we want to play ... Nc6 , ... Nf6 , ... Be7 and ... O-O , but after that we have two ways of developing, depending on what White does: either ... b6  Bb7 , or, in case White tries to push d4 , to play ... e5 ourselves, preventing that.} 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O Nf6 8. Nc3 {The most flexible and natural developing move. The knight simply belongs on c3 .} Be7 9. Rd1 {In my view the most critical move because it's also the most flexible. White obviously wants to push d4 , but keeps the option of d2 - d3 if circumstances change.} e5 {Absolutely essential! We really can't let White push d4 without first forcing e3 .} 10. d3 {This is an interesting strategical idea. White is arguing that ... e5 has weakened our light squares, and therefore prepares either Bg5xf6 or even Ng5 - e4xf6 , in both cases fighting for control over d5 .} Qc7 {A good move, trying to get ... Be6 as quickly as possible.} 11. Ng5 {A typical idea for such positions. White is trading off their worse knight and keeps the good one. It's all about the d5 -square!} O-O 12. Nge4 b6 13. Bg5 {Trying to maximize the pressure.} Be6 14. Qa4 {This is slightly annoying. Why would White be threatening to take twice on f6 here when we weren't afraid of it before? The reason is that White traded the f3 -knight instead of the c3 -knight! This actually makes a big difference. For one, from c3 it takes 1 move to reach d5 , whereas from f3 it takes 4 moves.} Nxe4 {Therefore, we don't allow the trade on f6 .} 15. Bxe4 {Gives us some extra options if we don't want to transpose.} Nd4 {This is the most interesting of the extra options. It turns out we have fantastic compensation for the exchange.} 16. Bxe7 Qxe7 17. Bxa8 Rxa8 {This is the sort of positions I love playing. We are a full exchange down, but the compensation is excellent. I've talked a lot about the knight being better on c3 than f3 , but here White suddenly wishes the knight was closer to the defense of the king!   There are many reasons for our compensation, but there are two main ones: one is that our knight is very hard to get rid of on d4 . White would dream of playing e3 , but that will never work due to the weak f3 -square.   The other reason is that White has no way to open any files for their rooks, so they will remain passive for a long time. We are in no real rush, but can continue to improve step by step. Pushing the h-pawn is natural, but pushing the f-pawn also makes sense.} *

