1. c4 e6 2. g3 {Fianchettoing the bishop is arguably White's most critical way of playing. Very often, the game now transposes to a normal Catalan. Of course, that's outside the scope of our repertoire, but we never have to allow a real transposition.} d5 3. Bg2 dxc4 {I have chosen to always recommend the capture on c4 . This eliminates the risk of a real Catalan transposition, which is a big upside. The other way to avoid that is to play 3... d4 , but I feel that those positions are much trickier to handle for Black, and also leads to structures that we are a lot less familiar with.} 4. Qa4+ Qd7 {Very controversial! From thousands of games, this has only been played in a handful. I was unaware of the move until my good friend and teammate, the highly creative GM Mateusz Bartel, played it in an important game in the European Club Cup, winning in excellent style.} 5. Qxc4 c5 {This is the idea. The queen looks strange on d7 , but it gives us the possibility of playing ... Nc6 without every worrying about White capturing the c6 -knight. Now we want to play ... Nc6 , ... Nf6 , ... Be7 and ... O-O , but after that we have two ways of developing, depending on what White does: either ... b6  Bb7 , or, in case White tries to push d4 , to play ... e5 ourselves, preventing that.} 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O Nf6 8. Nc3 {The most flexible and natural developing move. The knight simply belongs on c3 .} Be7 9. Rd1 {In my view the most critical move because it's also the most flexible. White obviously wants to push d4 , but keeps the option of d2 - d3 if circumstances change.} e5 {Absolutely essential! We really can't let White push d4 without first forcing e3 .} 10. e3 Qe6 {Another essential move. Again, we are happy with a queen trade on our terms, and if White wants to avoid it they have to make some concession.} 11. Qxe6 Bxe6 12. d4 O-O-O {The most aggressive move. Trading on d4 is solid, but this looks more fun.} 13. Nxe5 Nxe5 {The next couple of moves are all forced from both sides.} 14. dxe5 Rxd1+ 15. Nxd1 Rd8 16. Nc3 Nd5 17. Nxd5 (17. Bd2 Nb4 {Gives plenty of play.}) 17... Bxd5 18. b3 Be6 {An idea seen in different Catalan lines. We are a clear pawn down, but our majority is much more potent than White's. White would like to push f4 - f5 , but it takes ages whereas our own play with ... b5 , .... a5 , ... c4 etc. comes much faster. Importantly, we also control the only open file, but it's really mainly about the queenside pawns.} *

