1. c4 e6 2. g3 {Fianchettoing the bishop is arguably White's most critical way of playing. Very often, the game now transposes to a normal Catalan. Of course, that's outside the scope of our repertoire, but we never have to allow a real transposition.} d5 3. Bg2 dxc4 {I have chosen to always recommend the capture on c4 . This eliminates the risk of a real Catalan transposition, which is a big upside. The other way to avoid that is to play 3... d4 , but I feel that those positions are much trickier to handle for Black, and also leads to structures that we are a lot less familiar with.} 4. Qa4+ Qd7 {Very controversial! From thousands of games, this has only been played in a handful. I was unaware of the move until my good friend and teammate, the highly creative GM Mateusz Bartel, played it in an important game in the European Club Cup, winning in excellent style.} 5. Qxc4 c5 {This is the idea. The queen looks strange on d7 , but it gives us the possibility of playing ... Nc6 without every worrying about White capturing the c6 -knight. Now we want to play ... Nc6 , ... Nf6 , ... Be7 and ... O-O , but after that we have two ways of developing, depending on what White does: either ... b6  Bb7 , or, in case White tries to push d4 , to play ... e5 ourselves, preventing that.} 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O Nf6 8. Nc3 {The most flexible and natural developing move. The knight simply belongs on c3 .} Be7 9. Rd1 {In my view the most critical move because it's also the most flexible. White obviously wants to push d4 , but keeps the option of d2 - d3 if circumstances change.} e5 {Absolutely essential! We really can't let White push d4 without first forcing e3 .} 10. e3 Qe6 {Another essential move. Again, we are happy with a queen trade on our terms, and if White wants to avoid it they have to make some concession.} 11. Qf1 {Keeping the queens on the board should be the most critical.} O-O 12. d4 {Other moves don't really make sense.} cxd4 13. exd4 Nxd4 (13... exd4 14. Nb5 $1 {should be avoided.}) 14. Nxd4 exd4 15. Rxd4 {We should still exercise some care to develop the remaining pieces.} Bc5 16. Rd1 Bd7 {Such small sacrifices are very common in the Catalan. White usually loses too much time taking the b7 -pawn.} 17. Bg5 Ng4 {The more aggressive choice.} 18. Ne4 Bb6 {If we get one more move we would already be fighting for the initiative.} 19. Rd6 Qf5 20. h3 {These moves are all necessary from White, but I am not sure how easy it is to go for during a game.} Ne5 21. g4 Nf3+ 22. Bxf3 Qxf3 23. Re1 {The point. Suddenly our queen is trapped. I don't think this is an easy idea to spot a few moves before.} Bc6 24. Rd3 Qxe4 25. Rxe4 Bxe4 {Interestingly, we still have full compensation for the queen. The queen is usually at its strongest on a semi-closed board with lots of weaknesses to attack. Here we have no weaknesses at all, and our bishop has a stronghold on c6 from where it will never be kicked away.} ({Rc3 Bc6} 25... Be3 26. Bxe3 {Rxe3} Rad8 {Next we double on the d-file. The most White can hope for is a trade of rooks, but that's an easy draw.}) *

