1. c4 e6 2. g3 {Fianchettoing the bishop is arguably White's most critical way of playing. Very often, the game now transposes to a normal Catalan. Of course, that's outside the scope of our repertoire, but we never have to allow a real transposition.} d5 3. Bg2 dxc4 {I have chosen to always recommend the capture on c4 . This eliminates the risk of a real Catalan transposition, which is a big upside. The other way to avoid that is to play 3... d4 , but I feel that those positions are much trickier to handle for Black, and also leads to structures that we are a lot less familiar with.} 4. Qa4+ c6 5. Qxc4 c5 {This is an alternative way of playing the same idea. The only difference compared to our mainline is that the queen is on d8 instead of d7 . This makes some differences.   Sometimes the queen on d7 was a little in the way, specifically after ... e5 we needed to move it before playing ... Be6 . Secondly, the queen sometimes got into trouble on the d-file, whereas now we can just block the d-file with ... Bd7 , should it be necessary. The downside is that the queen on d7 was defending the knight on c6 , making it easier to develop the queenside.} 6. Nf3 Nc6 {Again we should definitely not allow d4 for free.} 7. O-O Nf6 8. Rd1 Be7 9. d4 cxd4 10. e3 (10. Nxd4 {with the queen on d7 this was highly dubious, whereas now it's just dead lost.} e5 $1 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. Qxc6+ Bd7 {The difference. We win a piece.}) 10... O-O 11. exd4 Bd7 {This is an important difference compared to the queen being on d7 . Placing the bishop on d7 is often a bit dodgy in the Catalan, but here it will quickly appear on c6 , providing an excellent blockade on d5 .} 12. Nc3 Na5 {Slightly odd square, but here it's about getting the bishop to c6 as soon as possible.} 13. Qe2 Bc6 {With such a blockade we can never have any problems.} *

