1. c4 e6 2. g3 {Fianchettoing the bishop is arguably White's most critical way of playing. Very often, the game now transposes to a normal Catalan. Of course, that's outside the scope of our repertoire, but we never have to allow a real transposition.} d5 3. Bg2 dxc4 {I have chosen to always recommend the capture on c4 . This eliminates the risk of a real Catalan transposition, which is a big upside. The other way to avoid that is to play 3... d4 , but I feel that those positions are much trickier to handle for Black, and also leads to structures that we are a lot less familiar with.} 4. Qa4+ c6 5. Qxc4 c5 {This is an alternative way of playing the same idea. The only difference compared to our mainline is that the queen is on d8 instead of d7 . This makes some differences.   Sometimes the queen on d7 was a little in the way, specifically after ... e5 we needed to move it before playing ... Be6 . Secondly, the queen sometimes got into trouble on the d-file, whereas now we can just block the d-file with ... Bd7 , should it be necessary. The downside is that the queen on d7 was defending the knight on c6 , making it easier to develop the queenside.} 6. b3 {This was the choice of the former World Champion. When playing such a rare line as 5... c5 , I believe this sort of slightly slower continuations are very likely to appear in practical play.} Nf6 7. Bb2 Be7 {With the queen on d7 we could play ... Nc6 with a quick ... b6  Bb7 idea, but with the queen on d8 we have to play more modestly.} 8. Nf3 Nc6 9. O-O O-O 10. Rd1 {This is the other natural move for White, going for the d4 -break.} Bd7 {This is one of the advantages of having the queen on d8 instead of d7 . Now we get fairly comfortable development with ... Rc8 next.} 11. d4 cxd4 12. Nxd4 Nb4 {There are other ways of playing, for instance just trading on d4 , but I like this more aggressive move.} 13. e4 {Strategically justified, but importantly also providing a square for the queen.} Rc8 14. Qe2 e5 {Continuing with the concrete play. If White were given time to complete development, they would have some edge.} 15. a3 {Else we would be able to enter on c2 .} exd4 16. axb4 Bxb4 17. Bxd4 Re8 {The structure has changed. Normally more pawns in the center is advantageous, but here it's compensated for by our incredible piece activity.} *

