1. c4 e6 2. g3 {Fianchettoing the bishop is arguably White's most critical way of playing. Very often, the game now transposes to a normal Catalan. Of course, that's outside the scope of our repertoire, but we never have to allow a real transposition.} d5 3. Bg2 dxc4 {I have chosen to always recommend the capture on c4 . This eliminates the risk of a real Catalan transposition, which is a big upside. The other way to avoid that is to play 3... d4 , but I feel that those positions are much trickier to handle for Black, and also leads to structures that we are a lot less familiar with.} 4. Qa4+ c6 5. Qxc4 c5 {This is an alternative way of playing the same idea. The only difference compared to our mainline is that the queen is on d8 instead of d7 . This makes some differences.   Sometimes the queen on d7 was a little in the way, specifically after ... e5 we needed to move it before playing ... Be6 . Secondly, the queen sometimes got into trouble on the d-file, whereas now we can just block the d-file with ... Bd7 , should it be necessary. The downside is that the queen on d7 was defending the knight on c6 , making it easier to develop the queenside.} 6. b3 {This was the choice of the former World Champion. When playing such a rare line as 5... c5 , I believe this sort of slightly slower continuations are very likely to appear in practical play.} Nf6 7. Bb2 Be7 {With the queen on d7 we could play ... Nc6 with a quick ... b6  Bb7 idea, but with the queen on d8 we have to play more modestly.} 8. Nf3 Nc6 9. O-O O-O 10. Ne5 {Magnus' choice, and a logical one. White is trying to open up for their bishops.} Nxe5 11. Bxe5 Nd7 {Looks passive, but our bishop is anyway going to be developed to b7 .} 12. Bb2 Rb8 {Intending ... b6  Bb7 . Now, White can play many different moves, but let's follow the game continuation for a while to get a better understanding of what is going on.} 13. Nc3 Bf6 {A good moment for this, as the knight is pinned.} 14. Rab1 b6 {Now we are ready to finish development. Given one more move we would be completely equal.} 15. b4 {Strategically the most challenging. White is trading a flank pawn for a central one.} cxb4 (15... Bb7 {Tari's move which was also fine. White eventually won the game, but it had more to do with White being the World's strongest player rather than the objective evaluation... 1-0 (40) Carlsen, M (2847)-Tari, A (2639) Krasnaya Polyana 2021.}) 16. Qxb4 b5 {This is the idea. I quite like it, as we are arguing that yes, White has gotten more central pawns, but we have a majority of our own! The plan is also really simple: just push ... a5 , ... b4 etc which will create a lot of counterplay. Later on, the idea of ... Bb7 is still available, but it's less urgent now as we anyway have evacuated the long diagonal.} *

