1. c4 e6 2. g3 {Fianchettoing the bishop is arguably White's most critical way of playing. Very often, the game now transposes to a normal Catalan. Of course, that's outside the scope of our repertoire, but we never have to allow a real transposition.} d5 3. Bg2 dxc4 {I have chosen to always recommend the capture on c4 . This eliminates the risk of a real Catalan transposition, which is a big upside. The other way to avoid that is to play 3... d4 , but I feel that those positions are much trickier to handle for Black, and also leads to structures that we are a lot less familiar with.} 4. Qa4+ c6 5. Qxc4 c5 {This is an alternative way of playing the same idea. The only difference compared to our mainline is that the queen is on d8 instead of d7 . This makes some differences.   Sometimes the queen on d7 was a little in the way, specifically after ... e5 we needed to move it before playing ... Be6 . Secondly, the queen sometimes got into trouble on the d-file, whereas now we can just block the d-file with ... Bd7 , should it be necessary. The downside is that the queen on d7 was defending the knight on c6 , making it easier to develop the queenside.} 6. Qb5+ Nc6 {This is similar to 6. d3 , but we should adjust a little as otherwise White might save on d3 .} 7. Bxc6+ bxc6 8. Qxc6+ (8. Qa4 {Just like after 6. d3 , not taking on c6 is also an option for White.} Nf6 {We can still play in the same way as against 6. d3 . Most probably, White will play d3 at some point in the future and transpose back.}) 8... Bd7 9. Qa6 Ne7 {This is an interesting setup. We make use of not having played ... Nf6 yet, intending to put a pawn there instead. Placing the central pawns on f6 and e5 makes a lot of sense, as they will work well together with our light squared bishop.} 10. Nf3 Rb8 {A nice touch. We try to get White to commit to Nc3 , which makes their position a tad less flexible.} 11. Nc3 Nc6 {We have full compensation with the bishop pair. Long-term, pushing ... e5 and jumping ... Nd4 will give good counterplay.} *

