1. c4 e6 2. g3 {Fianchettoing the bishop is arguably White's most critical way of playing. Very often, the game now transposes to a normal Catalan. Of course, that's outside the scope of our repertoire, but we never have to allow a real transposition.} d5 3. Bg2 dxc4 {I have chosen to always recommend the capture on c4 . This eliminates the risk of a real Catalan transposition, which is a big upside. The other way to avoid that is to play 3... d4 , but I feel that those positions are much trickier to handle for Black, and also leads to structures that we are a lot less familiar with.} 4. Qa4+ c6 5. Qxc4 c5 {This is an alternative way of playing the same idea. The only difference compared to our mainline is that the queen is on d8 instead of d7 . This makes some differences.   Sometimes the queen on d7 was a little in the way, specifically after ... e5 we needed to move it before playing ... Be6 . Secondly, the queen sometimes got into trouble on the d-file, whereas now we can just block the d-file with ... Bd7 , should it be necessary. The downside is that the queen on d7 was defending the knight on c6 , making it easier to develop the queenside.} 6. d3 {It sounds very strange, but I think this is the main downside of having the queen on d8 instead of d7 .} Nf6 7. Qb5+ {This is the idea! Let me say immediately that I think this is close to impossible for White to come up with over the board. The idea of the move is to force our knight to d7 instead of the much more active c6 -square.} Nbd7 {The most obvious move, and the engine recommendation, but I believe the positions arising are rather pleasant for White to play.} 8. Nf3 Bd6 9. a4 {This is the idea for White. We will be able to play ... b6 - Bb7 , but in the meantime White gets some pressure.} O-O 10. a5 Rb8 11. Nbd2 {Or castling first. It's all very similar.} Nd5 12. Nc4 Be7 13. O-O b6 14. axb6 axb6 15. Bd2 Bb7 16. Ra7 {I think we can stop here. With the aid of an engine and some more precise moves we are going to equalize this, but to me it just looks too easy for White to play. If there was only one specific way for White to play we could perhaps solve it move by move, but here there are many options from move 11-16 that all leads to the same style of play. It's certainly no disaster, but I simply think our mainline is making life more difficult for White.} *

