1. c4 e6 2. g3 {Fianchettoing the bishop is arguably White's most critical way of playing. Very often, the game now transposes to a normal Catalan. Of course, that's outside the scope of our repertoire, but we never have to allow a real transposition.} d5 3. Bg2 dxc4 {I have chosen to always recommend the capture on c4 . This eliminates the risk of a real Catalan transposition, which is a big upside. The other way to avoid that is to play 3... d4 , but I feel that those positions are much trickier to handle for Black, and also leads to structures that we are a lot less familiar with.} 4. Qa4+ c6 5. Qxc4 c5 {This is an alternative way of playing the same idea. The only difference compared to our mainline is that the queen is on d8 instead of d7 . This makes some differences.   Sometimes the queen on d7 was a little in the way, specifically after ... e5 we needed to move it before playing ... Be6 . Secondly, the queen sometimes got into trouble on the d-file, whereas now we can just block the d-file with ... Bd7 , should it be necessary. The downside is that the queen on d7 was defending the knight on c6 , making it easier to develop the queenside.} 6. d3 {It sounds very strange, but I think this is the main downside of having the queen on d8 instead of d7 .} Nf6 7. Qb5+ {This is the idea! Let me say immediately that I think this is close to impossible for White to come up with over the board. The idea of the move is to force our knight to d7 instead of the much more active c6 -square.} Nc6 {But we do not oblige! This comes down to a pawn sacrifice, but I believe we have very decent compensation.} 8. Bxc6+ {The only move, else White's play makes no sense whatsoever.} bxc6 9. Qc4 {White can also just retreat, arguing that the c6 -pawn is more of a hindrance than asset for us. Still, with the bishop pair, lead in development and potentially weak White king I don't think we should complain.} Nd5 {Finish development and then long-term most likely push ... f6 and ... e5 , opening up for the c8 -bishop.} *

