[PlyCount "20"]

1. c4 e6 2. g3 {Fianchettoing the bishop is the other main option for White.} d5 3. Nf3 dxc4 4. Qa4+ (4. Bg2 {This is annoying for us, as we won't get our lovely Qd7 -system. But against all other setups, it's a less flexible version for White.} Nd7 {A smart move order! In general, developing the queenside is more important than the kingside in these lines. That is also the reason White usually gives the check on a4 already on move 4. Now we will be in time to play a6 , b5 and Bb7 if White goes after the c4 -pawn.} (4... c6 $5 {This transposes to c4 c6 Nf3 d5 g3 dxc4 Bg2 e6 , deeply analyzed in chapter 6, starting here . Although that was one of the chapters from the Slav part, I believe it's perfectly viable also for QGD-players, as the play is not too characteristic of either Slav or QGD. It's just an independent, interesting line.}) 5. O-O (5. Qc2 Nb6 $1 {This is the reason we start with 4... Nd7 . White will struggle to win the c4 -pawn back.}) 5... Ngf6 6. Qa4 (6. Na3 Bxa3 7. bxa3 O-O {This is even a slightly better version than 4... c6 , as the c-pawn can go to c5 in one go.}) 6... a6 7. Qxc4 b5 8. Qc2 Bb7 {Transposes to the mainline, starting here .}) 4... Nd7 (4... Qd7 {This move is a fully playable alternative, but transposes directly to the Solid Option vs the Fianchetto of The Magnus Queen's Gambit course. If you play another QGD, I think it's easier to play 4... Nd7 .} 5. Qxc4 c5 6. d4 $1 {The difference between 3. Nf3 and 3. Bg2 - we didn't have time to prevent d2 - d4 .} cxd4 7. Nxd4 a6 8. Bg2 b5 9. Qd3 Bb7 10. O-O Nf6 {Transposes to d4 d5 c4 e6} 11. Nf3 {a6 g3 dxc4 Bg2 c5 O-O cxd4 Nxd4 Nf6 Qa4+ Qd7 Qxc4 b5 Qb3 Bb7 , analyzed here .}) 5. Bg2 a6 {The key idea for us in these lines - whenever possible, we really want to get ... b5 and ... Bb7 . Developing the light squared bishop usually means we have solved our opening problems.} 6. Qxc4 b5 7. Qc2 ({By far the most common move, though the funky} 7. Qh4 $5 {also exists.}) 7... Bb7 8. O-O Ngf6 9. Nc3 c5 10. a4 {The only critical idea in these positions. The thing to remember now is to never play ... b4 , as it gives up the c4 -square.} Bc6 {I like this. Opening the b-file means we can also protect the b5 -pawn with the rook, should it be necessary.} (10... Qb6 {This is the theoretical main line, but I consider it a little more difficult to handle as Black.}) *

