1. c4 e6 2. g3 d5 3. Nf3 dxc4 4. Bg2 Nd7 {This is the most flexible move. We make sure that we can still meet Qa4 with ... a6 , to develop the c8 -bishop as soon as possible.} (4... c6 $5 {This is of course a possibility, transposing to the 1. c4  c6 2. Nf3  d5 3. g3  chapter . It's true that this is in the Slav part of the repertoire, but that specific line is not one of the more specifically Slav-esque ones.}) 5. Qc2 Nb6 {Defending the pawn. This is the reason White usually plays Qa4 instead of Qc2 .} (5... a6 6. a4 $1 {This is something we need to avoid. Now it will get difficult to get ... b6 or ... b5 in a good way.}) 6. a4 {This is the extra option White gets against our knight on b6 .} (6. O-O Nf6 {transposes to O-O Ngf6 Qc2 Nb6 , here .}) 6... a5 {This is always essential. Allowing White to play a5 against our knight on b6 would be a strategic disaster.} 7. Na3 Bxa3 {As in almost all other variations of this line we take the knight on a3 .} 8. Rxa3 Nf6 {Now White has an important choice. Compared to the positions without a4  a5 included, the main differences are that the b4 -square is weak.} 9. O-O Nfd5 {Already fairly comfortable for us. White will get some typical Catalan compensation for the sacrificed pawn, but getting a knight to b4 provides us with both stability and counterplay.} *

