1. c4 e6 2. g3 d5 3. Nf3 dxc4 4. Bg2 Nd7 {This is the most flexible move. We make sure that we can still meet Qa4 with ... a6 , to develop the c8 -bishop as soon as possible.} (4... c6 $5 {This is of course a possibility, transposing to the 1. c4  c6 2. Nf3  d5 3. g3  chapter . It's true that this is in the Slav part of the repertoire, but that specific line is not one of the more specifically Slav-esque ones.}) 5. Qc2 Nb6 {Defending the pawn. This is the reason White usually plays Qa4 instead of Qc2 .} (5... a6 6. a4 $1 {This is something we need to avoid. Now it will get difficult to get ... b6 or ... b5 in a good way.}) 6. a4 {This is the extra option White gets against our knight on b6 .} (6. O-O Nf6 {transposes to O-O Ngf6 Qc2 Nb6 , here .}) 6... a5 {This is always essential. Allowing White to play a5 against our knight on b6 would be a strategic disaster.} 7. Na3 Bxa3 {As in almost all other variations of this line we take the knight on a3 .} 8. Rxa3 Nf6 {Now White has an important choice. Compared to the positions without a4  a5 included, the main differences are that the b4 -square is weak.} 9. e4 {Critical, simply preventing us from getting our knight to b4 .} O-O 10. O-O Bd7 {At first sight not a pretty move, but it's important to note just how weak the White a4 -pawn is. Basically, White will need to sacrifice it and hope they get enough counterplay in the meantime. From our end, the most important thing is to not overestimate our position. Yes, we will be one or even two pawns up, but White does get a fairly dangerous initiative. The main thing to keep in mind is the possibility of giving back material at the right moment, taking the sting out of White's attack.} 11. d4 {A good moment for this. Normally we'd be happy to trade off our doubled c-pawn, but here White will get unpleasant pressure along the d- and c-files.} Qe8 {It looks primitive, but in fact works well. The obvious point is to attack the a4 -pawn, but equally important is to step out of the g5 - d8 diagonal, as White was intending to create a highly unpleasant pin with Bg5 next.} 12. e5 {White is already all-in. There is no way to defend the queenside.} (12. Bg5 Bxa4 {This is entirely safe for us.}) 12... Bxa4 (12... Nfd5 {also works well. The idea then would be to overprotect the e6 -pawn, making ... f5 safer on the next move.}) 13. Qb1 {The only move. White need Ng5 on the next move.} (13. Rxa4 Qxa4 14. Qxa4 Nxa4 15. exf6 gxf6 {This is not enough; Black has a decisive advantage.}) 13... Nfd5 14. Ng5 g6 {The maximalist approach. In these positions ... g6 is generally the most optimistic move, where Black is unafraid of the attack and try to keep all the extra material. Instead, ... f5 is a move to immediately release the tension, but with the downside that e6 and b7 gets weaker. Here it would equalize without too many issues, but I think we have grounds to already play for the advantage!} 15. Ne4 Bb3 {This is an important part of our concept. The rook on a3 is locked out.} 16. Bh6 Nd7 {One of many reasonable moves. We are actually hoping White takes on f8 , as then the attack would entirely disappear. With two pawns for the exchange and an easy plan of just pushing on the queenside our position would be the preferable one.} *

