1. c4 e6 2. g3 d5 3. Nf3 dxc4 4. Bg2 Nd7 {This is the most flexible move. We make sure that we can still meet Qa4 with ... a6 , to develop the c8 -bishop as soon as possible.} (4... c6 $5 {This is of course a possibility, transposing to the 1. c4  c6 2. Nf3  d5 3. g3  chapter . It's true that this is in the Slav part of the repertoire, but that specific line is not one of the more specifically Slav-esque ones.}) 5. O-O (5. Qa4 a6 {transposes to Qa4+ Nd7 Bg2 a6 , here .}) 5... Ngf6 {We are still waiting for how White is going to recapture the c4 -pawn, and Ngf6 is the most flexible way to do so.} (5... a6 {This is generally dubious before White has moved their queen.} 6. Na3 $1 {Here ... a6 is rather useless.}) 6. Qa4 {By far the most common move.} a6 7. Nc3 {Sometimes this is played to annoy Black players, as ... b5 is not possible yet. But here there is a simple solution.} (7. Qxc4 b5 8. Qc2 Bb7 {transposes to} 9. Qa4 {Nd7 Bg2 a6 Qxc4 b5 Qc2 Bb7 O-O Ngf6 , analyzed later in this chapter.}) 7... Be7 {We simply continue to develop. At some point White will take on c4 , but then we are always ready to play ... b5 .} *

