1. c4 e6 2. g3 d5 3. Nf3 dxc4 4. Bg2 Nd7 {This is the most flexible move. We make sure that we can still meet Qa4 with ... a6 , to develop the c8 -bishop as soon as possible.} (4... c6 $5 {This is of course a possibility, transposing to the 1. c4  c6 2. Nf3  d5 3. g3  chapter . It's true that this is in the Slav part of the repertoire, but that specific line is not one of the more specifically Slav-esque ones.}) 5. O-O (5. Qa4 a6 {transposes to Qa4+ Nd7 Bg2 a6 , here .}) 5... Ngf6 {We are still waiting for how White is going to recapture the c4 -pawn, and Ngf6 is the most flexible way to do so.} (5... a6 {This is generally dubious before White has moved their queen.} 6. Na3 $1 {Here ... a6 is rather useless.}) 6. Qc2 Nb6 {Again, we should defend the c4 -pawn if given the chance.} 7. Ne5 {This is a typical way to play. If White would be able to win back the c4 -pawn they would probably have a slight edge, but we have a strong move available.} (7. a4 a5 {This doesn't change much. The main difference is that we get a square on b4 for a knight later on.} 8. Na3 Bxa3 9. Rxa3 Nfd5 {Transposes to Bg2 Nd7 Qc2 Nb6 a4 a5 Na3 Bxa3 Rxa3 Nf6 O-O Nfd5 , analyzed here .}) 7... Qd4 8. Nf3 {The only move.} Qc5 {Obviously we can also repeat, but I think we already have reasonable grounds for playing on. We'll keep our extra pawn, and although White has some compensation, it can hardly be enough for more than equality.} *

