1. c4 e6 2. g3 d5 3. Nf3 dxc4 4. Bg2 Nd7 {This is the most flexible move. We make sure that we can still meet Qa4 with ... a6 , to develop the c8 -bishop as soon as possible.} (4... c6 $5 {This is of course a possibility, transposing to the 1. c4  c6 2. Nf3  d5 3. g3  chapter . It's true that this is in the Slav part of the repertoire, but that specific line is not one of the more specifically Slav-esque ones.}) 5. O-O (5. Qa4 a6 {transposes to Qa4+ Nd7 Bg2 a6 , here .}) 5... Ngf6 {We are still waiting for how White is going to recapture the c4 -pawn, and Ngf6 is the most flexible way to do so.} (5... a6 {This is generally dubious before White has moved their queen.} 6. Na3 $1 {Here ... a6 is rather useless.}) 6. Na3 {This is generally an interesting way to play, but it would be stronger if we have wasted a tempo on for instance ... a6 or ... c6 .} Bxa3 7. bxa3 O-O {Our idea now is to push ... c5 , and then either ... b6 or ... b5 in order to develop the light squared bishop.} ({Such positions are covered extensively in the c4} 7... c6 {Nf3 d5 g3 chapter, starting here . This is just a bit of a better version for Black, as ... c6 wasn't the most useful move.}) 8. Bb2 c5 {We need this to prevent Nd4 after ... b5 .} 9. a4 {A typical move, preventing ... b5 .} b6 {This is a very nice idea.} 10. Ne5 {Otherwise we are in time to defend the c4 -pawn with ... Ba6 .} c3 {The point! Such intermediate moves are tricky to spot in practical play, but here it works really well.} 11. Bxc3 Nd5 {Now the bishop is hanging on c3 , which gives us an important tempo} 12. Bb2 Nxe5 {Trading the knights is a big improvement for us. Our d7 -knight was a fair bit more passive than White's. Additionally, it's an old and surprisingly valid rule that the side with two knights and a bishop against two bishops and a knight generally should seek to trade off the opponent's knight.} 13. Bxe5 f6 14. Bb2 e5 {We have a very nice position with good central control and excellent control over both dark and light squares.} *

