1. c4 e6 2. g3 d5 3. Nf3 dxc4 4. Bg2 Nd7 {This is the most flexible move. We make sure that we can still meet Qa4 with ... a6 , to develop the c8 -bishop as soon as possible.} (4... c6 $5 {This is of course a possibility, transposing to the 1. c4  c6 2. Nf3  d5 3. g3  chapter . It's true that this is in the Slav part of the repertoire, but that specific line is not one of the more specifically Slav-esque ones.}) 5. O-O (5. Qa4 a6 {transposes to Qa4+ Nd7 Bg2 a6 , here .}) 5... Ngf6 {We are still waiting for how White is going to recapture the c4 -pawn, and Ngf6 is the most flexible way to do so.} (5... a6 {This is generally dubious before White has moved their queen.} 6. Na3 $1 {Here ... a6 is rather useless.}) 6. Na3 {This is generally an interesting way to play, but it would be stronger if we have wasted a tempo on for instance ... a6 or ... c6 .} Bxa3 7. bxa3 O-O {Our idea now is to push ... c5 , and then either ... b6 or ... b5 in order to develop the light squared bishop.} ({Such positions are covered extensively in the c4} 7... c6 {Nf3 d5 g3 chapter, starting here . This is just a bit of a better version for Black, as ... c6 wasn't the most useful move.}) 8. Bb2 c5 {We need this to prevent Nd4 after ... b5 .} 9. a4 {A typical move, preventing ... b5 .} b6 10. Nd4 {Another way for White to pick up the exchange, but here the compensation is overwhelming.} cxd4 11. Bxa8 e5 {Now our center is very stable, and we have plenty of time to build up our initiative over the next couple of moves. Next up ... Nc5 , and then develop the bishop either towards g4 / h3 , or even the more modest a6 -square, just to keep the c4 -pawn alive. According to the engines, Black is only a bit better, but in a practical game, I would think White’s position is rather hopeless to play.} *

