1. c4 e6 2. g3 d5 3. Nf3 dxc4 4. Qa4+ (4. Bg2 {This is annoying for us, as we won't get our lovely Qd7 -system. But against all other setups, it's a less flexible version for White.} Nd7 {A smart move order! In general, developing the queenside is more important than the kingside in these lines. That is also the reason White usually gives the check on a4 already on move 4. Now we will be in time to play a6 , b5 and Bb7 if White goes after the c4 -pawn.} (4... c6 $5 {This transposes to c4 c6 Nf3 d5 g3 dxc4 Bg2 e6 , deeply analyzed in chapter 6, starting here . Although that was one of the chapters from the Slav part, I believe it's perfectly viable also for QGD-players, as the play is not too characteristic of either Slav or QGD. It's just an independent, interesting line.}) 5. O-O (5. Qc2 Nb6 $1 {This is the reason we start with 4... Nd7 . White will struggle to win the c4 -pawn back.}) 5... Ngf6 6. Qa4 (6. Na3 Bxa3 7. bxa3 O-O {This is even a slightly better version than 4... c6 , as the c-pawn can go to c5 in one go.}) 6... a6 7. Qxc4 b5 8. Qc2 Bb7 {Transposes to the mainline, starting here .}) 4... Qd7 {If you are playing the Solid Option vs 4. g3 in The Magnus Queen's Gambit , then this move still works perfectly well, and will most likely transpose to that course.} 5. Qxc4 c5 6. d4 {This is a difference with Nf3 instead of Bg2 - White is able to push d4 faster.} (6. Bg2 Nc6 {Transposes to c4 e6 g3 d5 Bg2 dxc4} 7. Qa4 {Qd7 Qxc4 c5 Nf3 Nc6 , analyzed starting here .}) 6... cxd4 7. Nxd4 a6 {Necessary. We really need to get ... Bb7 in to fight against White's strong bishop.} 8. Bg2 b5 9. Qd3 {The other queen moves will also transpose to the Magnus Queen's Gambit course.} Bb7 10. O-O Nf6 ({Transposes to d4 d5 c4 e6 Nf3 a6 g3 dxc4} 10... Bxg2 {c5 O-O cxd4 Nxd4 Nf6 Qa4+ Qd7} 11. Qc4 {b5 Qd3} Bb7 {, analyzed in chapter 8b) 3. Nf3 , 4. g3 (Solid Option) of The Magnus Queen's Gambit course, starting from here .}) *

