[ECO "A13"]
[PlyCount "24"]

1. c4 e6 2. g3 d5 3. Nf3 dxc4 4. Qa4+ (4. Bg2 {This is annoying for us, as we won't get our lovely Qd7 -system. But against all other setups, it's a less flexible version for White.} Nd7 {A smart move order! In general, developing the queenside is more important than the kingside in these lines. That is also the reason White usually gives the check on a4 already on move 4. Now we will be in time to play a6 , b5 and Bb7 if White goes after the c4 -pawn.} (4... c6 $5 {This transposes to c4 c6 Nf3 d5 g3 dxc4 Bg2 e6 , deeply analyzed in chapter 6, starting here . Although that was one of the chapters from the Slav part, I believe it's perfectly viable also for QGD-players, as the play is not too characteristic of either Slav or QGD. It's just an independent, interesting line.}) 5. O-O (5. Qc2 Nb6 $1 {This is the reason we start with 4... Nd7 . White will struggle to win the c4 -pawn back.}) 5... Ngf6 6. Qa4 (6. Na3 Bxa3 7. bxa3 O-O {This is even a slightly better version than 4... c6 , as the c-pawn can go to c5 in one go.}) 6... a6 7. Qxc4 b5 8. Qc2 Bb7 {Transposes to the mainline, starting here .}) 4... Nd7 {This is an important position to understand. Basically the main battleground is, as so often in these Catalan style positions, whether we are able to develop the c8 -bishop or not. In the previous chapter, White had Bg2 instead of Nf3 , which made it much harder for us to move our b-pawn, as the long diagonal is still open. That's the main reason why 3. Nf3 is considered a lot less critical than 3. Bg2 .} 5. Bg2 a6 {This is important. We do not play ... Ngf6 , as it is much more important to solve the issue of the c8 -bishop.} 6. Qxc4 {Otherwise, we would even save our c4 -pawn.} b5 7. Qc2 Bb7 {Just in time! With the bishop already developed to b7 most of our issues are gone.} 8. O-O Ngf6 {Now there is no reason to delay this anymore, as we have achieved our main strategic aim. In general, we have already equalized, but there is a single strategic idea left for White to try: they can put pressure on our b5 -pawn, trying to force in to b4 .} 9. Nc3 (9. a4 c5 10. Nc3 Bc6 {transposes to the current line.}) 9... c5 {This is important. White is going to play a4 next, and we really don't want to push ... b4 . Therefore, we prepare to defend our b5 -pawn.} 10. a4 Bc6 ({Playing} 10... Qb6 {is much more popular, but I prefer defending the pawn like this. It's nice to keep the queen on d8 , so that it protects our rook on a8 . It also opens up the b-file, so that we can defend the b5 -pawn with ... Rb8 if White tries to attack it further.}) 11. d3 Be7 12. Qb3 {This is how White plays against Qb6 instead of Bc6 , but here we have some extra options.} O-O {The simplest. Due to the b-file being open, the pawn on b5 is actually not hanging.} *

