ite to try: they can put pressure on our b5 -pawn, trying to force in to b4 .} 9. Nc3 (9. a4 c5 10. Nc3 Bc6 {transposes to the current line.}) 9... c5 {This is important. White is going to play a4 next, and we really don't want to push ... b4 . Therefore, we prepare to defend our b5 -pawn.} 10. a4 Bc6 ({Playing} 10... Qb6 {is much more popular, but I prefer defending the pawn like this. It's nice to keep the queen on d8 , so that it protects our rook on a8 . It also opens up the b-file, so that we can defend the b5 -pawn with ... Rb8 if White tries to attack it further.}) 11. Ne1 {This is the recommendation of Ntirlis in his book on the English. It's logical to trade off the defender of the b5 -pawn.} (11. Ng5 Bxg2 12. Kxg2 c4 {Will most probably transpose to the 11. Ne1 lines.}) 11... Bxg2 12. Kxg2 {Ntirlis stops here, saying that White has the more pleasant position to play.} c4 (12... Rb8 {is also fine, but I like this maximalist approach. We are not even giving White the a-file!}) 13. axb5 {The best move. With the pawn already on c4 we were seriously considering ... b4 next.} axb5 14. Rxa8 Qxa8+ 15. Nf3 Qa6 {This is subtle. We defend the b5 -pawn from a6 because of the x-ray towards d3 .} 16. d3 {White needs to play this sooner or later.} b4 17. Nb1 cxd3 18. Qxd3 Qxd3 {The reason we put our queen on a6 !} 19. exd3 Be7 {The ending is completely fine. We have a fantastic square on d5 for our knight, but with the b4 -pawn we don't really have more than equality.} *

