1. c4 e6 2. g3 d5 3. Nf3 dxc4 4. Qa4+ (4. Bg2 {This is annoying for us, as we won't get our lovely Qd7 -system. But against all other setups, it's a less flexible version for White.} Nd7 {A smart move order! In general, developing the queenside is more important than the kingside in these lines. That is also the reason White usually gives the check on a4 already on move 4. Now we will be in time to play a6 , b5 and Bb7 if White goes after the c4 -pawn.} (4... c6 $5 {This transposes to c4 c6 Nf3 d5 g3 dxc4 Bg2 e6 , deeply analyzed in chapter 6, starting here . Although that was one of the chapters from the Slav part, I believe it's perfectly viable also for QGD-players, as the play is not too characteristic of either Slav or QGD. It's just an independent, interesting line.}) 5. O-O (5. Qc2 Nb6 $1 {This is the reason we start with 4... Nd7 . White will struggle to win the c4 -pawn back.}) 5... Ngf6 6. Qa4 (6. Na3 Bxa3 7. bxa3 O-O {This is even a slightly better version than 4... c6 , as the c-pawn can go to c5 in one go.}) 6... a6 7. Qxc4 b5 8. Qc2 Bb7 {Transposes to the mainline, starting here .}) 4... Nd7 {This is an important position to understand. Basically the main battleground is, as so often in these Catalan style positions, whether we are able to develop the c8 -bishop or not. In the previous chapter, White had Bg2 instead of Nf3 , which made it much harder for us to move our b-pawn, as the long diagonal is still open. That's the main reason why 3. Nf3 is considered a lot less critical than 3. Bg2 .} 5. Bg2 a6 {This is important. We do not play ... Ngf6 , as it is much more important to solve the issue of the c8 -bishop.} 6. Qxc4 {Otherwise, we would even save our c4 -pawn.} b5 7. Qh4 {This is a funny-looking move that has gotten quite popular in the last couple of years. White is provoking our bishop to move to e7 . It looks insane, but there is a very concrete idea behind it.} (7. Qc6 Rb8 {Doesn't bother us. We simply play ... Bb7 next and will have gotten ... Rb8 for free.}) 7... Be7 8. Qe4 Rb8 {Normally, for instance with the bishop on f8 instead of e7 , we would just play ... Bb7 next and conclude that we have solved all our problems.} 9. Nd4 {This is the point! The bishop will be hanging on e7 later on. Still, it kind of goes without saying that this is all way too artificial for White to be good.} Ndf6 {One of many reasonable solutions. We use this knight, so that the d4 -knight is hanging.} 10. Nc6 Nxe4 11. Nxd8 Kxd8 12. Bxe4 Nf6 {We have no problems whatsoever in the ending.} *

