1. c4 e6 2. g3 d5 3. Nf3 dxc4 4. Qa4+ (4. Bg2 {This is annoying for us, as we won't get our lovely Qd7 -system. But against all other setups, it's a less flexible version for White.} Nd7 {A smart move order! In general, developing the queenside is more important than the kingside in these lines. That is also the reason White usually gives the check on a4 already on move 4. Now we will be in time to play a6 , b5 and Bb7 if White goes after the c4 -pawn.} (4... c6 $5 {This transposes to c4 c6 Nf3 d5 g3 dxc4 Bg2 e6 , deeply analyzed in chapter 6, starting here . Although that was one of the chapters from the Slav part, I believe it's perfectly viable also for QGD-players, as the play is not too characteristic of either Slav or QGD. It's just an independent, interesting line.}) 5. O-O (5. Qc2 Nb6 $1 {This is the reason we start with 4... Nd7 . White will struggle to win the c4 -pawn back.}) 5... Ngf6 6. Qa4 (6. Na3 Bxa3 7. bxa3 O-O {This is even a slightly better version than 4... c6 , as the c-pawn can go to c5 in one go.}) 6... a6 7. Qxc4 b5 8. Qc2 Bb7 {Transposes to the mainline, starting here .}) 4... Nd7 {This is an important position to understand. Basically the main battleground is, as so often in these Catalan style positions, whether we are able to develop the c8 -bishop or not. In the previous chapter, White had Bg2 instead of Nf3 , which made it much harder for us to move our b-pawn, as the long diagonal is still open. That's the main reason why 3. Nf3 is considered a lot less critical than 3. Bg2 .} 5. Bg2 a6 {This is important. We do not play ... Ngf6 , as it is much more important to solve the issue of the c8 -bishop.} 6. Qxc4 {Otherwise, we would even save our c4 -pawn.} b5 7. Qh4 {This is a funny-looking move that has gotten quite popular in the last couple of years. White is provoking our bishop to move to e7 . It looks insane, but there is a very concrete idea behind it.} (7. Qc6 Rb8 {Doesn't bother us. We simply play ... Bb7 next and will have gotten ... Rb8 for free.}) 7... Be7 8. Qe4 Rb8 {Normally, for instance with the bishop on f8 instead of e7 , we would just play ... Bb7 next and conclude that we have solved all our problems.} 9. Nd4 {This is the point! The bishop will be hanging on e7 later on. Still, it kind of goes without saying that this is all way too artificial for White to be good.} Ndf6 {One of many reasonable solutions. We use this knight, so that the d4 -knight is hanging.} 10. Qc6+ Bd7 11. Qc2 (11. Qxa6 {This seems excessively greedy to me, but it is possible and the queen won’t be trapped.} c5 12. Nc2 Nd5 {Threatening to trap the queen with ... Ra8 .} 13. Qa3 Ngf6 {We have no way of keep trying to trap the queen, but while she went all over the board we have developed our pieces and taken control over most of the board. There won’t be a direct breakthrough, but White will also struggle to get developed for a long time. Next up we castle, after which pushing …e5 and activating further makes sense. I believe the position is very scary for White to play.}) 11... c6 {This looks weird, but the idea is concrete. By placing the pawn on c6 we actually prevent White from playing Nc6 themselves.} (11... c5 12. Nc6 Bxc6 13. Bxc6+ Nd7 {Is also OK, but I prefer not giving up the bishop pair so easily.}) 12. O-O (12. Nxc6 $4 Rc8 {Wins a piece.}) 12... Rc8 {Now we are ready to push ... c5 without Nc6 being a reply.} 13. d3 (13. a4 c5 14. Nf3 Bc6 {White will most probably play d3 soon, transposing.}) 13... c5 14. Nf3 Bc6 {One of many reasonable ways to develop. We want our bishop on the long diagonal. The remaining issue to solve is the g8 -knight, but this will be done by playing ... Nd7 or ... Nd5 next, after which we are ready to finish development.} 15. a4 Nd7 {Making sure there is no Ne5 later on. As we've seen previously, the only real strategic idea for White in these positions is to provoke ... b4 , but here we will always be able to keep our pawn back on b5 , which means that we have no issues whatsoever.} *

