1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 b6 {This is a rare and in my opinion underestimated move. The basic idea is to oppose as quickly as possible on the long diagonal, so that we are able to always capture dxc4 as soon as White plays c4 . There is very little theory so it's hard to even pinpoint what are the mainlines and what is most important to know.} ({•} 2... Nd7 {As mentioned in the 2... Nd7 chapter, this is also a perfectly viable option for QGD-players.}) ({•} 2... Nf6 {The problem with playing this is first of all that we risk getting into a version of the Catalan that isn't in our repertoire. Secondly, White delaying c4 makes it even trickier, as all the open Catalans and the Bb4 + systems will not be possible for us.}) 3. c4 (3. d4 e6 {This is a direct transposition to the Magnus Queen's Gambit course after d4 d5 Nf3 e6 g3 b6 . However, also for players who play other versions of QGD, I don't think it's a big issue. Basically, the play is very similar to 3. Bg2 and 3. c4 , and indeed it often transposes. We still oppose on the long diagonal, and we still take it as soon as White plays c4 .}) 3... dxc4 4. Na3 {The most critical way.} (4. Qa4+ Nd7 5. Ne5 Bb7 6. Nc6 Qc8 {It's important to note that while the knight on c6 looks pretty, it doesn't actually do much and we will be able to trade it off soon.}) 4... Bb7 5. Nxc4 Nd7 6. Bg2 e6 7. O-O Be7 {A very important move order. For tactical reasons it's important to delay Ngf6 for one move.} 8. Qa4 {White's main idea is to get a knight to c6 and win the bishop pair. Against a really, really well-prepared player you are likely to get this position on the board.} Ngf6 9. Nce5 {If White plays slower moves we simply develop without issues.} O-O 10. Nc6 Qe8 11. Nxe7+ Qxe7 {This sort of position we have seen a few other places in the repertoire. White has the bishop pair, but our position is incredibly solid. Our idea should be to play ... c5 and ... a5 , and if White plays b3 we get counterplay by pushing ... a4 .} *

