[Result "*"]
[ECO "A07"]
[PlyCount "20"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 b6 {This is another controversial option. Just like 2... Nd7 goes very well stylistically with Slav players, I think 2... b6 goes very well with a QGD-repertoire. Indeed, it often directly transposes to the Magnus Queen's Gambit course, but when doing so in a non-critical version. There is no reason to think that you need to play my other repertoire specifically, though. The system with 2... b6 is an independent system in itself, and it can definitely be combined with any version of the Queen's Gambit that is in your normal repertoire. The move ... b6 in itself is to prepare ... Bb7 as quickly as possible, so that we can take on c4 without getting into trouble on the long diagonal. It's a favorite of the Serbian grandmaster Predke, who is always a creative opening researcher.} 3. c4 {In my opinion the best move, but also the most likely.} (3. d4 {This is very unlikely to be played, as most Reti players dislikes playing d4 so soon.} e6 {transposes to d4 d5 Nf3 e6 g3 b6 analyzed in chapter 12, 2. Nf3 3rd Move Sidelines, in The Magnus Queen's Gambit , starting here .}) 3... dxc4 {Just like what we learned from the 1. c4  e6 Chapters, we take instantly, as soon as White plays c4 . We need to do it immediately so that we are in time for ... Bb7 , opposing on the long diagonal.} 4. Qa4+ Nd7 5. Ne5 (5. Qxc4 e6 {Transposes to c4 e6 g3 d5 Nf3 dxc4} 6. Qa4 {Nd7 Qxc4 b6 , analyzed here .}) 5... Bb7 6. Nc6 {The knight looks scary here, but we should not panic. Step by step we will be able to trade it off.} Qc8 7. Bg2 e6 8. O-O {This was played in the only game reaching this position. Our main aim should still be to get rid of the annoying c6 -knight, but there are a few different ways of achieving it.} Bc5 {Makes sense immediately, as White can't push d4 yet.} (8... Ne7 {This is also possible, but makes it a little harder to push back the c6 -knight.} 9. Qxc4 Nxc6 10. Bxc6 {It’s no disaster, and eventually we will equalize, but forcing the c6 -knight or bishop to trade immediately feels a little safer to me.}) 9. Qxc4 Ne7 {Getting rid of the c6 -knight, after which we are completely fine.} 10. Qa4 a6 {White will have to trade on e7 soon, which solves our only problem.} *

