1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 b6 {This is another controversial option. Just like 2... Nd7 goes very well stylistically with Slav players, I think 2... b6 goes very well with a QGD-repertoire. Indeed, it often directly transposes to the Magnus Queen's Gambit course, but when doing so in a non-critical version. There is no reason to think that you need to play my other repertoire specifically, though. The system with 2... b6 is an independent system in itself, and it can definitely be combined with any version of the Queen's Gambit that is in your normal repertoire. The move ... b6 in itself is to prepare ... Bb7 as quickly as possible, so that we can take on c4 without getting into trouble on the long diagonal. It's a favorite of the Serbian grandmaster Predke, who is always a creative opening researcher.} 3. c4 {In my opinion the best move, but also the most likely.} (3. d4 {This is very unlikely to be played, as most Reti players dislikes playing d4 so soon.} e6 {transposes to d4 d5 Nf3 e6 g3 b6 analyzed in chapter 12, 2. Nf3 3rd Move Sidelines, in The Magnus Queen's Gambit , starting here .}) 3... dxc4 {Just like what we learned from the 1. c4  e6 Chapters, we take instantly, as soon as White plays c4 . We need to do it immediately so that we are in time for ... Bb7 , opposing on the long diagonal.} 4. Qa4+ Nd7 5. Ne5 (5. Qxc4 e6 {Transposes to c4 e6 g3 d5 Nf3 dxc4} 6. Qa4 {Nd7 Qxc4 b6 , analyzed here .}) 5... Bb7 6. Nc6 {The knight looks scary here, but we should not panic. Step by step we will be able to trade it off.} Qc8 7. Bg2 e6 8. Qxc4 Ne7 {Immediately challenging the knight.} 9. d4 Nxc6 10. Bxc6 Bc5 {Definitely not necessary, but it looks cute. We simply force the trade of bishops in a good way.} 11. Bxb7 Qxb7 12. O-O Bd6 {We are absolutely fine. In the future pushing ... c5 will equalize, but going for the ... e5 -push instead is more ambitious.} *

