1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 b6 {This is another controversial option. Just like 2... Nd7 goes very well stylistically with Slav players, I think 2... b6 goes very well with a QGD-repertoire. Indeed, it often directly transposes to the Magnus Queen's Gambit course, but when doing so in a non-critical version. There is no reason to think that you need to play my other repertoire specifically, though. The system with 2... b6 is an independent system in itself, and it can definitely be combined with any version of the Queen's Gambit that is in your normal repertoire. The move ... b6 in itself is to prepare ... Bb7 as quickly as possible, so that we can take on c4 without getting into trouble on the long diagonal. It's a favorite of the Serbian grandmaster Predke, who is always a creative opening researcher.} 3. c4 {In my opinion the best move, but also the most likely.} (3. d4 {This is very unlikely to be played, as most Reti players dislikes playing d4 so soon.} e6 {transposes to d4 d5 Nf3 e6 g3 b6 analyzed in chapter 12, 2. Nf3 3rd Move Sidelines, in The Magnus Queen's Gambit , starting here .}) 3... dxc4 {Just like what we learned from the 1. c4  e6 Chapters, we take instantly, as soon as White plays c4 . We need to do it immediately so that we are in time for ... Bb7 , opposing on the long diagonal.} 4. Na3 {In this instance, I think the most critical way to recapture on c4 is by the knight. Without having played ... e6 we can't take it, which otherwise is our most usual response.} Bb7 5. Nxc4 Nd7 {The knight always goes here, to keep the long diagonal open.} 6. Bg2 e6 7. O-O Be7 {Super important! It would be almost impossible to figure this out over the board, but there is a very concrete reason we need to start with ... Be7 instead of ... Ngf6 .} (7... Ngf6 8. Nce5 $1 {This sets some concrete problems.} Nxe5 9. Nxe5 Bxg2 10. Qa4+ $1 b5 11. Qxb5+ c6 12. Qb7 $1 {White is threatening mate on f7 , as there is no bishop on e7 blocking the queen!}) 8. d3 {This is how the only grandmaster game reaching this position continued. White was... me! The idea is to block the b7 -bishop and prevent the trade. It's not stupid, but also not really challenging.} Ngf6 9. e4 O-O 10. Qe2 {Now there are two interesting ways to play. Predke played 10... c5 with the idea of ... Nb8 - c6 , a typical and good maneuver.} (10. Bf4 a5 {This is very similar to the main line.}) 10... a5 {I'm recommending this instead. There is no immediate need for ... c5 as White can't really play d4 , so I like just grabbing more queenside space.} 11. Rd1 a4 12. Bf4 c5 {Still not necessary, but no big reason not to. With the pawn on a4 White constantly have to think about ... b5 , but we are not in any rush to play it. As White is not really intending anything, we have a lot of time. Slow improving moves like ... h6 , ... Re8 and so on makes sense. One day, when we feel like it, we will probably play ... b5 .} *

