1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 b6 {This is another controversial option. Just like 2... Nd7 goes very well stylistically with Slav players, I think 2... b6 goes very well with a QGD-repertoire. Indeed, it often directly transposes to the Magnus Queen's Gambit course, but when doing so in a non-critical version. There is no reason to think that you need to play my other repertoire specifically, though. The system with 2... b6 is an independent system in itself, and it can definitely be combined with any version of the Queen's Gambit that is in your normal repertoire. The move ... b6 in itself is to prepare ... Bb7 as quickly as possible, so that we can take on c4 without getting into trouble on the long diagonal. It's a favorite of the Serbian grandmaster Predke, who is always a creative opening researcher.} 3. c4 {In my opinion the best move, but also the most likely.} (3. d4 {This is very unlikely to be played, as most Reti players dislikes playing d4 so soon.} e6 {transposes to d4 d5 Nf3 e6 g3 b6 analyzed in chapter 12, 2. Nf3 3rd Move Sidelines, in The Magnus Queen's Gambit , starting here .}) 3... dxc4 {Just like what we learned from the 1. c4  e6 Chapters, we take instantly, as soon as White plays c4 . We need to do it immediately so that we are in time for ... Bb7 , opposing on the long diagonal.} 4. Na3 {In this instance, I think the most critical way to recapture on c4 is by the knight. Without having played ... e6 we can't take it, which otherwise is our most usual response.} Bb7 5. Nxc4 Nd7 {The knight always goes here, to keep the long diagonal open.} 6. Bg2 e6 7. O-O Be7 {Super important! It would be almost impossible to figure this out over the board, but there is a very concrete reason we need to start with ... Be7 instead of ... Ngf6 .} (7... Ngf6 8. Nce5 $1 {This sets some concrete problems.} Nxe5 9. Nxe5 Bxg2 10. Qa4+ $1 b5 11. Qxb5+ c6 12. Qb7 $1 {White is threatening mate on f7 , as there is no bishop on e7 blocking the queen!}) 8. Qa4 {This is one of the most challenging moves. I think a well-prepared White player is pretty likely to play this if faced with 2... b6 .} Ngf6 9. Nfe5 {This is also logical. On the one hand, trading the light squared bishops is usually in our favor, but on the other hand, White gets immediate access to the c6 -square.} Bxg2 10. Kxg2 c5 {We can't do anything to prevent Nc6 , so we might at least create a good square for our queen.} 11. Nc6 Qc7 12. Nxe7 Kxe7 {The king in the center is no concern at all, as we are easily able to evacuate it by ... Rhd8 and ... Kf8 .} 13. d3 Ne5 {This is a good moment to play ... Ne5 , as White was intending Bf4 next. The White knight is somewhat more active than ours, so it makes sense to trade them off.} 14. Kg1 {Preventing an annoying check on b7 .} Rhd8 15. Bf4 Qc6 {A nice way of solving the pin. After the trade of either queens or knights we have no problems whatsoever.} *

