1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 b6 {This is another controversial option. Just like 2... Nd7 goes very well stylistically with Slav players, I think 2... b6 goes very well with a QGD-repertoire. Indeed, it often directly transposes to the Magnus Queen's Gambit course, but when doing so in a non-critical version. There is no reason to think that you need to play my other repertoire specifically, though. The system with 2... b6 is an independent system in itself, and it can definitely be combined with any version of the Queen's Gambit that is in your normal repertoire. The move ... b6 in itself is to prepare ... Bb7 as quickly as possible, so that we can take on c4 without getting into trouble on the long diagonal. It's a favorite of the Serbian grandmaster Predke, who is always a creative opening researcher.} 3. c4 {In my opinion the best move, but also the most likely.} (3. d4 {This is very unlikely to be played, as most Reti players dislikes playing d4 so soon.} e6 {transposes to d4 d5 Nf3 e6 g3 b6 analyzed in chapter 12, 2. Nf3 3rd Move Sidelines, in The Magnus Queen's Gambit , starting here .}) 3... dxc4 {Just like what we learned from the 1. c4  e6 Chapters, we take instantly, as soon as White plays c4 . We need to do it immediately so that we are in time for ... Bb7 , opposing on the long diagonal.} 4. Na3 {In this instance, I think the most critical way to recapture on c4 is by the knight. Without having played ... e6 we can't take it, which otherwise is our most usual response.} Bb7 5. Nxc4 Nd7 {The knight always goes here, to keep the long diagonal open.} 6. Bg2 e6 7. O-O Be7 {Super important! It would be almost impossible to figure this out over the board, but there is a very concrete reason we need to start with ... Be7 instead of ... Ngf6 .} (7... Ngf6 8. Nce5 $1 {This sets some concrete problems.} Nxe5 9. Nxe5 Bxg2 10. Qa4+ $1 b5 11. Qxb5+ c6 12. Qb7 $1 {White is threatening mate on f7 , as there is no bishop on e7 blocking the queen!}) 8. Qa4 {This is one of the most challenging moves. I think a well-prepared White player is pretty likely to play this if faced with 2... b6 .} Ngf6 9. Nce5 O-O 10. Nc6 {The point. White collects the bishop pair.} Qe8 11. Nfe5 {Clamping down on the c6 -square like this also looks natural, but now we can save our bishop.} Bd6 12. Nxd7 Nxd7 {Important for a specific tactical reason.} 13. d4 (13. Ne7+ $4 Qxe7 14. Bxb7 Nc5 {The reason we take with the knight on d7 !} 15. Qc6 Rab8 {winning a piece.}) 13... Kh8 {Simply stepping out of the Ne7 +. The knight on c6 looks strong, but we are actually able to play around it pretty well.} 14. Qc2 f5 {Grabbing more space and preparing ... e5 . Later on, we can use the f-pawn to create some play on the kingside.} (14... e5 $2 15. dxe5 Nxe5 16. Nxe5 Bxg2 17. Nxf7+ $1 {This intermediate move is the reason we have to evacuate the f7 -pawn.} Qxf7 18. Kxg2 {White is a pawn up.}) 15. Bd2 e5 {We have excellent counterplay on the kingside. Our idea is to push ... e4 , which will undermine the c6 -knight. Probably White should trade on e5 , but then we no longer have any issues.} *

