1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 b6 {This is another controversial option. Just like 2... Nd7 goes very well stylistically with Slav players, I think 2... b6 goes very well with a QGD-repertoire. Indeed, it often directly transposes to the Magnus Queen's Gambit course, but when doing so in a non-critical version. There is no reason to think that you need to play my other repertoire specifically, though. The system with 2... b6 is an independent system in itself, and it can definitely be combined with any version of the Queen's Gambit that is in your normal repertoire. The move ... b6 in itself is to prepare ... Bb7 as quickly as possible, so that we can take on c4 without getting into trouble on the long diagonal. It's a favorite of the Serbian grandmaster Predke, who is always a creative opening researcher.} 3. c4 {In my opinion the best move, but also the most likely.} (3. d4 {This is very unlikely to be played, as most Reti players dislikes playing d4 so soon.} e6 {transposes to d4 d5 Nf3 e6 g3 b6 analyzed in chapter 12, 2. Nf3 3rd Move Sidelines, in The Magnus Queen's Gambit , starting here .}) 3... dxc4 {Just like what we learned from the 1. c4  e6 Chapters, we take instantly, as soon as White plays c4 . We need to do it immediately so that we are in time for ... Bb7 , opposing on the long diagonal.} 4. Na3 {In this instance, I think the most critical way to recapture on c4 is by the knight. Without having played ... e6 we can't take it, which otherwise is our most usual response.} Bb7 5. Nxc4 Nd7 {The knight always goes here, to keep the long diagonal open.} 6. Bg2 e6 7. O-O Be7 {Super important! It would be almost impossible to figure this out over the board, but there is a very concrete reason we need to start with ... Be7 instead of ... Ngf6 .} (7... Ngf6 8. Nce5 $1 {This sets some concrete problems.} Nxe5 9. Nxe5 Bxg2 10. Qa4+ $1 b5 11. Qxb5+ c6 12. Qb7 $1 {White is threatening mate on f7 , as there is no bishop on e7 blocking the queen!}) 8. Qa4 {This is one of the most challenging moves. I think a well-prepared White player is pretty likely to play this if faced with 2... b6 .} Ngf6 9. Nce5 O-O 10. Nc6 {The point. White collects the bishop pair.} Qe8 11. Nxe7+ Qxe7 {An interesting position. White has the bishop pair, which is their only claim for an advantage. As compensation, we have a solid and flexible structure, no weaknesses and only good pieces. The question is how to create any play. There are not that many active ideas available, and we should be a bit careful not weakening ourselves too much, but one nice way of getting some counterplay is to push the a-pawn.} 12. b3 {The most logical way to develop. The bishop is simply best placed on b2 .} c5 {This always makes sense, taking control over the dark squares in the center.} 13. Bb2 a5 {This is our idea. If the queen moves, we are happily playing ... a4 to create just a little bit of tension. It's not like we are creating any big threats, but rather just annoy White just enough for them not being able to do whatever they want.} 14. d4 {In general, we are not too worried about this, as we get firm control over the light squares.} Rfc8 15. Rac1 Bc6 16. Qc4 a4 {b3 is at least as weak as c5 . It's not unlikely that those pawns will get traded off, but then the position is just equal.} ({dxc5 axb3 Not necessary, but for simplicity’s sake we might as well throw it in. axb3} 16... Bd5 {Qf4 One of many squares, but they are all similar. bxc5! The correct recapture. Now, the b3 -pawn will always be a weakness. The most likely scenario now is that c5 gets traded for b3 , with an entirely equal position.}) *

