hallenging moves. I think a well-prepared White player is pretty likely to play this if faced with 2... b6 .} Ngf6 9. Nce5 O-O 10. Nc6 {The point. White collects the bishop pair.} Qe8 11. Nxe7+ Qxe7 {An interesting position. White has the bishop pair, which is their only claim for an advantage. As compensation, we have a solid and flexible structure, no weaknesses and only good pieces. The question is how to create any play. There are not that many active ideas available, and we should be a bit careful not weakening ourselves too much, but one nice way of getting some counterplay is to push the a-pawn.} 12. b3 {The most logical way to develop. The bishop is simply best placed on b2 .} c5 {This always makes sense, taking control over the dark squares in the center.} 13. Bb2 a5 {This is our idea. If the queen moves, we are happily playing ... a4 to create just a little bit of tension. It's not like we are creating any big threats, but rather just annoy White just enough for them not being able to do whatever they want.} 14. d3 {Such slow play is in my opinion the most strategically ambitious for White. The dream is that the bishop pair will become strong later in the game.} Rfc8 {There are many different ways to play this, but I like this setup. Also note that there is no immediate rush to push ... Bc6 and ... a4 . We can also keep the idea in our pocket and use it when we feel it appropriate.} 15. Rac1 h6 {Just to highlight that we are in no rush whatsoever. White has no obvious plan available, so we can keep improving with small moves like this. That being said, just straightforwardly pushing ... Bc6 and ... a4 is completely fine, as well.} *

