1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 b6 3. c4 dxc4 {We always take on c4 .} 4. Na3 (4. Qa4+ Nd7 5. Qxc4 Bb7 {Always good counterplay. Whenever White plays d4 , we are ready to attack the center with ... c5 . White's entire plan in the Reti often revolves around preventing the development of the light squared bishop, but here that has failed.}) 4... Bb7 5. Nxc4 Nd7 6. Bg2 e6 7. O-O Be7 ({Super important! There is a very concrete reason we need to start with ... Be7 .} 7... Ngf6 8. Nce5 $1 {This sets some concrete problems.} Nxe5 9. Nxe5 Bxg2 10. Qa4+ $1 b5 11. Qxb5+ c6 12. Qb7 $1 {White is threatening mate on f7 , as there is no bishop on e7 blocking the queen!}) 8. Qa4 Ngf6 9. Nce5 O-O 10. Nc6 Qe8 11. Nxe7+ (11. Nfe5 Bd6 12. Nxd7 Nxd7 {It's important that the knight on c6 , while looking pretty, isn't actually doing that much. We will easily play around it.} 13. d4 Kh8 $1 {With good counterplay.}) 11... Qxe7 12. b3 c5 13. Bb2 a5 {Important way to get counterplay. As soon as the queen leaves a4 , we play ... a4 ourselves putting pressure on White's queenside. White has the bishop pair, but as pawn pushes in the center likely just trades the bishops off, it's not easy to find a good plan.} *

