[ECO "A05"]
[PlyCount "16"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 b6 {This is a rare and in my opinion underestimated move. The basic idea is to oppose as quickly as possible on the long diagonal, so that we are able to always capture dxc4 as soon as White plays c4 . There is very little theory so it's hard to even pinpoint what are the mainlines and what is most important to know.} ({•} 2... Nd7 {As mentioned in the 2... Nd7 chapter, this is a perfectly viable option also for QGD-players.}) ({•} 2... Nf6 {The problem with playing this is first of all that we risk getting into a version of the Catalan that isn't in our repertoire. Secondly, White delaying c4 makes it even trickier, as all the open Catalans and the Bb4 + systems will not be possible for us.}) 3. Bg2 Bb7 4. O-O {This is another very common way for White to play.} e6 {An important move order. White still has the option of both e4 and c4 , therefore we need maximum flexibility.} 5. d3 (5. b3 Nf6 6. Bb2 {The double fianchetto leads to different style positions.} Be7 {The most solid move. Play is now very likely to transpose to} 7. c4 {e6 Nf3 d5 e3 Nf6 b3 b6 Bb2 Bb7 g3} c5 {, analyzed here} (7... Bd6 {is the alternative move.})) 5... Nf6 {It's important to keep the d-file open as we want to trade queens in case White plays c4 .} 6. Nbd2 {Going for a King's Indian Attack.} (6. c4 {The most common move in practice.} dxc4 7. dxc4 Qxd1 8. Rxd1 Bd6 {Preventing Bf4 . The ending is fine for Black.}) 6... Nbd7 7. e4 dxe4 8. dxe4 e5 {A safe and reliable setup for Black.} (8... Nxe4 {This is very risky. We should not forget that White has castled, and we have not, so opening up the center is always a risk.} 9. Nxe4 Bxe4 10. Qe2 Bb7 11. Bg5 $1 Be7 12. Ne5 $1 Bxg2 13. Rfd1 $1 {With strong pressure is a sample that shows why we should be careful to not open up the center too early. There are playable alternatives along the way, but White keeps annoying pressure for the pawn.}) *

