1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 b6 3. Bg2 {White can also try to play without c4 , or delay c4 until later on.} Bb7 4. O-O e6 {The most flexible move. We don't want to commit a knight to f6 too early, as then White might consider Ne5 !? without us being able to trade it off or push it back.} (4... Nd7 {This should be avoided if White doesn't play c4 immediately.} 5. d3 Ngf6 6. c4 $1 {The problem is that in case we trade on c4 our knight would be much better on c6 than d7 .}) 5. b3 Nf6 6. Bb2 {The double fianchetto is more dangerous without c4  dxc4 . With the pawn on b3 , we never really want to take on c4 , so it leads to different style positions.} Be7 ({The most solid move. Play is now very likely to transpose to c4 e6 Nf3 d5 e3 Nf6 b3 b6 Bb2 Bb7 g3} 6... c5 {, analyzed here .}) 7. c4 O-O 8. cxd5 {This is the independent option available to White.} (8. Nc3 c5 9. e3 Qc8 {Transposes to c4 e6 Nf3} 10. cxd5 {e3 Nf6 b3 b6 Bb2 Bb7 g3 c5 Bg2 Be7 O-O O-O Nc3 Qc8 , starting here .}) 8... Nxd5 {With the bishop on e7 and White's pawn still on e2 , we generally don't want to recapture with the e-pawn. The bishop would be less active on e7 , and the move e2 - e3 is somewhat wasting time.} 9. d4 Nd7 ({We want to play ... c5 and fight back in the center.} 9... c5 {is another very solid choice.}) 10. Re1 {The only way to try putting any pressure. On all other moves we just push ... c5 and equalize immediately.} c5 11. e4 N5f6 12. Nc3 {This is one of few positions where we actually need to know a few concrete lines. If we are not careful, we end up under serious pressure.} (12. e5 {This is strategically dubious, as we get an excellent square on d5 for our knight.} Nd5) 12... cxd4 13. Nxd4 Bc5 {We need to act quickly here. If we don't put immediate pressure on White, they would be able to solidify the center with a clear strategic edge.} 14. Ndb5 ({This is the alternative to} 14. Na4 {. Now there is a nice and surprising tactical solution.}) 14... Qe7 {In itself a logical and natural move, but White has a concrete idea.} 15. e5 {A typical tactic. Normally it would be winning for White, but we have a surprising resource.} Rad8 {Amazingly, it all holds together well for us.} 16. Bxb7 Nxe5 17. Qc2 Nd3 {This is too much for White.} *

