, it steps out of the b4 - e1 diagonal.} Ne5 {One of many reasonable moves.} 15. Na4 {Now ... Bb4 makes no sense, as the rook is not attacked on e1 .} (15. Rd2 Qe7 {This is very solid. White will struggle to kick our active pieces back.}) 15... Bxd4 {Giving up the bishop pair is never nice, but here we have concrete counterplay.} 16. Bxd4 Nc6 17. Bb2 Qe7 {With a rook coming to d8 next we have excellent central control. The knight on a4 is also slightly out of play.} *

