1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 b6 3. Bg2 {White can also try to play without c4 , or delay c4 until later on.} Bb7 4. O-O e6 {The most flexible move. We don't want to commit a knight to f6 too early, as then White might consider Ne5 !? without us being able to trade it off or push it back.} (4... Nd7 {This should be avoided if White doesn't play c4 immediately.} 5. d3 Ngf6 6. c4 $1 {The problem is that in case we trade on c4 our knight would be much better on c6 than d7 .}) 5. b3 Nf6 6. Bb2 {The double fianchetto is more dangerous without c4  dxc4 . With the pawn on b3 , we never really want to take on c4 , so it leads to different style positions.} Bd6 {This makes sense for those of you who play it also after c4 e6 Nf3 d5 e3 Nf6 b3 b6 Bb2 Bb7 g3 , as it's likely leading to similar positions. It's a slightly worse version, though, as White did not yet commit to e3 .} 7. c4 O-O 8. Nc3 Nbd7 9. d4 Re8 {White has not yet committed to e3 , but it will likely be similar in style anyway.} 10. Nd2 {Trying to push a quick e4 .} Rb8 {An interesting prophylactic move, defending the b7 -bishop.} 11. e4 Nxe4 12. Ndxe4 dxe4 13. Nxe4 Be7 {With the bishop on b7 defended, we can safely play ... Nf6 next. White has a small space advantage, but with so many pieces traded, that doesn't really mean anything. Trade everything on e4 and put pressure on the d4 -pawn.} *

