1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 b6 3. Bg2 {White can also try to play without c4 , or delay c4 until later on.} Bb7 4. O-O e6 {The most flexible move. We don't want to commit a knight to f6 too early, as then White might consider Ne5 !? without us being able to trade it off or push it back.} (4... Nd7 {This should be avoided if White doesn't play c4 immediately.} 5. d3 Ngf6 6. c4 $1 {The problem is that in case we trade on c4 our knight would be much better on c6 than d7 .}) 5. d3 Nf6 6. c4 {This has been played a fair amount, but to me it looks rather innocent.} dxc4 7. dxc4 Qxd1 8. Rxd1 Bd6 {This is an important move. The bishop is well-placed on d6 , preventing both Bf4 and Ne5 . Additionally, it can even go to e5 later, should White at some point play Nd4 .} 9. Nc3 a6 {We always need this, as Nb5 is an annoying threat.} 10. Nd4 {This was tried by Shevchenko, in the only game that ever reached this position.} Bxg2 11. Kxg2 Be5 {A small novelty, but a good one. We are not against taking on d4 as it gives us the opportunity to develop with ... Nc6 thereafter. If White does nothing, we might even consider ... c5 !? followed by ... Bxc3 to settle White with a sad doubled pawn.} 12. Bf4 {One of many reaonable moves, but I would just like to show our next move as I find it quite instructive.} Nfd7 {Far from the only move, but I like it. We keep the knight on b8 in order to develop it to c6 later on. With a knight on d7 we are also preparing ... Bxd4 followed by ... e5 . Our king will be well-placed on e7 , after which we eventually bring our rooks into the game.} *

