1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 b6 3. Bg2 {White can also try to play without c4 , or delay c4 until later on.} Bb7 4. O-O e6 {The most flexible move. We don't want to commit a knight to f6 too early, as then White might consider Ne5 !? without us being able to trade it off or push it back.} (4... Nd7 {This should be avoided if White doesn't play c4 immediately.} 5. d3 Ngf6 6. c4 $1 {The problem is that in case we trade on c4 our knight would be much better on c6 than d7 .}) 5. d3 Nf6 6. Nbd2 {Going for a King's Indian Attack style of play.} Nbd7 {This is a more normal continuation. We are no longer worried about c4 , as then the white knight would be much better on c3 than d2 .} 7. e4 dxe4 8. Ng5 {This has been the most common move in practice. It's a typical King's Indian Attack idea, but fails to put any real pressure on us.} Be7 (8... Nc5 {would trade almost the entire board, with a draw as the likely outcome. This is not better, but it keeps a lot of pieces on the board.}) 9. Ngxe4 Rb8 {We calmly defend our b7 -bishop. Next up we castle, after which it's time to think about a plan. It's hard to formulate a more long-term plan here, as it depends on how White is playing. Grabbing some queenside space with ... c5 makes sense, but generally feel we need to take it one move at a time. If White does nothing at all, a setup like ... c5 , ... Qc7 , ... Rbd8 and ... Rfe8 makes sense. It can also be interesting to play ... Nd5 in order to push ... f5 , but that is obviously a bit riskier.} *

