1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 b6 3. Bg2 {White can also try to play without c4 , or delay c4 until later on.} Bb7 4. O-O e6 {The most flexible move. We don't want to commit a knight to f6 too early, as then White might consider Ne5 !? without us being able to trade it off or push it back.} (4... Nd7 {This should be avoided if White doesn't play c4 immediately.} 5. d3 Ngf6 6. c4 $1 {The problem is that in case we trade on c4 our knight would be much better on c6 than d7 .}) 5. d3 Nf6 6. Nbd2 {Going for a King's Indian Attack style of play.} Nbd7 {This is a more normal continuation. We are no longer worried about c4 , as then the white knight would be much better on c3 than d2 .} 7. e4 dxe4 8. dxe4 {This sacrifices the e4 -pawn, but White would get excellent compensation for it.} e5 {The safe choice. The bishop is rarely on b7 in these structures, but to me, it makes a lot of sense. The e4 -pawn will always be hanging, and it's not in the way. However, this is still very much a typical King's Indian Attack style position, so White might not mind it too much.} 9. Qe2 {Another logical developing move, typical for the King's Indian Attack.} Bc5 {Again, this is the most active spot of the bishop.} 10. Nb3 (10. Nh4 O-O 11. Nb3 g6 {transposes to the current line.}) 10... O-O 11. Nh4 {The most testing move. The knight could be annoying on f5 .} (11. Nxc5 Nxc5 {After the trade of e-pawns the position is equal, but full of life!}) 11... g6 {Somewhat controversial. Generally I'd be afraid to play ... g6 when White can take our dark squared bishop, but here we have very fast counterplay.} 12. Nxc5 {Else we simply retreat the bishop to d6 .} Nxc5 13. Rd1 (13. f3 {is less accurate as it allows ... Ba6 .} Ba6 $1 14. c4 Ne6 {With the knight coming to d4 and White's knight out of play on h4 , we are doing well.}) 13... Qe7 14. f3 Rfd8 {This is an interesting strategic position. Had the White knight been on a better square White would be doing well with the bishop pair and especially the dark squared bishop. Here the knight is entirely out of play on h4 though, and we are getting counterplay in the center. ... Ne6 - d4 is still the main idea, but ... Ba6 is another way to put more pressure on White.} *

