1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 b6 3. Bg2 {White can also try to play without c4 , or delay c4 until later on.} Bb7 4. O-O e6 {The most flexible move. We don't want to commit a knight to f6 too early, as then White might consider Ne5 !? without us being able to trade it off or push it back.} (4... Nd7 {This should be avoided if White doesn't play c4 immediately.} 5. d3 Ngf6 6. c4 $1 {The problem is that in case we trade on c4 our knight would be much better on c6 than d7 .}) 5. d3 Nf6 6. Nbd2 {Going for a King's Indian Attack style of play.} Nbd7 {This is a more normal continuation. We are no longer worried about c4 , as then the white knight would be much better on c3 than d2 .} 7. e4 dxe4 8. dxe4 {This sacrifices the e4 -pawn, but White would get excellent compensation for it.} e5 {The safe choice. The bishop is rarely on b7 in these structures, but to me, it makes a lot of sense. The e4 -pawn will always be hanging, and it's not in the way. However, this is still very much a typical King's Indian Attack style position, so White might not mind it too much.} 9. c3 (9. Nc4 Bc5 {This is very similar to} 10. c3 a5 {Nc4 Bc5 . If anything, it's a slightly better version for us.}) 9... a5 {Securing a square on c5 for our bishop. This looks fine as well.} 10. Nc4 {The only critical move.} Bc5 {Allowing the complications in the center, as they only lead to trades.} 11. Nfxe5 {Against other moves we can simply castle.} Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Qxd1 13. Rxd1 Nxe4 14. Bxe4 Bxe4 15. Re1 f5 {The last important move. Due to the c5 - g1 pin White can't play f3 , so there is nothing to worry about on the e-file.} *

