1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 b6 3. Bg2 {White can also try to play without c4 , or delay c4 until later on.} Bb7 4. O-O e6 {The most flexible move. We don't want to commit a knight to f6 too early, as then White might consider Ne5 !? without us being able to trade it off or push it back.} (4... Nd7 {This should be avoided if White doesn't play c4 immediately.} 5. d3 Ngf6 6. c4 $1 {The problem is that in case we trade on c4 our knight would be much better on c6 than d7 .}) 5. d3 Nf6 6. Nbd2 {Going for a King's Indian Attack style of play.} Bc5 {This is a somewhat provocative move.} 7. c3 {In practical play this has been equally common, but it's rather innocent.} O-O 8. b4 Be7 {Next we will play ... c5 with a very solid position. With all 32 pieces on the board, anything can happen!} *

