1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 b6 3. Bg2 {White can also try to play without c4 , or delay c4 until later on.} Bb7 4. O-O e6 {The most flexible move. We don't want to commit a knight to f6 too early, as then White might consider Ne5 !? without us being able to trade it off or push it back.} (4... Nd7 {This should be avoided if White doesn't play c4 immediately.} 5. d3 Ngf6 6. c4 $1 {The problem is that in case we trade on c4 our knight would be much better on c6 than d7 .}) 5. d3 Nf6 6. Nbd2 {Going for a King's Indian Attack style of play.} Bc5 {This is a somewhat provocative move.} 7. e4 dxe4 8. Ng5 (8. dxe4 {This is the typical way for White to play, but with the bishop on c5 it no longer works.} Nxe4 9. Ne5 Nxf2 $1 {This is the difference. White loses a lot of material.}) 8... Nc6 {Another move that isn't strictly necessary, but makes sense. We block the long diagonal and take control over the d4 -square.} 9. Ngxe4 Nxe4 10. Nxe4 Be7 11. c3 {This is the move that made me not recommend 6... Bc5 as my main recommendation. White wants to play d4 next, after which our c6 -knight looks a bit strange.} f5 {Not strictly necessary, but looks reasonable.} (11... O-O 12. d4 Qd7 13. Bf4 Rae8 {Intending ... Nd8 !? to push ... f5 and trade the light squared bishops. It's provocative and rather interesting, but unfortunately not entirely equal.}) 12. Ng5 (12. Nd2 Qxd3 {Gives White some compensation, but not for more than equality.}) 12... Bxg5 13. Qh5+ g6 14. Qxg5 Qxg5 15. Bxg5 h6 {Forcing the bishop to choose.} 16. Bf6 (16. Be3 O-O-O {This is rather nice for Black. Our pieces are very active.}) 16... O-O 17. Bxc6 Bxc6 18. Be5 Rf7 {Perhaps White is a very tiny bit better, but basically Black should be fine.} *

