1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 b6 3. Bg2 Bb7 4. O-O e6 {Move orders are incredibly important. We need to delay ... Nd7 to keep the d-file open, and we need to delay ... Nf6 so that Ne5 is no concern.} 5. d3 (5. b3 Nf6 6. Bb2 Be7 {Without e3 , it's suboptimal to play our usual setup with Bd6 . As mentioned many times, it's still possible, but not 100% equalizing.} 7. c4 O-O 8. cxd5 Nxd5 $1 {We always take with a piece on d5 if White hasn't comitted to e3 yet.} 9. d4 Nd7 10. Re1 c5 11. e4 N5f6 12. Nc3 cxd4 13. Nxd4 {Important position! We need to react quickly, as if White consolidates their space advantage they are just better.} Bc5 $1 14. Re2 Ne5 $1 {Creating enough counterplay to maintain the balance.}) 5... Nf6 6. Nbd2 (6. c4 dxc4 7. dxc4 Qxd1 8. Rxd1 Bd6 9. Nc3 a6 {Such endings are usually pleasant. Remember that the king most likely belongs on e7 , closer to the action.}) 6... Nbd7 7. e4 dxe4 8. dxe4 e5 {We lose some time like this, but often our bishop on f8 becomes stronger than the one on g2 , which compensates for the tempo loss.} *

