1. b3 d5 2. Bb2 Nf6 {Again, developing the bishop makes a lot of sense, and following my repertoire with Bg4 is a perfectly viable alternative also for QGD-players. Stylistically I still believe the most reasonable thing though is to go for the same setup as we've done numerous times before.} 3. Nf3 (3. e3 e6 4. g4 {Such nonsense is popular online.} h6 5. h4 Nc6 $1 {Just very good for Black.}) 3... e6 4. c4 {This is the only tricky move order White can try. The idea is to not commit to e3 yet, keeping the option of g3 .} ({•} 4. e3 {Will transpose to the c4 e6 Nf3 d5 e3 chapter as soon as White plays c4 .}) ({•} 4. g3 c5 $1 {A good moment for this. White would really like to play c4 and cxd5 now, but as soon as c4 is played, we can play ... d4 . Playing with ... b6 is still possible here, but as White didn't play e3 yet, they would have a slightly better version. As we've discussed previously, though, this is still acceptable for Black if you prefer it for simplicity.} 5. Bg2 Nc6) 4... Bd6 {The most flexible move. We are being ready for both e3 and g3 .} (4... b6 {As mentioned many times, without e3 this is a slightly worse but still acceptable version for Black.} 5. g3 Bb7 6. Bg2 Bd6 7. O-O O-O {Transposes to Nf3} 8. cxd5 {g3 b6 Bg2 Bb7 O-O e6 b3 Nf6 Bb2 Bd6 c4 O-O , starting here .}) 5. g3 (5. e3 O-O 6. Nc3 a6 {As usual, this is necessary when White is 'threatening' Nb5 .} 7. d4 b6 {With the usual kind of play. This is very likely to transpose to the Magnus Queen's Gambit, but again, it's not really a concern even if you don't follow that course. The play is very similar to the c4 e6 Nf3} 8. cxd5 {e3 chapter and if you are familiar with that you will do well here, too.}) 5... c5 {The ambitious choice. We want to take over the center with ... d4 . This is one of the lines I advice you to study carefully in the main chapter.} 6. cxd5 {The most natural choice and by far most common move.} exd5 7. Bg2 O-O 8. d4 cxd4 {We always take on d4 .} 9. Nxd4 Nc6 {With a typical IQP-position. White is securely blockading the d-pawn, but we have very active piece play and potential for play both in the center and on the kingside.} *

