1. b3 d5 2. Bb2 Nf6 {Following the Slav vs 1. b3 Chapter and playing 2... Bg4 also makes sense for Queen's Gambit players, because it is immediately a comfortable equality and all lines are independent of a real Slav. Indeed, it is what I always did myself, even before adding the Slav to my repertoire. At the same time it's also reasonable to want to keep also 1. b3 into more 'real' QGD-territories which is also the philosophy of this LTR.} 3. e3 e6 4. g4 {This is an overly aggressive option, much in the spirit of the ' b3 -Cowboys'. But when playing fundamentally sound classical chess, we rarely have to worry about such over-aggressive attempts. Still, it's decently popular, especially online, so it makes sense to know the cleanest refutation.} ({•} 4. Nf3 Bd6 5. d4 {is very likely to transpose to the 2. Nf3 sidelines chapter of the Magnus Queen’s Gambit, for instance, after Bd3 Bb7} O-O {O-O with a direct transposition .}) ({•} 4. Nf3 Bd6 5. c4 {would then transpose to} O-O {, starting here .}) 4... h6 {Preventing g5 .} 5. h4 {White could try to revert to more normal play, but that would mean the g4 -pawn is simply misplaced. Instead, the Cowboys usually goes all out like this.} Nc6 {An unusual but very strong reply, adhering to the old rule that flank attacks should be met by play in the center. Now we are intending to push ... e5 .} 6. Bb5 e5 {Still works very well.} 7. Bxe5 Bxg4 {Normally White would like to play Be2 now, but here it would drop the e5 -bishop.} *

