1. b3 d5 2. Bb2 Nf6 {Following the Slav vs 1. b3 Chapter and playing 2... Bg4 also makes sense for Queen's Gambit players, because it is immediately a comfortable equality and all lines are independent of a real Slav. Indeed, it is what I always did myself, even before adding the Slav to my repertoire. At the same time it's also reasonable to want to keep also 1. b3 into more 'real' QGD-territories which is also the philosophy of this LTR.} 3. Nf3 e6 ({So we decide to not develop our bishop here either. Most likely, this will now transpose to the c4} 3... e6 {Nf3 d5} 4. e3 {, starting here , but there are a couple of independent lines. The most important thing to note is that White haven't yet committed to playing e2 - e3 . That always means we have to take g3 into account, and be prepared for that.}) 4. g3 {This move order is inaccurate, as it lets us grab the center in a good way.} c5 {Usually I recommend refraining from ... c5 this early, but here it's simply too good not to be played. Now c4 can always be met by ... d4 , which would leave the b2 -bishop out of the game.} 5. c4 d4 {This is simply good for Black. There are lines in the Reti where White allows this push, but then Black has always wasted time in different ways. Now we simply play ... Nc6 followed by ... e5 , and the bishop on b2 is entirely dead.} *

