1. b3 d5 2. Bb2 Nf6 {Following the Slav vs 1. b3 Chapter and playing 2... Bg4 also makes sense for Queen's Gambit players, because it is immediately a comfortable equality and all lines are independent of a real Slav. Indeed, it is what I always did myself, even before adding the Slav to my repertoire. At the same time it's also reasonable to want to keep also 1. b3 into more 'real' QGD-territories which is also the philosophy of this LTR.} 3. Nf3 e6 ({So we decide to not develop our bishop here either. Most likely, this will now transpose to the c4} 3... e6 {Nf3 d5} 4. e3 {, starting here , but there are a couple of independent lines. The most important thing to note is that White haven't yet committed to playing e2 - e3 . That always means we have to take g3 into account, and be prepared for that.}) 4. g3 {This move order is inaccurate, as it lets us grab the center in a good way.} c5 {Usually I recommend refraining from ... c5 this early, but here it's simply too good not to be played. Now c4 can always be met by ... d4 , which would leave the b2 -bishop out of the game.} 5. Bg2 Nc6 6. d4 Bd6 7. c4 ({The only independent option. If White castles, it transposes to} 7. O-O {Bd6} cxd4 {O-O .}) 7... dxc4 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Qxd8+ {This is the difference without castling included! We can’t recapture with the rook.} Nxd8 {An important move! Normally, I would say recapturing with the king makes more sense, but here we have a specific use for the d8 -knight.} 10. O-O {The usual way White plays in these situations. White wants to give up a pawn to create a queenside initiative.} cxb3 11. axb3 b6 {This shows why we need our knight on d8 . If White tries anything on the long diagonal, we simply play …Bb7 and our knight protects the bishop! This means that the eternal problem of the Catalan, the c8 -bishop, is now solved. White still has enough compensation to win back the pawn, but then it will just be equal.} *

