1. b3 d5 2. Bb2 Nf6 {Following the Slav vs 1. b3 Chapter and playing 2... Bg4 also makes sense for Queen's Gambit players, because it is immediately a comfortable equality and all lines are independent of a real Slav. Indeed, it is what I always did myself, even before adding the Slav to my repertoire. At the same time it's also reasonable to want to keep also 1. b3 into more 'real' QGD-territories which is also the philosophy of this LTR.} 3. Nf3 e6 ({So we decide to not develop our bishop here either. Most likely, this will now transpose to the c4} 3... e6 {Nf3 d5} 4. e3 {, starting here , but there are a couple of independent lines. The most important thing to note is that White haven't yet committed to playing e2 - e3 . That always means we have to take g3 into account, and be prepared for that.}) 4. g3 {This move order is inaccurate, as it lets us grab the center in a good way.} c5 {Usually I recommend refraining from ... c5 this early, but here it's simply too good not to be played. Now c4 can always be met by ... d4 , which would leave the b2 -bishop out of the game.} 5. Bg2 Nc6 6. O-O Bd6 {We place the bishop here in order to threaten ... e5 . This basically forces White to play d4 .} 7. d4 {Otherwise, we take over the center with ... e5 .} O-O 8. dxc5 (8. c4 dxc4 9. dxc5 Bxc5 {transposes.}) 8... Bxc5 9. c4 {White has to act quickly, otherwise we will take over the center.} dxc4 {We are happy to trade queens, especially if it means settling White with a weak pawn on c4 .} 10. Qc1 ({This is cunning. It looks similar to} 10. Qc2 {, but White has an extra option.}) 10... Qe7 11. Nbd2 {The idea. The reason the queen is on c1 instead of c2 is that cxb3 now doesn't come with tempo} e5 ({Luckily for us, this still works well. Just remember to avoid} 11... cxb3 12. Bxf6 gxf6 13. Ne4 $1 {and Black is lost.}) 12. Nxc4 e4 {We have to be very careful with such advances, as the pawn often just ends up weak or even immediately falling. Here it's all under control, though.} 13. Bxf6 ({The critical move.} 13. Nfd2 Bd4 {Prevents Bxf6 and gives us a great position.}) 13... Qxf6 14. Nfd2 Nd4 {Very important! White won't be able to pick up the e4 -pawn in a good way.} 15. Nxe4 Nxe2+ {Now follows a forced line.} 16. Kh1 Nxc1 17. Nxf6+ gxf6 18. Raxc1 Rb8 {The last important move. Now we are ready to play ... b6 next, after which everything is fine. The minor pawn structure deficiency is compensated for by the bishop pair.} *

