ransposition yet, as we have placed our bishop on d6 a bit earlier than usual.} O-O (5... b6 {This does not exactly transpose, unfortunately.} 6. Nc3 {Now White is 'threatening' cxd5 followed by Nb5 , which we usually don't allow.} a6 {The most logical choice.} 7. g3 {White changes track. It's no disaster, but when allowing this in the other situations, the pawn was always still back on a7 .} ({In those lines, for instance c4 e6 Nf3} 7. cxd5 {e3 Nf6 b3 b6 Bb2} Bb7 8. g3 {Bd6 we later played ... a7 - a5 in one move. So most likely we will be one or at minimum half a tempo down to that. Still, it's not a huge deal, but it's enough for me not being able to recommend it with a clear conscience.}) (7. g4 $5 {This is another option where I don't fell entirely confident, having played such slow moves as ... a6 and ... b6 .})) 6. Nc3 a6 {Our usual choice against Nc3 , especially if White hasn't wasted time with g3 yet. Now White has a few different interesting option to avoid transposition.} 7. g4 {This looks like coffeehouse chess, but it was tried recently in the high-level encounter Blübaum-Bartel. In general, the ideas of early g4 have gotten very popular in recent years, and we should definitely treat it seriously.} b5 {I really enjoy such moves. We are not going for any passive defending, but instead fight hard for the initiative!} 8. g5 Ne4 9. cxd5 (9. Nxe4 $2 dxe4 {would leave the g5 -pawn hanging.}) 9... exd5 10. Nxd5 {Again, such is too greedy for White.} Bb7 11. Nc3 Nxg5 {Even now it's not necessary to take, but with the long diagonal open it makes sense. White is struggling to equalize.} *

