ransposition yet, as we have placed our bishop on d6 a bit earlier than usual.} O-O (5... b6 {This does not exactly transpose, unfortunately.} 6. Nc3 {Now White is 'threatening' cxd5 followed by Nb5 , which we usually don't allow.} a6 {The most logical choice.} 7. g3 {White changes track. It's no disaster, but when allowing this in the other situations, the pawn was always still back on a7 .} ({In those lines, for instance c4 e6 Nf3} 7. cxd5 {e3 Nf6 b3 b6 Bb2} Bb7 8. g3 {Bd6 we later played ... a7 - a5 in one move. So most likely we will be one or at minimum half a tempo down to that. Still, it's not a huge deal, but it's enough for me not being able to recommend it with a clear conscience.}) (7. g4 $5 {This is another option where I don't fell entirely confident, having played such slow moves as ... a6 and ... b6 .})) 6. Nc3 a6 {Our usual choice against Nc3 , especially if White hasn't wasted time with g3 yet. Now White has a few different interesting option to avoid transposition.} 7. g4 {This looks like coffeehouse chess, but it was tried recently in the high-level encounter Blübaum-Bartel. In general, the ideas of early g4 have gotten very popular in recent years, and we should definitely treat it seriously.} b5 {I really enjoy such moves. We are not going for any passive defending, but instead fight hard for the initiative!} 8. g5 Ne4 9. Qc2 {This is how White usually plays these positions. They are ready to castle long later, while keeping decent attacking prospects on the kingside.} Bb7 10. Bd3 f5 {This is an important idea in these positions.} 11. gxf6 Qxf6 12. Nxe4 Qxf3 {Importantly, the rook is hanging on h1 now.} 13. Rg1 g6 {Simply defending against Rxg7 .} 14. cxd5 Bxd5 15. Qc3 {The only hope for White, but we can easily stop the threats.} e5 {Our attack is much stronger than White's. The key point is that our queen prevents White from castling long.} *

