[Round "?"]
[White "�️16) Nimzo-Larsen: 1.b3"]
[Black "3.Nf3 e6 4.c4 with 5.e3 #6"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "A13"]
[PlyCount "24"]

1. b3 d5 2. Bb2 Nf6 {Following the Slav vs 1. b3 Chapter and playing 2... Bg4 also makes sense for Queen's Gambit players, because it is immediately a comfortable equality and all lines are independent of a real Slav. Indeed, it is what I always did myself, even before adding the Slav to my repertoire. At the same time it's also reasonable to want to keep also 1. b3 into more 'real' QGD-territories which is also the philosophy of this LTR.} 3. Nf3 e6 ({So we decide to not develop our bishop here either. Most likely, this will now transpose to the c4} 3... e6 {Nf3 d5} 4. e3 {, starting here , but there are a couple of independent lines. The most important thing to note is that White haven't yet committed to playing e2 - e3 . That always means we have to take g3 into account, and be prepared for that.}) 4. c4 {The best move. White keeps flexible between e3 and g3 .} (4. e3 {Another transpositional move order.} b6 {A good rule of thumb us that after e3 , we can always play ... b6 . Generally, g3 -setups are the most critical against ... b6 . Here, White can still do it, but then the move e3 will be a waste.}) 4... Bd6 {White did not yet commit to playing e3 , which means that it's not as good for us to play ... b6 . As usual, we could have played 4... c5 and enter some more theoretical and concrete lines, but I prefer to keep the game independent. We place the bishop on d6 , as it is part of our ... b6 -setup anyway, so we are still ready for White going both e3 and g3 .} (4... b6 {Not the most accurate move, but if you are looking for simplicity then always going for this setup is possible. It's very likely to transpose to Nf3 d5 g3 b6 Bg2 Bb7 O-O e6 b3 Nf6 Bb2 Bd6 . White is a little bit better, but it's definitely playable. You can see the line here .} 5. g3 {The critical move against b6-setups. Other moves would also transpose.} Bb7 6. Bg2 Bd6 7. O-O O-O {transposes to Nf3} 8. cxd5 {g3 b6 Bg2 Bb7 O-O e6 b3 Nf6 Bb2 Bd6 c4 O-O , here .}) 5. e3 {This is not a direct transposition yet, as we have placed our bishop on d6 a bit earlier than usual.} O-O (5... b6 {This does not exactly transpose, unfortunately.} 6. Nc3 {Now White is 'threatening' cxd5 followed by Nb5 , which we usually don't allow.} a6 {The most logical choice.} 7. g3 {White changes track. It's no disaster, but when allowing this in the other situations, the pawn was always still back on a7 .} ({In those lines, for instance c4 e6 Nf3} 7. cxd5 {e3 Nf6 b3 b6 Bb2} Bb7 8. g3 {Bd6 we later played ... a7 - a5 in one move. So most likely we will be one or at minimum half a tempo down to that. Still, it's not a huge deal, but it's enough for me not being able to recommend it with a clear conscience.}) (7. g4 $5 {This is another option where I don't fell entirely confident, having played such slow moves as ... a6 and ... b6 .})) 6. Nc3 a6 {Our usual choice against Nc3 , especially if White hasn't wasted time with g3 yet. Now White has a few different interesting option to avoid transposition.} 7. Be2 b6 {Continuing our setup.} 8. g4 {This makes some sense here as well, especially as ... b5 now would lose a tempo. On the other hand, 7. Be2 is not the most active move in regard to the kingside attack.} Bb7 {... b5 would be a bit slow after having already played ... b6 , so instead we stick to a central strategy. The important thing is to always be able to meet g5 with ... Ne4 . Apart from that, we mainly want to centralize our pieces and hopefully one day push ... e5 .} 9. Rg1 Nbd7 10. Qc2 Ne4 {This is a good point to remember. After Qc2 , White is intending O-O-O , therefore we meet it with ... Ne4 , so that the f2 -pawn is hanging.} 11. g5 {This could also have been played earlier, but it's actually not that great for White. It takes away the g5 -square for the knight without really threatening anything in return.} Nxc3 {It might look odd to let White's queen onto the long diagonal, but we are ready to block it off.} 12. Qxc3 e5 {The pawn on e5 will be very hard for White to get rid off and as long as it is there, it is almost impossible for White to create a real attack. As for ourselves, the most important thing is overprotecting the center, but long-term we want to get counterplay on the queenside. Either with the familiar ... b5 -sacrifice, or by just pushing the a-pawn up the board.} *

