ransposition yet, as we have placed our bishop on d6 a bit earlier than usual.} O-O (5... b6 {This does not exactly transpose, unfortunately.} 6. Nc3 {Now White is 'threatening' cxd5 followed by Nb5 , which we usually don't allow.} a6 {The most logical choice.} 7. g3 {White changes track. It's no disaster, but when allowing this in the other situations, the pawn was always still back on a7 .} ({In those lines, for instance c4 e6 Nf3} 7. cxd5 {e3 Nf6 b3 b6 Bb2} Bb7 8. g3 {Bd6 we later played ... a7 - a5 in one move. So most likely we will be one or at minimum half a tempo down to that. Still, it's not a huge deal, but it's enough for me not being able to recommend it with a clear conscience.}) (7. g4 $5 {This is another option where I don't fell entirely confident, having played such slow moves as ... a6 and ... b6 .})) 6. Nc3 a6 {Our usual choice against Nc3 , especially if White hasn't wasted time with g3 yet. Now White has a few different interesting option to avoid transposition.} 7. Be2 b6 {Continuing our setup.} 8. g4 {This makes some sense here as well, especially as ... b5 now would lose a tempo. On the other hand, 7. Be2 is not the most active move in regard to the kingside attack.} Bb7 {... b5 would be a bit slow after having already played ... b6 , so instead we stick to a central strategy. The important thing is to always be able to meet g5 with ... Ne4 . Apart from that, we mainly want to centralize our pieces and hopefully one day push ... e5 .} 9. Rg1 Nbd7 10. Qc2 Ne4 {This is a good point to remember. After Qc2 , White is intending O-O-O , therefore we meet it with ... Ne4 , so that the f2 -pawn is hanging.} 11. cxd5 {A good moment for this trade, as it prevents us from playing ... e5 .} exd5 12. g5 {Creating a dangerous threat.} ({•} 12. d3 {Too early.} Ng5 $1 {Now it will be hard for White to advance on the kingside.}) ({•} 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Qc3 Nf6 {Is completely safe for us. ... Re8 followed by ... Be7 will come next.}) 12... Re8 {Again overprotecting the e5 -square. This time we don't have an e-pawn, but we can still put a piece there!} 13. h4 (13. Nxe4 dxe4 14. Qc3 Ne5 {is the reason we need the rook on e8 . This is a disaster for White as all the attack disappears.}) 13... Ne5 {With such nice central control, we don't need to worry too much about White's kingside attack. White should realize this and start to go for trades in the center, after which the position is just equal.} *

