Rc8 would let White develop exactly how they want, with some hopes for a small edge.} 11. bxc4 c5 {The idea is to put pressure on the d4 - and c4 -pawns.} 12. d5 {Definitely the critical move, and always the first one should look out for when giving up the center with ... dxc4 .} exd5 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. cxd5 b5 {Gaining queenside space. A very interesting and sharp middlegame position has arisen. If White is able to push e4 - e5 they would be doing very well, but we won't allow that. In the meantime we want to push ... c4 , and then try to prepare ... c3 which, if allowed, would cut out the bishop on b2 entirely.} 15. Qc2 {This is very precise. White is keeping the option of attacking our pawn chain with a4 as well.} Rc8 {Prophylaxis against a4 .} 16. a4 {Doesn't work, but on other moves we can go back to the ... Re8 -plan and look to push ... c4 later on.} b4 17. Nd2 {This would be strategically very good for White if the knight reaches c4 , but it won't.} c4 {Just winning, as the pawn can't be taken.} *

