ransposition yet, as we have placed our bishop on d6 a bit earlier than usual.} O-O (5... b6 {This does not exactly transpose, unfortunately.} 6. Nc3 {Now White is 'threatening' cxd5 followed by Nb5 , which we usually don't allow.} a6 {The most logical choice.} 7. g3 {White changes track. It's no disaster, but when allowing this in the other situations, the pawn was always still back on a7 .} ({In those lines, for instance c4 e6 Nf3} 7. cxd5 {e3 Nf6 b3 b6 Bb2} Bb7 8. g3 {Bd6 we later played ... a7 - a5 in one move. So most likely we will be one or at minimum half a tempo down to that. Still, it's not a huge deal, but it's enough for me not being able to recommend it with a clear conscience.}) (7. g4 $5 {This is another option where I don't fell entirely confident, having played such slow moves as ... a6 and ... b6 .})) 6. Nc3 a6 {Our usual choice against Nc3 , especially if White hasn't wasted time with g3 yet. Now White has a few different interesting option to avoid transposition.} 7. d4 b6 {This is very likely to transpose to The Magnus Queen's Gambit , chapter 11, starting from here .} 8. g3 {The only independent option. Now we have to be careful. If we just develop lazily, White will get their dream version. The way we avoid it is to go for a quick ... dxc4 followed by ... c5 , immediately attacking White's center. That would not have been possible had White still had their pawn back on d2 .} (8. Bd3 Bb7 9. O-O Nbd7 {Transposes to d4} 10. cxd5 {c4 e6 Nf3 a6 e3 Nf6 Nc3 Nbd7 b3 b6 Bd3 Bb7 O-O Bd6 Bb2 O-O , analyzed in detail in The Magnus Queen's Gambit , chapter 11, 3. Nf3 4th Move Sidelines, starting here .}) 8... Bb7 {Move orders don't matter too much as long as we play ... dxc4 over the next few moves.} 9. Bg2 {If White ever takes on d5 , we transpose back to the 1. c4  e6 2. Nf3  d5 3. e3 chapter.} Nbd7 10. O-O (10. cxd5 exd5 {will eventually transpose to the c4 e6 Nf3 d5 e3 chapter .}) 10... dxc4 {This is the moment. Again, slower moves like ... Re8 or ... Rc8 would let White develop exactly how they want, with some hopes for a small edge.} 11. bxc4 c5 {The idea is to put pressure on the d4 - and c4 -pawns.} 12. d5 {Definitely the critical move, and always the first one should look out for when giving up the center with ... dxc4 .} exd5 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. cxd5 b5 {Gaining queenside space. A very interesting and sharp middlegame position has arisen. If White is able to push e4 - e5 they would be doing very well, but we won't allow that. In the meantime we want to push ... c4 , and then try to prepare ... c3 which, if allowed, would cut out the bishop on b2 entirely.} 15. e4 {The most natural.} Re8 16. Re1 {It looks like White is threatening e5 , but we are just in time.} c4 17. e5 Bb4 {An excellent square. Now we can follow up with ... c3 if we want, but also ... Nc5 - d3 is still relevant.} 18. Qd4 {A well cultured player would immediately ask the question of what happens after this typical Exchange sacrifice.} Bc5 {We don't accept it!} 19. Qg4 Bxd5 20. Ng5 {The best move. Now we have to be very careful.} (20. e6 $2 Nf6 {Defends against the mate while retaining an extra pawn.}) 20... Be6 {The key! Instead of winning an exchange, we are sacrificing one. Tigran Petrosian would have been proud.} (20... Bxg2 21. e6 {would be winning for White.}) 21. Nxe6 fxe6 22. Bxa8 Qxa8 {We have one pawn for the exchange, but the main thing is our very dangerous queenside pawns. Just pushing ... b4 and ... c3 is a simple and strong long-term plan} *

