the most critical move, and also the move Adhiban recommends. As we have seen numerous times, the bishop is simply a bit better on g2 than on e2 / d3 .} c5 {White played g3 without having had to play e3 , which is a big signal for us to be careful. Our usual setup with ... b6 will not equalize. The main downside of g3 compared to e3 is that it does less for the immediate control over the center, which makes it logical for us to play ... c5 .} 6. cxd5 {Far and away the most natural choice. White will settle us with an isolated d-pawn.} exd5 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 {Now castling would transpose to our mainline, but White's move order gives us an extra possibility.} Ne4 {Immediately going for the attack!} 9. Nc3 (9. a3 Be5 {also gives us nice counterplay.}) 9... Bb4 10. Rc1 Qf6 {This is the idea! White lacks one move to castle here.} 11. f3 {Only move, but it's ugly.} Nxc3 12. Bxc3 Bxc3+ 13. Rxc3 Nc6 {Due to the weird f3 -move, we have good counterplay.} *

