the most critical move, and also the move Adhiban recommends. As we have seen numerous times, the bishop is simply a bit better on g2 than on e2 / d3 .} c5 {White played g3 without having had to play e3 , which is a big signal for us to be careful. Our usual setup with ... b6 will not equalize. The main downside of g3 compared to e3 is that it does less for the immediate control over the center, which makes it logical for us to play ... c5 .} 6. cxd5 {Far and away the most natural choice. White will settle us with an isolated d-pawn.} exd5 7. Bg2 O-O (7... d4 {is a more forcing solution, but I like to keep it simple. We are not afraid of the potential isolated d-pawn.}) 8. d4 (8. O-O Nc6 9. d4 {Without this move, White is not really getting anywhere.} cxd4 10. Nxd4 Re8 {transposes to the line we're studying.}) 8... cxd4 {We always take on d4 . The reason is that the knight is a bit better on f3 than d4 (as the bishop on b2 is kept open) and our bishop is a bit better on d6 , as it often wants to go to e5 later on.} 9. Nxd4 Nc6 {Now we have reached a sort of Tarrasch style position. For followers of The Magnus Queen's Gambit , the position will be very similar to the 3. Nf3 , 4. Nbd2 (Lazy Option), chapter 10b , where a very, very similar position is discussed. As usual, the comparison to that course works out well for us, as ... a6 isn't really very useful in these positions. The one upside for White is that the knight is not on d2 yet, giving White the option of Nc3 instead.} 10. O-O Re8 {Again the most flexible move is the best. The rook always belongs here, whereas the c8 -bishop is not yet sure where it wants go.} 11. Nf3 {This is a surprisingly interesting move. White wants to play Nc3 , but at the same time avoid our ... Nxd4 .} Bg4 12. Nc3 h5 {I like this a lot. Ever since Dubov reinvented the Tarrasch on the highest levels, pushing the h-pawn has become a standard idea in these positions. Here it looks like strange timing as White just put their knight on f3 , but with our bishop on g4 we are ready to take on f3 ant an appropriate moment.} 13. h3 {This is precisely what we are hoping for!} Bxf3 14. Bxf3 d4 15. Nb5 Be5 {With the pawn back on h2 I would be highly sceptical, but after h3 it's a completely different matter. Next our ... h4 will bring a serious attack!} *

