 , but with our bishop on g4 we are ready to take on f3 ant an appropriate moment.} 13. Nb5 (13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. Qxd5 Rxe2 {is just equal.}) 13... Bxf3 ({Simplest. The more complicated} 13... h4 $5 {is also interesting.}) 14. Bxf3 Be5 {The point. Now we are trading the strong b2 -bishop, after which we have no problems whatsoever.} (14... Be5 {Rxe5} 15. Nd4 {This is the most natural continuation for White.} Qd6 (15... Qb6 {followed by just swapping on d4 is equal, but this is more interesting.}) 16. Rc1 {Rae8 e3} h4 {All our pieces are well-placed and slowly our kingside initiative is beginning to tell.}) *

