1. b3 d5 2. Bb2 Nf6 {Following the Slav vs 1. b3 Chapter and playing 2... Bg4 also makes sense for Queen's Gambit players, because it is immediately a comfortable equality and all lines are independent of a real Slav. Indeed, it is what I always did myself, even before adding the Slav to my repertoire. At the same time it's also reasonable to want to keep also 1. b3 into more 'real' QGD-territories which is also the philosophy of this LTR.} 3. Nf3 e6 ({So we decide to not develop our bishop here either. Most likely, this will now transpose to the c4} 3... e6 {Nf3 d5} 4. e3 {, starting here , but there are a couple of independent lines. The most important thing to note is that White haven't yet committed to playing e2 - e3 . That always means we have to take g3 into account, and be prepared for that.}) 4. c4 {The best move. White keeps flexible between e3 and g3 .} (4. e3 {Another transpositional move order.} b6 {A good rule of thumb us that after e3 , we can always play ... b6 . Generally, g3 -setups are the most critical against ... b6 . Here, White can still do it, but then the move e3 will be a waste.}) 4... Bd6 {White did not yet commit to playing e3 , which means that it's not as good for us to play ... b6 . As usual, we could have played 4... c5 and enter some more theoretical and concrete lines, but I prefer to keep the game independent. We place the bishop on d6 , as it is part of our ... b6 -setup anyway, so we are still ready for White going both e3 and g3 .} (4... b6 {Not the most accurate move, but if you are looking for simplicity then always going for this setup is possible. It's very likely to transpose to Nf3 d5 g3 b6 Bg2 Bb7 O-O e6 b3 Nf6 Bb2 Bd6 . White is a little bit better, but it's definitely playable. You can see the line here .} 5. g3 {The critical move against b6-setups. Other moves would also transpose.} Bb7 6. Bg2 Bd6 7. O-O O-O {transposes to Nf3} 8. cxd5 {g3 b6 Bg2 Bb7 O-O e6 b3 Nf6 Bb2 Bd6 c4 O-O , here .}) 5. g3 {This is in my opinion the most critical move, and also the move Adhiban recommends. As we have seen numerous times, the bishop is simply a bit better on g2 than on e2 / d3 .} c5 {White played g3 without having had to play e3 , which is a big signal for us to be careful. Our usual setup with ... b6 will not equalize. The main downside of g3 compared to e3 is that it does less for the immediate control over the center, which makes it logical for us to play ... c5 .} 6. cxd5 {Far and away the most natural choice. White will settle us with an isolated d-pawn.} exd5 7. Bg2 O-O (7... d4 {is a more forcing solution, but I like to keep it simple. We are not afraid of the potential isolated d-pawn.}) 8. d4 (8. O-O Nc6 9. d4 {Without this move, White is not really getting anywhere.} cxd4 10. Nxd4 Re8 {transposes to the line we're studying.}) 8... cxd4 {We always take on d4 . The reason is that the knight is a bit better on f3 than d4 (as the bishop on b2 is kept open) and our bishop is a bit better on d6 , as it often wants to go to e5 later on.} 9. Nxd4 Nc6 {Now we have reached a sort of Tarrasch style position. For followers of The Magnus Queen's Gambit , the position will be very similar to the 3. Nf3 , 4. Nbd2 (Lazy Option), chapter 10b , where a very, very similar position is discussed. As usual, the comparison to that course works out well for us, as ... a6 isn't really very useful in these positions. The one upside for White is that the knight is not on d2 yet, giving White the option of Nc3 instead.} 10. O-O Re8 {Again the most flexible move is the best. The rook always belongs here, whereas the c8 -bishop is not yet sure where it wants go.} 11. Nc3 {The most natural move, especially as we discussed that having the knight still on b1 is one of White's upsides.} Bg4 {If you want to keep more pieces on the board, this is perfectly possible.} 12. h3 Bh5 13. Rc1 Qd7 {With the usual sort of Tarrasch style position.} *

