1. b3 d5 2. Bb2 Nf6 3. Nf3 e6 4. c4 (4. g3 c5 $1 {Again our usual setup with Bd6 , b6 etc works less well before White has played e3 .} 5. Bg2 Nc6 {With counterplay in the center.}) 4... Bd6 5. g3 c5 {By now, we are very familiar with the fact that we don't play ... b6 before e3 . We play ... c5 with the aim of pushing ... d4 , to make the b2 -bishop bad.} 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Bg2 O-O 8. d4 cxd4 {We always take, to trick the knight away from f3 .} 9. Nxd4 Nc6 10. O-O Re8 11. Nc3 Nxd4 {A typical liquidating sequence.} (11... Bg4 $5 {Gives more play for both sides. Later on, ... h5 - h4 is a typical idea to generate counterplay.}) 12. Qxd4 Be5 13. Qd2 Bxc3 14. Bxc3 Ne4 {Trading off enough pieces to equalize. The e2 -pawn is often hanging in the end.} *

