1. c4 ({•} 1. g3 d5 2. Bg2 e5 {Against this, I don't see any reason to refrain from the 1. f4 , 1. b4 , and Other Sidelines chapter. My recommendation there fits well with both QGD and Slav repertoires.}) ({•} 1. e3 d5 2. c4 e6 {This will eventually transpose to c4 e6} 3. Nf3 {d5 e3 analyzed in detail in chapter 11 , as White's knight really belongs to f3 .}) 1... e6 2. e4 {This is technically an option for White. While the Exchange French in general is at least as critical as for instance the Panov, the version with the pawn already on c4 certainly isn't. Black has very comfortable equality in numerous ways. I actually struggled a little bit choosing a setup here, but finally just went for natural developing moves.} (2. Nf3 d5 3. b3 {A slightly different move order. We could consider trying to transpose, but it's also tempting to punish White.} d4 $1 {This is now a bit too good not to be played. Basically White 'forgot' to trade on d5 in time. Now the bishop will end up out of the game on b2 , or the move b2 - b3 will be a full tempo wasted.}) 2... d5 3. exd5 exd5 4. d4 Bb4+ {This is one of the reasons the pawn shouldn't go to c4 this early in the Exchange.} 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. Nf3 O-O 7. Bd3 dxc4 8. Bxc4 Bg4 {There are a couple of ways for White to get just about enough counterplay for the structural weakness, but there is no doubt White is the one trying to equalize.} *

