1. c4 e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. b3 {This is another version of these setups, but a really bad one for White!} d4 {Usually we refrain from entering such Reversed Benoni style positions, but this is simply too good a version to pass out on.} 4. g3 Nc6 {Objectively ... c5 is also decent, but this is much simpler.} 5. Bg2 e5 {It's important not to delay this.} 6. O-O e4 7. Ne1 h5 {This is an idea worth remembering. We give a central pawn, but get a vicious kingside attack in return.} 8. Bxe4 h4 {Everything is comping with tempo, but the real problem for White is that the whole queenside is entirely unable to help with the defense.} *

