1. c4 e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. b3 {This is another version of these setups, but a really bad one for White!} d4 {Usually we refrain from entering such Reversed Benoni style positions, but this is simply too good a version to pass out on.} 4. g3 Nc6 {Objectively ... c5 is also decent, but this is much simpler.} 5. Bg2 e5 {It's important not to delay this.} 6. d3 {White has to stop e4 .} Bb4+ {The reason we must hurry with ... e5 . Such checks are very common practice in similar situations. Basically no matter which piece White blocks it with, it will be worse placed than it's original square.} 7. Nbd2 (7. Bd2 a5 $1 {Is similar. White don't want to trade on b4 , but otherwise the bishop is in the way on d2 .}) 7... a5 {A good follow-up, making sure White won't have a3 / b4 available.} 8. O-O Nf6 {The way the pieces are placed, White is struggling to get counterplay. I believe Black is already better.} *

