1. c4 e6 2. e4 {This leads to an Exchange French. In itself, the Exchange French has gotten a burst of popularity over the last couple of years, but here White has already committed to c4 , which makes a big difference.} d5 3. exd5 exd5 4. cxd5 Nf6 5. Bb5+ {This idea exists when Black plays ... c6 instead of ... e6 , but here it works less well as our bishop on f8 can get out immediately.} Nbd7 6. Nc3 Bd6 {We have a very pleasant position. The d5 -pawn will be recaptured eventually, after which White won't have a lot of counterplay to compensate for the isolated d-pawn.} *

