1. c4 e6 2. e4 {This leads to an Exchange French. In itself, the Exchange French has gotten a burst of popularity over the last couple of years, but here White has already committed to c4 , which makes a big difference.} d5 3. exd5 exd5 4. d4 Bb4+ {There are many different ways for Black to play, and basically all of them are completely fine. I honestly don't have a strong opinion which one is the best, but am at least confident that what I have chosen is simple enough.} 5. Nc3 (5. Bd2 {This would just trade more pieces, which is in our favor as we have the better structure.} Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 Nf6 {Intending ... O-O . I think we are already a little bit better.}) 5... Nf6 6. Nf3 O-O {Waiting for White to develop their bishop, so that we can take on c4 .} 7. Be2 (7. Bd3 {This is the same as Be2 .} dxc4 8. Bxc4 Nc6) 7... dxc4 {Settling White with the IQP.} 8. Bxc4 Bg4 {Playing for a blockade on the d5 -square also makes sense, but this looks like it poses some trickier questions for White.} 9. O-O Nc6 10. Be3 Qd6 {This is the one move we need to remember. The queen is well placed on d6 . It won't come under attack, and we are able to activate our a8 -rook next. There is also a concrete reason why d6 works well.} 11. a3 {Here both retreating and taking on c3 makes sense. Taking on c3 might sound strange, but we have very active pieces and still the better structure.} (11. Be2 {Avoids any issues with ... Bxf3 , but a bit passive, too passive to be posing any issues.} Rad8 {White's d4 -pawn is under pressure.}) 11... Ba5 {But this is also completely fine. The inclusion of a3 and Ba5 doesn't change much.} *

