1. c4 e6 2. e4 {This leads to an Exchange French. In itself, the Exchange French has gotten a burst of popularity over the last couple of years, but here White has already committed to c4 , which makes a big difference.} d5 3. exd5 exd5 4. d4 Bb4+ {There are many different ways for Black to play, and basically all of them are completely fine. I honestly don't have a strong opinion which one is the best, but am at least confident that what I have chosen is simple enough.} 5. Nc3 (5. Bd2 {This would just trade more pieces, which is in our favor as we have the better structure.} Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 Nf6 {Intending ... O-O . I think we are already a little bit better.}) 5... Nf6 6. Nf3 O-O {Waiting for White to develop their bishop, so that we can take on c4 .} 7. Be2 (7. Bd3 {This is the same as Be2 .} dxc4 8. Bxc4 Nc6) 7... dxc4 {Settling White with the IQP.} 8. Bxc4 Bg4 {Playing for a blockade on the d5 -square also makes sense, but this looks like it poses some trickier questions for White.} 9. O-O Nc6 10. Be3 Qd6 {This is the one move we need to remember. The queen is well placed on d6 . It won't come under attack, and we are able to activate our a8 -rook next. There is also a concrete reason why d6 works well.} 11. h3 ({The most natural, but it lets us show our idea.} 11. Rc1 Rad8 {is perfectly healthy for us.}) 11... Bxf3 12. Qxf3 Nxd4 {This is forced. After giving up the bishop, we have to act fast.} 13. Qxb7 {Otherwise, we are simply a pawn up.} Bxc3 14. bxc3 Rfb8 {This is the idea behind putting the queen on d6 - the queen on b7 has no good squares! Without this tactical idea we would be worse, but now it's all good. In my opinion, this is the only position you really need to remember against the Exchange French.} 15. Qa6 {The only available square.} Qxa6 16. Bxa6 Nc2 {The tactical justification of the entire operation. Now we trade off the bishop and settle White with a worse structure.} 17. Rad1 Nxe3 18. fxe3 Re8 {We have the better structure, but White's slightly more active pieces should give them enough play for a draw. Still, White having to play a few precise moves to make a draw is not a bad outcome of the opening for us!} *

