1. c4 e6 2. e4 {Mainly just a reminder that White has the option of going into an Exchange French, but with the pawn already on c4 this is much less scary.} d5 3. exd5 exd5 4. d4 Bb4+ {This check is the main reason White should refrain from an early c4 in the Exchange French.} 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. Nf3 O-O 7. Bd3 dxc4 {We always delay the capture until the bishop has moved from f1 .} 8. Bxc4 Nc6 9. O-O Bg4 10. Be3 Qd6 {Important square! This is the only thing to really remember in this complex. The remaining play is very logical; we want to play ... Rad8 and put pressure on the d4 -pawn.} 11. h3 Bxf3 12. Qxf3 Nxd4 13. Qxb7 {A typical tactical sequence for these lines.} Bxc3 14. bxc3 Rfb8 15. Qa6 Qxa6 16. Bxa6 Nc2 17. Rad1 Nxe3 18. fxe3 Re8 {The ending is equal, but with some potential for Black due to the weak White pawn structure.} *

