12. Nd2 {Black to play: find a plan!} a5 {Long term, making it harder for White to castle long, and creating weaknesses for White on the queenside no matter how they react.} (12... c6 {also a good solidifying move, with the idea of playing ... a5 next move.}) 13. Bg4 (13. a3 {The best try to keep control} c6 {Now it's very likely that the following line happens, which shows the strength of the a5 -move:} 14. Bg4 h6 $1 {Forcing the issue.} 15. gxh6 Rxh6 16. Nxg6 Nxg6 17. Qe2 Nf6 {Here White would really like to escape with the king.} 18. O-O-O {?} Qe7 $1 {Due to the weakness of the a3 -pawn, Black is clearly better.}) 13... a4 {With a very strong initiative on the dark squares.} ({Instead, the game continued with} 13... h6 $6 14. Nxg6 $1 Nxg6 15. gxh6 (15. Qf3 $1 {Shows why ... c6 was important to include earlier. Now White gains an important tempo.} c6 16. Bh5 {with certain counterplay.}) 15... Rxh6 16. Qe2 $6 (16. Bh5) 16... a4 $1 17. O-O-O axb3 18. axb3 Qe7 (18... Nf6 {with the idea of ... Qe7 /... Ba3 .}) 19. Nb1 (19. Bxd7+ $1 Kxd7 20. c4 $1 Ba3 21. Nb1 {Somehow, both kings are kind of weak now.}) 19... Kf8 20. Rdf1 Nf6 21. Nc3 $6 Ba3 22. Nb1 Bxb2+ 23. Kxb2 Nh4 (23... Qc5) 24. Rg3 Ne8 $1 {A beautiful way to bring the rook while keeping everything protected} 25. e4 d4 26. f4 Rha6 $1 27. fxe5 Ra1 $1 28. Rxf7+ Qxf7 29. Bf5 Qe7 {From the game Taimanov, Mark - Jussupow, Artur, URSS 1980.}) *

