17. Bxd4 {Black to play: find a good plan!} Bxd4 {Black should try to gain access to the c3 -knight for the knight, where it will be incredibly powerful.} (17... b5 18. Nb2 Ne4 {was even a better move order.}) 18. Rxd4 (18. exd4 $1 {Not nice but the lesser evil. This is why starting with 17... b5 is even stronger.}) 18... b5 19. Nb2 Ne4 {The c3 -square is often a serious weakness, also here.} (19... Qa3 $1 {The c3 -square can also be used for a rook!} 20. Bd3 g6 {It's hard for White to move at all due to the clumsy placement of the knight.}) 20. Bd3 Nc3 21. Qa1 Qa3 22. Rh4 (22. Nd1 {Still OK for White, but a very difficult move to play} Qxa2 (22... Nxa2 $4 23. Bb1) 23. Nxc3 Qxa1 24. Rxa1 Rxc3 25. Rxa6 Rxb3 26. Rb6 {White is holding}) 22... h6 {Already winning for Black! The knight on c3 vs the knight on b2 is simply enough for a decisive advantage!} 23. Bb1 (23. Nd1 Nxa2 24. Bb1 Qe7 $1) 23... Ne2+ (23... d4 24. exd4 Ne2+ 25. Kh1 Nxd4 26. Bd3 Nc2 {Definitely not necessary, but it shows how hopeless White's position is.} 27. Qb1 Nb4 {a2 is dropping and b3 soon thereafter.}) 24. Kh1 Nc1 {Funny, but not necessary.} 25. f4 Nxb3 26. Bh7+ Kxh7 27. Qb1+ f5 28. axb3 Qxb3 29. Qa1 Qxe3 30. Rh3 Qe2 31. Nd3 Rc7 32. Re1 Qd2 33. Rxe6 Rc3 34. Re7 Rdc8 35. Ne1 R8c7 36. Rxc7 Rxc7 37. Nd3 Rc3 38. Rg3 d4 39. Qb1 Qc2 40. Qf1 Rb3 41. Ne1 Rb1 42. h3 Qd2 43. Kh2 Qxe1 44. Qd3 Qh1# {Gunina, Valentina - Fridman, Daniel, Cappelle Online Blitz Open 2022.} *

