[PlyCount "40"]

{Black to play. How to grab the initiative?} 20. Bb1 Bb5 {Creating some tacticial possibilities, but mainly coming down to a beneficial trade.} 21. Re1 (21. Bd3 {The only move to keep it under control, but it's not easy to go for such a pawn sacrifice as White.} Qxe3+ 22. Qxe3 Rxe3 23. Bxb5 Rxc3 24. Nxc3 axb5 25. Rd1 {Unfortunately White is making a draw.}) 21... Bxe2 {The idea of the previous move. Now follows a typical scenario.} 22. Rxe2 d4 23. Rd3 dxe3 24. Rdxe3 Qc5 {White has a weak king. Additionally, the f6 -knight has a bit more potential than the b1 -bishop. If we put the pawn back on f2 , it would just be equal, but here it's a nightmare for White to defend with the eternally weak king.} 25. Kf1 Red8 26. Rd3 Rxd3 27. Qxd3 Nd5 {Still only slightly better, but highly unpleasant for White to play.} 28. Qd2 Nc3 29. Re1 b5 30. Qd7 (30. Bc2 b4 31. Bd3 {was a bit better than 30. Qd7 .}) 30... Ra7 (30... Rf8) 31. Qd8+ Kg7 32. Re8 Nxb1 33. Rg8+ Kh6 34. Qh4+ Qh5 35. Qe1 (35. Qd4 $1 Re7 36. Qg7+ Kg5 37. Rd8 {Very difficult to see} Nc3 {Somehow draw}) 35... Rd7 36. Qxb1 Qxh2 37. Qc1+ Kh5 38. Qc5+ f5 39. Rh8 Qh1+ {White resigned in the game Meszaros, Michal - Gurevich, Mikhail, Forni di Sopra 2011.} *

