14. Ne4 {White has sacrificed a pawn to establish a bind. How should Black react?} c5 {It's almost always worth it to give back a pawn like this, to liberate our position. Sometimes it's enough for an advantage and sometimes it's only equal, but the important thing is that Black can no longer ever be worse!} (14... Qb6 15. Rfc1 c5 {Similar, the same idea.}) 15. Nxc5 Qc7 16. Rfc1 Rfc8 {As Black I would be very optimistic in a game here, but it turns out White can still equalize by strong play.} 17. Bd4 Nb4 18. Qc3 Bxg2 19. Kxg2 (19. Qxb4 $1 {Surprisingly giving up the bishop pair is the way to equalize.} Bc6 {Usually one would think good for Black, but White has enough activity to keep the balance.} 20. Qa5) 19... Nc6 (19... Qc6+ 20. Kg1 a5 {Was another good option.}) 20. Na6 (20. Ne4 {With Nd6 coming soon White will equalize}) 20... Qd7 21. Bc5 Bxc5 22. Nxc5 Qd5+ 23. e4 Qxe5 24. Qxe5 Nxe5 25. Na6 (25. f4 Nc6 {White has some compensation, but it's still a pawn.}) 25... Rc6 26. Rxc6 Nxc6 27. Nc7 Rb8 28. Ra6 Nd4 29. Rxa7 g5 30. b4 g4 31. h3 h5 32. hxg4 hxg4 33. Na6 Rd8 34. Nc5 Nf3 35. Rd7 (35. Nd7 $1 Kg7 36. Kf1 Rh8 37. Ke2 Rh1 38. Nc5 {White is holding}) 35... Ra8 36. Rd1 Ra2 37. Nb3 e5 38. Nc5 Rb2 39. Nd3 Rb3 40. Kf1 f6 41. Ke2 Ra3 42. Rb1 Ra2+ 43. Rb2 Ra1 44. Ke3 Nd4 45. Kd2 Nf3+ 46. Ke3 Kf7 47. Rc2 Ra3 48. Rc5 Nd4 49. Rd5 Ra2 50. Rxd4 exd4+ 51. Kxd4 Rc2 52. Ke3 Rc3 53. Kd4 Rc4+ 54. Ke3 Ke6 55. Nf4+ Kd6 56. Nd3 Rc3 57. Kd4 Rb3 58. Ke3 f5 59. Kd4 fxe4 60. Kxe4 Rc3 61. Kd4 Rc4+ 62. Ke3 Kd5 63. Nf4+ Ke5 64. Nd3+ Kf5 65. f3 gxf3 66. Kxf3 Re4 67. Kf2 Kg4 {Sebenik, Matej - Hera, Imre Jr., Nova Gorica 2008.} *

