17. Qe2 {Black to play: what should be the plan?} Bg6 {With the idea of Bf6 , followed one day by the ... e5 push. Other moves are also OK, if they are played with similar ideas. We should focus our attention on the kingside.} ({•} 17... Bf6 {Equally natural and good.} 18. Nd2 Bxg2 19. Kxg2 e5 {Gives decent counterplay.}) ({•} 17... a4 $6 {Interesting strategic decision by Alekseenko, but doesn't work too well here. The knight will not stay on c4 for long.} 18. b4 Nb6 $6 19. c5 Nc4 20. Bc3 (20. Ne5 {This is the problem for Black, the beautiful knight gets traded off} Bxg2 21. Kxg2 Nxe5 22. dxe5 {The b2 -bishop is no longer an issue.}) 20... Bf6 21. Nd2 $6 (21. Ne5 $1 {Same idea as 20.Ne5.}) 21... Nxd2 22. Qxd2 Bxg2 23. Kxg2 e5 {Once we achieve this break, the position is very pleasant to play. It will end up similar to the Schneider-Roiz model game. The starting position was taken from the game Firouzja, Alireza - Alekseenko, Kirill, Titled Tuesday (January 2020).}) *

