20. Rd1 (20. Rc1 {More solid} g5 $5) {Black to play! Should we trade rooks?} 20... Rc8 {An important move! The c-file is generally more important than the d-file, as it's easier to cover the entry squares on the d-file (for instance, our knight on f6 easily covers d7 ). Still not much, but Black is definitely pressing. It's also the sort of position that can quickly get out of hand for White.} 21. Ne1 h6 {Once we've established control over the c-file, there is no rush.} 22. Rd4 b5 {Another sensible strategic idea. The idea is to establish a rook or knight on c3 later on.} (22... Rc1 {The game continuation.} 23. Rd8+ Kh7 24. Rd1 Rc7 25. Rd4 g5 $5 {Black is trying to increase the pressure little by little. Objectively it's still nothing special, but it's oh so easy to lose patience as White.} 26. Qf3 Qxf3 27. Nxf3 Kg7 28. Kg2 Rc1 (28... Nd5 $5 29. Nd2 Rc2 {Would have given some initiative.}) 29. Rc4 $2 {Finally White panics.} (29. Ne5 $1 Rc2 30. a4 Rb2 {Still some pressure, but White has counterplay with the strong e5 -knight.}) 29... Rxc4 30. bxc4 Ne4 {Now the queenside pawns are too weak and Brunello won in convincing fashion.} 31. Ne5 Nc3 32. a3 Nb1 33. a4 Nc3 34. a5 $2 (34. Nc6 Nxa4 35. Nxa7 Nb2 {is a clear extra pawn and excellent winning chances.}) 34... bxa5 35. c5 a4 36. c6 Nd5 37. e4 Ne7 38. c7 a3 39. Nc6 Nc8 40. Nb4 Kf6 41. f4 gxf4 42. gxf4 Ke7 43. Kg3 Kd7 44. Kh4 Ne7 45. Kh5 Ng8 46. f5 exf5 47. exf5 Kxc7 48. Kg4 Kd6 49. Kf4 Nf6 50. Na2 Kd5 {From the game Szabo, Bence - Brunello, Sabino, Spilimbergo 2019.}) *

