16. g3 {A position from the Semi-Slav, but similar to many of our structures. Black to play: what's the plan?} c4 {The main plan is to grab space on the queenside} 17. a4 {Trying to prevent ... b5 , but it's slow.} cxb3 18. Nd2 {Key moment. What should Black do?} h5 {Very important way to get counterplay. While White recaptures the b3 -pawn, we get a strong attack on the kingside.} 19. Nxb3 h4 {White has too many pieces stuck on the queenside and therefore the kingside is very weak.} 20. Bg2 {Overlooking a tactic in a difficult position.} ({•} 20. Qf5 g6 21. Qf3 hxg3 22. hxg3 Nf8 {N8h7- g5 is coming with promising pressure}) ({•} 20. Qd3 Ng4 $5 {also looks scary, but not immediately winning.}) 20... hxg3 21. hxg3 Bxg3 ({Black is better. If fxg3} 21... Qxe3 22. Kh1 Ng4) 22. Bf3 {Basically accepting defeat.} Bb8 23. Nd2 Nf8 24. Kg2 Ne6 25. Rh1 g6 26. Ba1 Qd6 27. Qb3 Kg7 28. Bb2 Ng5 29. Be2 Qe6 30. Rh4 Rh8 31. Rch1 Rxh4 32. Rxh4 Bc7 33. Qd1 Bd6 34. Qb3 Be7 35. Rh1 Rc6 36. Ba3 Bxa3 37. Qxa3 Qc8 38. Ndb1 Nge4 39. Nxe4 Nxe4 40. Qe7 Rf6 41. f3 Rxf3 {From the game Chuchelov, Vladimir - Shirov, Alexei, Bundesliga 2009.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Prusikin, Michael vs. Grandel"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D45"]
[PlyCount "96"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 c6 5. e3 a6 6. a3 Nbd7 7. c5 g6 {Facing a much lower-rated player I decided to keep more pieces on the board and go for as complicated a fight as possible. In general, going for ... g6 in these positions is always interesting but not 100% equalizing. Here Black arguably has a slightly better version as the a3 -move might not be the most useful.} (7... b6 8. b4 a5 {Is the more typical reaction which equalizes comfortably.}) 8. b4 Bg7 9. Bb2 O-O 10. Be2 Qe7 {With ... g6 played, the main idea for Black should be to push ... e5 , with or without establishing a knight on e4 first. We play ... Qe7 instead of ... Re8 as the queen will be fantastic on e5 later on.} 11. O-O {During the game this surprised me a fair bit, and indeed the engines agrees it's a mistake. White shouldn't allow Black to play ... e5 without a fight!} (11. Na4 {I expected this, making ... e5 harder to achieve. I would have had to move my f6 -knight to e4 or e8 in order to push ... e5 , but that is obviously less active than the game.}) 11... e5 {Now Black is already very comfortable.} 12. Nxe5 Nxe5 13. dxe5 Qxe5 {Normally achieving ... e5 is enough to equalize, but here it's arguably even more than that. The c3 -knight belongs to d4 , and White is a bit pinned up.} 14. Bf3 h5 {An excellent move! The idea for us is to develop an initiative on the kingside, and for that purpose the pawn is useful on h5 . It can either continue forward with h4 - h3 , but it also supports ... Ng4 or ... Bg4 . White could very well lack kingside defenders soon.} 15. Ra2 {Another sign that things aren't fantastic for White. The b2 -bishop needs protection, but the rook on a2 looks misplaced.} Qg5 {Simply stepping out of the discovered attack.} 16. e4 {In some sense logical in order to trade pieces, but even after the trades Black keeps a nice initiative due to the more active pieces.} (16. Ne2 {My expectation. The knight can continue to either d4 , or even f4 in order to support the kingside.} h4 {My intended reply. It's not clear if I want to push ... h3 next, but just keeping the pawn on h4 is also highly annoying for White. Next up, it's time to bring more pieces into the game, likely with ... Bf5 followed by ... Rae8 . White is struggling long-term because there is no pawn breaks that makes sense, meaning that it's hard to come up with a useful plan.}) 16... dxe4 (16... d4 $5 {Actually this was my original idea, as I thought I would have excellent compensation for the pawn. That's true, but after thinking for a while I decided the game continuation was at least as good and much simpler.} 17. Ne2 (17. Qxd4 Be6 {Creates too many threats.}) 17... a5 $1 18. Qxd4 Be6 19. Raa1 Rfd8 {Tempo after tempo!} 20. Qc3 Qd2 {Full compensation for the pawn, but perhaps not more than that.}) 17. Nxe4 Nxe4 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. Bxe4 Rd8 {It looks equal at first, but in fact Black is considerably better. The reason is mainly the more active pieces - the d-file, the queen, even the king. Additionally the White queenside pawns are a bit too far advanced, and the c8 -bishop has a strong protected square on e6 , something that the e4 -bishop doesn't} 20. f4 {A bad move. My opponent desperately wants to get Rd2 , but in doing so he weakens too many squares.} (20. Qa1+ {This was my expectation, but I wasn't unhappy about it.} Qf6 21. Qxf6+ Kxf6 {Here it's perhaps even clearer that Black is better, for all the same reasons as with the queens still on the board.} 22. f3 Be6 23. Rb2 Rd4 24. Kf2 {There is no direct way through, but there is also no way for White to trade more pieces.} g5 $5 {Something like this; still very, very unpleasant for White}) 20... Qf6 21. Rd2 Bg4 {Another tempo!} 22. Bf3 Bf5 {A natural enough move. It's only when digging really deeply that it turns out to be a mistake.} (22... Rxd2 23. Qxd2 Rd8 24. Qe3 Qd4 {This was the correct way. White has a lot of weaknesses and all our pieces are more active.}) 23. Rff2 (23. Rd6 $1 {It turns out that this would have worked.} Rxd6 24. Qxd6 Qxd6 25. cxd6 Rd8 {During the game I thought I'd just pick up the d6 -pawn for free and stopped thinking further.} 26. Rd1 Kf6 27. Kf2 Ke6 28. Re1+ $3 {It turns out the bishop ending is drawn even with an extra pawn} Kxd6 29. Rd1+ Ke7 30. Rxd8 Kxd8 31. Ke3 {turns out this is just a draw - the problem is that there is no way to enter with the king.} Kc7 32. Kd4 Kd6 (32... b6 33. g3 Kd6 34. Be2 a5 35. bxa5 bxa5 36. Bf1 c5+ 37. Kc3 {same issue as before, no way to enter} Kd5 38. Bg2+ Be4 39. Bf1 Bh1 40. Bd3 {The king can't enter.}) 33. a4 b6 34. a5 c5+ 35. bxc5+ bxc5+ 36. Kc3 Bd7 37. Be2 Bb5 38. Bd1 {apparently can never make progress here. I could try to open more files on the kingside, but it will only lead to pawn trades.}) 23... Rxd2 24. Rxd2 Qc3 {Now I'm firmly in the driver's seat again.} 25. Re2 {Trying to sacrifice a pawn for some activity} a5 {Another good move, activating my remaining rook.} (25... Qxa3 26. Qd4+ {Should not be allowed - suddenly White is very active.}) 26. Qd2 axb4 {A misjudgment.} (26... Qxa3 {I didn't dare this, but it turns out White's apparent counterplay isn't really in time. Compared to the previous move it's huge to have gotten ... a5 in} 27. Qd4+ Kg8 28. b5 {This was the reason I didn't go for this line in the game.} cxb5 $1 {I simply didn't take this seriously, as giving up the b7 -pawn felt wrong. But the engine points out that the a- and b-pawns are much stronger.} 29. Bxb7 Rf8 30. c6 b4 {the c-pawn isn't going anywhere!!}) 27. axb4 Qf6 28. Qb2 {Visually the most natural move, but this was my small trap!} (28. h3 {The only move, and White would still be fighting}) 28... Ra1+ 29. Kf2 Rb1 {The b4 -pawn is lost, and with the rooks still on the board it's completely lost.} 30. Qxf6+ Kxf6 31. Re8 Rxb4 {The rest of the game is unfortunately marked by time trouble for both sides and is rather irrelevant for educational purposes.} 32. Ke3 h4 33. Rh8 Rb3+ 34. Kf2 Be6 {Completely unnecessary to give the h-pawn} (34... Rb5 35. Rb8 Be6 {In the long run I'm winning. Either I can play ... h3 at an appropriate moment, or perhaps ... Kf5 to provoke further weaknesses.}) 35. Rxh4 Rb5 (35... Kg7 {Was also winning, as the rook gets stuck on h4 .}) 36. Rh8 Rxc5 {I thought the b- and c-pawns should be easily winning, but White has some counterplay.} 37. Rb8 b5 (37... Rc2+ 38. Ke3 Rb2 {much better with an active rook and particularly White's rook passive} 39. h4 (39. g4 Rb3+ 40. Kf2 c5 $1) 39... Rb3+ 40. Kf2 Kf5 $1 41. g3 c5 {Much, much better than the game.}) 38. Rb6 {unnecessary to allow, now I lose coordination} Bd7 39. h4 Rc4 {Giving a full tempo} (39... Rc2+ 40. Ke3 Ke6 41. g4 Kd6 {Still winning.}) 40. Ke3 Ke7 41. g4 Rc2 42. h5 (42. f5 $1 {An excellent bid for counterplay. Actually, I have played so over the last couple of moves that the position is even an objective draw!} gxf5 43. g5 {The h-pawn is going to be powerful.}) 42... gxh5 43. gxh5 Kd6 44. Rb8 Rh2 45. Rh8 (45. f5 {This was the last chance. It looks pointless, but the idea is to kick my rook away from the h-file.} Bxf5 46. Kf4 $1 {If the bishop moves, White can play Kg3 and kick me out.} Rh3 47. Rh8 Bd7 48. h6 {With enough counterplay for a draw.}) 45... b4 {Now it's winning again.} 46. Be4 b3 47. h6 f5 48. Bb1 Kc5 {White resigned.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Schneider, Stefan vs. Roiz"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D45"]
[PlyCount "108"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c6 5. e3 a6 6. b3 Bb4 7. Bd2 O-O 8. Bd3 Nbd7 9. O-O Bd6 10. c5 {Generally speaking a risky move strategically, as our . ..e5-break gains in strength. White does get some extra space on the queenside, but it takes a long while before that really becomes a relevant factor.} Bb8 {10... Bc7 looks more natural, but I guess Roiz had some ideas of ... Qc7 .} 11. Na4 (11. e4 {This is the main move we always need to keep in mind in this structure. It usually doesn't work well though, and this position is no exception.} e5 $1 {The typical counterstrike. Now White gets too weak on the dark squares.} 12. dxe5 (12. exd5 exd4 $1 13. Na4 Nxd5 {Our pieces are very active.}) 12... Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Bxe5 14. exd5 cxd5 {Another important position to be aware of. This mainly comes down to the d4 -square. If White controls it and is able to place a piece there, it's usually much better for White. But with Black controlling d4 the d5 -pawn becomes more of a strength than a weakness. As for our plan, we should just activate all our pieces to sensibel central squares.}) 11... e5 {The obvious counterstroke.} 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Bxe5 14. Bc3 (14. Rc1 {Made a bit more sense. Now all reasonable moves gives Black a good game, but I'd just like to show one important motife to be aware of} Bg4 (14... Re8 {also completely fine}) 15. Qc2 (15. f3 Bh5 {This is good for us, as we manage to play ... Bg6 next.}) 15... Bh5 $6 {This is what we need to avoid. Strategically speaking trading with ... Bg6 is great for us, but it's a move too slow here.} (15... Qe7 16. h3 Bd7 {Not getting our bishop trapped. Still pleasant for Black.}) 16. f4 $1 {Now the bishop on h5 will end up completely out of play, as ... Bg6 is always met by f5 .}) 14... Bxc3 15. Nxc3 Qe7 {This is somewhat similar to my game with Prusikin, but an even better version for Black. The play flows very naturally over the next couple of moves.} 16. Na4 Bg4 17. Qc2 Qe5 (17... Bh5 $5 {Another typical way to play. Note again that f4 isn't possible, due to the e3 -pawn hanging.} 18. Rae1 Bg6 {Black is much better with ... Ne4 coming after the trade.}) 18. Qc3 (18. Rae1 $1 {Making f4 an option later!} Rae8 19. f4 Qe7 20. h3 Bc8 $1 {Important not to end up in trouble on h5 . Black is still doing well here, but it would be much nicer with the light squared bishops already traded off.}) 18... Qg5 {Our long-term strategic idea is a kingside attack, so we should definitely not trade queens.} 19. Kh1 Rae8 20. Qb4 Re7 21. Nc3 Bf5 {Finally getting the desirable trade in.} 22. Rad1 Bxd3 23. Rxd3 {Again the problem for White in these positions is that there are no pawn breaks available, meaning there is no good plan. For Black it's much easier - we just push everything on the kingside.} Qf5 (23... Ng4 $1 {This was the fastest way to get the attack going.} 24. Rd2 (24. h3 $4 Qf5 $1 {Wins material immediately.} 25. Rd2 Nxe3) 24... f5) 24. Rdd1 h5 25. Kg1 Rfe8 26. Rd4 Qe5 (26... g5 $1 {The most natural. We really want to ... h4 - h3 next.} 27. h4 {I guess this was the reason Roiz avoided ... g5 , but it doesn't work too well.} Ng4 $1 {Very strong. The knight can't be kicked away ever.} 28. hxg5 Qxg5 {The c3 -knight would need to get to f3 to defend, but White is simply too late}) 27. h3 Qc7 (27... g5 {Still good.}) 28. Ne2 Ne4 29. Qa3 Re5 30. b4 Qe7 31. Rd3 Qh4 {Even after wasting quite a few tempi Black is still having a dangerous attack.} 32. Qb2 Rg5 33. Nf4 Rf5 34. Rd4 Qf6 35. Nd3 Ng5 (35... g5 $1 {Still very good. Next up . ..g4- g3 to get the attack going.}) 36. Nf4 Ne4 37. Nd3 (37. a4) 37... Ng5 (37... g5 $1) 38. Nf4 Ne6 {Finally Roiz is going for this trade. It's definitely still better for Black, but this time keeping the knights was even stronger.} 39. Nxe6 fxe6 40. Rd2 Qg6 {Of course Black has no interest in trading queens.} 41. Kh1 Ref8 42. a4 e5 43. b5 {Finally White is getting some counterplay, but it's rather little, rather late.} axb5 44. axb5 Rg5 (44... e4 {A good move, to prevent f3 .}) 45. Rg1 (45. f3 $1 {This was the best try. Usually one shouldn't move pawns in front of their own king, but here it's more important to let Rd2 and Qb2 join the defense.}) 45... h4 46. bxc6 bxc6 47. Qb6 Kh7 {Black is slowly increasing the pressure.} 48. Kh2 Rf6 49. Qb4 Qf5 (49... e4 {Still gives Black a nice initiative.}) 50. Qb1 (50. Qxh4+ {Both players miscalculated this line - it was actually possible to take!} Rh6 51. g4 $3 {Only move not to lose. I am sure both players missed some tactical detail around here.} Rxh4 52. gxf5 Rxf5 53. Ra2 {White has enough counterplay to make a draw.}) 50... e4 51. Qb2 Rfg6 52. Qa1 Qf8 53. Qc3 {Finally allowing a tactical finish.} (53. Rc2 {The pressure continues, but objectively White is still holding on.}) 53... Qf3 54. gxf3 Rxg1 *

