[PlyCount "106"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 c6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 a6 6. b3 Bb4 7. Bd2 Nbd7 8. Bd3 O-O 9. O-O Bd6 10. h3 h6 (10... e5 {The most natural move and my recommendation in the theory section.}) 11. e4 dxc4 {The typical reaction against e4 , but the inclusion of h3  h6 favors White slightly.} 12. bxc4 e5 13. c5 Bc7 14. Na4 (14. Be3 {This is a big difference! Normally we would be able to meet it with ... Ng4 , but there the inclusion of h3  h6 prevents that. This means that White will be able to consolidate the center, after which they are slightly better.}) 14... exd4 {Now we are back to a normal sort of position. We have an extra pawn, but White's pieces are active and we are somewhat stuck, so it's rather balanced. It's easy to end up in trouble as Black though, so we need to be aware of a few ideas of how to free ourselves.} 15. Re1 Re8 16. Qc2 Nh5 {Making use of the queen leaving d1 . Black is actually quickly drumming up rather serious play on the kingside now.} (16... Nf8 {This is the other typical regrouping, but in this case the knight might still want to go to e5 .}) 17. Rad1 Qf6 {Presumably missing White's next move.} (17... Ne5 $1 {This generally makes a lot of sense combined with ... Nh5 , as Black wins control over all the kingside squares.} 18. Nxe5 Bxe5 19. Be2 Qh4 $1 {Black is simply having a nice attack for free. Note especially how good control we have over the f4 -square (!).}) 18. Nxd4 Ne5 (18... Qxd4 19. Bc3 {Traps the queen!}) 19. Be2 Nf4 {We always have to be careful in these positions. It might look like Black is very active on the kingside, but there is always the risk that White's e- and f-pawns starts rolling. This is one such case where it very quickly can go from promising to a complete disaster for Black.} 20. Bxf4 Qxf4 21. g3 (21. Nb6 $1 Rb8 (21... Bxb6 {Necessary, but sad.} 22. cxb6) 22. Nxc8 Rbxc8 23. g3 $1 {The problem. Suddenly the pawns starts to move.} Qf6 24. f4 Ng6 25. Nf5 {Intending e5 next. Actually White is just completely winning - please remember to never allow such scenarios!}) 21... Qf6 22. Kg2 (22. f4 Bxh3 $1 23. fxe5 Bxe5 {doesn't work for White - there are too many threats.}) 22... Ng6 {Prophylactic against f4} 23. Bh5 (23. Nf5 {With a highly complicated position.}) 23... Nf4+ {An excellent practical attempt, although White can still survive with engine-like play.} (23... Nh4+ $5 {Also very interesting and equally messy.} 24. gxh4 Qxh4 25. Bxf7+ Kxf7 26. Qb3+ Kg6 27. Nb6) 24. gxf4 Qxf4 25. Nf3 (25. Re3 $1 {This looks impossible to find during a real game. The idea is to tuck the king away on e2 .} Qh2+ (25... Qg5+ 26. Bg4 h5 27. Nf3 Qg6 28. Nh4 Qg5 29. Nf3 {is a funny repetition}) 26. Kf1 Bxh3+ 27. Ke2 Be6 {Black still has good compensation for the piece, but objectively it's only unclear.}) 25... g6 26. Qc3 (26. Qd2 {This was the only try for White. By trading queens the attack disappears.} Qxd2 27. Nxd2 gxh5 {Black is a pawn up in the ending, but it's a rather useless extra doubled h-pawn.}) 26... gxh5 {Now Black is winning. The two bishops on c7 and c8 are too powerful.} 27. Rg1 Kf8 (27... Be6 $1 {Was winning.} 28. Kf1+ (28. Nb6 {Now pointless as the rook can just move} Rad8) 28... Kf8 29. Qg7+ Ke7 {The king is completely safe on e7 .}) 28. Nb6 {Now it's complicated again. There has been too many ups and downs already and the rest of the game isn't really relevant for our understanding.} Rb8 29. Nxc8 Rbxc8 30. Rd7 Be5 31. Qd3 Bg7 32. e5 Bxe5 33. Rb1 Rc7 34. Rxb7 Rxb7 35. Rxb7 Re6 36. Rb1 Bc7 37. a3 a5 38. Kf1 a4 39. Rd1 Rf6 40. Kg2 Rg6+ 41. Kf1 Rf6 42. Kg2 Re6 43. Qc3 Rg6+ 44. Kf1 Rf6 45. Rd3 Qf5 46. Ke2 Re6+ 47. Re3 Qxh3 48. Qh8+ Ke7 49. Nd4 Rxe3+ 50. fxe3 Qg2+ 51. Kd3 Qf1+ 52. Ke4 Qg2+ 53. Kd3 Kd7 *

