1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Bg4 3. Bg2 e6 4. c4 c6 5. b3 Nf6 6. Bb2 Nbd7 7. O-O Bd6 8. d3 O-O 9. Nbd2 h6 {This is never strictly necessary, but once given the time it makes sense to flick it in, to keep the g4 -bishp alive. It's also a good preparation for ... e5 , as then h3 can be met by ... Be6 (there is no Ng5 ).} 10. h3 Bh5 11. Qc2 Bg6 (11... a5 {Was certainly possible immediately as well} 12. a3 Qe7) 12. e4 {Natural, but in my opinion strategically unnecessary. White should probably keep playing the waiting game.} dxe4 {This is always our reaction. It makes the g6 -bishop more active and prevents any active ideas from White} 13. dxe4 Qe7 (13... e5 $6 {This might look natural at first, but in fact it's unnecessary. Long-term it makes sense to try to get a good knight vs White's lousy g2 -bishop, but here there are simply too many pieces left on the board.} 14. Nh4 {Intending Nf5 is an extra option White gets after ... e5 .}) 14. Rae1 Rfd8 {Now Black is ready to grab the initiative on the queenside} (14... e5 $6 15. Nh4 $1) 15. Kh1 (15. Qc1 {White should have played more active, for instance by this move that threatens e5 .} Bb4 {The best reply. Now ... Nc5 - d3 is a great threat.} 16. e5 $6 {Natural but White should prefer something more modest like 16.Re3} Ne8 {Take note of this position. It's a strategic disaster for White. The g6 -bishop is very strong and White doesn't have a single active piece. We can either establish a knight on d3 , or even simpler just push ... a5 - a4 and start the attack.}) 15... a5 {Now the initiative is coming by itself} 16. Re2 Ba3 {Simply increasing the pressure.} 17. Qc1 Bxb2 18. Qxb2 Nc5 {Simple and strong. By every move the pressure increases} 19. e5 Nfd7 {Black is almost winning strategically and the best thing is that White still has no counterplay whatsoever!} 20. Re3 a4 (20... Nd3 21. Qc3 N7c5 22. a3 Rd7 {Simply doubling on the d-file was very, very strong as well}) 21. Qc3 axb3 22. axb3 Ra3 (22... Ra2 $1 {Was apparently even stronger, but what Meier does is good enough.} 23. b4 Na6 24. c5 Ra4 {The b4 -pawn is dropping.}) 23. Qb4 Rda8 24. Nh4 Bh7 (24... Bc2 {The b3 -pawn is very weak. One possible idea to increase the pressure is ... Qd8 - b6 .} 25. Be4 {Doesn't work now.} Bxb3 26. Nxb3 R8a4) 25. Be4 {Now White at least gets some trades in, although Black is still better.} Qd8 26. Bxh7+ Kxh7 27. Nhf3 Kg8 28. Ne4 (28. Kg2 Qb6 29. Qc3 {Keeping the queens. Without the light squared bishops our advantage is nothing special anymore.}) 28... Nxe4 29. Rxe4 Qf8 {A key move, after which the b3 -pawn again gets way too weak.} 30. Qxf8+ Kxf8 31. Re3 Nc5 32. Rb1 Rd8 {Black is simply too active.} 33. Ne1 Rd2 34. Kg1 g5 35. g4 Ke7 36. Rf3 Raa2 37. b4 Ne4 38. Nd3 Rdc2 39. Re1 Rxc4 40. Rfe3 Nc3 41. Rc1 b5 42. Rce1 Nd5 43. Re4 Rc3 44. Rd1 Rcc2 45. Rd4 Nc3 *

