1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. e3 a6 6. b3 Bb4 7. Bd2 Nbd7 8. Bd3 O-O 9. O-O Bd6 10. Qc2 h6 11. Rfd1 {Usually the wrong rook, as this rook is needed on the kingside. It might not look very obvious why yet, but the game continuation shows it very clearly.} e5 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. h3 Be6 {A very typical position, but a slightly better version than usual for us. White's kingside is a little bit soft, and if we want to, we can liquidate by pushing ... d4 . But there is no need, as the piece play fully compensates for the isolated pawn.} 16. f4 (16. Rac1 {was safer}) 16... Bb8 {The typical reaction. As soon as the f-pawn moves, the bishop will be fantastic on a7 .} 17. Ne2 Ba7 {Now the e3 -pawn is weaker than d5 .} 18. Qb2 Qd7 (18... Re8 {While the game continuation is very tempting, it doesn't give anything special against White's most stubborn defense, so playing positionally like this was stronger.} 19. Nd4 Bd7 $1 {After ... Ne4  Bxe4  Rxe4 next Black has very serious pressure.}) 19. Nd4 (19. Kh2 {Was still more or less playable for White} Bf5 $2 {is too slow due to} 20. Bc3 $1) 19... Bxh3 {Always look out for such ideas! The queen on b2 is very far from the kingside.} 20. gxh3 Qxh3 21. Bf1 Qg3+ 22. Bg2 Rfe8 {Following the old rule "Invite all your friends to the party."} 23. Bc1 (23. Be1 {The only move to survive! But giving up the e3 -pawn with check is not an easy choice.} Qxe3+ 24. Qf2 Ng4 $1 25. Qxe3 Nxe3 26. Bf2 $1 (26. Rd2 Nc2) 26... Nxd1 27. Rxd1 Rad8 {Finally Black has a moderate material edge, but White is still in the game.}) 23... Ng4 24. Nf5 Qh2+ 25. Kf1 Qxf4+ *

