1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nd7 3. d4 Nb6 4. Nbd2 Bf5 5. Bg2 e6 6. O-O Nf6 (6... c6 7. Nh4 Bg4 {Is another way to play if Black wants to keep their bishop.}) 7. Nh4 c6 8. c3 {Too soft. It might look like not much is going on, but this quickly turns out to be wrong!} (8. b3 h5 9. Nxf5 (9. c4) 9... exf5 10. Nf3) 8... h5 {A very interesting and imaginative idea by Braun. With the center likely to be closed for a long time it's actually possible to go for a flank attack.} (8... Be7) 9. Nxf5 (9. Ndf3 {As White I would definitely have played this. True, it gives Black the option of keeping the bishop, but on the other hand White should not get mated anytime soon...}) 9... exf5 10. Qc2 g6 11. Nb3 {This is the first 'real' mistake from White, but after this it starts to go downhill pretty quickly.} (11. Nf3 {Was much more natural to keep the kingside defended.} Bd6 (11... Ne4 $6 {Don't be overambitious with Black! This looks natural, but is rather risky as it invites f3 , e4 .} 12. Ne5 $1 h4 13. f3 {It's still a mess, but White is getting serious counterplay.}) 12. Bg5 Be7 {Followed by ... Ne4 is solid.}) 11... h4 12. Bg5 hxg3 (12... Rh5 $5 {even this was possible, with a highly unclear position.} 13. Bxh4 g5 14. Bf3 gxh4 15. Bxh5 Nxh5 16. Qxf5 Ng7 {White has two pawns and a rook for the two pieces, and the position is very complicated.}) 13. hxg3 Bh6 (13... Rh5 $5 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. e3 g5 $5 {One day pushing ... f4 . It seems to me the White king should be more vulnerable than Black's, although the engines still considers it balanced.}) 14. Bxh6 {A typical mistake. In this line the f6 -knight is almost always more valuable than the dark squared bishop.} (14. Bxf6 $1 Qxf6 15. e3 {I would pick Black, but it's still only unclear. White is getting some counterplay by Nd2 followed by c4 .}) 14... Rxh6 15. Qd2 {An empty move, as the queen won't be able to contribute to the defense anyway.} (15. Bf3 $1 {The only move, but spending two moves giving up the best defender is not an easy choice. The reason it must be done is to be able to play Kg2 followed by Rh1 .} Ng4 16. Bxg4 fxg4 17. Kg2 Qf6 18. Rh1 Rh3 $5 {Is one way to keep the pressure up, but White is still defending.}) (15. Nd2 $6 {This idea is now too slow.} Ng4 16. c4 f4 $5 {Already this gives a promising attack.}) 15... Rh7 16. Qe3+ (16. Bf3 Nc4 $1 {Gives an additional important tempo.}) 16... Kf8 17. Nc5 {Too greedy, but it's already difficult to suggest good alternatives. Probably Bf3 was still the best try.} Kg7 18. Nxb7 {Of course this pawn is irrelevant.} Qh8 19. Rfd1 Ng4 20. Qf3 {It might look like White is still defending, but once Black bring the a8 -rook and b6 -knight into the game it all collapses.} Re8 21. e3 (21. Nc5 Rxe2 22. Qxe2 Rh1+ {is a nice mate.} 23. Bxh1 Qh2+ 24. Kf1 Qxh1#) 21... Nc4 22. Rd3 (22. Nc5 {Trying to bring the knight back but it's all too late.} Ncxe3 23. fxe3 Rxe3 {Mating.}) 22... Rb8 {Finally entering from the other side!} 23. b3 Rxb7 24. bxc4 Rb2 25. cxd5 Rh1+ {Beautiful, although by this point everything wins.} 26. Bxh1 Qh2+ 27. Kf1 Rxf2+ 28. Ke1 Qg1# *

