1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nd7 3. d4 Nb6 4. Bg2 Nf6 5. O-O Bf5 6. b3 e6 7. Bb2 {Such setups are very likely to happen in practice. White doesn't pay too much attention to our knight on b6 and just keeps making normal moves.} h6 {Again this is not really necessary as Nh4 isn't really a threat, but on the other hand it's solid enough.} 8. c4 c6 9. Nbd2 Be7 10. Rc1 O-O 11. e3 {Roundabout here it makes sense to talk about the plans for the middlegame. For Black, it's important to realize that there is no rush. White isn't really threatening to create any dangerous play, so we have a lot of time to strengthen our position. The b6 -knight should be brought back to d7 , and the a-pawn should march forward. Jumping ... Ne4 also makes sense. Long-term, we likely want to create something on the kingside, but it's too early to say exactly what. It might be pushing the h-pawn, it might be supporting the e4 -knight with ... f5 , or it might be something entirely different.} a5 12. Qe2 Nbd7 {This is necessary sooner or later. It also creates a small threat of ... a4 .} (12... a4 $6 13. c5 $1 Nbd7 14. b4 {Is nothing we should allow.}) 13. a3 Ne4 (13... Qb6 $5 {is another typical move aimed at the weak b3 -pawn.}) 14. Rfd1 (14. Nxe4 {Trading as much as possible and accept that it's equal was more prudent.} Bxe4 15. Nd2 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 f5 {This looks equal. We have some chances on the kingside but with two sets of pieces traded, it shouldn't amount to much.}) 14... Qb6 (14... Bg4 $1 {This is a nice way to create play. Suddenly White is a bit too pinned.} 15. Qd3 f5 {Intending to push either the h- or g-pawn}) 15. c5 (15. Nxe4 {Still the most solid way.}) 15... Qc7 {As soon as c5 is played the position becomes different. Now our main aim should be to push ... e5 .} 16. Ne1 Nxd2 17. Rxd2 e5 {Mission accomplished!} 18. b4 (18. dxe5 {It looks risky to give up the c5 -pawn, but it's strategically necessary so as to not end up in an entirely passive position.} Nxc5 19. Bxd5 $1 {This needed to be foreseen by White, otherwise the b3 -pawn would drop.} cxd5 20. b4 {A very messy position. White misses his light squared bishop, but our queenside pawns are a bit soft.}) 18... axb4 19. axb4 e4 {The dream! Now we can slowly build up on the kingside and attack for free. I say slowly as there is no counterplay and therefore no rush, but as the game shows it doesn't exactly go very slowly...} 20. b5 Nf6 21. Nc2 Bg4 (21... h5 {Perhaps even more straightforward, although the game continuation works well enough.}) 22. Qe1 Nh7 {Another good way of attacking. The f3 -square is juicy!} 23. h3 Be6 24. Qf1 h5 25. h4 {On all other moves Black would play ... h4 .} g5 26. hxg5 Nxg5 {Just look at the helpless state of White's queenside pieces.} 27. Ne1 Bg4 28. b6 Qc8 29. Ra1 Qf5 30. Bc3 Kg7 {There are many ways to win, but I like the calmness of Black's play. It really emphasizes just how helpless White is} 31. Rda2 Rab8 32. Bh1 Rh8 {Finally ... h4 is coming} 33. f4 {Desperation, but it's already way too late.} exf3 34. Rh2 Ne4 35. Rc1 Bg5 *

