1. c4 e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. b3 b6 5. Bb2 Bb7 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Bb5+ {This check provokes ..c6, which might be both good and bad. The downside though is that the bishop is simply better on g2 than e2 !} c6 8. Be2 Bd6 {Our usual setup works well here as well.} 9. d3 {Too timid in my opinion, although White had already given up hopes of an ambitious opening.} O-O 10. O-O Re8 {As usual in these positions I prefer to keep the knight on b8 for a while, so that it might go to ... c6 instead of d7 .} 11. Nbd2 c5 {Not necessary, but I felt that the knight on d2 would now be misplaced.} (11... Nbd7 {Still very natural and solid, of course.}) 12. d4 Nc6 13. Nb1 {This is a bit too much. It's true that c3 is a much better square than d2 for the knight, but two tempi is quite a lot.} (13. Rc1 {was more natural.} Qe7 {Followed by ... Rad8 with an interesting fight ahead.}) 13... Rc8 14. dxc5 (14. Nc3 $6 {This was almost certainly the idea, but it's not quite in time.} cxd4 $1 15. Nxd4 Nxd4 16. Qxd4 Be5 $1 17. Qd3 Ne4 $1 {And Black has too much pressure.}) 14... bxc5 15. Nc3 {This simply does not work. Perhaps White did not think his position could be so critical after only 15 moves, but with such hanging pawns the attack can come very fast!} d4 {Always the first move we should look at in this structure!} 16. Nb5 Bb8 17. exd4 a6 {Perhaps White underestimated this intermediate move? In any case, it now all collapses.} 18. Na3 (18. d5 Nxd5 19. Nc3 Nd4 $1 {Just look at the Black pieces - there is perfect harmony and they are all incredibly active. I would say that Black has "a nice initiative" but the engine kindly informs me it's already -4}) 18... Nxd4 (18... Qc7 {Apparently even stronger. The c8 -rook coming to d8 is more than White can handle. Importantly it also doesn't allow Bf3 as in the game.} 19. g3 (19. d5 Nxd5 $1) 19... Rcd8) 19. Nxd4 cxd4 20. Bf3 {With the bishop here White has some hopes of defending again.} Bxf3 {Allowing the queen to join the defense} (20... Qd6 21. g3 Qd7 {Still gives Black a strong initiative.}) 21. Qxf3 Ne4 22. Nc4 (22. Rfe1 {This was much more precise, forcing a concession and avoiding the disaster that happened in the game.}) 22... Rc6 {With the rook joining the attack it's now really dangerous for White. During the game I thought I was close to winning, but there was still one defense left.} 23. g3 (23. Qd3 Bxh2+ {I was very tempted by this during the game, but unfortunately it's only a draw.} (23... Rh6 {Objectively the strongest.} 24. h3 Qc7 25. f4 Rhe6 {Having provoked h3 and f4 White's king will be eternally weak.}) (23... Ba7) 24. Kxh2 Rh6+ 25. Kg1 Qh4 26. Qh3 {Only move to avoid mate!} Qf6 27. Qf3 Qh4 28. Qh3 {There is nothing more than the repetition.}) 23... Rf6 24. Qg2 Ba7 {Suddenly White is one move too late.} 25. Rad1 (25. Rae1 {The best try} Rfe6 {Intending ... d3 - d2 . If need be, Black can even add the h-pawn to the attack. Meanwhile White is hopelessly passive and can't trade a single piece.}) 25... Rxf2 26. Rxf2 d3 27. Kf1 (27. Rdf1 d2 {Wins a lot of material.}) 27... Nxf2 28. Rd2 Qe7 29. Be5 Ng4 *

