1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 b6 5. b3 Bb7 6. Bb2 Nbd7 7. cxd5 exd5 8. d4 {In general, this is a little less flexible for White than delaying d4 . It often transposes, but sometimes it can give us some extra options. This game is a good example of that.} Bd6 9. Rc1 a6 10. g3 Qe7 {This is the difference with the pawn already on d4 - Black can actually try to castle long! With the pawn back on d2 , White would be able to meet ... Qe7 by Nd4 , creating threats like Nf5 , whereas now our king will actually be rather safe on the queenside.} 11. Bg2 O-O-O {It might sound strange, but Black is already clearly better! And when we think about it, it really isn't all that strange. Our king is much safer than White's will be. We can push our kingside pawns, whereas the White queenside pawns are much slower. Part of the reason why is that we control the center better and therefore in essence a space advantage. And as usual, the side with the space advantage finds it easier shuffling their pieces back and forth. In this specific case, it means that we are much faster at bringing our pieces over to the kingside.} 12. Qc2 (12. O-O Kb8 {followed by either ... h5 or ... Ne4 is similar.}) 12... Kb8 {Not strictly necessary, but it's good for the nerves to step out of the c-file.} 13. O-O Ne4 (13... h5 $5 {As Black, I would be very tempted by this as well. The threat is simply to push ... h4 and give the exchange, in typical attacking fashion.}) 14. Nxe4 {Increases our control over the center, but it was already very difficult for White to find any meaningful counterplay.} (14. b4 {White could try this, but as soon as they play b5 we simply block with ... a5} h5 {The attack continues. White must either allow ... h4 , or play h4 themselves which allows a later ... g5 to open up fully.}) 14... dxe4 15. Nd2 f5 16. Nc4 h5 (16... Nf6 {This was even stronger.} 17. Ne5 {It looks like the knight is well-placed here, but it actually doesn't do much. It can trade itself off on c6 , but after that White gets stuck.} (17. d5 Nxd5 {Is now a good extra pawn. Additionally, ... Nb4 - d3 becomes an idea.}) 17... h5 $1 18. Nc6+ Bxc6 19. Qxc6 h4 {Our attack is already close to winning.}) 17. Nxd6 Qxd6 18. f3 (18. d5 $1 {This was the only move to pretend to get any sort of counterplay. Now at least the bishop on b2 is active.} h4 {Our attack is still strong, but not the sort of complete control as Black got in the game.}) 18... Nf6 (18... h4 $1 {was even stronger. The attack is simply breaking through.} 19. fxe4 fxe4 {White won't survive for long.}) 19. fxe4 fxe4 20. Rf5 h4 21. Qf2 (21. d5 {This was again the only attempt to get any sort of counterplay.} hxg3 $2 (21... Rhe8 {Prevents Be5 and keeps an edge.}) 22. Be5 $1 {Something like this is what White needs. The king is still highly vulnerable, but on the other side of the board c7 is falling.} gxh2+ 23. Kh1) 21... Ng4 22. Qe2 (22. Qf4 {Most probably White intended this, but it doesn't work.} Qxf4 23. exf4 (23. Rxf4 Nxe3) 23... hxg3 24. hxg3 Ne3 {Even without queen Black has a winning attack!} 25. Re5 Nxg2 26. Kxg2 e3+ {with Rh1 - h2 picking up the bishop next.}) 22... Nxh2 {A nice tactic to break through.} 23. Kxh2 hxg3+ 24. Kg1 Qh6 {The check on h2 is annoying but the real problem is that Black will soon win the f-file.} 25. Rf7 Bd5 {If the rook moves away from the f-file, . ..Qh2+ followed by ... Rf8 wins immediately.} 26. Rcxc7 {Desperation.} Bxf7 27. Rxf7 Rdf8 {Materially White is OK, but the attack is still ongoing.} 28. Qc4 Qxe3+ 29. Kf1 Rxf7+ 30. Qxf7 Qd3+ 31. Kg1 Qe3+ 32. Kf1 Rc8 33. Bh3 Qd3+ 34. Kg1 Qb1+ 35. Kg2 Qxb2+ 36. Kxg3 Qc3+ *

