[ECO "A13"]
[PlyCount "74"]

1. c4 e6 2. g3 d5 3. Bg2 dxc4 4. Qa4+ Qd7 {This game was played in the European Club Cup with me sitting a few boards way. It was the first time I saw the ... Qd7 -idea and what inspired me to recommend it in the course.} 5. Qxc4 c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O Nf6 8. Nc3 Be7 9. d4 cxd4 10. Rd1 e5 {We are well familiar with all of this from the theory section, but needless to say Black already had a significant time advantage in the game.} 11. e3 d3 12. Ng5 O-O 13. Rxd3 Qe8 (13... Qg4 {Confidently equalizing, but already having the psychological initiative Bartel goes for more.} 14. Qxg4 Bxg4) 14. Nb5 {A somewhat naïve move. Yes, it does threaten Nc7 , but White is forgetting about the queenside development.} Na5 {A well-calculated reply. White is forced to self-pin.} 15. Qa4 Bd7 16. Qxa5 (16. Rxd7 $1 {This was the best move for White, but while the move in itself is the first that comes to mind, it requires very serious calculation to make it work.} Qxd7 17. Qxa5 {White is material up, but the queenside is not yet developed.} Qd1+ 18. Bf1 Nd5 {This looks very strong. The g5 -knight is hanging, and ... Bb4 threatens to trap the queen next move. Amazingly, there is a defence though.} 19. e4 Bb4 20. Nc3 $3 {The only move to not be completely lost. Now the queen can escape via d5 .} Nxc3 21. Qxb4 Ne2+ 22. Kg2 Nxc1 23. Bc4 {The position is still a mess. The knight on c1 is in trouble, and there is some counterplay towards f7 . I would have no clue what was going on, and the engines are as usual giving 0.00. ..}) 16... Bxb5 {Now Black is simply better, due to the lead in development.} 17. Rb3 {This is the first moment of the game where White makes an outright bad instead of risky move. The rook has nothing to do on b3 .} (17. Rd1 {White had to accept this somewhat sad move to defend the first rank.} Rd8 18. Rxd8 Bxd8 19. Qe1 e4 {Still looks like an initiative for Black, although with a couple more accurate moves White should probably equalize.}) 17... Bc6 {Very natural. The trade of light squared bishops makes the White king a lot weaker.} (17... a6 {This simple move would also have given a huge initiative for Black. ... Nd7 - c5 is a strong plan looming.}) 18. Bd2 Rd8 (18... e4 {Strategically very strong. The knight will be forced to the terrible h3 -square. But it's easy to understand the temptation of what Bartel is doing, as trading the light squared bishops is also an achievement.}) 19. Bxc6 Qxc6 20. Rc1 Qd7 21. Rc7 {This move is a bit similar to 14.Nb5 and 17. Rb3 . White is playing for activity when he should instead try to solidify as much as possible and keep everything defended.} (21. Be1) 21... Qg4 {Suddenly it's too much for White to handle. The d2 -bishp is loose, the g5 -knight is hanging and the king is getting low on defenders.} 22. Rxe7 b6 {The simple refutation. Once the queen enters on e2 the attack becomes irresistable.} (22... Qe2 $4 23. Rxf7 $1 {Perhaps White relied on this trick.}) 23. Qxe5 (23. Qc3 Qe2 24. Be1 Rd1 {gives a winning attack.}) 23... Rxd2 {White is technically a pawn up, but the position is entirely hopeless. Apart from the weak king, there is also a simple threat of ... h6 , trapping the knight.} 24. Qf4 Rd1+ 25. Kg2 Qe2 26. g4 {White is trying to escape, but it's too late. Look how misplaced both of the rooks are.} h6 27. Ne4 Nd5 {Winning an exchange without losing the initiative. The rest is straightforward.} 28. Qe5 Nxe7 29. Qxe7 Qxg4+ 30. Ng3 Rd7 31. Qe5 Rc8 32. h3 Qg6 33. e4 Rd2 34. Rf3 Qe6 35. Qf4 Rcc2 36. Nf5 Qg6+ 37. Kh2 Qg5 *

