1. c4 e6 2. g3 d5 3. Nf3 dxc4 4. Qa4+ Nd7 5. Bg2 a6 6. Qxc4 b5 7. Qb3 {In general not a great square for the queen, as it often gets under attack.} Bb7 8. O-O Ngf6 9. Nc3 c5 10. d3 Be7 11. a4 {It does look pretty logical from White. The main strategic aim is to provoke ... b4 , therefore putting more pressure on the b5 -pawn makes sense? Well, the problem is that Black has a strong counterblow to grab the initiative now.} c4 {Remember this idea! It's a really common way to handle the Qb3 -setups.} 12. dxc4 Nc5 13. Qd1 (13. Qb4 $1 {Actually, it looks like White is still OK here, although I don't think anybody would voluntarily want to play in such a way.} Nxa4 14. Qb3 Nc5 15. Qb4 {Strangely enough, there doesn't seem to be more than equality here for Black.}) 13... b4 {This is the strategic idea. White is forced back into complete passivity.} 14. Nb1 Qxd1 {The queen trade is by no means forced, but it's tempting to get access to the b3 -square as quickly as possible.} 15. Rxd1 Nb3 16. Ra2 {The rook is truly terrible here.} Ne4 (16... a5 {As Black I would probably have played this. It makes sense to rule out White ever playing a5 to free up the rook. Additionally, it's a smart waiting move asking White what's next.} 17. Be3 (17. Nbd2 Rd8 {Creates another unpleasant pin.} 18. Re1 Nxc1 19. Rxc1 Bxf3 $1 {Important, to keep control over the key squares.} 20. Nxf3 Ne4 21. Ne5 Nc5 {The a2 -rook is still stuck. With the additional option of ... Bf6 , this more than compensates for the minus-pawn.}) 17... Ng4 $1 {Is the extra optionthat is very useful}) 17. Be3 {Now the bishop is a bit safer on e3 .} Bc5 18. Rd3 {A tactical error.} (18. Ng5 {This was the only move. Now not only White but also Black's position is a bit loose and the position would be messy. Still interesting for Black, but White is at least getting some serious counterplay.} Nxg5 (18... f5 $5 {is another exciting option.}) 19. Bxb7 Bxe3 20. Bxa8 Nh3+ 21. Kg2 Nxf2 22. Bc6+ Ke7 23. Rd7+ Kf6 {Is one of the possible lines. Don't worry if you have no clue what is going on - I don't either}) 18... Bxe3 19. Rxb3 {Desperation.} (19. Rxe3 O-O-O {-+ A very nice move that actually wins immediately. There is simply no way to stop ... Rd1 +.} 20. Rxb3 Rd1+ 21. Bf1 Rxb1 22. Rxb4 Rd8 {Rdd1 will win the house.}) (19. fxe3 $2 Nc1 {is another simple but beautiful point!}) 19... Bxf2+ 20. Kf1 O-O-O {Apart from a winning attack Black is also strategically winning with the bishop pair, better pawn structure and a2 -rook.} 21. Rd3 Ba7 22. Ke1 Rxd3 23. exd3 Nc5 24. d4 Nb3 25. a5 Nxd4 26. Nxd4 Bxg2 27. Nb3 h5 {With ... h4 coming next, White had enough.} *

