1. c4 e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3 dxc4 4. Qa4+ Nd7 5. Bg2 a6 6. Qxc4 b5 7. Qc2 Bb7 8. O-O Ngf6 9. d3 c5 10. a4 Be7 11. Nc3 Bc6 12. Bd2 {I like this game a lot because it shows how quickly things can go wrong for White, despite it being a strong grandmaster making natural moves. The thing is that our queenside space advantage gives a lot of potential play later on, so White should really do something quick about it.} (12. Nh4) 12... O-O 13. axb5 axb5 14. b4 {A typical shot, forcing an isolated pawn for Black. The problem is that the isolated pawn is also a passed pawn! It might not look like it yet, but the b-pawn will become a powerful asset.} (14. Rfc1 Qb6 {Pleasant for Black, but White is still very much in the game.}) 14... Rxa1 (14... Qb6 {This was even simpler.} 15. bxc5 Bxc5 16. e3 {Defending f2 .} Qb7 {With the simple yet strong idea of ... b4 - b3 next.} 17. e4 b4 {The difference to the game is that Nd1 is not available, as it would leave the a1 -rook hanging.}) 15. Rxa1 Qb6 16. bxc5 Bxc5 17. e3 (17. Nd1 $1 {This is the main reason Black should have delayed the trade of rooks. Now White gets to play Be3 and reach some sort of stability.}) 17... Qb7 18. e4 b4 {Keep an eye on this pawn!} 19. Nd1 Ra8 20. Rb1 (20. Rxa8+ Qxa8 {When fighting an outside passed pawns, it's usually a good idea to keep as many pieces as possible on the board. For every trade, the strength of the pawn increases.} 21. Be3 {Still, White would be able to play Nd2 - b3 next, after which the pawn is blocked at least for the time being.}) 20... Ra3 21. Be3 (21. Ne3 {This was a better try due to what happens in the game, but it's still highly unpleasant.}) 21... Ba4 {Very alert by Black. The d1 -knight doesn't look pretty, but trading it off increases the strength of the b-pawn.} 22. Qd2 Bxd1 23. Rxd1 Bxe3 24. Qxe3 b3 {Now Black is very clearly better.} 25. Rb1 b2 (25... Ra2 {A much better move order. The rook anyway needs to go a2 , and doing it before pushing ... b2 creates the additional threat of ... Ng4 .} 26. h3 (26. Qd4 Ng4 {Simply wins f2 .}) 26... b2 {Now Black has an extra tempo and ... Ra1 is coming soon.}) 26. Qd4 {Hitting the b2 -pawn.} Rb3 27. Nd2 e5 28. Qc4 (28. Qe3 $1 Rc3 29. Nc4 $1 {Looks risky but was still holding for White.} Rc2 30. Bf3 {Is an important extra resource - the bishop goes to d1 to kick the rook out.}) 28... Ra3 {Now Black is in control again.} 29. Qc2 (29. Bf3 Ra1 30. Bd1 {was the last chance. The b2 -pawn is blocked, but it also cannot be attacked, meaning it will be an asset for the rest of the game.}) 29... Ra1 {Now it's too much. White needed the bishop in the defence.} 30. Bf3 Qb4 31. Kg2 Rxb1 32. Nxb1 Nc5 {Simple and strong play by Sargissian. The only thing remaining is bringing the f6 -knight towards the queenside.} 33. Be2 Nfd7 34. f4 {Creating more weaknesses, but passive defense also wouldn't do.} exf4 35. gxf4 Ne6 36. Bg4 Nxf4+ 37. Kg3 Qe1+ {38.Kxf4 Qc1 + promotes the b-pawn.} *

[Event "?"]
