[ECO "A14"]
[PlyCount "68"]

1. c4 e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 Be7 5. O-O O-O 6. b3 b6 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Bb2 Bb7 9. d4 Nd7 10. Re1 c5 11. e4 N5f6 12. Nc3 cxd4 13. Nxd4 Bc5 14. Na4 (14. Re2 {Perhaps White mixed up the theory and had intented this move immediately.}) 14... Bb4 15. Re2 Nc5 16. Nxc5 Bxc5 17. e5 {A rather serious strategic mistake. It's not that White's position is so bad after this, but it becomes very easy to be Black.} (17. Rd2 {This was much safer for White, but it requires some serious calculation.} Nxe4 (17... Qe7 {Followed by doubling the rooks on the d-file is also possible, with a calmer game.}) 18. Bxe4 Bxe4 19. Nxe6 $1 fxe6 $1 20. Qg4 $1 {Is the tactical justification that equalizes.}) 17... Bxg2 18. Kxg2 Bxd4 {I like this decision. Westerberg simply secures a good knight vs bad bishop scenario.} (18... Nd5 {Perhaps more natural, but it does allow White to keep the knight.} 19. Nf3) 19. Qxd4 Nd5 {If you ask the engines, they say that White is close to equality, but for humans the position is a nightmare for White to play. The d5 -knight will stay there for the rest of the game, and long-term the king will feel vulnerable. White should probably try to trade as many heavy pieces as possible and stay put, but it's a depressing outcome of the opening.} 20. Rc1 Qd7 21. Rec2 Qb7 22. f3 {Creating a few moves weaknesses.} (22. Kg1 {was more solid. The knight is very good on d5 , but at least it's far away from f3 .} Rfc8 23. Ba3 {White is only slightly worse, but will be so for a very long time.}) 22... Rfc8 (22... h5 $5 {Makes sense already here.}) 23. Kf2 Rxc2+ 24. Rxc2 Rc8 {Westerberg is playing simple chess. He trades the queens in order to enter with the queen later on.} 25. Qd2 Rc6 (25... h5 $5 {I think this should have been included for Black sometime over the last couple of moves. It prevents White from playing g4 and gives the king a square on h7 . If the queens are traded, the king can even enter the game via g6 - f5 . But mainly it makes the White king feel even more vulnerable.}) 26. a4 (26. g4 $5 {To prevent ... h5 . Now the king will be somewhat safer on g3 .}) 26... a6 27. Bd4 Qc7 28. Rxc6 Qxc6 29. Ke2 (29. g4) 29... b5 30. axb5 axb5 31. Qd3 h5 {Better late than never! By every move the White position gets a little worse. It's still probably within the drawing margin objectively, but it gets harder and harder to defend. Now Black needs to bring the queen forward.} 32. Be3 (32. Qd2 $1 {Preventing ... Qc1 .} Qa6 33. Kf2 Qa3 34. Qc2 $1 {Controlling all entry squares. Black would have to play a slow manouvering game in order to make progress. Probably the way to make further progress will be connected to reshuffling the knight to f5 and then put the queen on d5 instead.}) 32... Qa6 {Now Black is entering.} 33. Qc2 (33. Bd2 Qa2 34. f4 {Was the last try, but now the queen is more active than before, and f4 further weakens the light squares.}) 33... Qa1 34. f4 Qf1+ {A small tactic in an already winning position.} *

