1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Nf3 a6 7. Bg5 Be6 8. Be2 g6 9. Bxf6 exf6 10. O-O Bg7 11. Qb3 O-O {A typical phenomena in these lines. Neither the b7 - nor the d5 -pawn is really hanging.} (11... dxc4 12. Qxb7 Na5 13. Qb4 Rb8 14. Qa3) 12. cxd5 (12. Qxb7 {Always needs checking, but rarely works.} Na5 13. Qb4 Rb8 14. Qa3 Nxc4 15. Bxc4 dxc4 16. d5 Bd7 17. Qxa6 {When calculating these kind of lines over the board it's easy to get confused and worried. Often White is temporarily a pawn up and the d5 -pawn is passed. But in fact it's almost always excellent compensation, and more often than not it's White who has to be careful. The d-pawn isn't really goin anywhere, and the queenside pawns are all weak.} Qc7 {The most ambitious move, keeping the c4 -pawn alive. Now we will soon win the b2 -apwn and our bishops will eventually get to work.}) 12... Na5 13. Qa4 Bxd5 14. Nxd5 Qxd5 {This is another of the positions that one might evaluate incorrectly during a game. At first glance White has a passed pawn for free, but there are a couple of more hidden issues. Firstly, the d-pawn is never really going anywhere, as it will be blocked on the dark square d6 . Secondly, the knight on f3 is not that great, but if it moves the d-pawn becomes weak. Thirdly, if White should ever push d5 and we block it by ... Bd6 , then our bishop is considerably stronger than White's. Finally, Black has the safer king and might also get counterplay along the e-file.} 15. Rac1 (15. Nd2 $1 {Actually, White's best move is this. It solves the problem of the f3 -knight being passive, but the d4 -pawn gets weaker. It likely leads to more drawish positions.} Rfd8 16. Bf3 Qb5 (16... Qxd4 17. Qxa5 Qxd2 {is also drawish.}) 17. Qxb5 axb5 18. Nb3) 15... Rfc8 16. Rfd1 {White is playing natural moves, but it's precisly the sort of driftingthat might end up dangerous in the long run.} Bh6 {The most natural move that also worked very well in the game, but it gives White an opportunity to get counterplay.} (16... Bf8 $5 {Would have been a strong prophylactic move, preventing the only active White idea. Later, the bishop goes to d6 where it controls a lot of important squares. Long-term, pushing the h- and perhaps even the g-pawn makes sense, as White's king is a little vulnerable.}) 17. Rc3 (17. Rc5 $1 {This was the move for White! At first it looks like it loses a pawn, but White is getting a lot of activity in the meantime.} Rxc5 18. dxc5 Qxc5 19. b4 Qe7 $1 {Hitting the e2 -bishop. During a game it's easy to stop the calculations here, but if we continue a bit we see that White has decent compensation for the pawn.} 20. Bf1 $1 Nc6 21. b5 {White's activity compensates for the missing pawn.}) 17... Rxc3 18. bxc3 Rc8 {Now the c3 -pawn is a serious weakness, especially combined with the bishop controlling the c1 -square.} 19. Qa3 (19. Qc2 b5 {Preventing c4 forever. Now White is forever stuck wit the weak c3 -pawn.}) 19... Bf8 20. Qb2 b5 21. Nd2 f5 (21... h5 {Another very thematic way to play, especially once the knight moves away from the kingisde. A later ... h4 will be rather unpleasant for White to face. They don't want ot play h3 as it would fatally weaken the dark squares, but allowing Black's pawn to h3 is also highly unpleasant.}) 22. Nb3 {Allowing Black to strengthen the positioneven further.} (22. Rc1 {Sitting tight. Black has a very, very nice position, but White isn't losing by force.}) 22... Nc4 23. Qc1 Nb6 {Beautifully played by Donchenko! Now the knight is headed for a4 , after which White collapses.} 24. Bf3 Qc4 25. Bb7 {Going for tactics, but as usual tactics works better for the player with the advantage.} Rc7 26. Bxa6 Nd5 {The a6 -bishop is simply trapped.} 27. Re1 Qc6 28. Re5 Nxc3 29. Nc5 Ne4 {One of many moves winning a piece.} 30. Qf1 Nxc5 31. Bxb5 Qf6 *

[Event "?"]
