[Black "Soham, Das vs. Gumularz"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "A03"]
[PlyCount "59"]

1. g3 Nf6 2. Bg2 d5 3. f4 {Another way to reach the Reversed Dutch, but luckily for us we can play the same setup against all move orders.} e6 4. Nf3 b5 5. O-O Bb7 6. d3 Nbd7 (6... Be7 {Is the recommended move in the Theory section. It doesn't matter much, but havingthe bishop on e7 is a little bit safer, especially in case White pushes e4 .}) 7. c3 Bd6 (7... a5 $5 {This was also interesting, albeit slightly weird. In the long run we want to grab as much space as possible on the queenside, but here it has the added benefit of preventing what White does in the game. As White is anyway unable to open the center quickly, we have time for such extravagancies.}) 8. a4 {This is by far the most common plan in these positions, and even the engine's preference, but I still feel it's a strategic win for Black. With 1.f4 White is clearly intending to play on the kingside and in the center, therefore any pawn moves on the queenside should be in our benefit. It shows the strength of our setup that White is already giving up the e4 -idea.} b4 9. a5 {This is what Black could have avoided by playing 7... a5 .} Rb8 {An important move, preparing a square on a8 for the bishop. Additionally, the b-file is likely to be opened some day.} 10. cxb4 {Givingup a bit too many squares. Now the b2 -pawn will be permanently backwards.} (10. Be3 {Was a better move, continuing to develop.} a6 {But I still don't see White's next move. Frankly, the position just looks a bit depressing.} 11. Nbd2 bxc3 12. bxc3 c5 {Threatening ... Ng4 .} 13. h3 O-O {A siumple plan next would be to move the b7 -bishop and play ... Rb5 , targeting the pawn on a5 .}) 10... Bxb4 {The opening can be considered a strategic disaster for White. a5 is weak, b2 is weak and there is nothing to really compensate for that.} 11. Qa4 c5 (11... Ba8 {Was even safer.} 12. f5 $2 exf5 {Now the pawn can just be taken. Compared to 12.f5 in the game there is no Bf4 -counterplay.}) 12. Nc3 (12. f5 $1 {This was a surprising way to get some counterplay.} exf5 13. Bf4 Rc8 $6 (13... O-O {! Is a high-level exchange sacrifice that is probably nice for Black, but again messier than what we want.} 14. Bxb8 Nxb8) 14. Nd4 $1 {Such lines are what we should be aware of against the Dutch. If we keep making good moves White will lack counterplay, but after some less careful moves the White pieces could spring to life. This is one such case.} g6 15. a6 Ba8 16. Nb5 {Suddenly both Nd6 + and Nxa7 are threatened. It's still not clear, but it's way more counterplay than White deserves.}) 12... O-O {Now Black is in control again.} 13. a6 Ba8 {Such positions are a disaster for White. The a- and b-pawns are weak, but the main problem is that there is no counterplay whatsoever.} 14. Na2 Ba5 15. Kh1 Qc7 {A good move, but it was already possible to take over.} (15... d4 $1 {In the middlegame, this is often a key push to gain access to the e3 -square and open up for the light squared bishop. We should always be aware of what happens after e3 though.} 16. e3 (16. e4 dxe3 {Is the same.}) 16... dxe3 17. Bxe3 Rxb2 {Simply a very healthy extra pawn.}) 16. Nc3 Bb4 17. Na2 Bc6 {Keeping the b4 -bishop makes sense, but it was also tempting to just let White grab it.} (17... Rb6 18. Nxb4 Rxb4 {White has the bishop pair, but that's not really an improvement. The b2 -pawn is weaker than ever, and ... d4 is coming soon.}) 18. Qc2 Ba5 19. Nc3 Rfe8 {I like the calmness of Gumularsz' play. He realizes that White isn't really threatening anything, so simply keeps improving his position little by little.} 20. Na4 Bb4 {Nc3- a2 - c3 - a4 does not make a great impression.} 21. Ne5 {A bid for counterplay, but it's too little too late.} (21. Nc3 Rb6 {For example, eventually picking up the a6 -pawn.}) 21... Nxe5 22. fxe5 Nd7 23. Bf4 d4 {Cutting off the e5 -pawn, which is now another weakness. But again, it's not so much the weaknesses that is White's main problem, but more the complete lack of counterplay.} 24. Bxc6 Qxc6+ 25. Kg1 Rb5 (25... Ba5 {Simply avoiding the trick in the game would have given Black an overwhelming position.}) 26. Nc3 {A tricky move! Soham is doing what he can to create at least some form of counterplay.} dxc3 27. bxc3 Qb6 (27... Ba5 28. c4 {Wins the piece back.}) 28. cxb4 {Finally White crumbles.} (28. Be3 $1 {Preparing to take on b4 without Black able to recapture with the pawn.} Bxc3 (28... Ba5 29. c4 Rb2 30. Qa4 {Still wins the piece back.}) 29. Qxc3 h6 {Black is still better, but it's a lot less clear than before the Nc3 -trick.}) 28... cxb4+ {Now it's just over. The b-pawn is a monster, and White's e5 -pawn ripe for taking.} 29. Kh1 Nxe5 (29... b3) 30. Qa4 {The game seems to have ended here. Perhaps White lost on time, or perhaps simply resigned without waiting to see how Black would realize the overwhelming advantage.} *

